<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
  
 Trump purchase of casino a safe bet with local economy  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ If you're looking for encouraging news about
the area economy, look no further than Donald Trump's willingness
to buy Kansas City's Flamingo Hilton Casino.
</P>
<P>
   Trump Hotels &AMP; Casino Resorts Inc. is apparently not only
willing to pay $15 million for the casino, but also is ready to
assume Hilton's obligations to city government, which amount to an
additional $30 million. This isn't quite half what Hilton spent to
develop the property, but given the local situation, it still seems
a strong vote of confidence in Kansas City's future.
</P>
<P>
   There are skeptics, of course, who see the deal as a steal
because casino ownership is like having a license to print money.
Tell that to Sam's Town, though, which packed it in after its
printing presses malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   Given the competition and the Flamingo's market position, this
is far from being a no-brainer. When casino developers began
pouring their investment millions into Kansas City, those
uncomfortable with the growing gambling presence were quick with
doomsday prophesies.
</P>
<P>
   The casino market is being overbuilt, they warned, implying some
sort of dire consequences. In fact, the investment money
represented a shot in the arm for Kansas City's construction
industry, regardless of how many casinos survived.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Sam's Town has been the only casualty, and
observers attributed its demise more to location than competition.
This theory seems validated by the decision of a major gaming
company to take Hilton's problem off its hands and take a flier on
a troubled operation.
</P>
<P>
   What makes Trump's interest in Kansas City significant is the
nature of the Flamingo's market, which is generally perceived as a
blue-collar, mostly working-class clientele. When the Trump people
run the pertinent numbers as they ponder deals, the strength of the
local economy gets considerable scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the key number was probably the area's
unemployment rate, which is well below the national rate. Trump's
financial strategists likely interpret this to mean the local
economy is strong enough to support a full-employment environment
for the foreseeable future. This, in turn, means there's no reason
those expected to patronize the Flamingo won't have lots of money
to spend on entertainment and recreation for long enough to make
this casino a sound investment.
</P>
<P>
   In a broader sense, the fact that industry experts believe the
area can support four major gambling operations is also a vote of
confidence in the Kansas City economy. This probably isn't what
gambling's opponents like to hear, but it seems to be the current
economic reality.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City has so far proved a reasonably strong market for
casino operators despite intense competition. This is more a
function of a strong economy than any lack of morality on the part
of those contributing to the casinos' profitability.
</P>
<P>
   The casinos do well by offering a good deal more than gambling.
It's apparent that aggressive, innovative operators are attracting
customers for their food and nongaming entertainment, as well as
for chances to flirt with Lady Luck.
</P>
<P>
   The bottom line is that the injection of gaming into Kansas
City's economy is proving a positive experience.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
