<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPE-MERCHANDISE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIRITUALITY ASIDE, POPE'S VISIT PROMISES BIG PAYOFF IN MATERIAL
WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ From ``pope-on-a-rope'' soap to ``papal doughnuts,''
a visit by Pope John Paul II has become a way to enrich the
pocketbook as well as the soul.
</P>
<P>
   The pope's visit to St. Louis on Jan. 26-27 should be no
exception.
</P>
<P>
   More than any concert or convention, the visit will be a
bonanza. Planners expect at least 50,000 visitors and an economic
impact of $25 million. That doesn't include the underground economy
of souvenir vendors.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, Amy Benson of St. Louis hears from someone hoping to
cash in.
</P>
<P>
   They call her family's Catholic Supply stores, hoping to add
their unlicensed items to the sizable papal displays. It might be a
Colorado outfit offering snow globes. Or maybe an artist designing
ornaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a temptation to get everything you can and put it out
there,'' Benson said, adjusting a display of papal medallions.
``But if they have something that's not very tasteful, we stay away
from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Archdiocese of St. Louis has followed the model of the
Vatican itself, competing with unlicensed vendors rather than
trying to control them.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese has licensed 40 vendors to sell items, including
T-shirts, posters, keychains, cameras and teddy bears. About 60
vendors made their pitches to the archdiocese, which gave special
consideration to local firms and those owned by women and
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The archdiocese did not charge for licenses, but will keep 2
percent of merchandise sales. The money will help pay for papal
events or go to local charities.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the archdiocese won't get much money, it hopes to
give consumers a tasteful alternative for souvenirs. Kansas City
consumers can buy the goods at www.archstl.org and from official
vendors at the events.
</P>
<P>
   Monsignor Ted Wojcicki, a member of the planning committee, said
the only inappropriate proposal was for ``papal wine.'' The
archdiocese didn't want to sanction a product that seemed to
trivialize an important part of Catholic ritual.
</P>
<P>
   But Wojcicki knows that the unofficial kitsch will surface on
Jan. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to sell what they want to sell. It's a free
country, and entrepreneurship is as American as apple pie,'' he
said. ``We just hope people respect the Holy Father by the items
they put out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, if restraint were only that easy.
</P>
<P>
   When the pope visited Baltimore in 1995, critics killed a
Pennsylvania baker's plans for a ``papal doughnut'' baked in the
likeness of the pope. Maryland vendors hawked the ``Miracle Mug,''
a coffee cup that caused the pontiff's image to appear when filled
with boiling water.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the ``pope-on-a-rope,'' a bar of soap with the
pope's likeness that could hang from a shower head.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, the Vatican has tried to get its share of the
profits, blending the commercial and the spiritual. The Vatican
sold more than 1 million CDs of the pope saying the rosary in
several languages. The pontiff's prolific writings are best
sellers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Not that brisk sales are guaranteed. Organizers of World Youth
Day in Denver and their merchandise supplier battled in court after
sales fell far short of expectations. Other vendors in cities such
as New York and Los Angeles have been disappointed when crowds
didn't materialize.
</P>
<P>
   As a tiny self-supporting city-state, the Vatican needs the
money it collects from sales at its museums and over the Internet.
Customers can buy replicas of paintings and statues that are among
the Vatican's treasures. The Vatican also has entered into a
partnership with department stores like Macy's and Marshall Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think good taste should prevail, even for them (the
Vatican). If they put it out and they're not offended, I guess it's
all right,'' said Owais Succari, director of the Institute for
Business and Professional Ethics at DePaul University, a Catholic
institution in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all part of the culture. A lot of things have been
commercialized,'' Succari added. ``But I think we really should
have a certain respect for historical figures, and that includes
the pope.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, the pope has condemned rampant materialism and
consumerism, especially in the industrialized world. But in an
address to the United Nations, John Paul also conceded that ``man
lives at the same time both in the world of material values and in
that of spiritual values.''
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders don't think it's wrong to sell items with the
pope's image. Just do it with respect, they say. An official
mission statement insists that the items can promote faith and
encourage love and respect for the pope.
</P>
<P>
   Vatican officials have said that selling items can help bring
the pope's message to believers all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Wojcicki is trying to ignore all that _ the dollars, the vendors
and the shoppers. He said his worries are more relevant to the
pope's visit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can spend the whole day thinking about the economic side
of this,'' he said. ``We'd rather try to stay on top of the
spiritual aspects.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the unofficial products created for past papal
visits:
</P>
<P>
   - In Baltimore, T-shirts were sold with the pope _ armed with a
can of seasoning and crab mallets _ blessing a flock of crabs whose
claws are raised to the heavens. The caption: ``Go forth and
multiply!''
</P>
<P>
   - A Maryland microbrewery created a batch of commemorative beer
called ``Ale Mary.'' A St. Louis brewpub, the Tap Room, is
following suit with its Holy Smoke Papal Porter beer.
</P>
<P>
   - A San Antonio outfit, called Papalphernalia, created cardboard
miter masks with eye cutouts. They were called the ``Holey See.''
</P>
<P>
   - A Detroit company created lawn sprinklers that spurted out
from the outstretched hands of the pontiff. Their slogan was ``Let
Us Spray.''
</P>
<P>
   - Phoenix unveiled faux-concert T-shirts featuring the pope
playing a guitar. They featured a stadium date of the ``Raising
Hell Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   - A Chicago company sold Pope Scopes, periscopes similar to the
ones often used by the gallery at golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   - A Mexican potato-chip maker, a sponsor of the pope's visit
this month, has created ``papitas del papa'' _ or pope chips. They
feature images of the pope and the Virgin Mary.
</P>
<P>
   - Carmel, Calif., saw posters depicting the pope and then-mayor
Clint Eastwood. The caption read: ``Thou Hast Made My Day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
