<SLUG> BC-DRINKING-COLLEGE-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGES HOPE TO SHOW STUDENTS THAT PEERS DRINK RESPONSIBLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: In the 1100s, the provost at the University of Paris
rode across campus on horseback with a band of archers, threatening
to shoot anyone found drunk and disorderly.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 900 years later, colleges and universities are still
trying to figure out how to deal with students who abuse alcohol.
The University of Kansas said recently it was launching a
communitywide effort, an approach the University of Missouri and
other schools also are taking.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest struggle we face is just getting people to realize
there is something that can be done about this,'' said William
DeJong, director of the Higher Education Center for Alcohol and
Other Drug Prevention for the U.S. Department of Education. ``We
can make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to change, most agree, is creating a culture on campus
that encourages responsible drinking and makes students aware that
most of their peers do, in fact, drink responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   Since Northern Illinois University in DeKalb began an
advertising campaign along that line, it has greatly reduced its
binge drinking rate. Binge drinking generally is defined as downing
five or more drinks in one sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Universities are encouraging bars to eliminate specials such as
penny pitchers and are keeping gymnasiums open late on weekend
nights to give students an alcohol-free place to gather. Many also
are tightening their alcohol policies and encouraging their
community leaders to crack down on underage and illegal drinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you have to do all of these things,'' said Henry
Weschler, director of College Alcohol Studies at the Harvard School
of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no single approach that is going to solve it.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent string of deaths has prompted universities to take
another look at problem drinking.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, fraternity pledges died from alcohol
poisoning at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and at
Louisiana State University.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, a KU freshman from Overland Park, Kan., died after
she was struck by a vehicle driven by an intoxicated, underage
student. Last fall, a student at the University of Michigan-Ann
Arbor died after she fell out a window after drinking at a party.
</P>
<P>
   In Lawrence, Kan., a 21-member task force appointed in July
spent six months examining the extent of underage and harmful
drinking in the community.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last fall at KU found that 58 percent of the students
questioned said they had engaged in binge drinking within the
previous two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The national binge drinking rate among college students is 42.7
percent, according to a Harvard study that Weschler directed. KU's
rate matches the rate at the University of Colorado-Boulder but is
higher than the rates at the University of Missouri-Columbia (44
percent) and at Kansas State University (45 percent).
</P>
<P>
   Comparing the rates is difficult at best because the surveys may
not ask exactly the same questions or be conducted at the same time
of year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, whether we are at 58 percent or 50 percent
or 42 percent, it's a situation we need to address,'' KU Chancellor
Robert Hemenway said.
</P>
<P>
   MU is using an approach similar to the one at Northern Illinois,
said Kim Dude, director of MU's alcohol and drug abuse office. It
focuses on helping students understand that most of their fellow
students are making good choices. The school also is educating
admission recruiters, faculty, residence hall employees and others
to send the right message to students.
</P>
<P>
   MU thinks its efforts so far have helped it reduce its binge
drinking rate from 53 percent in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Hemenway created the KU-led task force in cooperation with the
city's mayor and the president of Haskell Indian Nations
University. This month, the three agreed to try to implement the 11
recommendations that the task force issued in December. The plan
includes:
</P>
<P>
   - Promoting responsible drinking. KU has applied for a state
grant to duplicate the advertising approach used at Northern
Illinois University.
</P>
<P>
   - Cracking down on students who persistently violate alcohol
policies on campus, possibly expelling them.
</P>
<P>
   - Increasing the fine for a minor in possession of alcohol from
$200 to $300 on the first offense and then $500 for subsequent
offenses.
</P>
<P>
   - Increasing enforcement and penalties for persons who use false
IDs and for those who make them.
</P>
<P>
   - Trying to reduce underage drinking at private house parties.
One suggestion was to pass a state law requiring anyone who buys a
keg to register for it so authorities can better track who is
supplying alcohol to minors.
</P>
<P>
   - Promoting more alcohol-free events.
</P>
<P>
   - Encouraging education efforts in high schools and middle
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``At KU, it boils down to a three-part program,'' Hemenway said.
``You have to reduce illegal consumption...regulate (use) more
effectively...and educate young people to make intelligent
decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those three things _ reduce, regulate and educate _ are the
three pillars that we are going to sort of build our total program
at KU around.''
</P>
<P>
   KU student body president Kevin Yoder said he hopes that KU
administrators and community leaders do not take too
``heavy-handed'' an approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coming at it from an iron fist...hasn't been shown to be
effective anywhere,'' said Yoder, a task force member.
</P>
<P>
   Disturbances broke out on a half-dozen campuses last spring, at
least partly because students were frustrated with alcohol
crackdowns. At Michigan State University, students started a huge
fire in the streets of East Lansing shortly after the university
announced it was banning alcohol at a popular tailgate spot during
the fall football season. MORE
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: fall football season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The students were unhappy...but it proved to be a wise
decision,'' university spokesman Terry Denbow said. There's no more
unruly behavior in that tailgate lot, he said, and no more public
urinating. It's become an appropriate place for families, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional educational approaches that tell students not to
drink have had only limited success, those in the field say.
</P>
<P>
   That's why many schools now are focusing on preventing harmful
drinking. That's the emphasis KU plans to take.
</P>
<P>
   Task force members, however, kept bumping into the problem of
underage drinking, which is why some initiatives are geared toward
curbing it, said Jeff Weinberg, an assistant to the chancellor who
coordinated the task force.
</P>
<P>
   Yoder said the concern with underage drinking bothered him.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of stopping it, he said, ``I was more focused on
understanding that underage drinking exists and what are we going
to do to mitigate some of the risks associated with that?''
</P>
<P>
   Yoder did persuade the task force to recommend that KU explore
the idea of expanding its program to provide students safe rides
home from bars. But task force members said that would not
encourage the kind of healthful behavior they want to promote.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges do have to enforce the law, DeJong said, and the legal
drinking age throughout the nation is 21. That's not likely to
change, he said, even though some people, including a bar owner who
served on the KU task force, think it should be lowered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've already done that once, during the Vietnam War,'' DeJong
said. ``It was a disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowering the drinking age increased drinking among high school
and middle school students, he said, and increased deaths on the
highways. Colleges have no choice but to deal with their mix of
underage and legal drinkers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   While enforcing the underage drinking laws, MU, Colorado and
Michigan State said they were concentrating on teaching students
how to drink in a manner that keeps them safe.
</P>
<P>
   That's one of the keys to the Northern Illinois approach, said
Michael Haines, the school's coordinator of health enhancement
services. Advertisements in the college newspaper, for example,
tell students how to drink without getting a hangover, he said, or
what to do if a friend is drunk.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisements also drive home the point that most students
drink responsibly, he said, because most students do. When students
realize that their peers do not drink as much as they thought they
did, it encourages them to drink less, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Since Haines started the campaign at Northern Illinois 10 years
ago, binge drinking there has decreased by 44.8 percent, to 25
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We give students information on how to protect themselves,''
Haines said. ``They seem to appreciate that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
