A6557 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ABORTION-AZR &LR;      01-17 2977
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORTION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABORTION CENTERS ACCUMULATE RECORD OF 6 DEATHS, 28 SUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSIE STECKNER  
 and JODIE SNYDER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The owner of a Phoenix abortion clinic where a woman bled to
death operated a cross-country chain of abortion centers with a
troubled record, including six deaths, numerous injuries and
accusations that profits were put before patient care.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Arizona Republic'' investigation found that errors and
indifference allegedly exhibited in Phoenix were only the latest
questionable events at the low-cost, high-volume clinics owned by
New York physician Moshe Hachamovitch.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the physician who performed the abortion in Phoenix,
Dr. John Biskind, and clinic manager Carol Stuart were arrested on
charges of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch also is being investigated by the Maricopa County
Attorney's Office. Meanwhile, he faces a state medical board
investigation and a lawsuit by the family of Lou Anne Herron, the
woman who died in April at A-Z Women's Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republic'' interviewed former clinic employees, and
reviewed court documents and health agency and medical board
records. They reveal:
</P>
<P>
   The deaths of six women. Two were Hachamovitch's own patients;
four others died after abortions by doctors who worked for the
chain. One, a 15-year-old, died after an abortion that was
performed by a doctor so ill that he himself died the day of her
funeral, her attorney says.
</P>
<P>
   A Texas health department investigation revealing conditions so
unsanitary at a Houston A to Z clinic that officials moved to
revoke its operating license because it was an ``immediate threat''
to patients.
</P>
<P>
   A San Antonio police investigation in which two former employees
alleged that abortions were secretly performed by an A to Z medical
assistant and an administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch, 62, who still operates clinics in the Bronx and
Long Island, refused to comment for this article. His attorneys in
New York and Arizona refused as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief interview with ``The Republic'' last year,
Hachamovitch dismissed suggestions that Herron's death was anything
but accidental.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe that there was any wrongdoing or any criminal
intent,'' Hachamovitch said.
</P>
<P>
   As for himself, ``I have not done anything wrong. I still fully
support Dr. Biskind, not because of the mistake that he has done
but because of his (past) successes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch's three Arizona clinics provided tens of thousands
of abortions over two decades but closed after Herron's death. He
once owned as many as 10 clinics around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with his clinics have been well documented over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Former colleagues and court documents said some of those
troubles may have stemmed from Hachamovitch's intense drive to make
money. He undercut competitors; drew women from neighboring states
with ads and toll-free phone numbers; focused on costly, late
second-trimester abortions; and had each clinic's financial reports
faxed daily to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hach was so interested in making money. That's the thing you
have to understand,'' said a doctor who worked for Hachamovitch in
Texas and spoke on the condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hach . . . always talked about how fertile economically this
business was,'' the doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. William Ramos, who had a business partnership with
Hachamovitch in Nevada until the two had a contract dispute, put it
this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hachamovitch is a very skilled physician. He's a good surgeon.
(But) it was very clear that he was trying to run his clinics with
minimum expense and maximum profit.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just got himself into too many things at the same time and
he just wasn't watching the pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Tel Aviv, where abortion was done but not condoned,
Hachamovitch arrived in the United States in the 1960s, just as the
country was on the brink of legalizing abortion. He finished his
residency at Albert Einstein College of Medicine in the Bronx,
where he is now an assistant professor.
</P>
<P>
   New York was one of the few states where abortion already was
legal, and women would fly in from across the country for the
procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch was a hospital resident in charge of treating women
who had complications from abortions. That, he later said in a
court deposition, led him to ``make sure that abortion was legal
and available and affordable and safe.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Hachamovitch and a partner had incorporated a practice
in Westchester County outside New York City.
</P>
<P>
   He later told a writer that he believed middle- and low-income
women needed access to low-cost procedures; rich women could always
get them.
</P>
<P>
   His instincts apparently were right: New York court records
referred to Hachamovitch as a doctor with a ``volume operation,''
with doctors performing 17,000 abortions in 18 months in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The volume was about to increase. Hachamovitch received medical
licenses in Washington, D.C., and six states.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, he set up clinics in states with booming populations.
There was Florida, Texas, Arizona and a brief foray into Nevada.
Many offered late second-trimester abortions, from 20 to 24 weeks,
which cost patients more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got into the business very, very early, and became sort of
an entrepreneur,'' said the doctor who once worked with him in
Texas. ``He spread out all over the country. He was making big, big
bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   He also expanded into the Bronx, where he started a clinic in
three apartments. Years later, abortion opponents turned him in to
authorities for violating building codes but he was allowed to
stay.
</P>
<P>
   That makeshift clinic was a far cry from that in upscale White
Plains, whose operations were followed in a 1984 book that
chronicled a day in the life of an abortion clinic.
</P>
<P>
   The author described a tidy and welcoming clinic, with cookies
in the waiting room. The White Plains clinic had a competent and
knowledgeable staff as well as a compassionate group counseling
session for patients and their husbands, the author found.
</P>
<P>
   But that depiction contrasts with the portrait of his clinics
painted in at least 28 lawsuits claiming negligence and other
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Luz Maria Rodriguez, 40, who was eight to 10 weeks
pregnant, died from complications at the Bronx clinic. Right before
she was to be discharged, Rodriguez started turning blue from lack
of oxygen. Cardiopulmonary resuscitation was performed and
paramedics were called. Rodriguez was taken by ambulance to a
hospital, where she remained in a coma for four days until her
death.
</P>
<P>
   A medical-malpractice review found that the doctor had not
removed all the contents of Rodriguez's womb, which led to
hemorrhaging. As the clinic owner, Hachamovitch was found guilty of
malpractice and paid part of a $1.5 million settlement to
Rodriguez's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Christina Goesswein, 19, was brought into the
Bronx clinic. She had had sponges inserted a day earlier to dilate
her cervix, but was vomiting and having severe pain. Hachamovitch
opened the clinic in the middle of the night and proceeded with the
abortion; Goesswein died hours later.
</P>
<P>
   A medical examiner ruled that she died from an embolism of
amniotic fluid. A lawsuit is still pending against Hachamovitch in
the case, alleging he should have recognized her symptoms and
should not have done the abortion.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Board for Professional Medical Conduct found that
there was no lapse in care on Hachamovitch's part, but believed
he'd made a false record entry concerning the amount of blood
Goesswein lost.
</P>
<P>
   That and two other complaints of poor record keeping led the New
York board to suspend Hachamovitch's license for a year, but that
was knocked down to a one-month suspension.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch fought the one-month penalty, fearing that even a
brief lapse would cost him business and expose him to action from
other state medical boards, court records show. He appealed to New
York state courts as well as to federal court, arguing that the
state had violated his constitutional rights.
</P>
<P>
   His 6-year-long appeal continues.
</P>
<P>
   While Hachamovitch was fighting to protect his license in New
York, he was spending years cleaning up legal messes in his
now-defunct clinics in Dallas, Houston and San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some of his employees were questioning
conditions at his clinics and quality of patient care.
</P>
<P>
   The doctor who worked for Hachamovitch in Texas quit after four
years, saying his concerns for patients weren't heeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``His attitude was, `That wasn't my responsibility,' '' the
doctor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patient care was left entirely up to the personnel in the
office,'' he said. ``If he had someone really good, then patient
care was really good. The next person might come in and (that
person) was really horrible. Then that's what happened to patient
care _ it was horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctor also claimed that employees in the Dallas and Houston
clinics used inadequate equipment, reused IVs, neglected to change
bed sheets between patients and reused suction equipment and
sponges inserted into women's cervixes. Similar claims would be
made later by an employee and doctor who worked at A-Z in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Martha Hopkins, a former business manager for the San Antonio
clinic, also told Texas investigators that ``conditions were filthy
and that the records were in very poor order,'' according to Texas
Department of Public Safety records.
</P>
<P>
   She said she was pressured by Hachamovitch to do more of the
high-cost, late second-trimester abortions, and that she quit after
three months when he implied that she was stealing from the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with drugs being misused by doctors at the Houston
clinic prompted Hachamovitch to voluntarily surrender his federal
license to dispense medicine in 1986 and 1987.
</P>
<P>
   By 1994, Texas health officials were so concerned about
Hachamovitch's Houston clinic that they went to court to have his
operating license yanked.
</P>
<P>
   Problems began when 15-year-old Jammie Garcia Yanez-Villegas
died from an infection after an abortion by Dr. John Coleman at A
to Z. Two weeks later, a health department inspection revealed
dirty and unsafe surgical instruments, inadequately trained
personnel and incomplete patient records.
</P>
<P>
   The state went to court to shut him down, and Hachamovitch
voluntarily closed the clinic.
</P>
<P>
   Yanez-Villegas' family later named him in a wrongful-death
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this 15-year-old Hispanic girl comes in for her abortion,
there's no counseling from anyone who spoke Spanish, the consent
forms are all in English,'' said her lawyer, Ted Amshoff.
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch's attorney argued that the teen did get adequate
counseling, court records show.
</P>
<P>
   Amshoff said there were also concerns over Coleman, a prominent
Houston gynecologist. At the time of the abortion, Coleman, who had
emphysema, needed supplemental oxygen and was being evaluated for a
lung transplant, Amshoff said. Employees were concerned about his
ability to operate given his health problems, Amshoff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His staff in Houston told Hachamovitch that,'' Amshoff said.
``He (Hachamovitch) ignored that. He met with him and said `That's
no problem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In a deposition, Hachamovitch said Coleman assured him he was
working at full capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . He insisted on going on and proved that he had the
stamina and tenacity,'' Hachamovitch said.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after Yanez-Villegas died, Coleman died at age 64 of
acute respiratory failure.
</P>
<P>
   The teen's lawyer also claimed the clinic was unsanitary and had
inadequate equipment.
</P>
<P>
   He obtained a clinic administrator's memo that she was getting
bids for used equipment because ``our ultrasounds are not
repairable.''
</P>
<P>
   In another memo, a second employee wrote that a repairman was
concerned about the machine used to sterilize equipment: ``He
wanted us to know that the remaining autoclave is not designed to
handle as many loads as we are running per day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yanez-Villegas case was later settled, but the terms are
confidential, Amshoff said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Hachamovitch's San Antonio clinic became tangled in a
Texas Department of Public Safety probe, though it suffered no
criminal penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators were looking into allegations that two
non-doctors, who used to work at A to Z, performed as many as 250
abortions at another San Antonio clinic.
</P>
<P>
   One of the non-doctors admitted to investigators that he had
first learned to do the illegal abortions at A to Z by assisting in
the operating room. An A to Z business manager confirmed this,
saying the pair had performed abortions at Hachamovitch's clinic
but were later fired after some patients developed complications.
</P>
<P>
   The two non-doctors eventually went to prison on assault charges
for performing abortions at the other San Antonio clinic.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Hachamovitch closed his Dallas clinic in the face of
anti-abortion protests. A year later, Hachamovitch sold A to Z in
San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout these major battles, Hachamovitch also clashed with
patients in both Texas and New York, who alleged negligence at the
hands of his doctors in lawsuits dating as far back as 1985.
</P>
<P>
   One Texas woman alleged that a doctor ruptured her uterus, then
pulled her lower intestine through the uterus and out through the
cervix. Two others said they left clinics believing they had had
abortions, but later bore babies.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Hachamovitch still faces a malpractice case in the
death of a 28-year-old woman who died from complications of a
perforated uterus caused by a doctor at a Hachamovitch clinic.
</P>
<P>
   At times throughout his career, Hachamovitch would simply deny
knowing of any problems and disavow responsibility because he was
not the doctor treating the patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself an extremely good surgeon,'' Hachamovitch
said in a 1997 deposition in the case of a woman whose bleeding
would not stop after an abortion and ended up having a
hysterectomy.
</P>
<P>
   ``As such, I would not dictate to him (the surgeon who was being
sued) of how to operate or not operate on patients.''
</P>
<P>
   The court agreed, and dismissed him from the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview with ``The Republic'' last year about Biskind's
troubles, Hachamovitch explained that problems can be expected when
high numbers of procedures are performed. In the many years Biskind
worked at A-Z, he had two patients die, Hachamovitch said.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . He did thousands of patients successfully,''
Hachamovitch said. ``Yes, he had two or three or four problems. In
the ocean of all the cases this is really a drop.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Abortion Federation, uteruses are
perforated in less than 0.5 percent of legal abortions; the chance
of death is one for every 160,000 women.
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona and Texas employees said there was a push to do
more late second-trimester abortions at Hachamovitch's clinics
because those brought in more money. In 1998, A-Z in Phoenix
charged $299 for women seven to 11 weeks pregnant, compared with
$1,250 for women 20 to 24 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   When Hachamovitch opened clinics in Arizona, he immediately
undercut other doctors' prices, said Dr. Brian Finkel, a Phoenix
abortion provider who worked for Hachamovitch for several years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he could undercut prices, he knew he'd get more of the
market share,'' Finkel said. ``People will drive across town for
$25.''
</P>
<P>
   Hachamovitch eventually had at least three clinics in Arizona:
A-Z on McDowell Road, and Family Planning Institutes in west
Phoenix and Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   But, as elsewhere, there were problems.
</P>
<P>
   Biskind, who regularly flew in from Cleveland to work at A-Z,
came before the Arizona Board of Medical Examiners several times.
He was eventually censured for the death of a patient before he
gave up his license last year after Herron's death.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Occupational Safety and Health Administration fined
the A-Z clinic on McDowell Road for health hazards, including a
suction machine that was contaminated with blood, dirt and dried
soap.
</P>
<P>
   Shelia Allen, who worked for a month at A-Z in 1997 straight out
of trade school, remembered the clinic as chronically
short-staffed. Three days after starting there, she was in the
operating room helping with procedures.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone was always running around in a rush,'' she said. ``It
was always rush-rush. People didn't know what they were doing and
people would tell them exactly how to do it and not ask any
questions.''
</P>
<P>
   Like patients in other states, Phoenix women sued A-Z clinic and
the doctors it employed. Each time, however, Hachamovitch was not
the doctor actually involved in the case.
</P>
<P>
   He was the target of seven complaints made to BOMEX. The board
issued three letters of concern in two of the cases _ one for
problems with medical records and one for failing to file fetal
death certificates. It dismissed the other complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, two new complaints are pending for inadequate
supervision of his clinics. One, from Herron's family, blames
Hachamovitch in part for her April death.
</P>
<P>
   Herron went to A-Z seeking a late second-trimester abortion. The
staff took several ultrasounds, which showed her to be 24 to 26
weeks pregnant.
</P>
<P>
   Some employees told police they questioned whether Herron was
over the legal limit for an abortion. But Stuart told them that
Herron was Hachamovitch's private patient.
</P>
<P>
   Herron received the abortion; she bled to death over the next
three hours in the recovery room.
</P>
<P>
   The Herrons' attorney, Paul Lazarus, says Hachamovitch has to
take some of the blame.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly had a duty to properly train, supervise and
retain individuals who could meet the standard of care that people
who come into his office would expect,'' Lazarus said. ``We feel he
did not do that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0014EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 00:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6559 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAIL-AZR &LR;      01-17 2067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAIL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EYEWITNESSES DESCRIBE NIGHT JAIL INMATE DIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY KAMMER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few weeks after their son died in a struggle with guards at
the Madison Street Jail, Jaron and Deena Norberg found a haunting
message on their home answering machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello,'' a female voice said. ``I was there when Scott died,
and I need to talk to somebody about it, because they murdered him.
</P>
<P>
   ``And please _ I'm going to _ is anyone there, please?''
</P>
<P>
   The caller turned out to be Patricia Duran, 51, a jail clerk and
an eyewitness to the violent and controversial end to Scott
Norberg's life.
</P>
<P>
   Her sworn deposition became a key part of the Norberg family's
wrongful-death lawsuit that Maricopa County and its insurance
carrier settled this month for $8.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Duran's testimony, along with that of a guard involved in the
confrontation and several inmates who saw it, harshly contradicts
Sheriff Joe Arpaio's staunch defense that his officers did nothing
wrong when they subdued Norberg on June 1, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The county settled the case Jan. 7 after spending $1 million
dollars in pretrial legal expenses. The settlement requires the
county's insurance carriers to pay the $8.25 million. Arpaio did
not acknowledge any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   After the settlement was announced, a combative Arpaio expressed
regret that he would be unable to put up a courtroom fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted a trial,'' he said. ``We were ready for a trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the case gone to trial, Arpaio would have confronted witness
accounts that:
</P>
<P>
   Detention officer David Gurney triggered the fracas that quickly
brought a half-dozen officers into Norberg's cell.
</P>
<P>
   As Norberg struggled in a black metal ``restraint chair,'' a
towel over his mouth, one officer warned that Norberg couldn't
breathe, and two others responded that they didn't care.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to the county medical examiner's conclusion that
Norberg's death was the ``accidental'' result of ``positional
asphyxia,'' Norberg's inability to breathe was the result of
violent handling by the detention officers.
</P>
<P>
   Now the FBI and Maricopa County Attorney Rick Romley are
investigating the death of Norberg, 35, a former football star at
Tempe High School and Brigham Young University whose life spiraled
down into drug abuse and a series of arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio last week declined an ``Arizona Republic'' request to
elaborate on his office's version of the incident. Instead, aide
Jack MacIntyre said the record at trial ``would have shown that
there was no assault, there was no manslaughter, there was no
criminal conduct whatsoever'' by detention officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were doing their job,'' MacIntyre said Friday. ``They're
not from some alien spaceship or Nazi muscle camp.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, trial jurors would have learned the grim details of
Norberg's death, the basic facts of which are undisputed:
</P>
<P>
   His mouth gagged with a towel, his arms handcuffed behind the
chair, his body zapped repeatedly with stun guns, Norberg's
panicked struggle ended when he could no longer breathe.
</P>
<P>
   His faced turned a purplish blue, testified Kimberly Walsh, a
detention officer who'd warned other officers that Norberg couldn't
breathe. He kicked spasmodically one time, she said, then died.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who held the towel over Norberg's mouth, acknowledged
that she had complained about the incident to other officers
immediatedly after Norberg died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was angry . . . how things were done,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Duran testified that she called the Norbergs' home because she
was upset by the Sheriff's Office descriptions of the incident and
by letters defending the office that were published in newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   The letters ridiculed Norberg, ``saying that he was a drug
addict and he was a scumbag and he got what he deserved,'' she said
in her deposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, no, he didn't get what he deserved,'' Duran said.
``Nobody deserved what Scott got, because he didn't do anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Arpaio's office blamed Norberg for everything. Four months after
his death, the office released an investigation that absolved
detention officers of any wrongdoing. Arpaio expressed
satisfaction, saying the report had been prepared by ``very
professional detectives.''
</P>
<P>
   According to that report, the incident began when the 6-foot-2,
234-pound Gurney approached Norberg in a cell and touched his arm.
Norberg, who stood 5-foot-11 and weighed 180 pounds, ``jumped up,
turned around and flexed his body'' in a menacing manner. Then, as
officers surrounded him, he began ``swinging his elbows at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the case gone to trial, Duran and others would have
presented a far different story. It was a story the sheriff's
investigators had themselves heard, but one they glossed over and
downplayed. While their report included careful transcripts of
interviews with detention officers, it simply paraphrased Duran's
comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said she felt that what happened should never have
happened,'' the Sheriff's Office reported. ``She said she thought
it was excessive.''
</P>
<P>
   Duran had followed Gurney to the cell to serve Norberg with
court papers that reflected his arrest the night before. Norberg,
who according to a neighbor had seemed ``scattered and confused,''
was charged with assaulting an officer who responded to a report
that he had threatened two girls.
</P>
<P>
   Another jail clerk who had attempted to interview Norberg had
noted that he was disoriented. She wrote in a report that Norberg
``just looks at interviewer and will not speak.'' She added that he
was a ``possible 918,'' code for someone in emotional or mental
distress.
</P>
<P>
   Duran testified that Gurney should have followed usual jail
procedure with troubled inmates _ simply handed him his pretrial
paperwork and left him alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also here to tell you that any other officer would have
handed him his paperwork _ and I know that in my heart,'' Duran
said in a pretrial deposition. ``I'll die knowing that in my heart.
Anyone else would have handed him his paperwork, and Scott would
have never, ever, ever gone through any of that.''
</P>
<P>
   One inmate described Norberg's emotional distress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scott began talking to himself. . . . He just kind of kept
rambling on to himself and acted very abnormally,'' James Heffron
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few times, Scott started speaking what seemed like some
unrecognizable language. It seemed like he was speaking in
tongues.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, another inmate in the crowded cell became
irritated at Norberg and threw a bologna sandwich at him, Heffron
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Norberg) did nothing in retaliation,'' he said. ``He just
sat there with the piece of bread on his shoulder for 10 or 15
minutes before it fell off.''
</P>
<P>
   Duran said that when Gurney entered the cell, Norberg was
sitting on the floor. Gurney ordered him to get up, and when
Norberg didn't respond, ``Gurney reached down, grabbed him, with
his left hand, grabbed his right arm, pulled him up, pulled out his
stun gun and stunned him in his upper body.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with investigators the night of Norberg's death,
Gurney offered a different account.
</P>
<P>
   Gurney said that when he touched Norberg, the prisoner took a
swing at him with his left fist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It (Norberg's fist) probably moved about six to seven inches
before I put him in the bear hug,'' Gurney told investigators. ``At
that time the inmate became even more combative and started
screaming and . . . smashed me, pushed me, whatever you wanta call
it, into the, into the middle bunk'' of the holding cell.
</P>
<P>
   Court Commissioner Robert Bushor, who also was present at the
scene, also defended the officers' conduct.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there was any excessive use of force
throughout the incident,'' Bushor told sheriff's investigators. He
said Norberg had caused the incident by ``mouthing off'' to Gurney.
</P>
<P>
   However, inmate Rab Choudry's account is consistent with Duran's
description of an abrupt, unprovoked attack by Gurney.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most confusing part, because we had no idea why
it was happening,'' said Choudry, who, like Norberg, had been
arrested the night before and was waiting to go before a judge.
``We thought maybe he (Norberg) had done something earlier.''
</P>
<P>
   Jail surveillance videotape shows that there had been contact
between Gurney and Norberg about 80 minutes before the fatal
confrontation. It shows a dazed-looking Norberg in a hallway after
his interview with a pretrial services worker.
</P>
<P>
   The tape, which has no sound, shows detention officer Oldana
Musbach approach the shirtless Norberg as he wandered in obvious
confusion away from the desk where he had the interview.
</P>
<P>
   Norberg responded passively. He sat on the floor as Gurney
approached from the rear. Norberg put his hands over his head, and
Gurney dragged him by one leg into a holding cell. He had been
dragged twice previously by other officers.
</P>
<P>
   It was about this time that inmate Jarrett Blain saw Norberg,
according to a report by sheriff's investigators. Their report of
Blain's account adds a bizarre twist to the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Blain) stated that Norberg was talking funny, saying stuff
like he was `going to die in here,' '' the report says. Blain said
Norberg was not causing any problems or trying to fight with
anybody.
</P>
<P>
   Gurney's confrontation with Norberg triggered a furious
struggle. Duran testified that Norberg fell face first to the
floor. Then other officers rushed into the holding cell to help
Gurney.
</P>
<P>
   According to Choudry, they ``kicked, hit, whatever they could do
to inflict pain on this man.''
</P>
<P>
   Inmates shouted angrily at the guards, but none intervened as
Norberg was handcuffed behind his back and dragged by those
restraints, according to testimony of both officers and inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Martin Spidell acknowledged to a county investigator in
1996 that he told other officers, ``Maybe we should just kick his
ass so he quits fighting.'' At his deposition last year with
Norberg's attorney, however, Spidell refused to answer questions,
invoking his Fifth Amendment right against self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Inmate Herbert Thompson described Gurney as the most violent of
the guards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seen this man (Gurney) choking him, kneeing him, trying to
step on his balls, pulled his shoe off and twisted his foot down
sideways on the cement and stomped it,'' he said in a deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Norberg panicked as officers dragged him out of the cell,
several inmates said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was yelling, `Help me! Somebody please help me! Oh God!
Help me!' '' Thompson said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the guards were yelling, Thompson said, ``All I
remember is one guard saying something to the fact _ `We just keep
hitting him and he keeps moving.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he was so upset by what he saw that he wrote down
an account.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thing looked like a pack of dogs trying to kill
somebody and didn't know how,'' Thompson wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Heffron said he was ``deeply traumatized'' by the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I saw,'' he said, ``was a mob that killed a man while he
pleaded for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Norberg struggled mightily as the guards tried to force him into
the restraint chair, flailing about with what they later described
as ``superhuman strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, the officer, said one of the guards stood on Norberg's
back. Duran said he ``put up quite a fight. . . . I've never seen
anybody fight so hard to stay out of that chair as Scott did.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh, who held the towel clamped over Norberg's mouth,
testified that when she noticed that Norberg wasn't breathing, she
told Spidell.
</P>
<P>
   According to Walsh, Spidell responded, ``Who gives a
(expletive)? . . . He's still going to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh said she then gave the same warning to Gurney, who said,
``Who gives a (expletive)?''
</P>
<P>
   Gurney gave a different account to investigators.
</P>
<P>
   According to Gurney, ``Officer Walsh leaned over to me and said,
`He looks like he is turning blue,' and I said, `I think he is.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Norberg went limp, nurse Kay Campbell told the officers to
release him from the restraint chair. Walsh joined Campbell in a
futile attempt at cardiopulmonary resuscitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame it happened,'' Walsh said in a deposition last
year. . . . I mean, that night I was extremely upset. I tried to
save him, and he died. . . . I was also angry with myself. I was
just upset with the whole thing.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0029EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
