r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      01-17 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCAMMING A GREAT GENERATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The TV anchorman Tom Brokaw says anyone who came of age during
the Great Depression and World War II is a member in good standing
of the world's greatest generation. He wrote a book that says so
right on the cover. It's called ``The Greatest Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest generation _ isn't.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying it wasn't a pretty darn good generation. Maybe
even a great one. It certainly produced some of the greatest
individuals the nation has known.
</P>
<P>
   My mother and father, for example.
</P>
<P>
   And Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   And the Kennedy brother everybody still loves, even after the
revelations out about him and other women.
</P>
<P>
   According to Brokaw, though, these people and others represent
``the greatest generation any society has ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   No.
</P>
<P>
   They don't.
</P>
<P>
   It's true they lived through a Depression. It's true they risked
and (in many cases) lost their lives saving the world from Hitler.
It's true they were responsible for creating enormous wealth and
shaping much of the modern world. But that's only part of the
story.
</P>
<P>
   While fighting for freedom in Europe, they put
Japanese-Americans in internment camps and kept Black soldiers in
segregated outfits. &QL; 
GENERATION'S FAILURES
</P>
<P>
   The pitchmen pushing Brokaw's book say this was a generation
``united not only by common purpose, but also by common values _
duty, honor, economy, courage, service, love of family and country,
and, above all, responsibility for oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, it was the kind of family where a mother's place was
``only'' in the home.
</P>
<P>
   And a country with few civil rights for people of color.
</P>
<P>
   This was a generation that staged the worst witch hunts since
Salem, ruining the reputations and even jailing some of its
greatest artistic and scientific minds because of an exaggerated
``red menace.''
</P>
<P>
   As for honor and duty, were these men and women greater than
those who fought in the Civil War? Were their economic and
technological advances more important than those of the Industrial
Revolution? Were their political leaders better than Lincoln?
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about history, though. It's about commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Why give the ``greatest generation`` title to people from the
1800s when none of them are around to buy books?
</P>
<P>
   And why hedge your bets?
</P>
<P>
   ``The Good Generation'' isn't sexy enough. ``The Great
Generation'' is better, but if you want big numbers, it's got to be
``The Greatest Generation.''
</P>
<P>
   It's working, too. It's selling.
</P>
<P>
   Although, you might not buy the part about this generation
believing ``above all'' in ``responsibility for oneself.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, they produced and are benefitting from one of the
largest socialist experiments ever conducted by a society. A series
of government-controlled programs offering health care, housing and
higher education for hundreds of thousands of former soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   And then went to work for businesses that still collect billions
of dollars in corporate welfare. &QL; 
A CHUCKLE IN ITALY
</P>
<P>
   Outside the U.S., I'm guessing there are a few countries who
also might get a chuckle out of Brokaw's claim that this was ``the
greatest generation any society has ever produced.''
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, there once was a generation that included fellows
named da Vinci, Machiavelli and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters.
</P>
<P>
   The greatest generation had to come from the United States,
where it would get the greatest exposure. And reach the greatest
number of consumers. And engender the greatest sense of nostalgia.
And have the greatest chance of landing on the bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   All of which proves nothing about my parents and their peers,
but does show how the men and women who followed them, including
Brokaw, may in fact compose ``the greatest generation.''
</P>
<P>
   Of shills. &QL; 
 &UR; E.J. Montini can be reached at 444-8978 or at ed.montini &LR; pni.com
via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
