<HEADLINE>
NHL STILL AN UNDERDOG TO NBA, OTHER NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Hockey is obviously succeeding. The sport has made inroads to Texas
and Florida that have resulted in three NHL teams and copious
minor-league outfits.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The impact of adding key television markets such as Dallas/Fort
Worth, Miami, San Jose/San Francisco, Phoenix, Denver and Nashville
can't be disputed. The bottom line is more people are watching the
sport than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   But if the NHL believes it won't be hurt by the NBA's return,
it's not dealing with reality. The NHL hasn't come close to taking
the NBA's television audience, and there's no better example of
that than North Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. The Stars are the best team in the NHL and have
been putting a winning product on the ice for the past three
seasons. The Mavericks have been one of the worst outfits in the
NBA, and fans aren't sure if they could even reach the playoffs
this season.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, more people in North Texas would rather watch the
Mavericks on television than the Stars.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that is history, part of that is upbringing, and part of
that is demographics. One NHL representative put it perfectly when
he said the NBA has a core audience and the NHL has a cult
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is the NHL isn't easy to watch on
television. It's hard to follow the puck, and it's difficult to
understand strategy in a game that moves pretty quickly but gives
viewers fewscoring plays. The best way to enjoy an NHL game is
watching from start to finish, so you can pick up the subtle
battles between players and key matches that coaches seek. Doing so
takes more than two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA, on the other hand, gives you instant gratification.
Watch for 10 minutes, see a few highlight plays, check out a
``Seinfeld'' rerun for a half hour and come back for the final two
minutes of the game. It's a formula that's very TV-friendly.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars have more people coming to Reunion Arena than ever
before. Their television ratings have almost tripled since last
season (but is only 4.0). Sales of Stars merchandise is going
through the roof, and all it takes is a visit to a local elementary
school to see that kids love this team.
</P>
<P>
   But to think the NBA's return isn't going to hurt the NHL's
fight for the fan dollar is ignoring the obvious. This is a fight
in which hockey still is a heavy underdog.
SLAP SHOTS Relax, already Former Stars defenseman Enrico Ciccone
said that as a Montreal Canadiens fan growing up, the player he
hated most was Washington Capitals pest Dale Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd wake up in the middle of the night with my fists in balls,
just hating him and hating him,'' said Ciccone, now a fighter. ``He
was definitely on my 11-year-old hit list.''
</P>
<P>
   The two are now Capitals teammates. Bad craftsmen Vancouver
Canucks general manager Brian Burke spent five years with the NHL
front office and had a big hand in forging the current collective
bargaining agreement during the 1994 lockout. Now, he says that
soaring salaries are not the fault of that agreement, but of the
owners and GMs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tools are in place to hold salaries down,'' Burke
said. ``I just don't think we're using those tools in the right
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Burke is taking a hard line on Pavel Bure and said Thursday that
if he doesn't trade the holdout winger soon, he'll wait until the
March 23 trade deadline. Not fair The NHL had the right idea last
season when it decided to not force every team to have a
representative at the All-Star Game. This season, the league
decided to try to include every team and had some glaring
omissions.
</P>
<P>
   Jere Lehtinen might be the best player on the Stars from the
start of the season until now but will not be included. Even worse
is leaving off Los Angeles' Luc Robitaille, who has 14 goals and 18
assists. He might be the third-best left wing in the league.
Question of the week Q: Since fan balloting began in 1986, which
team has had the most starters elected to the All-Star Game?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Pittsburgh Penguins, led by Jaromir Jagr and Mario
Lemeiux's seven starts apiece, have 21. The Stars never have had a
player elected as a starter. The week ahead Monday: Philadelphia
Flyers at Ottawa Senators. The two hottest teams in hockey square
off with the possibility of an unbeaten streak on the line.
Wednesday: Toronto Maple Leafs at Stars _ Two of league's best
collide as the Maple Leafs seek revenge for a 5-1 loss. Jan. 24:
NHL All-Star Game. Five Stars representatives mean you have to
watch. Best of the best The Hockey News recently released a book,
``The Top 100 NHL Players of All Time'', and two of the players
have ties to the Stars. Here's the top 10, and the Stars' two
honorees: 1. Wayne Gretzky, Edmonton Oilers 2. Bobby Orr, Boston
Bruins 3. Gordie Howe, Detroit Red Wings 4. Mario Lemieuex,
Pittsburgh Penguins 5. Maurice Richard, Montreal Canadiens 6. Doug
Harvey, Montreal Canadiens 7. Jean Beliveau, Montreal Canadiens 8.
Bobby Hull, Chicago Blackhawks 9. Terry Sawchuk, Detroit Red Wings
10. Eddie Shore, Boston Bruins Others: 64. Brett Hull, St. Louis
Blues 86. Bob Gainey, Montreal Canadiens THE BUZZ Western
Conference: The Nashville Predators are hoping to become the first
expansion team to reach the playoffs in its first season. ``We're
right there knocking on the door for a playoff spot, and that is
our goal,'' captain Tom Fitzgerald said. ``We play the game to win,
not kill time before the summer arrives. Being a first-year team is
no exception.'' ... Nice to see that the fans finally snapped to
attention and voted Colorado's Peter Forsberg over Detroit's Sergei
Fedorov to start the All-Star Game at center. After being edged by
Forsberg in voting, Fedorov was left out of the game by league GMs.
... The Canucks' Bill Muckult is an easy choice as rookie of the
year at the midway point with 13 goals and 12 assists, but quietly
building a case is Colorado Avalanche center Chris Drury, who has
10 goals and 11 assists. ... The Kings have struggled on the power
play at 11.5 percent and have given up a league-high seven
short-handed goals, giving them the worst combined power play in
the NHL. ... Phoenix's five-man defense could get a real test now
that Gerald Diduck is out with a knee injury. The Coyotes signed
defenseman J.J. Daigneault last week.
</P>
<P>
   Eastern Conference: Now that the New York Islanders have made
the swap for Felix Potvin, they have one too many goalies. Tommy
Salo, who has five shutouts this season, is sitting at home hoping
for a trade. ``I am not very happy,'' Salo said. ... When Senators
goalie Damian Rhodes was credited with a goal two weeks ago, he
became the fifth goalie in NHL history to score. Rhodes didn't
actually shoot the puck in the net, but he was the last player to
touch it before the Devils knocked it into their own net. Islanders
goalie Billy Smith did the same thing in 1980, and Chris Osgood,
Martin Brodeur and Ron Hextall have shot pucks into empty nets. ...
The hottest road team in the NHL isn't the Stars or Flyers, but the
New Jersey Devils, who are 12-6-1 away from home. ... The Maple
Leafs are a healthy 15-7-2 at home, and team president Ken Dryden
said he's not worried about that magic leaving when the Maple Leafs
move out of Maple Leafs Garden on Feb. 13. ``It's not like this
franchise has a long history of winning here, so I don't think
moving ... should be a problem,'' Dryden said. ... The Flyers have
two of the longest unbeaten streaks of the decade, going 17 games
in 1996-97 and 15 games this season. The Pittsburgh Penguins have
the longest streak of the decade at 18 games (17-0-1). ... The
Tampa Bay Lightning are the latest team to tire of Craig Janney's
act. The enigmatic center is a good playmaker, but he continues to
build a reputation as locker-room poison. He has been told by the
organization to stay at home and await a trade. ... The Senators'
Ron Tugnutt is 11-5-3 with a league-low 1.73 goals-against average,
and said he thanks a stint in the minor leagues. Tugnutt, 31, was
sent to the American Hockey League in 1995-96 after six seasons in
the NHL. ``I played \R58 games\S with Portland. I look at that year
as a turning point.'' (Mike Heika writes for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
