<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-Q&AMP;A-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LOOK AT THE MAVERICKS' MISSION FOR '99
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
The Mavericks open their 20th training camp Tuesday. They posted a
20-62 record last season, but showed promising signs down the
stretch. ``Star-Telegram'' staff writer Dwain Price answers 10
questions the Mavericks must address if they hope to compete for a
playoff spot.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: Everybody says Steve Nash is a rising star in this league. Is
that true or is it management's way of covering itself because the
team gave up last summer's first-round pick for him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nash has all the qualities to become a NBA star. In a way,
he's Jason Kidd minus the hotdog and mustard. And he can
consistently bury the jumper from the perimeter. Nash is a leader,
and fans will grow to love his personality and his insightful
approach to the game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It appears the only ingredient preventing the Mavericks from
reaching the next level is some type of dominating presence inside.
Do they have one?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not really. If the Mavericks can re-sign Kurt Thomas, he
gives them a much-needed enforcer. Nobody consistently wins NBA
championships unless they have at least one enforcer. Samaki Walker
also is a rugged individual with star quality. But Thomas and
Walker are forwards, and the Mavericks need a rugged center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Shawn Bradley ever going to become the dominant center Don
Nelson thinks he can become?
</P>
<P>
   A: That's entirely up to Bradley. In the five years Bradley's
played in the NBA, he has not lived up to his potential. But he is
who he is. Coaches and teammates say he's lazy and doesn't work
very hard in the off-season. Every now and then Bradley will post
some incredible numbers to get his teammates' hopes up and have
coaches and fans saying ``wow.'' The Mavericks' best course of
action is to make sure they're solid at the other four positions,
then whatever they get from Bradley is a bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Dirk Nowitzki built a nice resume against some bland
competition in Germany. Is he the real deal, or is he another in a
long line of players from overseas whose game is too soft to cut it
in the NBA?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nowitzki is a typical European star player: He has a lot of
offensive skills, but his defense is lacking. In due time, he'll be
a decent defensive player. But his offensive talents and
ballhandling skills are as good as any NBA player. And he has
tremendous range for a guy 6-foot-11. Nowitzki is a quicker version
of Toni Kukoc and has a better shooting eye than Detlef Schrempf,
two European players who have made it big in the NBA. Mavericks
fans should have great pleasure watching his development over the
years.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How come Michael Finley wasn't mentioned as a possible heir
apparent to Michael Jordan?
</P>
<P>
   A: Good question, and the answer is simple. Finley, who attended
high school near Chicago, plays on a bad team that receives very
little national press coverage. But the Jordan-Finley comparisons
are eerie. Finley has Jordan's incredible work ethic, uses Jordan's
trainer in the off-season, once played Jordan one-on-one when he
was in high school and was hand-picked by Jordan last season to
model Jordan's new apparel line. Also, remember Jordan scored a lot
of points, played a lot of minutes and lost a lot of NBA games
until he got a supporting cast. Well, Finley has been scoring a lot
of points, playing a lot of minutes and losing a lot of NBA games.
But the supporting cast is on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why does anyone think Don Nelson will turn the Mavericks into
winners?
</P>
<P>
   A: Remember when Jimmy Johnson took over the Cowboys in 1989,
and he had the good graces of owner Jerry Jones to make whatever
trades were necessary to turn the team around. Mavericks owner Ross
Rerot Jr. has given that same power to Nelson. Less than eight
months on the job, Johnson engineered the Herschel Walker 12-player
trade with Minnesota. Less than a month with the Mavericks, Nelson
pulled off the nine-player trade with the New Jersey Nets. Nelson
will keep renting players like Dennis Scott and Cedric Ceballos,
and they'll keep leaving if Nelson doesn't think they are a perfect
fit.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the season started today, who would be the starters?
</P>
<P>
   A: Steve Nash at point guard, Michael Finley at two-guard, Dirk
Nowitzki at small forward, Samaki Walker at power forward and A.C.
Green at center. Nelson wants to start Thomas at power forward, but
Thomas is a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If the Mavs are unable to re-sign Thomas, is the power
forward spot in shambles?
</P>
<P>
   A: Not at all. In case you missed it last season, Samaki Walker
was a one-man wrecking crew before his season was cut short by
injuries. He was commanding _ and beating _ double teams, and
overpowering any one-on-one matchup. Even Charles Barkley was
scratching his head after Walker took him to school. If he ever
averages 35 minutes in this game, Walker will average 18 points and
10 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will playing four games in one week adversely affect the
Mavericks?
</P>
<P>
   A: It shouldn't. They have a relatively young team, so playing
that many games in one week should be an advantage because they
should have fresher legs.
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK, since Finley, Nash and Walker are ``rising stars'' and
Nowitzki a promising rookie, when can the starving Mavericks fans
expect this team to at least reach the playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   A: If the Mavs can add a free-agent center such as Sam Perkins,
the playoffs probably could happen this season. Without Tom
Gugliotta, Minnesota will fade, leaving one Western Conference
playoff spot available. Realistically speaking, the Mavericks are a
quality center away from reaching the playoffs. If that piece of
news doesn't make Shawn Bradley work harder, nothing will. (Dwain
Price writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0054EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
