<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-OVERVIEW-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAD DASH COMING FOR NBA TEAMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
On April 22, 1889, a new Oklahoma was formed when residents lined
up to stake greener pastures in the Great Land Run.
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Jan. 19, 1999, a new NBA will be forged when players line up
in search of greener contracts in the Great Free-Agent Run.
</P>
<P>
   With Michael Jordan now retired to golf, the NBA's A.M. Era _
like the Great Land Run _ will fittingly begin via shotgun start.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never seen anything like it. I expect full and total
chaos,'' said Indiana Pacers general manager Donnie Walsh. ``It'll
be a mad scramble.''
</P>
<P>
   When the ink dries on the league's new collective bargaining
agreement tomorrow, approximately 200 free agents will dash onto
the open market searching for lucrative contracts, a chance to win
a championship, or simply a place to call home. What is usually a
leisurely four-month period of signings and trades stretched over a
summer will suddenly be crow-barred into a frenzied two weeks that
will drastically restructure the NBA's balance of power.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the six-month labor lockout, the abbreviated regular
season is scheduled to start the weekend of Feb. 5-7.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cram city,'' said agent Steve Kauffman. ``Major decisions have
to be made in split seconds. In the end, some guys may wind up
being left out in the cold. It's going to be wild.''
</P>
<P>
   Forget wining and dining marquee players. It's all about signing
them. Quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are so many people you are interested in and you don't
want to lose one while waiting for another to make a decision,''
said Charlotte Hornets vice president Bob Bass. ``There won't be
the process of bringing in a major player and showing him the
facilities and having him talk to everyone. You'd like to find
someone right away and hope it's a home run.''
</P>
<P>
   The only sure thing in this unprecedented free-agency period is
that it won't produce double-take contracts such as the $126
million deal signed a year ago by Minnesota Timberwolves forward
Kevin Garnett. The new CBA took care of that, putting a maximum cap
on salaries based on experience in the league. None of the
contracts signed can now be worth more than $14 million in the
first year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly had \RGarnett's contract\S thrown in our faces by
agents who said, `Well, if you can afford that why can't you afford
this?','' said Utah Jazz owner Larry Miller. ``\RThe CBA\S put a
stop to that. They'll still make their money, but now we've got
control of the reigns.''
</P>
<P>
   Players will still have options, but because of the ceiling on
maximum salaries there won't be agent-driven, bidding wars
escalating into the absurd. While agents and players watch the
league's transaction wire like an investor eyeing the stock-market
ticker, the free-for-all will be inexpensive-for-none.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming the salary cap is $30 million (with the possibly of it
increasing to $32 million) by Tuesday, the Bulls ($18 million),
Nuggets ($12 million, Suns ($11 million) and Rockets ($10 million)
are in the best financial shape to sign players. Of course, they
also have the most spots to fill as the Bulls and Rockets have only
four players signed.
</P>
<P>
   At the top of a list that resembles a high school blue-chip
recruiting page are forwards Scottie Pippen, Antonio McDyess, Tom
Gugliotta and Charles Barkley, point guard Rod Strickland, and
centers Vlade Divac and Isaac Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Now that long-time running mate Jordan has retired, Pippen is
expected to leave Chicago despite the fact that the Bulls can offer
him a pro-rated salary of $14 million this season. The Rockets and
the Suns are aggressively pursuing Pippen and McDyess, who also has
a meeting in Chicago scheduled tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm Chicago's property to lose,'' Pippen said last week. ``But
that doesn't necessarily mean I'll end up here.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the CBA, teams can sign a player to a minimum
three-year contract and then trade him. The move would enable the
Bulls, for example, to sign Pippen and then trade him for players
or draft picks rather than losing him without compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are going to be very, very popular,'' said Pippen's
agent, Jimmy Sexton.
</P>
<P>
   McDyess, the Suns' property, could earn $86 million by staying
in Phoenix and only $67 million if he moves to Houston or Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver's on at the top of the list,'' said his agent, Tony
Dutt. ``There's pressure on him to act fast. But the real test
won't be how fast he made the choice, but how well he made it.''
</P>
<P>
   Gugliotta, Minnesota's All-Star, must weigh $105 million to stay
put and $81 million to leave for suitors like Phoenix or the
Lakers, who are considering dealing forward Elden Campbell and
guard Eddie Jones. Barkley, property of the Rockets, said he'll let
the initial dust settle before deciding between the Rockets,
Seattle SuperSonics and possibly other teams.
</P>
<P>
   Another key pawn in the game will be former All-Star guard
Latrell Sprewell, whom the Golden State Warriors will undoubtedly
trade. The Miami Heat, San Antonio Spurs and Pacers have shown
interest, with the Heat's offer of Jamal Mashburn and P.J. Brown
thought to have the inside track.
</P>
<P>
   While it's unclear who the hottest player on the market is,
there's no doubt Houston is suddenly the most attractive
destination. With loads of money, popular coach Rudy Tomjanovich,
and the likelihood of Hakeem Olajuwon-Charles
Barkley-Pippen/McDyess front court, the Rockets are on most
players' short list.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the running for a lot of people, as this is not a bad
place to live,` Rockets vice president Carroll Dawson says.
``Watching TV reports during the lockout, I've seen 20 players a
day in town playing, and it looks like an All-Star game.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, Chicago's image is icier than its cruel winter
weather. General manager Jerry Krause seems determined to rebuild
rather than reload, but players aren't thrilled about the curse of
filling Jordan's Nikes. Center Luc Longley appears headed for
Phoenix, while backup guard Steve Kerr is hinting he'll land in
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's cold as hell there, and they're rebuilding,'' said
free-agent guard Damon Stoudamire. ``Without Jordan, without
Pippen, they're a lottery team. That doesn't have much appeal to
me.'' (Richie Whitt writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sign here, please?! When the NBA's free-agent signing period
commences Tuesday, approximately 200 players will frantically
search for new, well-paid homes in what promises to be one of the
most frenzied months in league history. A look at where each
position's three most expensive signatures will be signed: POINT
GUARDS Player Top dollar Top suitors Comment Damon Stoudamire $6
million Blazers/Rockets Likely staying put in Portland. Rod
Strickland $7 million Wizards/Rockets Loyalty? Says he'll go to
highest bidder. Kevin Johnson $4 million Lakers/Magic Perfect
compliment to Derek Fisher in L.A. SHOOTING GUARDS Player Top
dollar Top suitors Comment Rex Chapman $4 million Suns/Spurs Game's
most creative scorer stays in Phoenix. Jim Jackson $4 million
Warriors/Clippers Deteriorated skills make him average at best.
Brent Barry $4 million Warriors/Suns Has shown rare desire to play
in Golden State. SMALL FORWARDS Player Top dollar Top suitors
Comment Scottie Pippen $14 million Rockets/Bulls Back surgery, age
(35) make him risky. Rick Fox $4 million Hawks/Lakers Recently
called Lakers a ``long shot.'' Clifford Robinson $5 million
Suns/Hornets Also shopping his wares in Houston. POWER FORWARDS
Player Top dollar Top suitors Comment Antonio McDyess $10 million
Nuggets/Rockets Likes Denver, close friend Nick Van Exel. Tom
Gugliotta $9 million 'Wolves/Suns Trade to Lakers also on front
burner. Charles Barkley $7 million Rockets/Sonics May take $2
million for chance at title. CENTERS Player Top dollar Top suitors
Comment Vlade Divac $9 million Hornets/Sonics Likely traded to
Seattle or Sacramento. Rik Smits $9 million Pacers Wants to stay in
Indiana and vice-versa. Isaac Austin $8 million Magic/Bulls Penny
Hardaway pushing hard for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
