<HEADLINE>
NCAA TOURNAMENT IS A SCANDAL IN WAITING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Should you want to sneak up on an NCAA suit and spook him toward
the nearest cardiac care unit, the operative three-letter word is
``bet'', not ``boo''.
</P>
<P>
   Every night as they try to drift off to dream land, NCAA
president Cedric Dempsey and his lieutenants see these words
flashing across their synapses: ``gambling scandal''.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is frightened to the death penalty by gambling. In
particular, the organization is tossing and turning over the
possibility of the NCAA Tournament, its signature and money-making
event, being besmirched by a betting scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have had more revelations of illegal sports wagering and
point shaving in the last year,'' Dempsey said in his annual state
of the association address at last week's NCAA Convention in San
Antonio. ``And, regrettably, we may only have seen the tip of the
iceberg. ... It's maybe the most insidious of all issues facing
college sports today.''
</P>
<P>
   At the convention, a proposal was submitted that would require
all officials who work the NCAA Tournament to undergo a criminal
background check. Several conferences have been running spot checks
on officials over the past few years. What is hard to fathom is why
the NCAA has waited so long to institute such safeguards.
</P>
<P>
   And, the NCAA cited a gambling survey by the University of
Michigan. The survey said that nearly 35 percent of all athletes
have gambled on sports while in college, with 45 percent of the
male athletes saying they've gambled on sports. Five percent of
male athletes said they have ``provided inside information for
gambling purposes, bet on a game in which they participated or
accepted money for performing poorly in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, I question the accuracy of a survey that elicits
responses from just 25 percent of the participants. And, I wonder
how many of the student-athletes honestly answered the questions.
After all, this wasn't the semester final in English Lit.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that gambling is pervasive in our society.
Sports, we all have been told by the experts, mirror society. It
was estimated that last year's Final Four generated $80 million in
wagers _ more than Super Bowl XXXII. From office pools to lotteries
to big-time bookies, a large percentage of the populace is involved
in gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The NCAA is diligently disseminating anti-gambling information.
It distributes a seven-minute anti-gambling video to each Division
I team; all 64 teams that make the tournament are required to view
it. And at last year's Final Four, coaches, players and officials
were briefed by the NCAA's Bill Saum and an FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   But the NCAA's anti-gambling efforts are as futile as holding
back the tide. Saum is the only NCAA employee assigned to the
gambling issue _ and he also deals with the issue of agents. The
NCAA has about two dozen enforcement agents enforcing its 489-page
book of arcane rules on recruiting, eligibility and conduct _ and
one man taking on organized gambling.
</P>
<P>
   The day before last year's Final Four in San Antonio, two former
Northwestern players were indicted for point shaving. The
Northwestern point-shaving scandal followed a point-shaving scandal
at Arizona State, which followed a point-shaving scandal at Tulane,
which followed a point-shaving scandal at Boston College.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the betting incidents we know about in college
basketball. Bet _ sorry about that, Ced _ that there are dozens
more we don't know about. And all of those incidents involved a
single school and regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, the NCAA Tournament is clean. Dempsey says a gambling
scandal would be ruinous because it would cause the public to lose
confidence in the tournament's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The odds _ aw, man, my bad, Ced _ are it will happen. Who knows
when or where, but it will happen. An NCAA Tournament gambling
scandal is a ticking time bomb, ready to explode.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boom.'' (Wendell Barnhouse writes for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
