TOP QUESTION FOR '99: WILL Gordon BE CAUGHT? HEADLINE GOES HERE 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Stock-car racing's annual rite of winter, the
Charlotte Motor Speedway Media Tour, is all about ``bench-racing.''
And as any fan of ``RPM 2Night'' will attest, talking about the
races is the next best thing to being at the races.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Approximately 200 media members spent last week touring various
NASCAR Winston Cup shops in anticipation of the 1999 season. A
dizzying array of team alliances, elaborate garages, sponsorship
packages and paint schemes was trotted out from here to
Spartanburg, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   This just in: Practically every Cup driver, crew chief, car
owner and CEO believes his team has raised the performance bar for
next month's Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Translation: Each is hoping to win whatever races Jeff Gordon
does not.
</P>
<P>
   So, let the speculation begin. From the back of the No. 9702
State Fair Corny Dogs bus, here are the most asked questions about
NASCAR's 51st season:
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there any reason to believe that Jeff Gordon will not win
his fourth Winston Cup championship this year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unless Gordon and crew chief Ray Evernham opt to run a Vega
instead of the Chevrolet Monte Carlo, none whatsoever. On the heels
of a record-tying 13 race victories, including three of the last
four, Gordon and Evernham apparently are only hitting their stride.
Gordon may not win as many races in 1999. So what? The guy wins 10
races during his ``off'' years.
</P>
<P>
   The No. 24 team's proven advantages in shop preparation, pit
stops and strategy will allow Gordon to pile up those valuable
Winston Cup points until his detractors can't stand it no more.
</P>
<P>
   Additional motivation will be supplied by the return of team
founder Rick Hendrick, who has spent the past two years battling
bone marrow cancer and myriad legal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a sentimental favorite to win the championship?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure, the driver who has little use for sentiment _ Mark
Martin. The 1998 points runnerup, and arguably the series' fiercest
competitor, Martin remains a popular choice to unseat Gordon.
Martin recently turned 40, as the clock continues to tick on his
quest to hand owner Jack Roush his first Cup championship. The No.
6 team's restrictor-plate engine program will have to improve
immediately at Daytona International Speedway _ or be served
another helping of self-doubt.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Which driver would most media members like to see atop the
points chart?
</P>
<P>
   A: Your friend and his, Rusty Wallace. Rusty rocks. Rusty
shocks. Rusty can fill up a notebook and melt down a tape recorder
like you wouldn't believe. Rusty arguably is the frankest interview
in NASCAR, even with his quotes routinely sanitized of their
expletives. And incidentally _ as the most recent Ford Taurus tests
at Daytona proved _ Rusty still can drive the wheels off a stock
car. Damn right.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who else figures to challenge Gordon for R.J. Reynolds
Tobacco's season-ending millions?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Usual Suspects, including Martin, Wallace, Dale Jarrett,
Jeff Burton, Bobby Labonte and maybe Jeremy Mayfield. Of that
group, the ever-classy Jarrett seems most at-ease with the prospect
of having to chase down the 24. And Gordon said he expects to see
plenty of Burton's No. 99 in his rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What about Dale Earnhardt and his quest for an unprecedented
eighth Cup championship?
</P>
<P>
   A: In a word, ``fuggetaboutit''. Earnhardt will go into the
Daytona 500 as defending champion for the first time. And during
this tour, he began hinting that he would like to work out a new
contract that will keep him driving at Richard Childress Racing
once his current deal expires in 2000. That would be a bonus for
fans of Earnhardt and Dale Earnhardt Jr., who plans to join the Cup
circuit full time in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But realistically, Earnhardt's window of opportunity on breaking
out of his championship tie with Richard Petty was closed by Gordon
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are some of the more intriguing new alliances for 1999?
</P>
<P>
   A: Richard Childress Racing, Dale Earnhardt Inc. and Andy Petree
Racing have begun a shared aerodynamic research and development
program for their Chevrolets. Petree and No. 1 driver Ken Schrader
have added Kenny Wallace to their stable, which figures to become
NASCAR's version of The Comedy Zone.
</P>
<P>
   Prodigal son Kyle Petty has carted his pony tail, ear rings and
Pontiac Grand Prixs from Concord, N.C., to Level Cross, N.C.,
joining daddy King Richard at Petty Enterprises (and driver John
Andretti). Also, three-time Cup champion Darrell Waltrip, who is
determined to race through Y2K, has joined Travis Carter's Ford
stable as teammate to Jimmy Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is there a clear-cut favorite for Raybestos Rookie of the
Year?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tony Stewart is drawing the most preseason hype. The former
Pep Boys Indy Racing League champion will team with perennial
top-10 contender Bobby Labonte at Joe Gibbs Racing at its lavish
new facility.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stewart, Buckshot Jones and Elliott Sadler are winners and
graduates of NASCAR's Busch Grand National Series. Jones is working
out of his father's sparkling new $2 million facility. Sadler will
have all the knowledge of the famed Wood Brothers _ and their
owners' points covering the first four races _ at his disposal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will Dale Earnhardt Jr.'s five-race, 1999 Winston Cup
schedule include Texas Motor Speedway?
</P>
<P>
   A: Unfortunately for TMS general manager Eddie Gossage, no.
Little E, who won his first NASCAR Busch race in Fort Worth last
April, is scheduled to make his points-paying Cup debut in the
Coca-Cola 600 at Charlotte Motor Speedway on May 30. CMS was chosen
essentially because it is the Earnhardt clan's home track. The
reigning Busch champion and NASCAR's next superstar, Earnhardt Jr.
also will run Cup events at New Hampshire International Speedway
(July 11), Michigan Speedway (Aug. 22), Talladega Superspeedway
(Oct. 17) and the season-ender at Atlanta Motor Speedway (Nov. 21).
</P>
<P>
   Fans at TMS will have to console themselves with Junior's
appearance against Gordon in the BGN Coca-Cola 300 on March 27.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When can we expect the debut of the new Chevy Monte Carlo?
</P>
<P>
   A: Target race is The Winston non-points all-star event at CMS
on May 22, followed by the Coca-Cola 600 on May 30. Only two
versions of the new MC exist _ a high-downforce version built by
Bobby Hutchens at Richard Childress Racing and a superspeedway car
fabricated by Eddie Dickerson of Hendrick Motorsports. Dickerson is
anticipating NASCAR approval of final templates around Jan. 26,
followed by full-scale production.
</P>
<P>
   What does the car look like? It's so hush-hush, Gordon said he
has neither seen nor driven the car. But with the exception of the
rear deck lid, Dickerson said it looks very much like ``The
Intimidator'' concept car unveiled by Chevrolet last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Q: At 34 races over 40 weeks, is the Winston Cup schedule
maxed-out?
</P>
<P>
   A: Promoters seeking second Cup dates are betting millions it is
not. Developer Bruton Smith believes there is room for another four
Cup dates under the current system (with second races, naturally,
going to his TMS and the recently acquired Las Vegas Motor
Speedway).
</P>
<P>
   Smith also continues to take every opportunity to lobby NASCAR
president Bill France Jr. for an American and National League-style
series that would allow the schedule to grow to 40, 50 or 60
events. Smith also admits that devising a formula to separate the
stars by league looms as a major political headache.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is the driver formerly known as Geoff Bodine now asking
to be called Geoffrey Bodine?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bodine said ``Geoffrey'' is what his mother always called
him, especially after he made her mad. Besides, he now wants to
separate himself from all those other drivers named ``Jeff.'' Like
that was a problem? But the boys in the back of the No. 9702 State
Fair Corny Dogs bus have a theory. Bodine turns 50 on April 18, and
what we may have here is the onset of a mid-life crisis. (In
NASCAR, a new Harley-Davidson usually cures that).
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the runaway popularity of Winston Cup continue if Dick
Trickle fails to find a full-time series ride this season?
</P>
<P>
   A: Absolutely. This train is leaving the station. But race
highlights on ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' just won't be as much
fun-fun-fun. (John Sturbin writes for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0056EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
