<HEADLINE>
RANDALL CUNNINGHAM'S CAREER HAS BEEN BORN AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
MINNEAPOLIS _ By now, the story of quarterback Randall Cunningham's
return has been told many times.
<TEXT>
<P>
   How he went from playing in an old-timer's football game in 1996
to the Pro Bowl team in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   How he went from laying marble in Las Vegas to quarterback of
the most explosive team in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   How he went from a dangerous mobile quarterback with the Eagles
in his youth to a dangerous pocket passer at age 35.
</P>
<P>
   But as Cunningham prepares to take his Vikings (16-1) into
today's NFC Championship Game against the Atlanta Falcons (15-2) at
the Metrodome, the real story has nothing to do with his play on
the field.
</P>
<P>
   It's about his transformation from reviled egomaniac to beloved
teammate. It's about his conversion from a selfish superstar to the
peoples' choice.
</P>
<P>
   Grambling coach and former Washington Redskins quarterback Doug
Williams called Cunningham this week to wish him luck. Packers
defensive end Reggie White, who played with Cunningham on the
Philadelphia Eagles, said he should have won the league's most
valuable player award.
</P>
<P>
   Vikings coach Dennis Green calls him a team leader.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham credits his religious faith for changing his life and
resurrecting his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My marble company) didn't deal in grave stones,'' Cunningham
joked. ``But it sure looks like I've come back from the dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm the same person. I just play with more humility. I
thank God for everything. This is possible because of what He's
done inside of me, giving me peace and pulling down His grace upon
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Vikings receiver Cris Carter, a former Eagle who remembers the
old Cunningham, certainly likes the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing now is he's far more aware of other people
compared to just being concerned about himself,'' Carter said.
``He's really changed.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham's humility and spiritual renewal were born out of
lessons he learned during his brief retirement from football in
1996 following 11 seasons as the Eagles' scrambling quarterback.
Cunningham won two MVP trophies and was a perennial Pro Bowl
player.
</P>
<P>
   But he left the game as an unwanted superstar when the Eagles
decided to not re-sign him following the 1995 season and make
Rodney Peete their starter. No teams called, so he decided to go
home to Las Vegas and start a marble business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I owned the company, I did the work with my
employees,'' Cunningham said. ``To get down with those guys in the
trenches, laying tile and lining counter tops, dirt flying in you
face, your eyes burning at night and your back hurting in the
morning, it made me realize it was a whole lot tougher out there.
It shows another side of you when you humble yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who became the Vikings' starter after Brad Johnson
was injured in the second game of the season, remains somewhat in
awe of his accomplishments. He showed that the time away took
little from his rifle arm or his outstanding athletic ability,
completing 259 of 425 passes for 3,704 yards and 34 touchdowns. He
was the league's top-ranked passer with a rating of 106.0, while
earning his fourth trip to the Pro Bowl and being named all-pro.
</P>
<P>
   The old Cunningham would have considered what has transpired as
vindication regarding his bitter departure from the Eagles. The new
Cunningham said he has no ill feeling toward the Eagles, blames
himself for part of the problem and prays for the Eagles and what
they are going through after a 3-13 season.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said he's just thankful he joined the Vikings in
1997. He could have signed with the New Orleans Saints to be a
starter for more money, but he said God led him to the Vikings to
back up Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham said he would have been content with the same role
this season if Johnson had stayed healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, an ordained minister, is a believer. He said if
Cunningham would have came in with a different attitude the
quarterback situation could have torn the team apart, but said
Cunningham's humility has been a source of strength for the team
during this remarkable season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he says he doesn't care about his role on this team, he
really means it,'' Carter said. ``Things have just worked out well
with Brad's injuries. But I believe he's handled it tremendously
well, which he wouldn't have done in Philadelphia.''
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham maintains the success he's enjoyed this season won't
make him revert to the past. Instead he intends to use past
mistakes to help him deal with the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had success in the past and I have failed in the
past,'' Cunningham said. ``This time I am trying to take it in a
more mature way. I am truly blessed. I know now how to be thankful
for things I took for granted in the past.'' (Clarence E. Hill Jr.
writes for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
