<HEADLINE>
HUNTERS USING 19TH-CENTURY GUNS TO BAG GEESE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB HOOD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ROCHESTER, Texas _ When a bluish-white puff of smoke billowed from
the muzzle of Jimmy Heisz's double-barrel shotgun in a peanut field
here the other morning, it was a historic event for his hunting
companions.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sandwiched between the cloud of smoke and a heavy morning fog
that had completely blocked out the sky, a big Canada goose came
crashing to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The bird was Heisz's first of the morning taken with a 14-gauge
Wesley-Richards shotgun manufactured 149 years ago, a two-burner
loaded with No. 2 Bismuth shot packed in front of an equal amount
of Pyrodex powder.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was in the middle of a harvested peanut field near
here. Hunting guides Smokey and Kathy Rathbun of Webfoot Outfitters
in Rochester had chosen the spot for the morning hunt by scouting
this vast farming country for where the geese were feeding a day
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The Rathbuns had instructed six hunters with modern shotguns to
lie on their backs amid a spread of more than 100 Outlaw silhouette
decoys moments before dawn, with Heisz and two other muzzleloader
hunters to their right.
</P>
<P>
   The percussion cap muzzleloaders included Heisz's gun made in
1850, a Scott 10-gauge twin-burner manufactured in 1828 and used by
Jim Kern of Arlington, and a 15-gauge Dixie Gun Works doublebarrel
replica which closely resembled the 1828 shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that the hunters had modern shotshell guns and
muzzleloaders was not intended to be a test of one against the
other. As with most hunters who choose to hunt with muzzleloaders,
it was a matter of choice _ an escape from the norm and a
pleasurable way to enjoy a bit of hunting history.
</P>
<P>
   Using authentic muzzleloaders for waterfowl hunting was all but
obliterated several years ago when the federal government banned
the use of lead shot and required hunters to use non-toxic shot.
Until Bismuth became available two years ago, steel shot was the
only legal choice.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for muzzleloaders, steel shot is harder than the
Damascus barrels of the antique shotguns and may not be used
without the threat of causing damage to the barrels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bismuth has changed all of that,'' Kern said. ``It is the
closest thing to lead shot and doesn't damage the barrels of these
old guns. Bismuth has opened up a whole new ballgame for
muzzleloaders.''
</P>
<P>
   Heisz's Canada goose was one of four bagged from a flight of
about 15 geese which had emerged suddenly out of the fog, tricked
by the Rathbun's excellent calling and the spread of decoys that
had been set in a banana-shaped pattern.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest attraction for geese here are the peanut and wheat
fields leased by Webfoot Outfitters. Scouting the fields the
evening before a hunt allows the guides to determine which fields
the geese are feeding in so they can set up their decoy spreads the
following morning.
</P>
<P>
   Lying on their backs near the edge of the decoys, the hunters
stared into the heavy fog above, anticipating the arrival of geese
from a nearby roosting area. Almost an hour passed before the first
sounds of honking geese could be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The fog was so thick that the geese could only be heard, not
seen, until they were right on top of the hunters. The Rathbuns'
calls quickly brought responses from the honking geese, but their
exact whereabouts was shielded by the dense, damp whiteness.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes passed. The honking of the geese grew louder. They were
coming closer, but where were they?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a flight of about 15 Canadas sifted out of the fog and
over the decoys, only to disappear just as quickly to one side.
</P>
<P>
   The honking and the calls of the geese filled the air. The
hunters using modern arms fingered the safeties on their shotguns.
The muzzleloaders touched the hammers over their percussion caps.
</P>
<P>
   The geese reappeared again out of the fog, only this time there
were about 30 of them. Some cupped their wings and began a rapid
decent to the decoys. Others reduced the flapping of their wings
and swung their heads from side to side. The honking conversation
between the geese and the hunting guides was awesome.
</P>
<P>
   With geese overhead no more than 25 yards, Smokey Rathbun called
out to the hunters to ``take them.''
</P>
<P>
   The hunters sat up, raised their guns, and fired. Four geese,
including two shot by the muzzleloaders, tumbled from the flock.
The rest of the birds were swallowed once again by the fog.
</P>
<P>
   At ranges of up to 35 yards, the muzzleloaders proved just as
deadly as the modern arms. Outside that, the cartridge guns held
the advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you learn when shooting geese with a muzzleloader is
that you must swing through when you fire,'' Kern said. ``You
should swing through with a modern shotgun, too, but with a
muzzleloader, the ignition is so much slower and the shot is coming
out of the barrel at a much slower speed than with conventional
arms, a more pronounced swing will put the shot out there in an
elongated pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Other things a muzzleloader learns amid the haste of reloading
when flocks of honking geese are overhead and are stretching
hunters' nerves to near the breaking point, Kern said, is that the
system doesn't work if you pour a measure or shot down the barrel
ahead of the powder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can get pretty exciting when you are trying to reload a
muzzleloader with geese right on top of you,'' Kern said. ``There
is a certain system that you must follow _ powder first, a fiber
wad, followed by a card wad, then the shot and a fiber wad on top.
If you forget what you are doing, it can be pretty interesting.
</P>
<P>
   As the morning pressed on, an occasional flock of Canada geese
neared the decoys under the dense fog. Occasionally, a few
speckledbellies appeared, but this was a day for mostly Canada
geese _ and muzzleloaders. (Bob Hood writes for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
