<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Texas outlasts Kansas State to go 5-0 in Big 12
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JEROME SOLOMON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
AUSTIN _ Basketball games often are won with big plays down the
stretch, and usually those plays come on the offensive end of the
floor.
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case Saturday for Texas and Kansas State.
</P>
<P>
   Muoneke
</P>
<P>
   Texas went the last seven minutes, 33 seconds without making a
shot from the floor, while Kansas State failed to hit a field goal
over the last 6:22.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns made enough free throws to hold off the Wildcats
and send the season's largest home crowd away happy with a 65-59
Big 12 Conference win before 10,172 at the Frank Erwin Center.
</P>
<P>
   UT is 9-8 overall and 5-0 in conference, but the Longhorns' five
Big 12 opponents thus far have a combined league record of 6-17;
their next three (Kansas, Oklahoma State and Oklahoma) are 11-1.
</P>
<P>
   Forward Gabe Muoneke led Texas with 20 points in just 29 minutes
as a result of foul trouble and a hyperextended left elbow that
forced him to leave the game with 2{ minutes left.
</P>
<P>
   X-rays on the elbow showed no fracture, but Muoneke, the
Longhorns' leading scorer, is listed as questionable for UT's
showdown with Kansas in Lawrence on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be a lot to overcome because Gabe is such a big part of
this team,'' point guard Ivan Wagner said. ``Because we have so few
people, we've been having to deal with adversity all season long,
(so) we're prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   After beginning the second half 5-of-11 from the foul line, the
Longhorns hit four consecutive free throws in the last 30 seconds
for the final points of the game.
</P>
<P>
   K-State (12-6, 1-4) had closed to within 61-59 on two free
throws by Shawn Rhodes on a questionable over-the-back foul call on
a Chris Mihm rebound.
</P>
<P>
   But William Clay drained two free throws with 30 seconds to go
and Kris Clack, who was slowed by flu symptoms, grabbed a rebound
off a missed 3-pointer and dropped in a pair with 23 seconds left
to give Texas the win.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-foot Mihm had his fourth double-double in the last six
games, with 13 points and a game-high 11 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of offense in the final minutes was the capper to an
unusual game in which Texas had an early 15-0 run and held a
20-point lead (34-14) with 5:35 left in the first half, only to see
K-State respond with an 18-1 spurt to pull within 35-32 at
halftime.
</P>
<P>
   By the game's end, the Longhorns staved off a solid effort from
the Wildcats, who have now dropped 17 of their 18 road games in the
Big 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could bottle that first 11 minutes,'' Texas coach
Rick Barnes said. ``We were really good the first 11 minutes. They
couldn't get the ball into the paint area, and we were really doing
some good things there. But they're too good a team (for that to
have continued). They do some real nice things on the offensive
end, and they execute probably as well as any team we've played.''
</P>
<P>
   The early run was so promising that at one point Barnes turned
to his assistant coaches on the bench and asked, ``Are we this
good?''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the early run, the Longhorns won their second
consecutive game while being outshot from the floor, after going
0-6 in such games earlier in the season.
</P>
<P>
   Texas made 21 of 59 shots from the field (35.6 percent) and
17-of-29 (58.6 percent) from the foul line, but forced 25 turnovers
and held the Wildcats to a 37.3 percent shooting effort (19-of-51).
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't turn it over 25 times and shoot 37 percent and win
on the road,'' Kansas State coach Tom Asbury said.
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns forced four of those turnovers and got a pair of
blocked shots by Mihm during a 2:24 span midway through the first
half and it added up to 15 straight points.
</P>
<P>
   After Clay hit a 3-pointer, Wagner, who had five steals, fed
Muoneke for a three-point play.
</P>
<P>
   Clack, who has 17 steals in Texas' last four games, swiped the
ball from the Wildcats' Josh Reid and fed Mihm a nice bounce pass
for a layup.
</P>
<P>
   A Mihm block on one end was finished by a Wagner trey, followed
by a Clack steal and dunk.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Carter closed the run, putting Texas ahead 28-11 with a
bucket in the paint after the Wildcats' Josh Kimm turned the ball
over on a double dribble.
</P>
<P>
   But K-State outscored UT 18-1 over the last 8:44 of the half.
</P>
<P>
   Reid had nine of his team-high 18 points in that stretch,
including two 3-pointers, and Cortez Groves closed it with a steal
from Wagner and a spinning layup as time expired.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you fall down like that, you know you have to step it
up,'' Reid said. ``The last time we came here we fell down and got
blown out by 40 points (104-63 on Jan. 12, 1997), and we weren't
going to let that happen again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
