<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6577 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-SALTLAKE-HNS &LR;      01-17 1048
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SALT </SLUG>
 LAKE-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's all downhill for Salt Lake as illicit tactics come to light
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Just a few years ago, locals fretted mostly over the potential for
polygamy jokes and complaints about 3.2 beer.
</P>
<P>
   In Salt Lake City, those may be remembered as the good old days
of an increasingly troubling Olympic experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said the Olympics would bring the kind of publicity money
can't buy,'' Stephen Pace, an outspoken Olympics critic and the
head of Utahans for Responsible Spending, told reporters last week
</P>
<P>
   ``They were right about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Since November, the once idyllic notion of hosting the world has
been tarnished by stories of vote buying, under-the-table payments,
cozy scholarship, job and internship deals _ even rumors of illicit
sex.
</P>
<P>
   So what happened to turn a relatively out-of-the-way city _ one
culturally and politically dominated by the Church of Jesus Christ
of Latter Day Saints (The Mormons) _ into an Olympic Sodom and
Gomorrah?
</P>
<P>
   Frustration, in part. Greed, almost certainly. And to a large
extent, perhaps, the seductive nature of doing business behind
closed doors, without public knowledge or consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This culture of corruption has taken root,'' Utah Governor
Mike Leavitt said, ``because of a lack of accountability.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtually from the time the Utah capital was awarded the 2002
Games back in 1995, the Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC) came
under fire for its secretive ways. City and state officials who
inquired about finances and budget concerns routinely were given a
standard response.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust us.''
</P>
<P>
   That modus operandi began to come into greater question in the
summer of 1997, when then-Chief Executive Officer Tom Welch was
forced to resign in the wake of charges of spouse abuse, casting
the Utah Olympic operation in a bad light nationally for the first
time. (Welch and wife Alma since have divorced.)
</P>
<P>
   SLOC's response to greater scrutiny? To dig in even deeper,
imposing a media gag order on employees, who were required to refer
even the most innocuous of questions to designated spokesmen.
</P>
<P>
   Still, even amid growing concerns over budget shortfalls and
possible taxpayer exposure, Welch's successor, Frank Joklik, and
the committee were able to conduct business pretty much as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Until a few months ago, at least.
</P>
<P>
   The trouble began in late November when a local television
reporter obtained a letter written by SLOC second-in-command Dave
Johnson to Sonia Essomba, daughter of an IOC member from Cameroon.
The correspondence indicated that a $10,000 tuition payment would
be the last of its kind.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, SLOC was forced to acknowledge a scholarship program
that had distributed more than $400,000 to 13 individuals, six of
them with IOC connections.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations _ and the staggering behind-the-curtain price of
doing Olympic business _ began to snowball.
</P>
<P>
   Among other embarrassing disclosures: Some $70,000 in cash was
paid to various IOC delegates, including $50,000 to Jean-Claude
Ganga of the Republic of Congo, who also allegedly received free
medical treatment and reportedly profited an additional $60,000
from a friendly real estate deal.
</P>
<P>
   Free medical services were arranged for other visitors with
Olympic ties. Another IOC delegate, Sergio Santander Fantini, is
said to have snared a $10,000 ``campaign contribution'' in his bid
for mayor of Santiago, Chile. Jobs and internships were provided
others with IOC ties, mostly by private companies, one by the city.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the revelations, Joklik and Johnson resigned last
week, while Welch was stripped of his $10,000 a month consulting
job and a $500,000 pension. Meanwhile, Salt Lake City Mayor Deedee
Corradini, who played a high-profile role in landing the Games, has
announced she would not seek a third term.
</P>
<P>
   The worst, however, may be yet to come as the United States
Justice Department looks into the possibility of tax evasion and
fraud charges, with a grand jury scheduled to convene as early as
this week.
</P>
<P>
   While Utahans bemoan the controversy that is sure to tarnish
their Olympic dream, some historical perspective may help explain a
process gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Salt Lake City was awarded the Games in 1995, the
quest was nearly 30 years old, with no shortage of setbacks and
disappointments.
</P>
<P>
   In January of 1966, the city was chosen as the U.S. candidate
for the 1972 Games, which eventually went to Sapporo, Japan. After
Denver won the 1976 bidding, only to bail out, Salt Lake again was
presented as an alternative, losing this time to Innsbruck,
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-1985, Salt Lake City competed against Anchorage, Alaska,
Reno, Nev., and Lake Placid, N.Y., for the U.S. spot in the running
for the 1992 and '94 Games. Anchorage was chosen for both years,
but lost out to Albertville, France, and Lillehammer, Norway,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Enough? Hardly. By June of 1989, Salt Lake was pounding the
Olympic bricks once more, again earning the USOC's backing in the
international field. This time, the Games were awarded to Nagano,
Japan, by a vote of 46 to 42.
</P>
<P>
   After those five failures, Salt Lake City was named in January
1995 as one of four finalists for the 2002 Games, joining Quebec,
Canada, Sion, Switzerland, and Ostersund, Sweden. In the following
three months, 54 IOC delegates visited Utah as part of the final
push.
</P>
<P>
   In what now appears more than a little ironic, the U.S. entry
received a record 54 votes, 40 more than runners-up Sion and
Ostersund in the most lopsided outcome ever.
</P>
<P>
   Some might suggest that the Salt Lake bidders came to realize
that a clean, relatively safe community with nearby mountains, a
history of good snow and a modern, world-class airport wasn't
enough to get the job done. An internal investigation conducted by
the USOC, in fact, has revealed concerns about elaborate
hospitality and gift-giving dating back to a 1989 visit by a USOC
site selection team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bidding for the Games uncovers every wart a city has,'' Tom
Welch said in a January 1997 interview with the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   To their chagrin, Utahans only now are being allowed to peek
behind the curtains and see them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
