<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6578 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLY-IMAGE-HNS &LR;      01-17 2176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-IMAGE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tarnished image of Olympics may threaten financial stability
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It began with a report on a Salt Lake City television station.
On the other side of the world, an 80-year-old Swiss fanned the
flames, giving full voice to what previously had been mostly
whispers and innuendo.
</P>
<P>
   Soon enough, the fires were burning out of control back in Salt
Lake and points in between.
</P>
<P>
   As increasingly tawdry tales of sex, lies and ethically
questionable cash payments and sweetheart deals threatened to
engulf the Olympic movement, Michael Payne rushed off to make
another stop _ and an ironic one at that.
</P>
<P>
   Payne was headed to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   As the International Olympic Committee's chief marketing
officer, Payne was hoping to put out a few blazes in particular _
most notably in the corporate offices of Coca-Cola, an Olympic
sponsor since 1928 and currently on board through 2008. The
following day, he was scheduled to address the concerns of
officials from United Parcel Service and Home Depot, other clients
beginning to harbor second thoughts about being identified with the
budding five-ring circus.
</P>
<P>
   In a city openly scorned by IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch
just 2{ years earlier, the image of an IOC official returning, hat
in hand, said much about an organization in sudden and violent
turmoil. So smug and superior in the summer of '96, the Lords of
the Rings were back in Georgia with considerably less
self-satisfied expressions, hoping to kiss, make up and keep the
checks coming.
</P>
<P>
   The cash cow that the world's most famous sporting event has
become wasn't on its deathbed by any means, but vital signs were
beginning to deteriorate. Already, the potential financial fallout
from the Olympic bribery scandal is almost unsettling to the powers
that be as any tales of illicit payments and dirty deeds _ perhaps
even more.
</P>
<P>
   Consider:
</P>
<P>
   Texaco-Caltex, the American oil company, ended 12 months of
negotiations by taking a pass on a $6.3 million sponsorship
arrangement for the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia,
citing a downturn in the industry as the determining factor.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, Salt Lake Organizing Committee (SLOC) officials were
fielding inquiries from anxious partners beginning to question the
wisdom of their investments.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, David D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock Mutual
Life Insurance Company _ a worldwide Olympic corporate sponsor _
was asking the IOC to extend its investigation beyond Salt Lake,
suggesting that anything less would mean ``the rings won't be
tarnished, they'll be broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is in the midst of a $40 million commitment through
the 2000 Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. West, the telephone carrier, delayed a $5 million payment
to the Salt Lake City effort in the wake of the scandal before
finally handing over the check Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Even before news of the trouble began to spread, organizing
committees for Sydney and Salt Lake were struggling to meet
obligations. Of Salt Lake's $1.45 billion budget, $859 million is
supposed to come from corporate sources, with about $250 million of
that yet to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   For now, finding new money may take a back seat to keeping
current clients in line, as Payne's dash to Georgia suggests.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Games are going to be based on the support of our
sponsors,'' John Krimsky, Deputy Secretary General of the United
States Olympic Committee, said. ``It's a very fragile relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their brand, their product, their service is tied closely to
what they put their name on.''
</P>
<P>
   All this, of course, is an easier sell when the tie is to Tara
Lipinski's golden night in Nagano or Picabo Street blasting down a
Japanese hill or Michael Johnson grabbing history-making double
gold in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   When the connection is with IOC delegates conducting global
shakedown tours of overeager bid committee officials, corporate
checkbooks may close in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, this has become cause for alarm as citizens begin to
assess damage that could extend far beyond a tarnished image.
</P>
<P>
   Already, taxpayers are out $59 million to build the already
completed bobsled and luge run, plus support facilities, near Park
City. SLOC also is expected to provide an additional $40 million to
maintain and operate the facilities after the Games have come and
gone.
</P>
<P>
   That's $99 million already on the line, with the Games still
more than three years away. Should SLOC fail to make budget, the
city and state could be liable for that and any additional debts
incurred _ a particularly bitter pill in light of the organizing
committee's penchant for conducting business in secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are already facing tough times with a growing city,'' said
Salt Lake City council member Deeda Seed, a longtime SLOC critic.
``(Now) we've heard that it may be more difficult in terms of
revenues. We need to have some serious discussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one thing, the city shouldn't have to pay for corruption.
It takes two to corrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let the IOC pay.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat of lingering bills has some Utah legislators mulling
a referendum on whether the Games should be held at all. A recent
poll showed that 70 percent of the state's residents still wanted
to see the Olympics go on as planned, but that was taken before
revelations that the public may eventually face a major tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, a Utah Olympic push that dates back to the mid-1960s
has gone badly awry long before the flame residents actually had
bargained for is scheduled to be lit. While the IOC has set a Jan.
24 date for releasing the results of an already completed internal
investigation that has resulted in 13 members being asked to
explain their actions, USOC and Salt Lake officials are hoping to
straighten things out by the end of February.
</P>
<P>
   That may be optimistic. In addition to its own national
governing body, SLOC is being investigated by its own ethics board,
the IOC and _ perhaps even more ominously _ the United States
Department of Justice, which is looking into possible fraud and tax
evasion. A grand jury could begin hearing evidence as early as this
week.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of it all, the USOC has been conducting its own
internal inquiry of potentially questionable SLOC ties. Last
Thursday, Alfredo LaMont _ in charge of international relations for
the USOC _ resigned because of an ``undisclosed business
relationship'' with former SLOC president and one-time bid
committee head Tom Welch.
</P>
<P>
   Legal bills alone surely will add to SLOC's mounting financial
woes. And the bad news and unflattering headlines aren't likely to
end soon as Utah residents already in shock wait for the other shoe
to drop.
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Few Olympic veterans have been shocked by the revelation that
IOC members were not always averse to requesting impromptu palm
readings. Rumors of elaborate gifts and under-the-table payments
have been part of the scene for years.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Lewis, for one, was particularly blunt in his reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone believes this is the first time this has
happened,'' the nine-time gold-medal winner and former UH star said
last week. ``I don't know of any organization that has more power
or makes more money that is less regulated in the entire world than
the IOC.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis dismisses suggestions that the IOC can be trusted to clean
up its own mess.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IOC is investigating itself,'' he said. ``So, like
everybody else, we are all a little skeptical.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk of improprieties has only increased with the growth of the
Games. The budget for Sydney now is expected to top $3.54 billion _
an enormous figure to track and account for by just about anyone's
standards.
</P>
<P>
   How much scandal will cut into that pie remains to be seen,
though the degree of exposure seems particularly great in an
industry where image and integrity make up much of the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The timing couldn't be much worse. For the most part, the Games
have been in a financial upswing since the success of the 1984
Summer Olympics in Los Angles, but even before the recent
revelations, there were signs of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Television ratings for the 1998 Nagano Games were down from four
years earlier in Lillehammer, due in part to the 14-hour (Houston
to Nagano) time difference that all but eliminated live coverage.
Failing to make the projections on which advertising rates were
based, CBS eventually had to provide compensatory spots for
sponsors on subsequent broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney, next on the Olympic agenda, will present many of the
same logistical problems for NBC, which has contracted to televise
the Olympics through 2008. A further complication for TV: The
Sydney Games will be held Sept. 15-Oct. 1, 2000 (Spring in
Australia), making for greater competition from college and
professional football in the United States on weekends and from the
start of the fall TV season on rival networks.
</P>
<P>
   As such, the 2000 Games have potential to continue the ratings
slump that began in Nagano, which could further frighten sponsors
and cut into future rights fees. The Salt Lake Games are more
time-slot friendly to American television, of course, but SLOC's
current difficulties have created a different sort of negative.
</P>
<P>
   Can credibility be restored?
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics, such as Lewis, liken having Samaranch oversee the
housecleaning to putting the fox in charge of safeguarding the hen
house. Others note that the speed with which the IOC wrapped up its
internal investigation and identified the culprits hints strongly
that the organization knew who the crooks were all along and
preferred to turn the other way until forced to do otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   Even if some kind of order can be restored in Utah, it's likely
that brushfires will pop up elsewhere in the months to come.
</P>
<P>
   Some, in fact, already have.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Toronto Sun quoted a senior member of the city's
failed 1996 Olympic bid describing a variety of scams by IOC
members.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective visitors would request two first-class, round-trip
plane tickets (as IOC rules dictated at the time), then either cash
the tickets and not make the trip at all or convert them to economy
class and keep the difference.
</P>
<P>
   During a period when Toronto, Atlanta and Salt Lake City all
were mounting Olympic bids, some IOC members requested first-class,
round-trip tickets to each city, then would cash two sets of
tickets and take connecting flights within North America, again
pocketing the difference.
</P>
<P>
   Those incidents, according to the Sun, were documented by the
Toronto bid team and presented to the IOC _ which evidently took no
action.
</P>
<P>
   On the heels of that story, a senior member of Sydney's bid team
hinted at other dirty dealings, saying he had been approached by
one IOC delegate and an intermediary soliciting bribes in the midst
of the ultimately successful Australian effort.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, investigators into allegations of wrongdoing related
to Nagano's successful bid for the '98 Winter Games may find only a
trail of ashes.
</P>
<P>
   According to one bid committee report, about $18 million was
spent on Nagano's efforts to land the Games, more than half of it
going into ``public relations efforts.'' A senior official from
that bid committee said last week, however, that a 90-volume
accounting book detailing transactions was burned in 1992 because
it contained ``secret information.''
</P>
<P>
   &QC;
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Michael Payne did his best to put a positive spin on
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has allowed us to address unequivocally some of the
rumors that have been around for some time and be able to weed out
any unacceptable and unethical behavior,'' the IOC money man told
reporters after meeting with executives at Coca-Cola and UPS and
speaking by phone with Home Depot officers.
</P>
<P>
   Reaction, evidently, was mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident they will do what they said they would do -
take swift and decisive action,'' Coca-Cola spokesman Ben Deutsch
said.
</P>
<P>
   UPS, however, declined to commit beyond Sydney, saying a
decision would be made later this year, though the company
expressed a willingness to keep an open mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, I think it's going to come out better,'' spokeswoman
Susan Rosenberg said. ``It has forced everybody to go back in and
do some analysis and close scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``For better or worse, it may be held up to higher standards,
and now they are going to enforce and clarify what those standards
are.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, a McDonald's representative said late last week that
the global fast-food giant had no plans to curtail its involvement
with the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, these are very different times for the Lords of the
Rings, who suddenly find themselves dragged out from under the
table, their activities exposed to the harsh light of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the sponsors and public opinion are waiting for the
reaction of the IOC, how we can clean our house,'' Samaranch said.
``The reaction will be on the 24th.''
</P>
<P>
   The repercussions, most likely, will last far beyond.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
