<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 01:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6580 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      01-17 1415
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets' free-agent pursuit depends on crucial signing
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; PriceBy JONATHAN FEIGEN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
Saturday, Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich and his staff handed out
tickets to the season's first preseason game, next Saturday night.
Now he and Rockets officials have less than a week to make sure
they will not have to play in it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets claim just three healthy players and three draft
picks, and their pursuit of free agents that would allow them to
play full-court basketball against the Spurs is on hold until the
NBA's new collective-bargaining agreement is sealed, likely
Tuesday. That would allow the Rockets to bring in, they hope, Suns
free agent Antonio McDyess or Bulls free agent Scottie Pippen and
then let the chain reaction begin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get excited about all the names and having them a part of
the team,'' said Brent Price, one of the three healthy Rockets
under contract. ``If you're talking Pippen vs. McDyess, they're
different players that bring different qualities to the team.
Pippen offensively and defensively can do it all. He's got
experience. He knows what it takes to win a championship. And
McDyess as far as talent goes, there's explosion, shot-blocking and
scoring ability. And to put him side by side with Hakeem (Olajuwon)
is a very exciting possibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always exciting when there's free agents moving. It's
exciting to me to see who I'm playing with and exactly who's going
to be on the court. It's going to be chaotic at first. But things
will settle down and we'll get back to real competition out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, the competition is to get the players to put on the
court. McDyess' agent, Tony Dutt, said McDyess remains undecided.
Pippen has made it clear he would like to play for the Rockets. But
he might receive contract offers larger than the Rockets could put
together, if the Bulls can reach a deal to sign him and then trade
him to a team that could pay more than the roughly $9 million of
cap space the Rockets have available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rockets have always shown the desire to win a
championship,'' Rockets free agent Eddie Johnson said. ``They won
two when (Michael) Jordan was out and they've always shown desire
to put a team on the floor that can win the championship. I like
that, especially as an older player. Free agents like that also.''
</P>
<P>
   Until one of the two targeted free agents signs somewhere,
everything is on hold. But if Pippen or McDyess ends up playing for
the Rockets, the rest of this season's roster likely will come from
the rookies and last season's roster.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say for sure, but it sure looks like it,'' Tomjanovich
said. ``But you could get a free agent for those minimums.''
</P>
<P>
   While Rockets management awaits answers, here's a look at the
players waiting to cut deals.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley _ Asked this week where he would play this
season, Barkley did not hesitate to divulge his plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palm Springs,'' he said. But beyond the Pro-Am of the Bob Hope
Desert Classic remains uncertain. Even when Barkley will confirm
plans beyond this week's golf game with a former player named
Jordan is unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley has made it clear he would like to return to the Rockets
_ under the right conditions. The contract is not one of the
conditions, giving the Rockets room to sign McDyess or Pippen and
still bring back Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley, 35, has said he would play for the minimum, for a team
that could chase a championship, and with Pippen or McDyess the
Rockets would qualify. Without one of the free-agent stars, Barkley
likely would consider Seattle a more viable contender, and he still
could consider New York and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't made a decision,'' Barkley said. ``I want to sit
down and talk to the six teams (that have shown interest in him).
I'm going to sit back and be patient. I'm not in a hurry. I'll make
my decision when everybody (decides).''
</P>
<P>
   Othella Harrington _ Harrington has made it clear he would like
to remain in Houston, even if it means competing in a frontcourt
crowded with McDyess and Barkley for playing time. But Harrington
likely will draw interest that could pay at least as much and
possibly offer more of what he truly seeks _ playing time.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington has said he is ready to compete for playing time, but
might have to choose between the Rockets' potentially crowded
frontcourt and a clearer shot at an increased role.
</P>
<P>
   He will have at least some time to play the field and get a
clearer idea of where he fits. Harrington likely would fit in the
Rockets' plans as a salary-cap exception, and as such sign after
the Rockets have filled the $30 million of cap money. But time will
move far faster when contracts may be signed than in the wait since
the lockout ended.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Maloney _ The Rockets would like to have Maloney back and
he could return. But the backcourt would be crowded with point
guards, with Price and rookie Bryce Drew in place.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Cuttino Mobley, a natural shooting guard, might be ready
to help at the position, especially defensively. And if the Rockets
sign Pippen, Mobley would have help running the offense if he is
needed in spot duty at the point, making the position deep.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the Rockets, the Magic and Bucks have shown the most
interest in Maloney. But Maloney has started the past two seasons
for the Rockets, and the Rockets will try to bring him back,
especially once the other pieces are in place.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, Matt would like to stay,'' said Maloney's agent,
Keith Glass. ``We have to check everything out we can. There is
some interest in Matt. The Rockets are certainly interested. I know
they're involved in some other things. I'm thrilled with interest
in Matt. We didn't know how it would be, but I'm absolutely
thrilled. We would like to stay in Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Bullard _ The Pistons and Magic are interested, but Bullard
wants to be back in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the luxury of being a free agent, you can field other
offers,'' Bullard said. ``But the best situation for me is here.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bullard's agent, Herb Rudoy: ``His instruction to me is to
try to get it worked out. He loves being there, loves Rudy and
wants to stay. (Rockets vice president Carroll Dawson) and I are
going to talk about it. Whatever they want, we're going to be
cooperative.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockets want his shot, especially in the frontcourt. With
Pippen, Bullard likely would find more open shots. With McDyess, he
would help prevent teams from helping too much on McDyess and
Olajuwon inside.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Johnson _ The phone in Johnson's agent's office has not
been ringing off the hook. But Johnson does not seem to mind. He
said he wants to be back in Houston and the Rockets have indicated
they want him back.
</P>
<P>
   As a 10-year veteran, he would receive the $1 million minimum,
but under the new league agreement would cost $500,000 of cap
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get to 39, you're not surprised when teams are not
calling, age is such a taboo in sports,'' Johnson said. ``Teams
recognize I've been able to overcome that age tag. I still have the
ability to make a difference. There is some interest, of course,
but my goal all along has been to come back to Houston.''
</P>
<P>
   Mario Elie _ The Rockets have spoken to Elie's agent and Elie
would come back for the right offer. But he will not wait for the
Rockets to work through their other free-agent issues. If a team
offers what he wants most _ a chance at another championship and a
multiyear contract _ he said he would jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a preference,'' Elie said. ``I just want the best
situation whether it is here or elsewhere. I'm happy. The phone has
been ringing. I still want to win. I want to finish my career on a
winning note.''
</P>
<P>
   That probably will not be in Houston. Elie said that at least
eight teams have shown interest. San Antonio could be the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Stephens _ Regardless of which ``impact'' free agent the
Rockets bring in, they likely will make some changes in the offense
to create more movement and penetration. But they will not change
enough for Stephens to fit as easily as other free agents from last
season's roster, or that might come in at the minimum. An
outstanding one-on-one talent, Stephens could get a shot from a
more one-on-one oriented team.
</P>
<P>
   Emanual Davis, Serge Zwikker _ Davis and Zwikker will spend the
season in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Drexler _ Whereabouts unknown.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
