<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LIFELESS IN DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Looking ahead to the upcoming All-Star
break, the Kings set a goal of winning their last few games before
the hiatus, all at home, to position themselves for a strong run to
a playoff berth in the season's final two-plus months.
</P>
<P>
   Well, it sounded like a good idea, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Jaromir Jagr and the Pittsburgh Penguins took full
advantage of a flat Kings team Saturday night, recording a 5-1
victory before a crowd of 16,005 at the Forum. The score would have
been worse for the Kings, but two near-goals by the Penguins were
disallowed by the video goal judge.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings rewarded their fourth sellout crowd with one of their
most lifeless performances of the season, strange considering
they'd played only once in the previous four nights and the
Penguins had played the night before, losing in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   But Kings coach Larry Robinson had been wary of the Penguins
precisely because they had lost the night before, and he told his
players exactly that at the end of Saturday morning's practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `We've got to be ready for tonight, this team is
going to come and come hard,''' defenseman Mattias Norstrom said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kings _ playing without defenseman Steve Duchesne,
sidelined with back spasms and listed as day to day _ failed to
heed Robinson's warning.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings (16-23-4) were a collective no-show against the
Penguins (20-12-7), who have spent this season seemingly oblivious
to the potential distraction of seeing their franchise sink into
bankruptcy. The Penguins, who lost to the Kings in Pittsburgh by a
3-0 margin in December, won this game largely on the strength of
special teams, scoring two power-play goals and a shorthanded goal.
</P>
<P>
   The shorthanded score, by Ian Moran, was one Kings goalie Jamie
Storr would have liked to have had back, and it was the goal that
gave the Penguins a 1-0 lead 10:39 into the game. Moran beat Storr
between the pads with a seemingly harmless 40-foot slap shot from
the right boards.
</P>
<P>
   Just 51 seconds later, Jagr skated around Donald Audette at the
blue line, then stickhandled past Rob Blake and flipped the puck
past Storr, giving the Penguins two goals on their first three
shots of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Things only got worse in the second period, after Blake was sent
off for a high-sticking penalty at 6:36. The Penguins capitalized
on the subsequent power play, with Alexei Kovalev carrying the puck
from the right point to behind the Kings' net, then centering to
former King Robert Lang for an easy one-timer that was his 18th
goal this season.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Penguins were content to protect their lead,
and the Kings were extremely cooperative, failing to muster a shot
in the second period until a 60-footer by Yanic Perreault at the
9:27 mark. In fact, the Kings managed only six shots at Penguins
goalie Tom Barrasso in the game's first 32 minutes, and the teams
combined for only 35 shots on goal in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings gained a minimal amount of life with 5:11 left in the
second period when Garry Galley scored his first goal this season,
a slap shot from the top of the right faceoff circle with the Kings
on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   But 2:19 later, the Kings got caught deep in the attacking zone,
allowing a 2-on-1 rush to the Penguins. Dan Kesa, covered by Doug
Bodger, passed across to Jan Hrdina, who was unchecked by Sean
O'Donnell. Hrdina redirected Kesa's pass into a wide-open net,
blunting the Kings' comeback hopes.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins had blown third-period leads and suffered defeats
in their previous two games, ending their 47-0-6 streak when
leading after two periods under coach Kevin Constantine. But there
would be no collapse on this night, with Kevin Hatcher padding
Pittsburgh's margin with a power-play goal early in the third
period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0145EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6585 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN     01-17 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON SLUGGISH IN VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson is oh-so-lucky that power is the last
thing to go.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Botha, a relatively obscure fighter from South Africa,
was poised to do the impossible Saturday at the MGM Grand. For
four-plus rounds, he had Tyson where he wanted him: frustrated,
confused and behind on the score cards.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if the boxing gods weren't quite ready to say
goodbye to Iron Mike, the former two-time champion fired a straight
right into the willing chin of a brave opponent with seconds left
in the fifth round and that was that.
</P>
<P>
   Botha was able to stagger to his feet but it was too late: He'd
been counted out by referee Richard Steele one second before the
end of the round.
</P>
<P>
   Instantly, Botha's opportunity to make history and the prospect
of a fascinating final seven rounds had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The punch was vintage Tyson (46-3, with 40 knockouts). He had
his entire 223 pounds behind it and Botha (39-1, 24 KOs) obliged by
meeting it while moving forward _ an unpleasant combination for the
person on the receiving end.
</P>
<P>
   The near-full house of roughly 12,519, who paid to see either
such or Tyson snap as he did when he bit Evander Holyfield's ears
in his last fight 19 months ago, loved it. They cheered wildly when
it happened and oohed and aahed every time the replay was shown on
the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   However, that's about all they had to cheer about in regard to
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   He was admittedly rusty as the result of the layoff, but his
skills may have also eroded dramatically. That, and Botha's
strategy, had those at the MGM thinking the unthinkable for a good
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson cited the layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous amount of rust,'' he said. ``I told my trainer,
`Don't worry, I'll catch him late, I'll catch him late.'
(Cornerman) Stacey (McKinley) and those guys got a little excited,
but I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opening bell, Tyson did the things he supposedly learned
from new trainer Tommy Brooks: He jabbed and moved his head as he
had early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted all of a half round as Botha, who weighed a pudgy
233 pounds, began to frustrate the 7-1 favorite with a shockingly
effective game plan. Simply, he kept his distance from Tyson's
bombs and held him when danger seemed to be approaching. At the
same time, he repeatedly found the opportunity to throw effective
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, who became a stationary target and threw single punches
ala the two Holyfield fights, was so frustrated he locked Botha's
left arm under his own at the end of the round and wouldn't let go.
Steele attempted to separate the two but couldn't get it done,
which set off a brief melee in the ring that for a moment had
everyone thinking the same thing: Tyson didn't lose it again, did
he?
</P>
<P>
   He lost a point in the second round when he hit Botha in the
face with a forearm after the bell. But, beyond that, he behaved.
</P>
<P>
   He was losing the fight, though.
</P>
<P>
   Botha baffled Tyson with his tactics throughout and seemed to
gain confidence with every round. He talked to Tyson in an attempt
to unnerve him whenever the two clinched, he smiled repeatedly and
even taunted the once-awesome champion late in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Botha appeared to gain even more ill-advised
bravado. He engaged Tyson in two brief toe-to-toe exchanges early
in the round and survived.
</P>
<P>
   And then his luck ran out. Tyson was bound to land a big shot
and finally he did late in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Botha fell to his side. He attempted to rise but fell on his
face. He tried it again with the same result before finally finding
his way to his feet. At that moment, Steele waved him off and he
staggered backward into the ropes _ clearly unable to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was winning,'' Botha said. ``Oh, what a fighter (Tyson). Oh
my, what a dummy (himself). I was going to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson touched off another little incident when he rushed toward
Botha. It seemed clear that he had good intentions, though: He
wanted to hold up his beaten opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, Tyson showed unusual class. He hugged
Botha warmly and congratulated him on a good effort _ an effort
that was better than his in all but one way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tyson seemed to have neither the fury one might expect
after waiting so long to begin his second comeback nor the skills
his fans somehow still expect from him. He looked powerful but
otherwise ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to have him fight again in April and again a few
months later _ against, possibly, Axel Schulz and Vaughn Bean _ and
then face Holyfield for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   If this Tyson shows up to face his nemesis, have pity on him: He
likely will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to fight, I need to put on better shows,'' Tyson said.
``I'm not looking to jump into the mix real quick. I need to do one
step at a time, go back to the gym and start working right away.''
</P>
<P>
   In other bouts, Goyo Vargas (39-6-1, 28 KOs) survived a 12-round
knockdown to outpoint Ben Tackie (18-1, 11 KOs) in a 12-round
lightweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   Zab Judah (19-0, 14 KOs) stopped Wilfredo Negron (17-4, 14 KOs)
at 1:44 of the fourth round of a scheduled 12-round junior
welterweight fight.
</P>
<P>
   Judah will next fight Vince Phillips for the title.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Whitaker (18-0, 16 KOs) defeated Alex Stewart (43-9, 40
KOs) when the scheduled 10-round heavyweight fight was stopped
because of a cut under Stewart's right eye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
