<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PUNCH LIFTS TYSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS---With one thundering right hand taken out of mothball
from the late 1980s, Mike Tyson stormed dramatically back into the
fistic limelight Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   It landed flush on the jaw of Francois Botha, who was counted
out at 2:59 of the fifth by referee Dick Steele, as Botha
floundered haplessly on the mat.
</P>
<P>
   But for a frenzied time in this brief but interesting match at
the MGM Grand Garden, it seemed as though Mike Tyson once again had
come unraveled and would face the prospect of yet another shameful
disqualification.
</P>
<P>
   There he after the first round had ended throwing wild punches
at Botha, who was throwing wild punches right back at Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   It was a riotous scene, as the referee, Dick Steele, was unable
to halt the hostilities and as both fighters' cornermen rushed in
to separate the enraged combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the two men were escorted back to their corners, as
phalanx of armed Las Vegas police stood around the ring to make
sure law and order would prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Between rounds, the chairman of the Nevada State Athletic
commission, Mark Ratner, got into the ring and spoke to Steele.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to make sure everything was under control,''
said Ratner later.
</P>
<P>
   It was, although Steele would deduct a point from Tyson in the
second round for throwing an illegal punch (his elbow, a familiar
Tyson tactic).
</P>
<P>
   After that, things settled down and, incredibly, Francois Botha,
a 30-year-old, 6-2, 233-pounder from South Africa, was the fellow
doing all the trashing talking, as well as a lot of the heavy
punching.
</P>
<P>
   This was no waltz for Tyson, who up until his climatic punch
showed the rust of his 18-month suspension from the Evander
Holyfield folly.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, weighing a hefty 223, was slow and sluggish against his
similarly slow-motion opponent, who fought smartly, tying up Tyson
inside and keeping him off balance with left jabs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just took me a little time to get going,'' said Tyson.
``But I knew I'd get him. Everyone was worried, but I wasn't. I'm a
warrior. I knew I'd get him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I say?'' said Botha. ``Tyson just caught me. I got
careless.''
</P>
<P>
   Up until that moment when Tyson caught Botha with the kind of
terrifying, wicked punch that left people like Michael Spinks and
Trevor Berbick and Larry Holmes and many others unconscious back in
the 1980s when Tyson was earning his fearsome reputation, Botha was
performing exceptionally.
</P>
<P>
   He clipped Tyson several times with a straight right hands, and
kept avoiding Tyson's lunging left hooks and right hands.
</P>
<P>
   I actually had Botha ahead by a point when the end came and when
the crowd erupted with loud cheers, the loudest being from Shelly
Finkel, Dan Goossen and all the other new members of Team Tyson who
would have lost a ton of future profits had Tyson been upset.
</P>
<P>
   Botha actually taunted Tyson throughout the fight, constantly
talking to him and even mocking him with theatrical facial
expressions.
</P>
<P>
   Contrary to most pre-fight analysis, Botha wasn't a bum.
</P>
<P>
   He wasn't scared one bit of Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Tyson wasn't scared of him, either, but for almost
five minutes he certainly didn't faintly resemble the fighter who
once was so intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, for a time, it seemed as though the impossible might
happen.
</P>
<P>
   But Mike Tyson still can hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't see the punch coming,'' said Botha. ``I've never
been hit that hard before.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just caught him good,'' said Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   He did.
</P>
<P>
   Still, until that moment, he was quite ordinary against an
ordinary fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Tyson still has a lot of prove if he's to become the
heavyweight champion again.
</P>
<P>
   He won't have the luxury of fighting a Francois Botha if he
wants to reach such a goal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
