<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS FALL INTO DEEPER HOLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Pacific-10 season is barely one-third
completed, but USC appears finished.
</P>
<P>
   At least when you consider the lofty goals the Trojans
entertained as far back as, oh, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   USC's chances of making the NCAA Tournament seem about as good
as one of its guards making a 3-point shot these days.
</P>
<P>
   A dire assessment? Perhaps, but that's where USC finds itself
following a lethargic 89-75 loss to California before 5,112 at the
Sports Arena on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After just six conference games, the Trojans have a few
unflattering facts to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   _They were swept by the Bay Area schools on their homecourt.
</P>
<P>
   _They have lost three straight games and four of their past
five.
</P>
<P>
   _They are 1-3 at the Sports Arena in Pac-10 play.
</P>
<P>
   _The starting guards have shot 4 for 26 the past two games.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, USC coach Henry Bibby was asked how his weekend was
going.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not over yet, OK?'' Bibby said, alluding to the fact the
Trojans play 10th-ranked UCLA on Wednesday. ``We sure have to play
better than we did (against Cal) or it's going to be
embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (10-5, 2-4) are in the midst of what players deemed
a make-or-break three-game homestand, and are currently 0-2 after
double-digit losses to Stanford and Cal (11-4, 2-3).
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look good,'' Bibby said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe all our games are must-win,'' center Brian
Scalabrine added. ``We're two games below .500. It's kind of
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The culprits against Cal were two chronic problems the Trojans
have battled recently: poor outside shooting and porous inside
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Even armed with the information that Cal was without 7-foot
center Francisco Elson, who suffered a concussion Thursday night
against UCLA, USC couldn't handle the Bears under the basket.
</P>
<P>
   Cal forwards Carl Boyd and Michael Gill each had 17 points,
which was a career-high for Boyd. That's worse than it sounds,
because Boyd averages just 6.4 points per game while Gill averages
9.0.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't stop those guys,'' Bibby said. ``That's what hurt
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't respond to too much tonight. We didn't play any
defense. They scored any time they wanted to. They beat us on the
boards.''
</P>
<P>
   It was probably an ominous sign that Cal jumped out to a 7-0
lead, but the Trojans battled back and actually led 32-29 with 1:20
left in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Trojans went to sleep. Boyd stole a ball and drove for
a layup, forward Sean Lampley scored a layup and guard Thomas
Kilgore sank a jump shot at the buzzer to give the Bears a 35-32
halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the key to the game,'' Bibby said. ``Two
layups and a jump shot. That was a momentum swing.''
</P>
<P>
   USC was still in a slumber to start the second half, as the
Bears started with an 18-6 run that extended their lead to 53-38
with 14:21 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we should be coming out with more intensity,'' said
forward Greg Lakey, who had a career-high 17 points and eight
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   This loss was often uglier than Thursday's 72-55 loss to
Stanford, which at least is ranked fourth in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a lack of desire,'' Bibby said. ``We're
playing some pretty good teams. We're a young basketball team.
We're starting (first-year players) Brandon Granville, Sam Clancy
and Brian Scalabrine. We're playing against good, veteran teams.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have been hurt by the sudden disappearance of their
offense. They made three of 19 shots from 3-point range, and went 0
for 9 in the second half. Starting guards Granville and Elias Ayuso
were 2 for 14 from the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem like our wide-open jumpers are falling,''
Scalabrine said. ``I just know it's a lot harder to get a wide-open
look than it was five games ago.''
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans are now forced to regroup, with UCLA ahead, and
seven road games still remaining on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cal is 2-3. It's not like it's a runaway yet,'' Bibby said.
``It's not too far away yet. There is some life and we can be in
the hunt but we've got to go get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: USC yell leader Ruben Rodriguez suffered a possible
broken wrist early in the second half after he fell awkwardly while
attempting a slam dunk during a timeout.... The Trojans drew their
second-straight crowd of more than 5,000.... USC guard Quincy
Wilder had a career-high 18 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
