<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6590 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-LIGHTNING-RANFORD     01-17 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-LIGHTNING-RANFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANFORD RECOVERY SAVES THE DAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins had Bill Ranford where they wanted him late
in overtime of Saturday night's game against Tampa Bay at the
FleetCenter. After nearly three hours of play, Boston was on the
verge of the winning score, with Sergei Samsonov skating in alone,
the puck on his stick.
</P>
<P>
   But after Samsonov faked Ranford to the ice and carried the puck
across to the far side of what appeared to be an open net, the
former Bruins goalie somehow cartwheeled a skate in front of
Samsonov's shot, preserving a 2-2 tie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lucky,'' Ranford said. ``He put a hell of a move on me, and I
was down and out. I threw everything I had at him, and if you give
a guy that much time, a guy with that much skill ...''
</P>
<P>
   Ranford was talking minutes after the game, attempting to
explain how the contest had climaxed _ actually anticlimaxed _ with
one play 3:53 into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done that before _ it's not the first time I've done
that,'' Ranford said. ``It doesn't always work, and it's not
pretty. In fact, it's pretty ugly. It's not like I planned it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had already committed myself and I was dead in the water.
The puck jumped a little bit on him, and he might have lost a
little control.''
</P>
<P>
   The aesthetic qualities of this save might not have met
Ranford's standards. But his sense of drama could not have been
much better. The play made for a disappointing conclusion from the
Bruins' perspective, a heroic ending from Tampa Bay's view. Both
teams displayed resourcefulness, and the Bruins' recovery from a
miserable start appeared sufficient to overtake the Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had gained momentum and seemed destined to win in
overtime. They had nearly clinched the victory as P.J. Axelsson
draped himself over Ranford after being hooked by Petr Svoboda,
leaving the net open. The Bruins played with a man advantage and,
for part of the power play, a two-stick advantage before Rob
Zamuner cleared with his glove. Even with Tampa Bay at full
strength, the Bruins were in command.
</P>
<P>
   On the key late play, Dmitri Khristich took possession with his
back to the goal just outside the right faceoff circle, then laid
off to Samsonov, who faked to Ranford's left. Ranford went down
with his stick. Then, as Samsonov slipped to the far side, Ranford
rolled onto his back, kicking his legs out and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried for the corner but he made a good stop,'' Samsonov
said. ``I thought I had him. I tried to shoot up high, but I
couldn't get it up as high as I wanted and it hit his skate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There wasn't any time to think about it. I did what I had to
do, and I thought I had him.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lightning must have thought they had the Bruins as well.
Tampa Bay dominated the first period, but a Jason Allison goal with
20 seconds remaining in the second period tied the game and
resuscitated the Bruins. Then, early in the third period, Rob
DiMaio broke in alone on Ranford, who committed and left the far
side open, for the go-ahead goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should easily have won,'' Ranford said. ``We were unlucky
on their first goal, and on the second goal, we've got to be more
aware. They went from being out of the game to being in the game
and leading. We were dominating the first half, but then they took
it to us in the second half of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got their legs and turned it on and fought hard. But we
kept battling to the end, and that is something we haven't been
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
