<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON SHAKES OFF RUST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson wasn't Mike Tyson Saturday night but
fortunately he didn't have to be because Francois Botha couldn't
help being Francois Botha.
</P>
<P>
   After four rounds, the South African heavyweight seemed to have
the clearly rusty Tyson frustrated and befuddled but his growing
confidence fatally turned to overconfidence three minutes later and
when it did, Tyson turned over a straight right hand and the next
thing Botha was doing was turning over on his back.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson looked out of sync and lacking in the kind of punching
power and speed that had always been his trademarks, until Botha
stood right in front of him late in the fifth round and tried to
land a slow, wide right to the face of the two-time heavyweight
champion.
</P>
<P>
   As Botha's right shoulder moved, Tyson reacted, countering what
he knew was coming with a straight right hand of his own that
landed square in the middle of Botha's face before Botha's right
ever got near Tyson. Botha collapsed in a heap of broken flesh,
like a folding chair.
</P>
<P>
   Botha's eyes rolled up in his head and a vacant look came over
him as he lay on the floor, first on his backside and then
tottering forward as if he was going to use his face for support.
Three times he struggled to get up and three times he fell back,
his legs unable to support him, his mind clouded by the sound of
Chinese chimes ringing in his head.
</P>
<P>
   As referee Richard Steele reached 10 at 2:59 of the round, Botha
finally got up on legs that had been knocked stiff and he staggered
backward, slumping into the ropes. Those four strands of red were
all that were keeping him upright, but he slumped back down toward
the floor anyway and Tyson rushed in and tried to pull him back up,
knowing what had been a nasty affair was suddenly over.
</P>
<P>
   By that juncture, Botha had won all four rounds on the cards of
judges Dalby Shirley and Dave Moretti and was leading, 39-36, on
that of Bill Graham, growing confident enough in his dominance that
he several times stood with both hands down, taunting Tyson minutes
before he found himself wondering why it had suddenly gotten so
dark at the MGM Grand Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was trying to bait him,'' said Botha. ``I just walked
into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to that point, Tyson had looked like a guy who hadn't fought
in 19 months, which was exactly what he was. He at times looked
like a shot fighter, winging wild punches, flying off balance, and
getting drilled by some solid right hands and combinations from an
opponent whose hand speed was far slower than Tyson's but not so
slow that Tyson could avoid his fists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a tremendous amount of rust,'' said Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, at one point late in the fourth round, Botha shoeshined
Tyson, winging punches with both hands off his sides as Tyson bent
over and covered up. When he did, the crowd could be heard
laughing, an emotion usually reserved for Tyson's cowering
opponents in the past.
</P>
<P>
   But this was no longer the feared Tyson of old. The two beatings
from Evander Holyfield have taken much of that bullying mystique
away from him and now every fight is just that, a fight.
</P>
<P>
   This makes life difficult for a little man like Tyson, who is
small by heavyweight standards. It doesn't mean he can't win, as he
showed Saturday night, but it does mean he'll now have to fight to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Botha (39-2) came in at a portly 233, nearly 10 pounds heavier
than he had been for his two best fights, a win over Axel Schulz
for the International Boxing Federation title several years ago and
a 12th-round loss at the hands of Michael Moorer in his next
outing. Why he did that was difficult to fathom since his ability
to move in the early rounds seemed central to any chance he had at
victory but perhaps he had his own plan afoot.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson had come in at a career-high 223 but carried the weight
far differently, his body taut and without a hint of fat while
Botha was loose around the belly and seemed even more flacid as
they pushed him into the ring after his long, lonely walk from his
locker room.
</P>
<P>
   Botha looked tense as he shrugged off the white buffalo hide he
had worn into the ring but so did Tyson, who came in wearing a
black T-shirt that read ``Be Real,'' black trunks, and a black
kufi, a Muslim prayer cap.
</P>
<P>
   As the national anthem was being performed, Panama Lewis,
Botha's banned trainer, tried to make his way to ringside, from
where his instructions could be heard by Botha in his corner but he
was blocked by several members of the Nevada State Athletic
Commission and Botha was left to his own devices.
</P>
<P>
   As Botha stood at his corner pacing slowly, Tyson went to a
neutral corner and prayed silently, his gloved fists held to the
sky as Botha was being introduced. Less than three minutes later,
the fight was on and three minutes after that there was nearly a
second straight riot at a Tyson fight at the MGM when both boxers
were wrestling as the round ended and Tyson appeared to try to snap
Botha's arm in a clinch.
</P>
<P>
   As he did, Botha screamed and Tyson put his left forearm in his
face as Steele tried to figure out what to do. Not content to wait
for justice, Botha then rifled a punch after the bell off Tyson's
head and both sets of cornermen poured into the ring to separate
them as a wall of security guards rushed the ring.
</P>
<P>
   When order was restored, the second round began with a wild-eyed
Tyson whistling wild, amateurish punches that didn't land, while
Botha occasionally landed some solid shots. More and more the two
began to wrestle again in the clinches until Tyson tried to push
Botha in the face with an open glove and Steele took a point away.
</P>
<P>
   Botha later admitted he had hoped to goad Tyson into just such
an incident and he succeeded as Tyson's self-control seemed to be
nonexistent at that point.
</P>
<P>
   In the third round, Botha began to open up and scored with some
powerful right hands to the head as Tyson looked lost, although not
hurt. By then Tyson's right eye had begun to puff slightly and the
crowd seemed stunned.
</P>
<P>
   Botha finally landed a big right hand to the head early in Round
4 but Tyson kept coming forward, looking to land one of those
powerful combinations that remained dangerous. It was at that
juncture that Botha began to clown, dropping his hands and staring
at an opponent unsure of just what to do.
</P>
<P>
   When he did, his demise had begun.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long to unfold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
