<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-LIGHTNING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAD OUTING HAS BRUINS FIT TO BE TIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Bruins reached the midpoint of their season
Saturday night and arrived there with one of the worst games
they've played in their three seasons plus on FleetStreet. But one
thing the 27-team NHL affords is the chance to play poorly, even
for two-thirds of the game, and still manage a point, as the Bruins
did in their 2-2 tie against the league-worst Tampa Bay Lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we did everything possible not to win it,'' said Bruins
head coach Pat Burns, his club hitting midseason banged up and
struggling in an 0-2-1 mini-tailspin. ``But we tried not to lose
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Truth was, the Bruins came within a skate-blade of stealing the
victory, turned back by a sensational skate save by former Boston
netminder Bill Ranford with 67 seconds left in overtime. Faced with
an unprotected Sergei Samsonov on his doorstep, Ranford dropped
into one of those Dominik Hasek-like rolls and flips _ kicking up
both legs while on his back _ and turned back Samsonov's backhand
sweep that was labeled for inside the left post.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my arms up,'' said Bruins captain Ray Bourque, his
hoped-for celebration cut short by a fraction of an inch. ``I've
seen Billy make some incredible saves _ and that was another one of
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   For most of the evening, the best goaltending story was in the
Boston net, where Rob Tallas was on his way to running his record
vs. Tampa to 5-0-1. By early in the second period, when the Bolts
held a 1-0 lead, Tallas already had made 24 stops. At the other
end, Ranford had faced but five shots. When Bourque finally hit
Ranford with a long-range slapper for Boston's fourth shot overall,
with 6:00 gone in the second, the sellout crowd of 17,565 offered a
sarcastic jeer. Remember the days when Steve Kasper was leading the
lethargic, veteran-heavy Bruins? It had that feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game should have been over after the first two periods,''
said Tampa coach Jacques Demers. ``But we needed a great save by
our goaltender in overtime, off that little poison.''
</P>
<P>
   That ``little poison'' was Samsonov, and Demers offered the
description only as a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't mean that to insult him,'' he said. ``It's just that
he's a little poison _ he's all over the place. He's a great little
find for Boston.''
</P>
<P>
   Pavel Kubina, a 21-year-old defenseman from the Czech Republic,
hasn't been a bad find for the Bolts. With 1:02 gone in the second,
he cracked the blue line, turned Bourque inside out with a fake,
and closed to within 20 feet to beat Tallas with a wrister.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until 8:12 of the second, when Ken Baumgartner did
some old-fashioned pumpkin smashing, that the Bruins finally got
their game going. Baumgartner picked a fight with Tampa's No. 1
whack job, Andrei Nazarov, and The Bomber won quickly with a
righthand jab that bloodied the big Russian's nose. Suddenly, some
shots began to be delivered from Boston's dormant sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's equalizer came off the stick of Jason Allison, who
hadn't scored in a month. Cutting behind the net, left to right, he
curled out from behind the right post and waved a backhander over
the puck. With Darcy Tucker still on has back, and Ranford down,
Allison muscled a blind backhander that sailed high into the net at
19:20. It wasn't out of the skate-and-shoot handbook, but it did
give Allison his third goal in 22 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins appeared to pocket a win at 9:42 of the third when
Rob DiMaio, streaking out of the penalty box, collected a perfect
Dmitri Khristich relay and raced in alone on Ranford. The closest
Bolt was Benoit ``Bye-Bye'' Hogue, left about 15 feet behind in
DiMaio's vapor trail. DiMaio raced in, dropped Ranford with a fake,
and tucked in the backhander for the 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bolts, easily on course to earn the No. 1 draft pick for
the third time in franchise history (now in year No. 8), salvaged
the point when Chris Gratton connected on a wrister from the right
circle. He swooped up from the goal line, turned in the right
faceoff dot, and connected far side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on my post _ I got caught looking to one side,'' said
Tallas, who has played well enough in the first half to split the
job with Dafoe in the second half (we'll see how that plays out).
</P>
<P>
   The point came down to Samsonov vs. Ranford, the L'il Poison
first collecting the puck just a stick length away from the right
post. As he pulled it to his backhand and moved toward the left
post, Ranford put his paddle to the ice and tracked Samsonov as he
made the lateral move. As Samsonov lifted the shot, Ranford was
rolling on his back and lifting his legs, a move that this morning
will have Hasek filing a copyright lawsuit. Skate save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Sammy had it; I thought it was in,'' said Burns, his
club 19-15-7 and clinging to the last Eastern Conference playoff
spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
