<HEADLINE>
JAGR TALKS ABOUT DISTRACTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The rumors have been around for nearly two years, a combination
of the Pittsburgh Penguins' empty coffers and the empty seats at
most of the Kings' home games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night was a night the Kings could only wish they'd had
Jaromir Jagr on their side. The Penguins' star scored a dazzling
goal in a 5-1 victory over the Kings, and afterward, he was asked
to address rumors that Pittsburgh's bankruptcy ultimately could
cause him to be sent to a different team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, I heard that two years ago,'' Jagr said, referring
to rumors that the Kings tried to purchase his contract in 1997.
``If the owners or the general manager think they have to trade me,
that's their decision. I love to play for Pittsburgh. If they can't
afford me, then I'd love to play in L.A. or New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Penguins' financial woes have been a distraction,
Jagr said, ``I don't really think about it. We're getting paid,
we're getting a paycheck like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hit parade (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to quantifying Mattias Norstrom's value to the
Kings, statistics aren't much help.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Blake's defense partner has just four points this season,
but according to statistics provided by the National Hockey League,
Norstrom began play Saturday with 115 hits, second to Nashville's
Bob Boughner (119) among defensemen in the league, and fourth among
all players. Detroit's Darren McCarty (136) and New Jersey's Bobby
Holik (131) were Nos. 1 and 2 on the hit parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I realize the role I have on this team,'' Norstrom
said. ``When I play out there, I try to play physical. It's not
like I'm running around looking for hits. But if I can, I try to
take the body.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, I'm playing against the top line, the top
players. Hopefully, I can frustrate them by taking the body, and
with that come the hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the physical toll to himself from delivering so many
hits, Norstrom said, ``Actually, halfway through the season, I feel
surprisingly fresh. Knock on wood, I've been pretty healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   As for his negligible offensive statistics, which don't tell the
story of his worth to the Kings, Norstrom said, ``For me, ever
since I've been here and even in Sweden, I've been a stay-at-home
defenseman. If the team has success, I have success. It's great to
score goals. But it's not something I miss.''
</P>
<P>
   One who got away (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   During the 1993-94 season, center Robert Lang, then of the
Kings, went on an end-to-end rush and tucked the puck into the net
against the New York Rangers for his first NHL goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings were predicting big things for the Czech native, who
had been their seventh-round choice in the 1990 draft, but things
never worked out for him in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1996-97 season, Lang was back playing in his native land,
but last season, he returned to the NHL, first in Boston, then in
Pittsburgh, with a stop in between to win a gold medal for the
Czech Republic at the Winter Olympics in Nagano.
</P>
<P>
   This season, the 28-year-old Lang is the Penguins' third-leading
scorer, and scored his 18th goal Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's always been a good player,'' Blake said. ``They really
didn't give him a chance here. He wasn't playing a lot of minutes,
wasn't playing on the power play. He's very talented. He played on
the fourth line here. Back then, our fourth line probably couldn't
have played in the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks (subhed)
</P>
<P>
   Winger Russ Courtnall decided by mutual agreement with Coach
Larry Robinson not to return to the lineup Saturday from the broken
ankle that has sidelined him for two months. ``The smart thing to
do is to have another couple of good practices, then play in the
Colorado or New Jersey games (Tuesday or Thursday),'' Courtnall
said. ... Winger Craig Johnson on his separated rib cartilage:
``It's still sore. Right now, I've got to ice it and wait for them
to scar over.'' Johnson is listed as week to week to return to the
Kings' lineup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
