<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6595 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-HNS &LR;      01-17 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Tyson gives Botha blast from past
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LAS VEGAS _ Francois Botha on Saturday night emerged from his fight
against Mike Tyson with his ears intact.
</P>
<P>
   For most of the first four rounds, it appeared he might come
away with the scalp of the former heavyweight champion, too.
</P>
<P>
   But with one second left in the fifth round, Tyson with a short
right hand to the chin dropped the big South African and ended what
the ``White Buffalo'' had earlier termed his chance at greatness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked right into it,'' said Botha, the No. 2-ranked
heavyweight by the International Boxing Federation. ``I just tried
to fight him and I walked right into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Tyson connected, he looked like the same angry and
confused fighter who 19 months ago bit the ears of IBF/World Boxing
Association heavyweight champion Evander Holyfield and earned a
suspension of his boxing license by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   When he approached the pay-per-view TV microphones once his work
was done, Tyson sounded like that same fighter, filled with anger
and fury.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need respect,'' he said. ``You show me respect and stop
writing all these trash articles, I'll show you respect. I'm a man,
I'm not afraid to die. But when I die, I'm going straight to
Paradise.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I'm not worried because I'm in a hurry to die. And no
one's going to write bad about me without me retaliating back.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all due respect, there are people who are trying to
assassinate my character, get the judges in Indiana upset, the
judges in Maryland upset. I'm a man and I can only take so much.
I'm not going to sit back and take so much punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need love, just like everybody else. You can't talk about
me, disrespect me. I have children, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The references to judges in Indiana and Maryland were about
pending litigation involving Tyson in both states.
</P>
<P>
   He is due for a hearing in Maryland later this month, an
offshoot from an auto accident in which he was involved last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The results of that hearing could affect a parole hearing in
Indiana, also later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was Tyson's first bout since the biting incident, which
also took place at the MGM Grand Garden Arena in June 1997.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first round, it appeared Tyson had made little
progress in the last year and a half at managing his rage or
getting his boxing skills together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of rust,'' he said afterward. ``A lot of
rust.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a lot of questionable tactics, too. When the bell
sounded ending the first round, Tyson, in a clinch, with his right
arm wrapped around the left of Botha, employed a twist that had
Botha yelling in pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, he was just holding me and I twisted him around,'' said
Tyson. ``He was just holding me and I was just lucky enough to get
a shot and knock him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson started slowly and his first few punches missed the mark
by a wide margin.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, meanwhile, was having a field day. He landed at will and
employed the same sort of smothering tactics used by Holyfield to
stem whatever power Tyson might have.
</P>
<P>
   In the second round, Tyson was again at the mercy of Botha. He
openly argued with referee Richard Steele over what he thought were
illegal tactics by the South African. But it was Tyson who would
have a point deducted by the referee, who later said it was for
``unnecessary roughness.''
</P>
<P>
   As was the case at the end of the first round, when the two
fighters went after one another after the bell and had to be
separated by handlers from both corners. The second round ended
with punches being thrown after the bell.
</P>
<P>
   In the third and fourth rounds, Botha continued to confuse and
punish Tyson. In the fourth, he began toying with the 32-year-old
former champ.
</P>
<P>
   With his arms down around his waist instead of up in a defensive
posture, Botha wiggled a glove in Tyson's direction as he kept up a
steady stream of talk that continued through the first four rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was in control,'' said Botha, ``and slowly but
surely was going to win the fight.''
</P>
<P>
   But Botha came out of the fourth round with a cut on the bridge
of his nose, the result of one of the few punches from Tyson that
landed.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson began the fifth round with a solid left jab, began to find
the range with his punches much more frequently than before and
with the straight right hand secured his first victory in nearly
three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was controlling the fight real easily and staying away from
his punches,'' said Botha. ``Then I let my guard down. I was
playing around too much. It just shows you, you can't get careless.
I did and I paid dearly for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is now 46-3 with 40 knockouts. Botha, who briefly held the
IBF heavyweight title in 1994, is 39-2 with one no-decision and 24
KOs.
</P>
<P>
   After the fight was over, Tyson was whisked back to the dressing
room where he had to take stitches to close a wound over his right
eye.
</P>
<P>
   But the win he had wanted so dearly was in the bag, no matter
how sluggishly it was obtained.
</P>
<P>
   ``My trainer got excited, just a little bit,'' Tyson said of
Tommy Brooks. ``And I told him, `It's a long fight, I'm working on
him, I'll slow him down.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little worried at first because he went out, he
started looping his punches,'' said Brooks. ``He came back to the
corner and I told him you've got to throw your straight punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been working for 2{ months on firing at the body. He was
head-hunting. But he came out, settled down and started throwing
straight punches.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
