<SLUG> BC-BKC-PEPPERDINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEPPERDINE CONTINUES HOME SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By NEVIN BARISH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU _ Road games have not been very kind to Pepperdine this
season. Home games, however, are another story.
</P>
<P>
   The Waves improved to 8-1 at the Firestone Fieldhouse this year
with a 79-70 victory over San Francisco on Saturday night in a West
Coast Conference game.
</P>
<P>
   Pepperdine has now won 18 of its last 21 home games dating back
to the start of last season.
</P>
<P>
   Jelani Gardner once again led the Waves (12-7, 3-1) offensively.
Gardner, the conference's seventh-leading scorer (averaging 13.5
points a game heading into Saturday), had 20 points and seven
assists. He has led the Waves in scoring in each of the last six
games.
</P>
<P>
   Kelvin Gibbs added 17 points for Pepperdine, which has won three
of its past four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Team defense, that's what's been the key,'' said Pepperdine
center Nick Sheppard, who put up 13 points and six rebounds, when
asked about the team's improvement since a 31-point loss to Gonzaga
last week. ``Our defense has really stepped it up.''
</P>
<P>
   For San Francisco (8-11, 0-3), it was yet another loss in a
rapidly disappointing season. The team raced out at the start of
the season, going 7-1 _ including a win over Xavier and a close
three-point loss to UCLA. But injuries and the loss of point guard
Dony Wilcher, who left the program, have sent the Dons spiraling to
10 losses in their past 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   The big bright spot for San Francisco was Gerald Zimmerman, the
conference's second-leading scorer. Zimmerman, who scored a
career-high 32 points in a loss to Loyola Marymount on Friday,
poured in 31 against Pepperdine. Ali Thomas added 18 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
