<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6600 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     01-17 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS LIFELESS IN DEFEAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD _ At the end of Saturday morning's practice, Kings
coach Larry Robinson gathered his players around him and told them
he was worried.
</P>
<P>
   Their level of attention wasn't what it should be. And Saturday
night, Robinson's fears were proven to be well-founded.
</P>
<P>
   Before a crowd of 16,005 at the Forum, only the fourth sellout
this season, the Kings snoozed their way through a 5-1 loss to the
Pittsburgh Penguins, failing to win for the third time in their
last four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't focused,'' Robinson said. ``We weren't focused the
other day in practice, we weren't focused this morning at the
skate, and that's just the feeling I got. Again, I was right.
Everything we talked about at the meeting, we did the exact
opposite. We played right into their hands.''
</P>
<P>
   The score would have been worse for the Kings (16-23-4), but two
near goals by the Penguins were disallowed by the video goal judge.
The Kings were playing without defenseman Steve Duchesne, sidelined
with back spasms and listed as day to day. But he was hardly the
only no-show in a game in which the highly skilled Penguins were
allowed to free-wheel around the ice all night.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins (20-12-7), who lost to the Kings in Pittsburgh by a
3-0 margin in December, won this game largely on the strength of
special teams, scoring a pair of power-play goals and a shorthanded
goal.
</P>
<P>
   The shorthanded score, by Ian Moran, was not one Kings goalie
Jamie Storr should have allowed, and it was the goal that gave the
Penguins a 1-0 lead 10:39 into the game. Moran beat Storr between
the pads with a seemingly harmless 40-foot slap shot from the right
boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It went under the toe of my pad,'' Storr said. ``It was one of
those saves I should have had.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson said: ``You can be on top of your game and have
something like that deflate you. And there wasn't a lot to deflate.
We looked like the team that had played three games in four nights.
They gave us a clinic.''
</P>
<P>
   Just 51 seconds later, Jaromir Jagr skated around Donald Audette
at the blue line, then stickhandled past Rob Blake and flipped the
puck past Storr, giving the Penguins two goals on their first three
shots of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had the 2-0 lead,'' Jagr said, ``they had to change
their style and open the game up.''
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse in the second period, after Blake was sent off
for a high-sticking penalty at 6:36. The Penguins capitalized on
the subsequent power play, with Alexei Kovalev carrying the puck
from the right point to behind the Kings' net, then centering to
former King Robert Lang for an easy one-timer that was his 18th
goal this season.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the Penguins were content to protect their lead,
and the Kings were extremely cooperative, failing to muster a shot
in the second period until a 60-footer by Yanic Perreault at the
9:27 mark. In fact, the Kings managed only six shots at Penguins
goalie Tom Barrasso in the game's first 32 minutes, and the teams
combined for only 35 shots on goal in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings gained a minimal amount of life with 5:11 left in the
second period when Garry Galley scored his first goal this season,
a slap shot from the top of the right faceoff circle with the Kings
on a power play.
</P>
<P>
   But 2:19 later, the Kings got caught deep in the attacking zone,
allowing a 2-on-1 rush to the Penguins. Dan Kesa, covered by Doug
Bodger, passed across to Jan Hrdina, who was unchecked by Sean
O'Donnell. Hrdina redirected Kesa's pass into a wide-open net,
blunting the Kings' comeback hopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we got our first goal, we started to turn it around,''
Robinson said. ``Then, we gave them a goal. If they don't get the
fourth one, we'd started to pick our game up a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hatcher scored the game's final goal on a power play early
in the third period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
