<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6603 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-WRITETHRU-L     01-17 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON WINS   WITH ONE PUNCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Mike Tyson is oh-so-lucky that power is the last
thing to go.
</P>
<P>
   Francois Botha, a relatively obscure fighter from South Africa,
was poised to do the impossible Saturday at the MGM Grand. For
four-plus rounds, he had Tyson where he wanted him: frustrated,
confused and behind on all score cards.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if the boxing gods weren't quite ready to say
goodbye to Iron Mike at 32, the former two-time champion fired a
straight right into the willing chin of a brave opponent late in
the fifth round of a scheduled 10-round heayvweight bout and that
was that.
</P>
<P>
   Botha was able to stagger to his feet but it was too late: He'd
been counted out by referee Richard Steele one second before the
end of the round. Instantly, Botha's opportunity to make history
and the prospect of a fascinating final seven rounds had vanished.
</P>
<P>
   The punch was vintage Tyson (46-3, with 40 knockouts). He had
his entire 223 pounds behind it and Botha (39-1, 24 KOs) obliged by
walking into the pile driver _ an unpleasant combination for the
person on the receiving end of such violence.
</P>
<P>
   The near-full house of roughly 12,519, who paid to see either
such distruction or Tyson snap as he did when he bit Evander
Holyfield's ears in his last fight 19 months ago, loved it. They
cheered wildly when it happened and oohed and aahed every time the
replay was shown on the big screen.
</P>
<P>
   However, that's about all they had to cheer about in regard to
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, he was either extremely rusty as the result of the
layoff or his skills have eroded further. That, and Botha's
strategy, had those at the MGM thinking the unthinkable for a good
20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson cited the layoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``A tremendous amount of rust,'' he said. ``I told my trainer,
`Don't worry, I'll catch him late, I'll catch him late.'
(Cornerman) Stacey (McKinley) and those guys got a little excited,
but I was OK.''
</P>
<P>
   At the opening bell, Tyson did the things he supposedly learned
from new trainer Tommy Brooks: He jabbed and moved his head as he
had early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   That lasted all of a half round as Botha, who weighed a pudgy
233 pounds, began to frustrate the 7-1 favorite with a shockingly
effective game plan.
</P>
<P>
   Simply, he kept his distance from Tyson's bombs and held him
when danger seemed to be approaching. At the same time, he
repeatedly found the opportunity to throw effective combinations.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson became a stationary target as he was against Holyfield and
very frustrated, so frustrated he locked Botha's left arm under his
own at the end of the first round and wouldn't let go.
</P>
<P>
   Steele attempted to separate the two but couldn't get it done,
which set off a brief melee in the ring that for a moment had
everyone thinking the same thing: Tyson didn't lose it again, did
he?
</P>
<P>
   He lost a point in the second round when he hit Botha in the
face with a forearm.
</P>
<P>
   But, beyond that, he behaved. In fact, he had more difficulty
controlling the fight than himself.
</P>
<P>
   Botha baffled Tyson with his tactics throughout and seemed to
gain confidence with every round. He talked to Tyson in an attempt
to unnerve him whenever the two clinched, he smiled repeatedly and
even taunted the once-awesome champion late in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Botha appeared to gain even more ill-advised
bravado. He engaged Tyson in two brief toe-to-toe exchanges early
in the round and survived. And then his luck ran out: Tyson, back
to throwing big punches rather than combinations, was bound to land
one and finally he did.
</P>
<P>
   Botha fell to his side. He attempted to rise but fell on his
face. He tried it again with the same result before finally finding
his way to his feet. At that moment, Steele waved him off and he
staggered backward into the ropes _ clearly unable to continue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was winning,'' Botha said. ``Oh, what a fighter (Tyson). Oh
my, what a dummy (himself). I was going to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson touched off another short-lived incident when he rushed
toward Botha as he stumbled backward. It seemed clear that he had
good intentions, though: He wanted to catch his beaten opponent
before he fell.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately afterward, Tyson showed more unusual class. He
hugged Botha warmly and congratulated him on a good effort _ an
effort that was better than his in all but one way.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tyson seemed to have neither the fury one might expect
after waiting so long to begin his second comeback nor the skills
his fans somehow still expect from him. He looked powerful but
otherwise ordinary.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to have him fight again in April and again a few
months later _ the candidates include Axel Schulz, Vaughn Bean and
Lou Savarese _ and then face Holyfield for the third time.
</P>
<P>
   If this Tyson shows up to face his nemesis, who beat him twice,
have pity on him: He likely will be destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to fight, I need to put on better shows,'' Tyson said.
``I'm not looking to jump into the mix real quick. I need to do one
step at a time, go back to the gym and start working right away.''
</P>
<P>
   In other bouts, Goyo Vargas (39-6-1, 28 KOs) survived a 12-round
knockdown to oupoint Ben Tackie (18-1, 11 KOs) in a 12-round
lightweight bout.
</P>
<P>
   Zab Judah (19-0, 14 KOs) stopped Wilfredo Negron (17-4, 14 KOs)
at 1:44 of the fourth round of a scheduled 12-round junior
welterweight fight.
</P>
<P>
   Judah will next fight Vince Phillips for the title.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0039 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6604 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LA     01-17 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD TOO MUCH FOR UCLA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With five minutes remaining, the game ended and
the clinic began.
</P>
<P>
   And Stanford did all the teaching.
</P>
<P>
   For 35 minutes, UCLA challenged the Cardinal in a way it had not
been challenged in Pac-10 play, but even the Bruins' best effort
was not enough. Stanford broke open a close game and defeated UCLA
72-59 on Saturday night, before a crowd of 12,992 at Pauley
Pavilion that included Stanford sophomore Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't get rattled when they go on the road in a hostile
environment,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said. ``That's why they
win, and they did it tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Leading 54-53 with 5:31 remaining _ and with UCLA's most
effective player, center Dan Gadzuric, on the bench with five fouls
_ the Cardinal shifted into a dimension of poise and precision the
baby Bruins simply do not possess.
</P>
<P>
   After a 10-0 surge, the No.4 Cardinal was in total command and
cruised to its 11th consecutive victory. The game ended with a
frustration foul by Baron Davis on Stanford guard Art Lee, and with
objects thrown onto the court from the UCLA student section. (A
piece of candy hit Davis on the lip.)
</P>
<P>
   But until Stanford's late surge, which included a stifling zone
defense, it was a riveting duel of tactics and talent, structure
and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   The dominant theme was Stanford's smothering defense. The
Cardinal was acutely aware of Davis' every move and dropped four
players into the paint at the slightest hint of penetration. The
strategy choked off UCLA's greatest weapon and forced the Bruins to
the perimeter. They shot 40.6 percent from the field and made 1 of
14 shots from 3-point range.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked,'' Davis said. ``We didn't execute on the offensive
end. That was our biggest problem of the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Foul trouble was a close second. UCLA (12-4, 4-2) had five
players disqualified, and it committed 35 fouls to Stanford's 19.
</P>
<P>
   The costliest was Gadzuric's fifth, with 6:45 left and the
Bruins trailing 51-49. He departed with 15 points _ his best game
of the season _ and seemed to take UCLA's spirit with him, as
Stanford's game-breaking run began one minute later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an unusual game,'' Lavin said, careful not to directly
criticize the officiating and incur the Pac-10's wrath. ``I've
never seen anything quite like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor had the Cardinal, but for a different reason. UCLA's
uber-aggressive defense challenged every pass and every rebound,
but the Bruins also grabbed and clawed continuously. Perhaps they
were overly excited. Perhaps they were frustrated by Stanford's
structured offense. Either way, the Cardinal didn't think enough
fouls were called.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was brutal,'' coach Mike Montgomery said. ``I've never
seen anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford controlled the tempo from the outset, jumping to a 9-4
lead and drawing two quick fouls on Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso.
Lavin removed them immediately, guessing correctly that the Bruins
could stay in striking range with a small lineup for the remainder
of the first half. The Bruins trailed 33-27 at halftime and were
thrilled about it.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric and Moiso were back on the court when the second half
began, and Gadzuric made three early baskets _ including a
ferocious dunk _ to jump-start UCLA's attack.
</P>
<P>
   A technical foul on Stanford guard David Moseley, followed by
another Gadzuric dunk, gave UCLA a 47-42 lead with 12:14 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `Now, we've got them,''' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to contain UCLA's quickness, Stanford switched to a 2-3
zone. It worked as designed _ and as practiced Friday afternoon _
sending UCLA's offense into instant stagnation. The Bruins scored
six points in 10 minutes against the zone, and Stanford took
control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had seen some tape of them struggling in zone in other
games,'' Montgomery said. ``It ended up working well for us. It
bought us some time and enabled us to gain the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins did some of their best work without guard Earl
Watson, who missed five minutes in the second half because of a cut
finger on his right (shooting) hand. Watson returned with eight
minutes left and immediately hit Moiso for a lay-up. But by that
point, the Cardinal was in charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They executed well in the stretch, and we didn't execute well
against the zone,'' Lavin said. ``A lot had to do with foul
trouble, and Earl had the stitches on his finger.''
</P>
<P>
   The margin was 11 with 90 seconds left when the crowd departed,
leaving the Bruins deflated and defeated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seemed to give up,'' Davis said angrily. ``It seemed like
we just gave up.''
</P>
<P>
   Why not? The clinic was over.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Watson said he might be out a week or two because of his
cut finger.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0248EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
