<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 02:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6605 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN     01-17 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-SIDE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GADZURIC'S PLAY ONLY GOES SO FAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The selfless, seamless play of the Stanford men's basketball
team last season so inspired former basketball great Bill Bradley
he was moved to write his fourth book, ``Values of the Game.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on the way UCLA center Dan Gadzuric played in the second
half of the Bruins' 72-59 loss Saturday to the back and intact
Stanford squad, it looked like he had spent the intermission
reading Bradley's chapter on resilience.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric didn't let his early foul trouble keep him down and in
doing so he very nearly turned the game around. He contributed five
points and an assist during a marvelous three-minute run early in
the second half after a 3-pointer by Ryan Bailey had given the
10th-ranked Bruins their first lead, at 38-37.
</P>
<P>
   His teammates seemed to feed off Gadzuric's energy, and when the
6-foot-10 freshman dunked over Stanford's 6-9 junior Mark Madsen to
give the Bruins their largest lead of the night at 47-42, the No.4
Cardinal suddenly looked vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric looked like Godzilla when he stole the ball and
converted a twisting five-foot jumper at the other end to keep the
Bruins ahead 49-46. Shortly after that, though, he picked up his
fourth foul while fighting David Moseley for a defensive rebound.
</P>
<P>
   As the air left Gadzuric's game, the rest of the Bruins got
deflated.
</P>
<P>
   With the Bruins down by three and clawing to regain the lead,
Gadzuric was whistled for an over-the-back foul, his fifth, while
tipping in a shot with 6:45 left.
</P>
<P>
   He retired to the bench with 15 points, four rebounds, two
steals and one assists in 19 compact minutes. He took the momentum
with him when he left the floor and the wily Cardinal moved in
quickly to fill the vacuum, rising above the din of a pumped-up
Pauley Pavilion crowd of 12,922 to record its 11 consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was Dan's breakout game,'' Bruins coach Steve Lavin said
afterward. ``His physical presence, his confidence, was
outstanding. He dominated both ends of the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Gadzuric wasn't so sure. He just knew he had to come out in the
second half and play as aggressively as he had at the game's start.
He had scored the opening basket on a dunk, then spent most of the
rest of the half on the bench after picking up his second foul with
13:57 left.
</P>
<P>
   Hacks happen when you're surrounded by as much tall timber as
was Gadzuric. He gave up four inches and three years of experience
to his Cardinal counterpart, Tim Young, and it showed in the early
going.
</P>
<P>
   After 20 minutes Young had five points, four rebounds, three
blocks and two assists. That looked a lot better than Gadzuric's
four points, zero rebounds, zero blocked shots and zero assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told me to keep playing aggressive and if I fouled out,
I fouled out,'' Gadzuric said. ``So I just came out strong and
played hard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 0251EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
