<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6607 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-AZR &LR;      01-17 0788
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-BOTHA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON TAKES THE 5TH  
 SHORT RIGHT STOPS BOTHA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ One punch is Mike Tyson's signature.
</P>
<P>
   It's his only expression. Little else about this heavyweight
jumble of contradictions makes much sense.
</P>
<P>
   The anger, controversy and profanity have turned him into a
nihilistic figure who defies a reasonable explanation in every
language but one.
</P>
<P>
   The punch.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson (46-3, 40 KOs) let the punch speak for him all over again
Saturday night with the beautiful delivery of a right hand for a
fifth-round knockout of South African Frans Botha (39-2, 24 KOs) at
the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson had a lot of crazy things to say after the victory in his
first bout since he bit Evander Holyfield's ears in June 1997. He
talked about dying and respect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need respect,'' he said. ``Everybody has been writing a lot
of trashy articles about me. I'm a man. I'm angry. I need to be
loved like everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not afraid to die. When I die, I'm going to paradise.''
</P>
<P>
   But there isn't much love in a sport that Tyson himself has
called ``the hurt business.''
</P>
<P>
   The ring is only paradise for a punch. And within those ropes,
Tyson is still very much alive with the one thing, perhaps the only
thing, he does best.
</P>
<P>
   The South African walked straight into a Tyson right that was as
deadly as any he has ever thrown. It was textbook perfect.
</P>
<P>
   At 2:59 of the round, Botha, nicknamed the White Buffalo, hit
the canvas like a slaughtered calf. He tried to climb to his feet,
but he collapsed on the ropes and then rolled around in a
semiconscious state.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the emphatic end to what had been an ugly
confrontation. Tyson, showing the effects of 19 idle months, missed
wildly with hooks.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Botha was surprisingly effective with tactics
that included a lot clutching, grabbing and talking.
</P>
<P>
   He was clearly trying to enrage Tyson. For a while, it appeared
he might succeed. At the end of the first, the two fighters had to
separated by the corners.
</P>
<P>
   As referee Richard Steele tried to break up the two fighters,
Tyson threw an elbow. Botha retaliated. You could almost hear the
ticking in the Tyson time bomb. It looked as if he was about to
explode.
</P>
<P>
   Before the the second round, Marc Ratner, executive director of
the Nevada State Athletic Commission, climbed into the ring and
spoke to Steele, who followed with a warning to both fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't win with a foul,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   But the fouls continued. At the end of the second, Tyson was
penalized one point for a head butt and an elbow as Steele again
tried to break up the two.
</P>
<P>
   In the third, Tyson, cut above his right eye, repeatedly looked
at Steele as though he were frustrated by Botha's tactics.
</P>
<P>
   But it was working. After four rounds, Botha led on three of the
judges' score cards.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, it didn't matter. Tyson was about to apply his
signature on a bout worth $10 million to him and $1.85 million to
Botha.
</P>
<P>
   All the while, Muhammad Ali watched.
</P>
<P>
   Ali arrived and took a seat alongside actor Jack Nicholson about
an hour before Tyson answered an opening bell for the first time in
19 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ali, Ali,'' the crowd chanted in a nostalgic tone full of
echoes from a very different time. A bygone time. And probably a
better one.
</P>
<P>
   For Tyson, there were none of the chants that always accompany
and help to define a legend. He's become a curiosity, if not a
cartoon character in an X-rated comic book. Ali was a reason to
celebrate. He and the fans became one. His fight was their fight.
The link was almost choreography. Folk art.
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson is a peep show. His nitroglycerin mix of anger,
insecurity, contempt, fear and loathing for seemingly everything,
perhaps even himself, is no celebration.
</P>
<P>
   People gather to watch him fight the way they stop and stand to
look up at a man poised to jump off a towering ledge of a tall
building.
</P>
<P>
   Will desperation shove him off the edge? Or just sheer lunacy?
With Tyson, nobody can ever be sure of anything. Only the hint of
imminent danger is there.
</P>
<P>
   So there the audience was Saturday night, gathered around a ring
as though it were a gallows. A couple of condemned men were about
to enter the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Botha was condemned by the simple fate of having neither speed
nor power. Tyson was too much for Botha and, one day, maybe too
much for himself.
</P>
<P>
   Even in victory, he walked the walk of a man condemned by his
own inability to control the runaway rage that has always left him
perilously balanced with one foot on the ledge and the other other
dangling in the depths of demise. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
