<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 03:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6608 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-ARIZONA-NEWMEXICO     01-17 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-NEWMEXICO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MEXICO SURPRISES ARI ZONA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAUL CORO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE _ Arizona senior Jason Terry said all along that his
team lacked the killer instinct to come out strong since the new
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats got part of that fixed with its best first half in
the core of a plane engine that is The Pit. But killer instinct
also means burying a team when you have it down.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Arizona put itself in a position to lose. Just as Terry
rallied the Wildcats back from 10 down after being 15 up with a
go-ahead runner, Arizona watched New Mexico use the final 4.6
seconds to get a buzzer-beating layup from Damion Walker in the
Lobos' 79-78 victory Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Between what seemed like a long 4.6 seconds to Arizona and
officiating that had A.J. Bramlett and Eugene Edgerson saddled with
four fouls in the second half, Arizona Coach Lute Olson said his
500th game coaching the Wildcats will be his last in Albuquerque.
</P>
<P>
   ``The home next year will be the end of the series
unequivocally,'' Olson said of the 81-year duel.
</P>
<P>
   No. 7 Arizona let No. 16 New Mexico, standing-room-only crowd,
and the pride of Tempe Corona del Sol High School, guard Lamont
Long, back into the game and wound up losing for the third straight
time at The Pit. The last two Arizona losses at The Pit came in
seasons that the Wildcats reached the Final Four.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't play much better than we did except for those lulls
in the second half,'' Arizona center and Albuquerque native A.J.
Bramlett said. ``I wanted to beat them more than anybody, but we
came out a better team for battling them all the way down to the
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (12-2) led the Lobos (16-2), 43-28, at the half off an
8-0 run, but it all vanished in less than nine minutes of the
second half. With New Mexico star center Kenny Thomas in foul
trouble, Long took over to make up for a two-point first half with
20 second-half points.
</P>
<P>
   His pair of free throws put New Mexico ahead, 75-65, with four
minutes remaining, capping a 25-8 Lobos run that came during
Bramlett's and Edgerson's foul trouble. Bramlett went from one to
four fouls less than five minutes into the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats rallied, as they have all season, behind senior
guard Jason Terry, but did it late. Terry's solo offensive effort
and a Ruben Douglas steal and layup pulled Arizona within one,
77-76, before Terry hit the last of his 17 second-half points on a
running jumper to put the Wildcats ahead with 4.6 seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   New Mexico did not take its final timeout. John Robinson's
upcourt dribble drew four defenders atop the three-point line,
where he fed into Walker for the winner, even with Michael Wright's
deflection on the shot. It was the third time the Lobos have
rallied from 15 down this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach told me if I don't have anything good to say to not say
anything at all,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   After trips to Brigham Young, UCLA and Arizona State, Wright and
Douglas shrugged off the raucous environment with brilliant first
halves.
</P>
<P>
   Wright outpowered New Mexico, racking up 13 points and 12
rebounds in the first half. He and Bramlett escorted Thomas to 10
minutes of first-half bench time because of foul trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas came out aggressively to quiet the Lobos faithful
quickly. His steal, three-point play and jumper got Arizona ahead
10-3.
</P>
<P>
   With Thomas and Long out, New Mexico went to the perimeter and
hit 4 of 15 three-pointers rather than its normal 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' fourth foul sat him again 6:49 into the second half
after Walker's nine points in three minutes recharged the Lobos
howlers. New Mexico scored on its first eight possessions of the
half to trim the lead to 49-46. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
