<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0045 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 13:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6650 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARABS-JEWELS18-COX     01-17 1744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARABS-JEWELS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Questions surround `sheikh,' jewelry scheme
 &HT;    By Mary McLachlin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH _ If it happened _ and at least two witnesses
say it did _ the scene on the tarmac at Palm Beach International
Airport played out like a cheesy, made-for-TV movie:
</P>
<P>
   A huge, bearded man in flowing robes and headdress _ a sheikh,
perhaps? _ emerges from a private aviation company and boards an
unmarked jet parked at the far end of a ramp. With him are two
women wearing ``I Dream of Jeannie'' harem outfits. A young man in
a dark suit, Arabic-looking headdress and sunglasses stands beside
the plane, arms crossed, on guard.
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, a limousine pulls up to the Hawker Siddeley HS125
and three men get out _ a dapper yachtsman-type, an elderly
businessman and another dark-suited guard in silk-scarf headgear
and sunglasses. The guard frisks the other two before they board
the plane.
</P>
<P>
   When they step down 20-30 minutes later, and get back into the
limousine, one carries a wooden box. Inside: a jewel-encrusted
dagger.
</P>
<P>
   After the limo leaves, everybody else goes back into the
aviation office. The women, described as looking ``like a couple of
hookers dressed up in an Arab costume,'' disappear. The guards pull
off their makeshift kaffiyehs. And the ``sheikh'' sheds his sheets
and heads for the parking lot in ordinary shirt-and-pants outfit.
</P>
<P>
   The bizarre performance, described by reluctant witnesses in a
lawsuit, allegedly was staged in October 1995 as part of an
elaborate scheme to bilk the businessman out of millions of
dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents theorize that the charade was set up to make
Detroit broadcasting magnate Aben Johnson believe the claims of his
companion, local jewel dealer Jack Hasson, that he had connections
to the world's richest man, the Sultan of Brunei _ and that the
sultan was interested in buying the collection of estate jewelry
Hasson had sold Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Hasson allegedly told Johnson he had a line to the sultan
through his friendship with golfer Jack Nicklaus _ a claim denied
by Nicklaus, who has testified that he never met the sultan.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 71, sued the former Palm Beach Gardens jewelry merchant
last year, claiming most of the goods Hasson sold him from December
1988 to June 1997 were fake, or that Hasson lied about their
origins and value. The suit seeks restitution and damages totaling
$180 million, the largest jewelry fraud claim against an individual
on record.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 former customers have sued Hasson in the past
decade, including Jack and Barbara Nicklaus, claiming he cheated
them in various ways. Hasson sometimes countered with slander suits
but eventually settled all the complaints, most under confidential
terms. However, details are emerging as the former customers are
called as pre-trial witnesses in Johnson's suit.
</P>
<P>
   Hasson has denied Johnson's allegations and sued him for
slander, claiming he drove him out of the jewelry business.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who worked for Hasson or were associated with him
have testified they've been questioned by FBI agents and called
before a federal grand jury investigating Hasson's dealings. The
FBI won't confirm or deny the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Six people have been questioned under oath so far about the
alleged airplane incident. Three gave corroborating testimony,
according to transcripts of their depositions; two, including one
of the ``harem,'' refused to answer, saying it could incriminate
them; and the 340-pound boat carpenter alleged to have played the
``sheikh'' denied everything.
</P>
<P>
   The mysterious ``Arab'' on the airplane, according to court
documents, was supposed to be ``Prince Akmed,'' nephew and personal
representative of the Sultan of Brunei. And the bejeweled dagger
given to Johnson was supposed to be a token of the potentate's
esteem and appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   It was all an elaborate hoax, the suit alleges, designed to make
Johnson think he was meeting with a member of the royal family of
Brunei aboard the ``prince's'' private jet and to keep Johnson
spending money with Hasson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson paid Hasson roughly $50 million for jewelry after the
alleged incident, in addition to the $30 million he'd already
spent.
</P>
<P>
   Hasson owned two private jets in 1995, according to the
testimony of his chief pilot at the time. Jimmie Wade Keeling, 62,
said he got a telephone call one morning telling him to move the
older model plane as far out on a ramp as possible and cover or
remove Hasson's ``Jack of Diamonds'' logo _ a diamond with a
jumping marlin and sailfish.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot said he couldn't remember whether the call was from
Hasson or his friend and business partner, Ted Keys. And even
though he was curious, he said, he never questioned the order.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not my business to ask my boss why he has me do
something,'' he said, a theme repeated by other witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   Keeling said he told co-pilot Tim McCarty to get some washable
paint to cover the logo on the tail. McCarty, 31, testified that he
went to a Kmart and bought children's fingerpaint to obscure the
outside logo and that he scraped off an inside logo with a razor
blade.
</P>
<P>
   Keeling said he sat in the pilot's seat, kept the air
conditioning running and watched the scene unfold.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the captain and mate of Hasson's sportfishing yacht
had left the Sailfish Marina, where the 55-foot ``Jack of
Diamonds'' was docked, and driven to the airport, according to the
mate's testimony.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Hughes, 35, said the captain, Sean O'Neill, told him
that Hasson wanted them to bring dark suits, but O'Neill didn't say
why. Hughes testified that after they put on the suits, Ted Keys
and Jimmy Speiser, an employee of Hasson's, helped them tie pieces
of black or dark blue silky material around their heads.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said Speiser told him to get into a limo, driven by Keys,
which would pick up Hasson and a friend, and that he and O'Neill
were to keep their mouths shut and not say anything to anyone.
O'Neill stood by the stairs leading to the plane, Hughes testified.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, 27, refused to answer any questions during his
deposition, claiming Fifth Amendment rights against
self-incrimination. Lawyer John Tierney wouldn't even let O'Neill
give his birthdate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been advised by the Assistant United States Attorney
that he is a target of a federal indictment . . . because of this
subject matter, and we're not going to answer any questions,''
Tierney told Johnson's lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Keys nor Speiser has given a deposition yet, and Speiser
could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Keys said in an interview that he had testified before the
federal grand jury and had not claimed a Fifth Amendment privilege.
Regarding the scene at the airport, he said:
</P>
<P>
   ``The people that I know who have testified _ that is, the
pilot, co-pilot and the mate _ to my knowledge, have told the
complete truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Eaton, 49, alleged to be one of the harem women, pleaded
the Fifth Amendment 50 times during her deposition. She refused to
answer questions about the airplane incident or about a sworn
statement she made in October, in which she said the only time she
had been on Hasson's plane was when he had paid for her and another
woman to pose as sexy ``flight attendants . . . for scenery'' while
he showed it to a prospective buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes testified that he didn't know Eaton when he saw her in
the ``genie'' outfit, but recognized her six months later when
Hasson sent him to her for a massage. He said he had sex with her
``three or four'' times, but didn't pay for it and didn't know if
Hasson paid her.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson's lawyer asked Eaton if she had used her home on
Gun Club Road to entertain men or provide sexual favors, she
pleaded the Fifth Amendment. She did testify that police had raided
her house in 1992 and charged her with offering to commit
prostitution; she said she was ordered to perform community service
and the record was sealed.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Eaton also was arrested in 1991 on a disorderly
conduct charge _ dancing topless on the deck of a boat in Miami's
Bayside Marina _ for which she paid a fine and court costs.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents allege Hasson also recruited Eaton to play the
role of ``Ms. Fricker,'' daughter of a wealthy _ and imaginary _
client from whose estate he wanted Johnson to buy millions of
dollars worth of jewelry. When questioned about it, Eaton refused
to answer, citing her right to avoid self-incrimination.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Speiser, a marine carpenter who stands 6'2'' and weighs
340, denied posing as ``Prince Akmed.'' Speiser, whose brother
James worked for Hasson, testified that he didn't know where Brunei
is but had heard of it ``in the news once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Nicklaus, whose name and friendship Hasson allegedly
invoked as a connection to the Sultan of Brunei, testified that he
designed a golf course for Prince Hakeem of Brunei, but had never
met his uncle, the sultan.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus said he and his wife discovered through a routine
insurance appraisal that the ruby in a $35,000 diamond and ruby
ring bought from Hasson was synthetic. When they complained,
Nicklaus testified, Hasson apologized and replaced it _ with
another synthetic stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that point then we had all the jewelry appraised,''
Nicklaus said, ``and the jewelry was (worth) substantially less
than what I'd paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The couple sued in 1997, claiming fraud. Hasson settled by
agreeing to buy back 13 pieces of jewelry for $380,000 and to never
identify the jewelry as having belonged to the Nicklauses or refer
to them as having been his customers.
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus testified that Hasson refused to take back one item, a
wooden family tree with little gold bears on it, representing
himself, his wife and their children _ an idea he'd had for a
family Christmas present and that Hasson had assigned an employee
to make.
</P>
<P>
   The Bear Tree fell apart, Nicklaus testified, and the ``solid
gold'' bears turned out to be ``plastic and lead and paper and with
a thin coat of gold leaf or paint'' over them.
</P>
<P>
   It stuck in his craw, Nicklaus said, especially after Hasson
said his employee had worked extra during the holidays on the tree
and suggested Nicklaus give him a present.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I bought him a couple of nice fishing rods for Christmas,''
Nicklaus said, ``for making sure I got my paper Bear Tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1330EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6651 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STENT-GRAFT18-COX     01-17 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STENT-GRAFT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEALTH/SCIENCE: Tiny tube can open arteries, stop pain
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, GRAPHIC
 &HT;    By Dan Moffett
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ At 76, Max Frenkel lost two of the joys
of his life _ ballroom dancing and table tennis _ to legs that were
crippled by clogged circulation.
</P>
<P>
   Pain and cramping came with each step, and even standing became
an ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Frenkel's problem would have been dismissed as an
unfortunate function of aging that medical science could do little
to rectify.
</P>
<P>
   But today Frenkel is dancing again _ three times a week with
wife Paula _ and taking on all comers on the ping-pong table. The
West Palm Beach retiree's recovery is evidence of what physicians
are calling a quiet revolution in cardiovascular surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A tiny metal tube, about a half-inch long, that could easily be
mistaken for the spring in a ballpoint pen is what put the bounce
back in Frenkel's feet.
</P>
<P>
   It is called a stent, and few inventions in the 1990s have made
such powerful impacts in so many different arenas.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtrooms, competing corporations have battled over who
should control development rights to the technology. On Wall
Street, investors have made huge profits by backing companies that
marketed the device.
</P>
<P>
   But it is in the operating room where the collapsible stent is
making its most enduring contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a dramatic increase in the use of stents
throughout the circulation (system),'' said Dr. Barry Katzen,
medical director of the Miami Cardiac and Vascular Institute. ``The
quiet revolution is that we have developed more applications to
address quality of life issues in ways we haven't been able to
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzen performed the angioplasty procedure on Frenkel last year,
inserting a stent into the arteries of both legs to return normal
blood flow and treat the advanced peripheral vascular disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within three days after my operation, I was walking without
pain and in a week I was dancing again,'' Frenkel said. ``The
results were outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   In stenting, a surgeon inserts the coil _ usually a cage of
surgical-grade stainless steel that resembles chicken wire _ by
running a catheter through a small incision made to the femoral
artery in the groin. A mild sedative to aid relaxation is used, but
not a general anesthetic.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors ask patients to move or breathe deeply so that x-rays
can be taken to direct the catheter to the proper place where the
stent is deployed.
</P>
<P>
   A balloon containing the stent is threaded to the weak spot; the
balloon is deflated, and the stent spring-loads into place. A
typical procedure lasts 90 minutes and patients are released from
the hospital after about two days.
</P>
<P>
   The stent acts as latticed scaffolding, permanently implanting
itself into the wall of the vessel, holding it open and preventing
it from collapsing again, an occurrence called restenosis.
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, Frenkel had angioplasty without the stent and his
symptoms returned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell the difference with the stents,'' he said. ``I
think it definitely feels better with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The stent, despite its conceptual simplicity, has had a history
of false starts and complications on its way to acceptance.
Implanting metal tubes in arteries was first attempted 30 years
ago, but the technology was not advanced enough for successful
results.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '80s, with the rising popularity of balloon
angioplasty, Dr. Julio Palmaz of the University of Texas Health
Science Center in San Antonio created the modern prototype for the
collapsible stent. Palmaz, with Dr. Richard Schatz, developed a
stainless steel wire tube with soldered joints that could be
crimped over a balloon delivery system. In 1994, that stent was
approved for coronary applications by the Food and Drug
Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Cordis, a Johnson &AMP; Johnson company that owns the Palmaz-Schatz
stent, has taken competitors Guidant, Boston Scientific and
Arterial Vascular Engineering to court claiming infringements of
its patents. The competing companies have argued successfully to
date that their stents are significantly different in design.
</P>
<P>
   Stock soars for stent makers
</P>
<P>
   Most of the later models are more flexible or are coated to
prevent clotting, one of the most troublesome complications with
the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Guidant's stock price has quadrupled to about $110 per share as
its portion of the stent market has grown over the past two years.
Worldwide sales of stents are expected to approach $2 billion by
the year 2001, with about 56 percent of all coronary angioplasties
(about 200,000 yearly in the United States) using the device.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be misled by the humble appearance of the half-inch tube.
Each stent, which is sold with the catheter to deploy it, sells for
about $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   Aorta repairs may be next
</P>
<P>
   New models are in production with a constellation of eclectic
names: The Gianturco, the Wallstent, the Multilink Duet and Phytis
stents. They are being touted for their diamond coatings,
radioactivity or revolutionary architecture.
</P>
<P>
   The potential uses for stents are only beginning to be
understood. Studies show that patients who receive them during
coronary angioplasty are much less likely to need heart bypass
surgery later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really has been an explosion in the quality of the
technology,'' said a physician at Good Samaritan Medical Center in
West Palm Beach. ``But there's one thing you have to keep in mind:
You're not really curing anybody; you're just fixing the plumbing.
It's not magic. Still, it's gratifying when you see you're able to
treat someone and avoid major surgical procedures.''
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, Katzen is working to perfect a stent graft that would
repair aneurysms in the aorta, the main blood vessel to the heart.
Each year in the United States, 25,000 people die from ruptured
aortas, the 13th leading cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to see a dramatic improvement in the quality and
number of stents available,'' said Katzen, 52, who has been the
Miami institute's director and lead researcher for 10 years.
``Patients have more alternatives that are minimally invasive today
and they will have even more in the near future.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
