<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6653 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAYS-DRUGSAIDS18-COX     01-17 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYS-DRUGSAIDS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCIENCE/HEALTH: Group warns AIDS infection rate on rise
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ After years of holding steady, HIV infection rates are
rising among young gay men in Atlanta, possibly because of
recreational drug abuse, an AIDS advocacy group is warning.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't contaminated syringe needles, the usual route
of infection when illegal drugs are involved. It's unprotected sex
that occurs when people are high and their inhibitions are low, due
to the influence of psychedelic drugs like Ecstasy and crystal
methamphetamine, say AID Atlanta officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've seen a steady increase in the number of positive (HIV)
test results, particularly among young gay men,'' said Mark King,
director of education at the AIDS service organization.
``Anecdotally, what we're hearing is that very often substance
abuse has been a factor in their infection.''
</P>
<P>
   AID Atlanta, which offers free anonymous HIV testing, reports
that the number of positive test results in 1998 jumped by nearly
50 percent over 1997 figures _ even though the agency performed
fewer tests overall in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 2.7 percent of 4,144 people tested for HIV were
positive for the AIDS virus, compared to 1.8 percent of 4,290
tested in 1997. Before 1997, the percentage of positive HIV tests
had been flat for several years, so the spike in numbers raised
immediate concerns, King said.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Georgia Department of Health does not yet track HIV
infections, it's unclear whether the higher percentage of positive
tests also is occurring statewide. AID Atlanta is one of the more
popular local agencies for HIV testing because its service is free.
Its clients include a wide cross-section of people at risk for
AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials are working on a plan to track HIV
infections within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, about 2 percent of people who take HIV tests are
found to be infected, said Paul Bartels, a prevention case manager
at AID Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that our (rate) is almost 3 percent is cause for
concern,'' Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug abuse and unsafe sex have become issues for the gay
community nationwide. The Gay Men's Health Crisis in New York
recently canceled an annual AIDS fund-raising party because it had
become associated with recreational drug use and unprotected sex.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, three ambulances were dispatched to a party at the
Colony Square Hotel attended primarily by gay men, King said,
because people had overdosed on gamma-hydroxybutyrate, or GHB,
which can cause blackouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have here is a culture in which substance use is
widely accepted and very little judgment is cast on it,'' King
said. But he emphasized that this drug culture thrives only in
small portion of the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most gay men in the metro area live lives like all of us do,
they go to work and they go home, and are as surprised and
concerned about drug use as everyone else,'' King said. ``That
being said, I think there are after-hours dance clubs in which
certainly well over half the people in attendance are on one drug
or another. And I'm being conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Lee Anisman, whose Buckhead practice, Pride Medical Group,
is roughly 70 percent gay males, said he is seeing a definite
correlation between overindulgence in drugs and alcohol and a new
wave of HIV infections, particularly in men in their 20s.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is disheartening, to say the least,'' Anisman said.
``It's always a similar story: `I was out this weekend. . . I did
too many drugs, I mixed drugs with alcohol and I don't even
remember what I ended up doing. But I ended up in some stranger's
house, and I don't know if I used a condom.' Six months later they
show up HIV positive.''
</P>
<P>
   In response to these concerns, AID Atlanta and Pride Medical
Group are hosting a forum Wednesday to discuss the drug culture and
educate people about the risks of drug abuse. The forum, called
``BUZZED,'' is at 7 p.m. at Grady High School in midtown Atlanta.
(Information: 404-872-0600).
</P>
<P>
   King says the forum's purpose is not to criticize drug users,
but to inform them of the risks and to urge them to take
precautions against HIV infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can come to this forum and know you're not going to get
slammed, humiliated or lectured to,'' he said. ``If you just want
information about what this drug might do to you long-term, or how
to avoid overdosing, you will get it in a non-judgmental way.''
</P>
<P>
   King acknowledges that the agency's seminar will likely draw
fire from both those who feel drug use shouldn't be condoned and
those who say AID Atlanta is making much ado about nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to remember that our mission is to reduce HIV
infection,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Drug abuse probably isn't the only element contributing to the
rising infection rates; complacency probably is a factor as well,
doctors and AIDS educators agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Younger people tend to underestimate the seriousness of HIV as
a disease,'' Bartels said.
</P>
<P>
   Because powerful new drugs have greatly extended the life spans
of HIV-positive people and improved their quality of life, many
people have the misperception that HIV is easily treated and
controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had a patient say to me, `Oh, it's just like living with
diabetes,' '' said Charles Dickey, a therapist with Anisman's
practice. ``That is totally erroneous.''
</P>
<P>
   The HIV drugs exact an enormous price, both financially and
physically: A year's worth of therapy costs $10,000 to $15,000 on
average and can cause debilitating side effects. Also, the drugs
are limited in number, and people can quickly build resistance to
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to see a resurgence of people going down the tubes
again, and it's going to happen in a very short period of time,''
Dickey said.
</P>
<P>
   Another growing problem is that older gay men, especially those
who have lived through much of the 20-year AIDS epidemic, are
emotionally exhausted and ready to relax their precautions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're so burned out, hearing about AIDS and safe sex,''
Anisman said. ``There are also some people who feel, `I'm going to
get the virus anyway, so what's the difference?'
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1331EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
