</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MLKPOLL18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two-thirds of Americans believe Ray didn't act alone in King's
death, poll shows
 &HT;    WITH POLLSIDE
 &HT;    By Arthur Brice
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Only one man was ever sought or charged in the
assassination of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr., but 31 years
after King's death, more than two-thirds of the country believes
that others besides James Earl Ray were involved in the killing, a
new Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll reveals.
</P>
<P>
   Results of the Journal-Constitution's Southern Focus Poll
suggest that the percentage of Americans who believe Ray was not
involved at all in the King shooting is greater than those who
believe Ray acted alone.
</P>
<P>
   Ray pleaded guilty in 1969 to killing the civil rights leader
but recanted within days. He maintained his innocence until his
death in April at the age of 70. The King family believes Ray is
innocent and supported his efforts over the last few years to
obtain the trial that he circumvented with his plea.
</P>
<P>
   The telephone poll showed that 12 percent of the public believes
Ray alone was reponsible. An additional 46 percent of Americans
believe Ray was partly responsible for King's death but others were
probably involved. Another 25 percent of Southerners (23 percent of
non-Southerners) believe that people other than Ray killed King.
The remainder said they didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 818 Southerners and 394 non-Southerners was
conducted Sept. 23-Nov. 15, 1998, and has a margin of error of plus
or minus 5 percentage points. Generally, there was little regional
difference in the responses given by Southerners and
non-Southerners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very happy that other people share our conclusions that
there were others involved,'' said Dexter Scott King, son of the
slain civil rights leader. ``It's encouraging because ... there was
never a full-blown trial to get to the bottom of everything.''
</P>
<P>
   At the instigation of the Kings, the Justice Department opened a
limited probe last year to investigate documents a former FBI agent
said he found in Ray's car in 1968 and also claims by a former
Memphis restaurant owner that he was paid $100,000 to hire an
assassin to kill King. The probe is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   Though most respondents said they believed others besides Ray
were involved, there was less support for more investigation.
Fifty-five percent of Southern and non-Southern respondents believe
no further investigation is needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's time to stop dredging all this stuff up,'' said poll
respondent Amy Cecil, a 49-year-old nursing home employee from
Lexington, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Dexter King said some people may feel a sense of hopelessness
because the murder happened such a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's understandable,'' he said. ``People honestly feel that
there's nothing that can be done, so why waste your time?''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-five percent of poll respondents (and 50 percent of
African-American respondents) said they would like to see more
federal investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are too many questions,'' said Beverly Niemzak, 40, a
homemaker in Gadsden, Ala. ``I don't know that the investigation
was ever taken far enough. ... There are too many things that just
shout that it wasn't done the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it was the government or something like that.
Just other people who had the same sentiments as him (Ray).''
</P>
<P>
   The House Select Committee on Assassinations reached a similar
conclusion in 1978 when it said after a two-year investigation that
Ray likely was involved in a conspiracy with two white supremacists
from St. Louis who were already dead by the time of the panel's
probe.
</P>
<P>
   African-Americans in particular are likely to believe people
other than Ray were involved. In the South, 42 percent of blacks
said they believed Ray was not involved in the slaying, that others
were responsible. Outside the South, 46 percent of blacks believed
Ray was innocent of the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothea Wise, a 34-year-old African-American from Durham, N.C.,
typified the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government may have had a little play in it,'' said Wise,
a customer service representative for Central Carolina Bank.
``James Earl Ray was just the man to be used and to take the fall
for everybody else. He was just a pawn.''
</P>
<P>
   On one point, poll respondents reached a strong consensus:
King's family has done a good job of preserving his memory.
</P>
<P>
   Despite complaints by some critics that the Kings have not done
as much as they could have to carry on King's work, the family got
high grades from most Americans _ an ``A'' grade from 50 percent of
Southerners and 47 percent of non-Southerners, and a ``B'' from 24
percent in the South and 26 percent of people in the rest of the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very encouraged by that,'' Dexter King said. ``We have
always sought to continue and follow in my father's footsteps by
the example he set through service to others. In spite of the
controversy out there, people realize we're committed to our work
and our cause.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
