</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES-PLAN18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Park works on plan for Everglades
 &HT;    By Robert P. King
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal government's $7.8 billion
Everglades rescue plan would provide more water for suburbs while
failing to restore South Florida's marshes and bays, scientists at
Everglades National Park say.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than scrap the plan, park leaders say they want to
help the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers fix it.
</P>
<P>
   That fixing has gone on furiously in recent weeks, as corps
engineers, South Florida water managers and other federal and state
officials have looked for ways to put more water into the park
during rainy seasons without drowning marshes to the north.
</P>
<P>
   But time is running short: The corps is set to finish the plan's
final draft in April, three months before submitting it to
Congress. Environmentalists, farmers and water utility directors
are trying to shape the blueprint.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, heartened by the plan yet frustrated by its
shortcomings, said they hope the park's blunt critique can help
steer it closer to a true Everglades restoration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're far apart at all,'' park Superintendent
Richard Ring said Friday after meeting in Washington with corps
restoration chief Stu Appelbaum and other federal officials. ``The
(plan) does a lot of good things. It doesn't get close enough in
certain key areas.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the park's scientists concluded Dec. 31 that the corps'
draft proposal _ made public in October _ would not fully restore
any part of the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   They said it would only add modest amounts of water to estuaries
in the southern part of the park, and could undermine pollution
cleanup efforts. It would leave too much territory fragmented by
canals and levees, especially in the northern Everglades. And
cities and suburbs would see big boosts in their water supplies
long before most of the environment got help.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is insufficient evidence to substantiate the claims that
(the plan) will result in the recovery of a healthy, sustainable
ecosystem,'' the scientists wrote. ``Rather, we find substantial,
credible, and compelling evidence to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps' proposal is aimed at creating more than 300 wells and
251,000 acres of marshes, reservoirs and quarries _ enough land to
blanket Manhattan a dozen times _ to reverse some of the worst
features of the South Florida's federally created drainage system.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers say the new features would store hundreds of
billions of gallons of water that canals now flush in muddy
torrents out to sea. That water would serve the region's growing
population, expected to double in the next 50 years, while
restoring some of the free flows that farming and development have
robbed from the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   Other state and federal agencies have offered more positive
critiques, asserting that the plan would improve fishing in Lake
Okeechobee and Florida Bay, prevent droughts and aid imperiled
endangered species such as wood storks and manatees.
</P>
<P>
   Even Ring offered a conciliatory message in a letter to the
corps Thursday (1/14), saying the plan would create ``substantial
improvements'' over South Florida's sprawl-ridden status quo.
</P>
<P>
   He said Friday that his agency's criticisms were meant to help
the corps, not attack it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure wouldn't want anybody beating around the bush on
anything the park service was doing,'' Ring said.
</P>
<P>
   The corps' Appelbaum added: ``These issues are not new issues.
We've been working steadily to make progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, the corps and other agencies have drafted proposals for
looping additional water from the West Palm Beach Canal and other
coastal waterways back into the Everglades. They also have sped up
their proposed timetable for elevating a stretch of Tamiami Trail
so water can sluice more freely into the park.
</P>
<P>
   Ring and Appelbaum said it's too early to say how much the new
features would add to the project's price, which is already
expected to be roughly $400 million a year for 20 years. Park
scientists said the plan should include a proposal to scrape
polluted muck from the bottom of Lake Okeechobee, which could cost
$1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups largely support the corps plan, calling it
the Everglades' last chance. Still, some activists have organized a
telephone campaign to buoy Ring and his staff, Broward County
environmentalist Patti Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Their message: ``Stick to your guns,'' Webster said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
