<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6690 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-PREPAID-TUITION18     01-17 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-PREPAID-TUITION18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Kiplinger' rates Fla. prepaid college plan among worst in U.S.
 &HT;    By Don Horine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With a couple of weeks to go until the
1998-99 enrollment deadline, the Florida Prepaid College Program
got some unwanted publicity last week: A respected national
publication ripped the program as one of the worst in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The prepaid tuition programs run by Florida and Alabama received
grades of C- _ the two lowest ratings _ by Kiplinger's Personal
Finance Magazine.
</P>
<P>
   There were two reasons. First, Kiplinger's said it considers
savings plans _ which 20 states have in place and 20 others are
planning to start _ as superior to prepaid-tuition plans because
they have a gentler impact on financial aid eligibility and have
the potential of earning higher returns because they are usually
invested partly in the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Second, Kiplinger's noted, Florida and Alabama require
purchasers to take on a risk that other states do not. If a student
for whom a Florida or Alabama contract has been purchased doesn't
go to college, the purchaser gets back only the amount put in _
with no interest.
</P>
<P>
   In prepaid-tuition plans, purchasers pay for four years of
college and sometimes dormitory costs at current prices. When a
student is ready for his freshman year, the account will cover
tuition, no matter how much it has gone up.
</P>
<P>
   According to Florida officials, its plan is the largest of its
kind in the country, having sold more contracts than all other
states combined. By Jan. 29, when the current enrollment period
ends, officials project the program will have sold 500,000
contracts since 1987, most of them for tuition and others for
housing.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Wallace, executive director of Florida's program, disagreed
with Kiplinger's assessment that investment plans were better than
prepaid plans. While purchasers of investment plans can earn
interest, they also run the risk of losing a lot if the economy
goes downhill, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under our program, no matter what happens to you, or inflation
or the economy or the cost of education, you are guaranteed your
costs will be paid for,'' he said. ``You can't put a price tag on
that. They didn't give good enough weight to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wallace agreed with Kiplinger's that Florida imposes a heavy
penalty if a student doesn't use the plan. To minimize that, he
said, officials are asking the legislature this year to allow
students to receive as much money from their prepaid plan toward
tuition at a trade school as they would have received under a state
university or community college contract.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace doubted the article would have much of an effect on the
number of signed contracts returned by Jan. 29. About
three-quarters of the contracts usually come in during the last two
weeks ``and I suspect it'll be the same this year,'' he said.53E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
