<HEADER>
A6692 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TX-TOBACCO18-COX     01-17 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-TOBACCO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paying the state's tobacco lawyers: It's not over yet
 &HT;    By Osler McCarthy
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The great Texas tobacco case was supposed to be
over.
</P>
<P>
   The injured party _ the state of Texas _ has been getting money
from its judgment in the largest single legal settlement in
history. The state's lawyers have already received their first $200
million paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   Squabbling and fighting and hair-pulling over the attorneys'
fees all was supposed to have ended.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The $17.3 billion Texas tobacco litigation is destined for
another stop in federal court to find a way to settle the festering
dispute over how much the five private lawyers hired by the state
should be paid.
</P>
<P>
   At issue: Attorney General John Cornyn, who has been on the job
for two weeks, has announced an investigation of the lawyers'
conduct. He says they might have acted illegally or unethically in
representing the state. If he were to allege wrongdoing, he could
sue the lawyers, who were hired by his predecessor. If he were to
win, he could strip them of any fees in the case.
</P>
<P>
   As it stands now, the lawyers are being paid by the tobacco
industry. But a pending federal court order awards the lawyers part
of the state's take in the case. Because of Cornyn's investigation,
they have refused to sign over their right to being paid by the
state instead of the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he wants us to do is to renounce the court order
immediately while he, Cornyn, takes his sweet time investigating,''
said University of Texas law professor Charles Silver, who
represents the lawyers former Attorney General Dan Morales hired.
``Why should we go on forever litigating this?''
</P>
<P>
   The possibility of taxpayers footing the bill for legal fees is
the very thing that Cornyn and fellow Republican Gov. George W.
Bush have worked to guard against throughout the long-running
dispute over fees.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco lawsuit sought to reimburse the state for the cost
of treating ill smokers. The case was settled in January 1998
without going to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn has said the attorney fees being paid by the tobacco
industry _ calculated at $3.3 billion over 25 years _ are too high.
He rekindled fears last week that he might try to challenge the
fees, which were set by an arbitration panel. In a letter last week
to John Eddie Williams of Houston, one of the private lawyers,
Cornyn said the fee is ``clearly excessive and unreasonable.'' He
wrote that the lawyers ``should be more than satisfied with a
smaller award.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver said the prospect that Cornyn may be trying to force a
showdown on fees could force them to litigate Cornyn's concerns
before the federal judge supervising the lawsuit and perhaps to
choose to collect from the state. The alternative could be facing a
suit brought by Cornyn in state court, before a new judge
unfamiliar with the case.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over attorney's fees flared anew two weeks ago when
the private lawyers asked U.S. District Judge David Folsom for more
time before making their decision to take their fee from the
tobacco companies. Under an agreement with Bush and seven
legislators who sued to protest the attorney fees, all agreed to
let arbitrators decide the amount of the fees the tobacco companies
would pay. The agreement left open the option for the lawyers to be
paid by the state.
</P>
<P>
   When the lawyers refused to sign away that option on Dec. 30,
Bush and Cornyn characterized that as an attempt by the lawyers to
get more money from the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``General Cornyn would oppose any effort from these attorneys to
come after any taxpayer money,'' said Cornyn's spokesman, Ted
Delisi.
</P>
<P>
   Silver said his clients simply want to give Cornyn time to
complete his investigation and had no intention of asking the state
for more money. But he said if Cornyn challenges the arbitration
award, the lawyers might be forced to come after the state for
their paycheck. The arbitrators awarded the lawyers 19 percent of
the state's $17.3 billion award _ calculated to be $3.3 billion
over 25 years. The federal court order set their fee at 15 percent
of the state's award _ or $2.6 billion over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Cornyn was not threatening to challenge their
arbitration fees, the lawyers might be better off claiming their
money from the state. Under the rules of multibillion-dollar
finance, $2.6 billion could be worth more than $3.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That's because if the lawyers collect from the state, they could
file and lien and take their money up front. Because of inflation,
$2.6 billion now would be worth more than $2.6 billion 25 years
from now.
</P>
<P>
   If the private attorneys collect from the tobacco companies,
they must be paid from a $500 million a year fund set up to pay
lawyers in all the states' tobacco cases. That amount would not
grow with inflation and would become smaller over time, as more and
more lawyers who sued the industry on behalf of other states share
in the pot of money.
</P>
<P>
   The private lawyers have asked for a conference with Folsom, who
is expected to set a hearing soon. Cornyn has not offered details
of the possible wrongdoing his office is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to investigate the facts surrounding the tobacco
litigation to determine if civil or criminal wrongdoing has been
committed,'' he said last week, without offering details.
</P>
<P>
   Some, including the private lawyers, have questioned whether
Houston attorney Marc Murr, who was awarded $1 million in fees,
performed any substantive work on the case. Morales hired Murr, a
friend and former colleague, as an adviser on the case. Others have
said the private lawyers might have acted against the state's
interest by arranging to be paid separately from the state instead
of letting the full award come to the state and then taking their
share from that.
</P>
<P>
   Morales said Cornyn's investigation is a proper step for a new
officeholder _ and he is confident Cornyn will find everything was
proper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Admittedly, this has been a complex and sophisticated
litigation matter,'' Morales said. ``I do not begrudge John one
iota to fully investigation the litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
