 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
(js) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of Monday, Jan.
18:
</P>
<P>
   CULTURE
</P>
<P>
   (Coded e)
</P>
<P>
   CIVIL-RIGHTS-PHOTOS (New York) _ The debut of ``America and the
Civil Rights Movement, 1954-1968'' offers more than 50 images
documenting the civil rights movement. The photographs are
accompanied by text and information-laden captions because, the
show's curator says, many people still do not know why a civil
rights movement was needed. By Felicia R. Lee.
</P>
<P>
   UNKNOWN-INDIAN-MUSEUM (Los Angeles) _ The Southwest Museum, the
oldest museum in Los Angeles, is considered by many experts to be
one of the top collections of American Indian artifacts in the
country. The collection, only about 2 percent of which is ever on
display, focuses on the Indians of the Southwest, the Great Basin,
California, the Plains and the Northwest. It is also nearly
unknown, except to scholars, By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   HAUNTED-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``The Haunted Wood,'' by Allen
Weinstein and Alexander Vassilliev, is a history of Soviet
espionage in America during Stalin's dictatorship and will appeal
most of all to readers thoroughly familiar with the previous record
of Soviet espionage. Reviewed by Christopher Lehmann-Haupt.
</P>
<P>
   MOONDRUNK-MUSIC-REVIEW (New York) _ ``Moondrunk'' is part of a
valorous attempt by Lincoln Center's ``Great Performers'' series to
give classical concerts a new look in different venues. One is
thankful even while disagreeing with some of the results. Reviewed
by Bernard Holland.
</P>
<P>
   TV-HOOVER-REVIEW (Undated) _ Monday night's ``American
Experience'' leaves no doubt that the Hoover Dam was quite a gamble
for its time and produced big winnings for its major players and
for America's Southwest. Reviewed by Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   TV-NIGHT-REVIEW (Undated) _ Rick Schroder is hot. This week the
young star (a recent addition to ``N.Y.P.D. Blue'') is on the cover
of TV Guide, smiling just above the words ``He's great!'' On Monday
night he's the star of an ABC movie, ``What We Did That Night.''
Well, every career move can't be a winner. Reviewed by Anita Gates.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Coded f)
</P>
<P>
   VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TALKS (Undated) _ It took two weeks of
all-night strategy sessions and telephone calls between
sleep-deprived executives in four time zones for Vodafone to woo
Airtouch from the embrace of Bell Atlantic. Vodafone prevailed and
last Friday announced a $60 billion Vodafone-Airtouch combination
that will create a global wireless powerhouse to rival
telecommunications blockbusters like AT&AMP;T or British
Telecommunications. By Laura Holson.
</P>
<P>
   AIRTOUCH-GINN-PROFILE (Los Angeles) _ Sam Ginn's gamble has paid
off, in a huge way. With the acquisition of Airtouch Communications
Inc. by Vodafone Group PLC, Ginn, the chairman and chief executive
of Airtouch, will walk away with hundreds of millions of dollars
from stock and options he owns. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   LINUX-MICROSOFT-CHALLENGE (Undated) _ A young Swiss programmer
is coordinating a project intended to let PC users run their
normally Windows-dependent programs on Linux _ a free operating
system, whose devotees would very much like to overthrow
Microsoft's hegemony. The growing numbers of proponents of the open
source software movement argue that open source is the path to
higher quality, more reliable programs. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   ONLINE-ANTISMUT-LAW (Undated) _ The American Civil Liberties
Union and 15 other groups and businesses have filed a lawsuit to
overturn the Child Online Protection Act, which makes it a crime
for a commercial Web site to knowingly make available to those
under 17 certain sexually explicit material. The ACLU contends that
a virtual brown-paper wrapper would undercut not just free speech
online but Internet commerce. Hearings are scheduled to begin
Wednesday in U.S. District Court in Philadelphia. By Pamela
Mendels.
</P>
<P>
   DIGICOM-COLUMN (Undated) _ Few industries have gorged themselves
on digital commerce with greater appetite than the
telecommunications companies. But the result has been a wired world
that to many customers seems like a cross between the best-known
works of Edvard Munch and Jean-Paul Sartre: we scream, but there is
no exit. By Denis Caruso.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FRENZY-MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ You want Internet
companies? We'll give you Internet companies. That's the message
Wall Street is sending investors in the first quarter. But analysts
are warning that investors could suffer huge losses by eagerly
chasing these hot and volatile issues. By David Barboza.
</P>
<P>
   BOND-CALENDAR (Undated) _ The week's planned offerings.
</P>
<P>
   EQUITIES (Undated) _ Equity issues coming to market this week.
</P>
<P>
   DIVIDEND-MEETINGS (Undated) _ Major meetings this week.
</P>
<P>
   BIZGLANCE (Undated) _ Major financial stories at a glance.
</P>
<P>
   PATENTS (Undated) _ The weekly patents column. By Teresa
Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIA-BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Coding varies.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-HITS-MEDIA (Pasadena, Calif.) _ Maybe network television can
still produce hits after all. In five days, three networks started
new series and all of them scored ratings that would qualify them
as significant hits, by far the biggest new hits of what has been a
woebegone television season. By Bill Carter.
</P>
<P>
   TV-TABLOIDS-MEDIA (Undated) _ At the very moment when tabloid
topics have become big news in the most respected newspaper and
television news programs, the generation of shows that spawned the
term ``tabloid television'' is dying. From a heyday when there were
a half-dozen such shows, only three remain. Tabloid news magazines
have withered because certain kinds of tabloid-style stories have
migrated to the traditional news organizations. By Laurie Mifflin.
</P>
