<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILD-ABUSE-DEATHS18-     01-17 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILD-ABUSE-DEATHS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Child abuse resulting in death reflects trend
 &HT;    By Shannon Joyce
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ In the past month, authorities believe
two Western Slope children were killed and one was seriously
injured by men who were caring for them but who were not their
biological fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Local mental health and social service professionals say the
incidents reflect a dangerous pattern among young parents who
cannot control their anger.
</P>
<P>
   And if the cases are proven in court, these incidences would
parallel national statistics that show when a child is abused by a
person who is not the biological parent, eight times out of 10 it's
a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we tend to see in young parents is the inability to deal
with the frustrations of child rearing and their own feelings,''
said Tom Papin, director of the Mesa County Department of Human
Services.
</P>
<P>
   When these parents become frustrated or angry with their kids,
Papin said, they often resort to beatings.
</P>
<P>
   But Sally Schaefer, the CEO of Hilltop Community Resources Inc.,
a local organization that provides social services to young
parents, said it's more than the men not being able to control
their tempers. Fathers, Schaefer said _ especially those who are
the primary caretakers of their children or stepchildren _ have
fewer places to turn for help than young mothers.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said Hilltop has a pre-natal care program and a support
group for young mothers, but the funding for its young fathers
program was cut several years ago. Several local organizations
offer parenting classes for couples, she said, but the lack of
programs aimed at young men and their problems creates a detectable
void.
</P>
<P>
   According to authorities, the recent spate of high-profile child
abuse cases started two weeks before Christmas:
</P>
<P>
   _ On Dec. 10, 1998, Ashley Brown, 3, suffered at least three
blows to her head, immediately knocking her unconscious. She died a
week later.
</P>
<P>
   Her stepfather, Michael Hunter, 18, was arrested and charged
with first-degree murder and child abuse resulting in death. Hunter
said Ashley fell from a two-foot tall doll house onto a carpeted
floor and then wouldn't wake up after she took a nap, according to
court records.
</P>
<P>
   Court records stated Hunter has an extensive criminal record,
including convictions for burglary and arson. He was cited with
child abuse and neglect on Nov. 20, 1998, for allowing Ashley's
sister to play in the street.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Jan. 4, 14-month-old Kayanna Pierce suffered three fatal
skull fractures, according to court records. Her mother's
boyfriend, Jeremiah ``Jerry'' Duran, 20, was arrested and charged
with first-degree murder in the death. Duran and the girl's mother,
Bethany Gerard, told investigators the girl was choking and stopped
breathing, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   Both Duran and Gerard had been investigated for child abuse
twice, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   _ On Jan. 5, a 3-year-old Montrose boy was allegedly beaten and
submerged in scalding water, suffering second-degree burns, police
said. Christopher Krebs, 25, the child's mother's boyfriend, was
arrested and held in jail in the boy's beating.
</P>
<P>
   Krebs said the boy fell into the water, but authorities didn't
find any injuries to suggest the boy tried to catch himself from
falling, according to court records. The boy's biological father
said he had also expressed concerns that the boy and his 6-year-old
brother might have been abused.
</P>
<P>
   There are some similarities between either all or some of the
cases. For example, Krebs and Duran are not married to the alleged
victims' mothers, and Krebs and Hunter were watching the toddlers
while their mothers worked when the injuries occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Also, all three cases reflect trends found in studies of child
abuse, including that when a child is abused by someone who is not
a parent, the abuser is likely to be a young man.
</P>
<P>
   A study published by the U.S. Department of Health and Human
Services in 1993 stated 28 percent of abused children are abused by
someone who is not their biological parent. Of those children, 90
percent were abused by a man and 40 percent were abused by someone
under the age of 26.
</P>
<P>
   For children who are abused by a biological parent, the abusers
are almost evenly split between mothers and fathers.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of a child's death, Papin, with the Mesa County
Department of Human Services, said many people wonder why the child
wasn't removed from the home before the child died.
</P>
<P>
   Because of confidentiality rules, Papin said he could not
comment on specific cases. But he said, even if the person has a
past criminal history, Human Services can do little without clear
evidence the child is in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't take every child out of the home,'' Papin said.
``There are so many gray areas; we can't just walk in and shoot
from the hip.''
</P>
<P>
   In a case like Ashley's, when the suspect in a child's murder
was investigated by his agency, Papin said Human Services conducts
an internal review of the agency's work and files a report with the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Legally, there's not much else concerned parents can do if they
suspect a stepparent or partner of their ex-spouse is abusing their
child. In addition to filing a complaint with Human Services, the
law also allows parents to file a complaint in divorce court.
</P>
<P>
   If the person has a violent criminal history, a judge can
prohibit a parent or stepparent from having contact with the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a perception regarding the power we have,'' Papin
said. ``We don't have the authority to remove a child.''
</P>
<P>
   Papin said social workers work closely with law enforcement
officers, the child's school, the courts and the Colorado West
Mental Heath Center on each case.
</P>
<P>
   Once a complaint is received, he said, social workers review any
past complaints and develop a plan of action.
</P>
<P>
   Usually a social worker is sent to the home to interview the
family and decide if the children are safe, Papin said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's first goal is to keep a family together, Papin
said, but if caseworkers believe the child is in danger, either the
police or the courts can help them remove the child from the home.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are checks and balances,'' Papin said. ``We can't send a
social worker to your house and say, `Give me your kid.''' In some
cases, Papin said, the case is closed during the initial review; in
others, the separated family has to follow a regimen of counseling
and supervised visitation.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer, with Hilltop, and Papin agree that in many cases, the
counseling must focus on ways to deal with anger.
</P>
<P>
   Schaefer said unless a parent knows other disciplinary
techniques, inexperienced parents revert back to basic emotions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't have parenting skills, you go to the basic
instincts; yelling and hitting,'' Schaefer said. ``If you don't
have any other tools, that's what's left.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
