<HEADER>
A6722 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     01-17 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; IN THE THICK OF BATTLE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco writer  &UR; Marilyn Wann &LR; 's piercingly funny _ OK,
jolly, but the word seems un-PC _ book ``Fat!So?'' (Ten Speed;
$12.95) includes a set of cut-out trading cards portraying ``The
Heroes and Villains of Fat History.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the villains: Weight Watcher  &UR; Jean Nidetch &LR; ; cq  &UR; Irving &LR; 
 &UR; Fisher &LR; , who invented calorie-counting in 1906; and former Surgeon
General &UR; C. Everett Koop, &LR;  who held a news conference to ``declare
war on fat (and fatsoes).''
</P>
<P>
   Among the heroes: Wagnerian soprano  &UR; Amalie Materna &LR; , who
``created the fat lady icon in opera'';  &UR; Saartjie Baartman &LR; , a
South African tribal woman who became a circus attraction, the
Hottentot Venus; and  &UR; Rene Laennec &LR; , inventor of the stethoscope.
</P>
<P>
   Wann quotes Laennec's account of examining a fat young woman in
1816. ``Owing to her stoutness little information could be gathered
by application of the hand and percussion. ... I recalled a
well-known acoustic phenomenon: namely, if you place your ear
against one end of a wooden beam the scratch of a pin at the other
extremity is most distinctly audible. ... Taking a sheaf of paper I
rolled it into a very tight roll. ... I was both surprised and
gratified at being able to hear the beating of the heart with much
greater clearness and distinctness than I had ever done before.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; IVANA HOLDS ONTO EVERY NAME &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Upon learning that Culture Club, a new Manhattan restaurant with
an '80s theme, wanted to name one of its drinks the Donald and
another the Ivana, lawyers for &UR; Ivana Trump  &LR; filed legal papers
saying that ``Ivana, Ivana's, Ivana Trump and other related names''
are her ``intellectual property.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the former Mrs. Trump is no longer married to ``the
Donald,'' she said that name belongs to her, too, because she made
it up, and because the Donald, although once commonly used for Ms.
Trump's ex, is the term currently used ``to refer to Ms. Trump's
son.''
</P>
<P>
   The club owners told the New York Daily News that even though
 &UR; Donald Trump &LR;  had approved the use of his name, they would respect
his former wife's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - In San Francisco on Thursday, guitarist  &UR; Squid Vicious &LR; 
literally bumped into  &UR; Mick Jagger &LR; , the former strolling down
Valencia Street, the latter emerging _ with bodyguard and driver _
from a restaurant and ducking into his car.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; - Jimmy Carter  &LR; is writing his first novel, set in Georgia
during the Revolutionary War. An aide told the Atlanta Journal
Constitution that he's hard at work on historical research, and he
says it makes him ``feel like he's back in college.''
</P>
<P>
   - ProfNet, an online news site for academic institutions and
technology companies, includes an item in which a New York woman is
``assembling the long-awaited Studmuffins of Science'' calendar for
Y2K. The woman says she's looking ``for sources from universities
who can recommend attractive male science-types'' who might
participate. She's hoping to round up candidates by the end of the
week, when she's planning to stage a promotional event at the
convention of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   - That Starr Wars poster being passed around the Net appeared in
the January issue of Mad magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Just Eight, a new matching service in Los Angeles, offers
singles the opportunity of six dinners at trendy restaurants,
accompanied by seven other gourmet singles. The cost, says Wine and
Food magazine, is $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cosmopolitan magazine bestowed upon &UR; Liv Tyler  &LR; a ``Fun,
Fearless Female Award'' for the amazing feat of having her hair
cut. Elsewhere in the wide world of Important Things That Women Do,
the Chicago Tribune quotes  &UR; Whoopi Goldberg  &LR; pondering her role in
history: ``Who would have thought that I would be hosting the last
Oscar telecast of the century?''
</P>
<P>
   - The Hollywood Historic Trust is selling letters of the famous
hillside ``Hollywood'' sign for $100,000 a year on the QVC Home
Shopping Network on January 23 and 24. Corporations who ``buy''
letters can't identify themselves on the sign, but can use pictures
of it in advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   - Gung Hay Fat Tuesday: The Chinese New Year and the first day
of Lent coincide this year, on February 26.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Change is so important. Otherwise it's so easy to get &LR; 
 &UR; stuck.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Patti Hansen &LR; , who used to be a model and has been married to
Rolling Stone Keith Richards for about 20 years, shares her wisdom
with readers of More, the Ladies' Home Journal offspring that touts
itself as ``smart talk for smart women.''
</P>
</TEXT>
