   &UR; - Jimmy Carter  &LR; is writing his first novel, set in Georgia
during the Revolutionary War. An aide told the Atlanta Journal
Constitution that he's hard at work on historical research, and he
says it makes him ``feel like he's back in college.''
</P>
<P>
   - ProfNet, an online news site for academic institutions and
technology companies, includes an item in which a New York woman is
``assembling the long-awaited Studmuffins of Science'' calendar for
Y2K. The woman says she's looking ``for sources from universities
who can recommend attractive male science-types'' who might
participate. She's hoping to round up candidates by the end of the
week, when she's planning to stage a promotional event at the
convention of the American Association for the Advancement of
Science in Anaheim.
</P>
<P>
   - That Starr Wars poster being passed around the Net appeared in
the January issue of Mad magazine.
</P>
<P>
   - Just Eight, a new matching service in Los Angeles, offers
singles the opportunity of six dinners at trendy restaurants,
accompanied by seven other gourmet singles. The cost, says Wine and
Food magazine, is $1,500.
</P>
<P>
   _ Cosmopolitan magazine bestowed upon &UR; Liv Tyler  &LR; a ``Fun,
Fearless Female Award'' for the amazing feat of having her hair
cut. Elsewhere in the wide world of Important Things That Women Do,
the Chicago Tribune quotes  &UR; Whoopi Goldberg  &LR; pondering her role in
history: ``Who would have thought that I would be hosting the last
Oscar telecast of the century?''
</P>
<P>
   - The Hollywood Historic Trust is selling letters of the famous
hillside ``Hollywood'' sign for $100,000 a year on the QVC Home
Shopping Network on January 23 and 24. Corporations who ``buy''
letters can't identify themselves on the sign, but can use pictures
of it in advertising campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   - Gung Hay Fat Tuesday: The Chinese New Year and the first day
of Lent coincide this year, on February 26.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``Change is so important. Otherwise it's so easy to get &LR; 
 &UR; stuck.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Patti Hansen &LR; , who used to be a model and has been married to
Rolling Stone Keith Richards for about 20 years, shares her wisdom
with readers of More, the Ladies' Home Journal offspring that touts
itself as ``smart talk for smart women.''
</P>
