A6728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CULTURE-NOTES-ART-NYT     01-17 0515
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CULTURE-NOTES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: `GODOT' IN CHICAGO; AT HOME WITH THE BRITISH MUSEUM;
THE LONDON SYMPHONY ORCHESTRA AND THE TITANIC; GEORGE WASHINGTON'S
NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., N.J., N.Y., U.K.)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ON THE ROAD
</P>
<P>
   The tramps are coming. Samuel Beckett's immortal tramps,
Vladimir and Estragon, that is. In Chicago Monday night, they will
be swapping vaudeville routines and musing metaphysically at the
Goodman Theater in ``Waiting for Godot.'' Starring Andre De Shields
and Ross Lehman and directed by Michael Maggio, the production will
run through Feb. 20. Information: (312) 443-3800.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSE HUNTING
</P>
<P>
   In 1754, trustees of the British Museum, founded by an act of
Parliament a year earlier, purchased for the museum's home, the
Montagu House, which stood among fields and streams on the
outskirts of London in Bloomsbury. Montagu House was soon outgrown
as the collections of books, manuscripts, natural history specimens
and antiquities increased. In 1823, Robert Smirke was commissioned
to design a home that, with its Greek Revival facade, has become
the international symbol of a museum. The institution is still
growing and changing, and from Saturday to April 18 it will be the
subject of ``Building the British Museum,'' an exhibition devoted
to the history of the homes it has occupied for nearly 250 years.
Information: 011-44-171-636-1555.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL NEWS
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Today's news is that the London Symphony Orchestra,
led by Sir Colin Davis, will play this week in New Jersey and New
York. Yesteryear's news is that the orchestra, founded in 1904, was
to arrive in 1912 aboard the RMS Titanic to begin the first U.S.
tour by a British orchestra. But when the 21-day, 23-city,
32-concert tour was rescheduled from late April to April 2, the
ensemble departed on March 28 aboard the RMS Baltic. The oldest
surviving orchestra in London will be spotlighting Edward Elgar
(its music director in 1911-12) and Beethoven on Saturday at
Prudential Hall at the New Jersey Performing Arts Center in Newark
and at Avery Fisher Hall at Lincoln Center on Sunday and Jan. 25
and 26 in the Great Performers' series ``The Glory of Britain: Sir
Edward Elgar.'' P.S.: This time, the orchestra will arrive by
plane. Information, New Jersey: (888) 466-5722. Information, New
York: (212) 721-6500.
</P>
<P>
   LOCAL HERO
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ His name adorns streets, avenues, parks,
neighborhoods, bridges and a triumphal arch. But George Washington
(1732-1799), commander in chief of the Continental Army and first
president of the United States, was not a New Yorker. Still, as a
general, he knew victory and defeat in New York and as president he
was a New York resident from April 1789 to the summer of 1790. From
Saturday through July 4, the city as he experienced it will be the
focus of ``Washington's New York,'' an exhibition at the Museum of
the City of New York comprising art and artifacts from the
Revolution through his presidency. Information: (212) 534-1672.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
