<SLUG> BC-ADVERTISING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOUNTS AND PEOPLE IN THE ADVERTISING WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marine Midland Bank in Buffalo, a unit of HSBC Group, has named
Partners &AMP; Shevack/Wolf in New York, part of Wolf Group, to handle
its marketing communications account, which had been at the Buffalo
office of Eric Mower &AMP; Associates. Billings were estimated at $25
million.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after a three-month review that had been
narrowed to Shevack/Wolf and two other New York-based finalists,
both of which withdrew from consideration in November: the Bates
USA unit of Cordiant Communications Group PLC and the D'Arcy Masius
Benton &AMP; Bowles Communications unit of MacManus Group.
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham Ends Bermuda Relationship
</P>
<P>
   DDB Needham New York has resigned the Bermuda Department of
Tourism account, which the agency had handled for a decade, by
withdrawing from a review that began last month. Billings were
estimated at $10 million to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tate, president at DDB Needham New York _ part of the DDB
Needham Worldwide unit of Omnicom Group _ attributed the withdrawal
to ``the increasingly political environment surrounding tourism in
Bermuda,'' which led the agency ``to apply our talent and energy
where we believe our chances are significantly greater.'' His
reference was to the fact that the review began after an election
that brought a change in parties controlling the Bermuda
government.
</P>
<P>
   The other agencies participating in the review have not been
identified; Adweek reported last week that 15 or more had been
invited to take part.
</P>
<P>
   Hachette Closes a Magazine
</P>
<P>
   Hachette Filipacchi Magazines in New York, a unit of Lagardere
Group, has made a number of personnel changes as it closed a
publication.
</P>
<P>
   John Fennell, executive vice president and chief operating
officer, said that the company closed Eating Well magazine because
it had not been attracting enough advertising or circulation.
Eating Well was started in 1990 by Telemedia Inc.; Hachette bought
a 50 percent stake in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   E. Michelle Amlong, 34, who had been publisher at Eating Well,
becomes associate publisher at George magazine, succeeding Deborah
Marcogliese, who left. Lawrence Brittan, 34, who had been
advertising director at Eating Well, was named to the vacant post
of advertising director at Family Life magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Family Life, Lucille Sitra, 44, a regional sales
director at Hachette, was promoted to vice president and publisher.
She succeeds Carolyn Bekkedahl, who left to become publishing
director at Shape magazine in Los Angeles, published by Weider
Publications Inc. And Michael Hyman, 48, corporate marketing
director at Hachette, was named to the new post of vice president
for marketing at George.
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Moves Two Assignments
</P>
<P>
   Hasbro Inc. in Pawtucket, R.I., is expanding its relationships
with two roster agencies by awarding them the accounts of brands
previously sold by Galoob Toys Inc., which Hasbro acquired last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The Micro Machines account, with billings estimated at $22
million, was reassigned to Grey Advertising in New York from Towne,
Silverstein, Rotter in New York. The assignment includes licensed
products to be sold in conjunction with the next three ``Star
Wars'' films.
</P>
<P>
   And the Pound Puppies account was reassigned to Jordan McGrath
Case &AMP; Partners in New York, also from Towne, Silverstein. Billings
on that brand, which Jordan McGrath introduced in 1985, were
estimated at $9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Accounts
</P>
<P>
   Bayer Pursell LLC, Birmingham, Ala., a joint venture of the
agricultural division of Bayer AG and Pursell Industries, a
fertilizer maker, to BBDO South, Atlanta, part of Omnicom, as its
first national agency of record. Though billings were not
disclosed, Adweek estimated that they could be as much as $20
million.
</P>
<P>
   CB Richard Ellis, Los Angeles, to Horizon Media, Los Angeles, to
handle media planning and buying for the company, which offers real
estate services like property sales and leasing. Billings were
estimated at $5 million to $10 million. Creative duties continue
in-house.
</P>
<P>
   Astoria Federal Savings and Loan Association, Lake Success,
N.Y., part of Astoria Financial Corp., to Brouillard
Communications, New York, owned by WPP Group PLC, to handle its
advertising and public relations account, which had been at
Greenstone Roberts Advertising, Melville, N.Y. Billings were
estimated at $4 million to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb, Rochester, N.Y., expanded its relationship with
Bozell Worldwide, New York, a unit of True North Communications, by
consolidating the Revo sunglasses account at the agency, which also
handles Bausch &AMP; Lomb accounts like contact lenses and Ray-Ban
sunglasses. Revo had been at Citron Haligman Bedecarre, San
Francisco, since October. Billings were estimated at $1 million to
$2 million.
</P>
<P>
   People
</P>
<P>
   Al Paz, executive vice president and client services director at
Robert Becker Inc. Euro RSCG, New York, a unit of Havas
Advertising, was named president and chief strategic officer. He
assumes the president's title from Sander Flaum, chief executive,
who was named to the new post of chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Smith was named to the new post of account services
director at Fallon McElligott New York City. He had been vice
president and group director at Kirshenbaum Bond &AMP; Partners, New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Ginsburg was named to the new post of senior vice
president for business development at Lois/EJL New York, a unit of
Lois/USA. He had been president and partner at HBG Advertising in
New York, which was recently acquired by Lois/EJL.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Dukmejian was named publisher at Mutual Funds magazine,
New York, part of the Time Inc. unit of Time Warner Inc.,
succeeding Edward Frey, who left. Dukmejian had been director for
sales development at Sports Illustrated magazine, New York, also
part of Time Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt DeMars, special projects manager at Out magazine, New York,
published by Out Publishing Inc., was promoted to advertising
director. He succeeds Amy Simmons, who was named publisher at HIV
Plus, a new magazine also from Out Publishing.
</P>
<P>
   Eden Collinsworth was named to the new position of cross-media
business development director at Hearst Corp., New York. She had
most recently been president and chief executive at Buzz Inc., Los
Angeles, which closed.
</P>
<P>
   Paige Powell was named to the new post of West Coast marketing
and editorial strategist at Paper magazine, New York, published by
Paper Publishing Co. Ms. Powell, who will be based in Portland,
Ore., had been president at Paige Powell Productions, Portland,
Ore. Also at Paper, Hunter Hill, advertising manager, was promoted
to the new post of development director.
</P>
</TEXT>
