<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6733 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNKNOWN-INDIAN-MUSEUM     01-17 1183
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNKNOWN-INDIAN-MUSEUM-870&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHWEST'S SPIRIT RIDES ON VAN GOGH'S COATTAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., states of the Southwest, Northwest and Plains)  (js) 
 BY JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Los Angeles County Museum of Art had been an
excited beehive of activity in recent months as it prepared to open
its biggest show in years, ``Van Gogh: Masterpieces From the Van
Gogh Museum, Amsterdam.'' Already the show, which opened Sunday,
has been extended by six weeks into May, and nearly a third of the
tickets, which are going for as much as $20 each, have been sold.
</P>
<P>
   But the greatest beneficiary of this blockbuster exhibition may
not be the LACMA, as the county museum is known: it could well
prove to be the highly regarded, if nearly forgotten Southwest
Museum, which is exhibiting American Indian artifacts in a corner
of the county museum's newly refurbished exhibition space where the
van Goghs are on display. The institution is wagering that the huge
crowds expected at the van Gogh show will stay around to see the
magnificent and rare Navajo and Pueblo textiles it is showing. In
short, it is hoped that the popularity of the Dutch master will
help in the rebirth of the Southwest Museum. The Southwest Museum
was founded in 1907 and is the oldest museum in this city. It is
considered by many experts to be one of the top three or four
collections of American Indian artifacts in the country.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, only about 2 percent of which is ever on
display, focuses on the Indians of the Southwest, the Great Basin,
California, the Plains and the Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   It includes about 140,000 photographs recording aspects of
Indian culture and life that have long since disappeared; in fact,
many of these items were acquired near the turn of the century when
experts realized Indian tribes were moving inexorably from the wild
to reservations, and that this was the last opportunity for
preserving artifacts from the old way of life.
</P>
<P>
   The collection is considered encyclopedic and irreplaceable. It
is also nearly unknown, except to scholars, and that is where the
popularity of the melancholy painter may help. The hope is that
visitors to the van Gogh show will saunter into the Southwest
Museum's annex at the site, and that that may draw them later to
visit the museum's principal space in the out-of-the-way
neighborhood of Mount Washington, about halfway between downtown
Los Angeles and Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   At the least, the Southwest Museum's three-year lease of the
space from the county museum, which could be extended by decades if
this strategy proves a success, has opened up the vast storerooms
of the museum. Only a couple dozen of the more than 200 textiles
and rugs on display have ever been seen in public, and the museum
hopes to rotate the displays regularly to give viewers more of a
glimpse of its holdings.
</P>
<P>
   The story goes back to the 1980s, when the Southwest Museum
weathered several crises, some of which had been building for
years. Tough financial times coupled with its meager endowment, now
valued at about $6 million, meant that it had to reduce staff and
researchers' access to its storerooms. And in 1989 it suffered an
embarrassing blow when it was disclosed that the FBI was
investigating the disappearance of some 120 valuable pieces from
the collection, valued at about $3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Museums have a tendency to keep such embarrassments quiet. Not
only did this one make headlines in Los Angeles, but the museum's
former director, Patrick Houlihan, was convicted in 1993 on charges
that he had stolen some of the missing items.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an occasion of great sadness because the director was
highly respected,'' said W. Richard West Jr., the director of the
Smithsonian Institution's National Museum of the American Indian.
``That museum was underappreciated and underutilized. It was less
about the collection than the location.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the museum's efforts to restore its tarnished luster
were hampered by the relatively obscure location. The museum has
been housed since 1914 in a handsome Mission Revival structure in
Mount Washington constructed by the museum's founder, Charles
Fletcher Lummis. That site all but guaranteed modest attendance, in
the view of the trustees, and they considered either moving to a
more accessible neighborhood or merging with another museum.
</P>
<P>
   (The story, ironically, is similar to the fate of the old Museum
of the American Indian, Heye Foundation, in Manhattan. It, too, was
housed in a somewhat out-of-the-way location in upper Manhattan,
and it suffered from neglect. It eventually transferred its vast
collection to the Smithsonian, and much of it has moved to the old
Customs House, now refurbished, at a busy site in lower Manhattan.)
</P>
<P>
   By the mid-1990s the Southwest Museum's trustees had decided, in
the face of harsh opposition to a move from local residents, to
stay put, but they also hired a new director who made it clear that
he would not sit still.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that I would not settle for the status quo,'' said
Duane H. King, now the executive director. ``They decided to stay
at the present location, but at the same time there was a
realization we had to reach a much broader audience, so we started
to consider a second location. Instead of expecting the public to
find us we have to go to the public now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fortuitously, the county museum provided what may turn out to be
the ideal solution. Several years ago it began to refurbish an
adjacent structure, the old May Company department store, an
abandoned modernist gem on Wilshire Boulevard, built in 1939.
Opened this fall, the new space is called LACMA West, and the
county museum's president, Andrea Rich, said that the aim was, in
part, to turn it into a sort of ``village green,'' bringing in
collections from elsewhere in this vast county.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great museum but it was suffering,'' Ms. Rich said of
the Southwest Museum. ``We knew they needed something dramatic
location-wise, and what they were offering was complementary to our
collection. We gain because a lot of people love this material.''
</P>
<P>
   So the Southwest Museum took a lease on about 8,000 square feet
and installed, for a start, its new show, ``Common Threads: Pueblo
and Navajo Textiles in the Southwest Museum.'' An exhibition of
artifacts from the Blackfoot Indians is scheduled in the spring.
About 2,000 people a month have been visiting the new show already,
which is about the same number that have been visiting the main
museum. Museum officials said they expected the number of visitors
to the textile show to at least double after the opening of the van
Gogh exhibit.
</P>
<P>
   In a symbolic gesture, the FBI returned at the end of last year
26 of the items that had been taken illegally from the museum's
storerooms during the 1980s, bringing a greater sense of closure to
that episode, King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not certain how things will work out yet, but there's
certainly more hope,'' said King.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
