<HEADLINE>
BUILDING THE 8TH WONDER OF THE WORLD WITHOUT SAFETY NETS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Cal., Nev., other southwestern states)   (Production notes at end) 
(DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Many Americans, on the way to or from exploring the
technical wonder of Las Vegas slot machines, take a break at Hoover
Dam. It may not offer quite the charge of the slots, but Monday
night's ``American Experience'' leaves no doubt that the dam was
quite a gamble for its time and produced big winnings for its major
players and for America's Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s, in an effort to control the Colorado River,
typically described as ``raging,'' the U.S. Bureau of Reclamation
undertook to bring water and power to arid country. For farmers, a
government official says: ``The river was an enemy. It was too
thick to drink and too thin to plow.''
</P>
<P>
   Pictures of surging waters and forbidding country and accounts
of the feats of engineering and organization that went into
dominating them bring back the ambition and drama of the
accomplishment. But attention is given to the human story, too, of
thousands of young men, desperate for some sort of job in the
Depression, who had nothing to lose except possibly their health
and lives. The killing heat, the rudimentary living conditions, the
unending pressures for speed that did not allow for safety
precautions took their toll. The ``high scalers'' swinging 800 feet
up with their jackhammers and charges of dynamite look like circus
performers without nets.
</P>
<P>
   In these sensitive times, viewers may notice that the workers
shown were all white; that changed with the election of Franklin D.
Roosevelt and the advent of Harold Ickes as his Secretary of the
Interior, but even then segregation prevailed, notably in what some
welcomed as the ideal community built for workers and their
families in Boulder City.
</P>
<P>
   ``They built them rabbit hutches and called them houses,'' says
a critic. Another describes this forced effort at social planning
as a combination model town and police state, but for most of its
residents it was better than anything they had ever known.
</P>
<P>
   The hour gives only passing attention to a strike, quickly
crushed by management, over the dangerous working conditions, and
there is barely a reference to the environmental concerns that
would come later. Here the emphasis is on the success of what some
called ``the eighth wonder of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   The workers, under a hard-driving boss, Frank Crowe, driven in
turn by a consortium of contractors looking toward big profits,
beat the deadlines and changed lives in a vast area of the United
States that included the little town of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Some things remained the same. You can see workers in their rare
off times, getting rid of their paychecks in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAN EXPERIENCE
</P>
<P>
   Hoover Dam
</P>
<P>
   PBS, Monday night at 9 (Channel 13 in New York)
</P>
<P>
   Produced, written and directed by Stephen Stept; John Heus,
co-producer; John J. Martin, editor; original music by Tom
Phillips; Peter Coyote, narrator. A production of Firstlight
Pictures. ``The American Experience'' is produced by WGBH/Boston.
For ``The American Experience'': Margaret Drain, executive
producer; Mark Samels, senior producer; David McCullough, series
host.
</P>
</TEXT>
