<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 16:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOONDRUNK-MUSIC-REVIE     01-17 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOONDRUNK-MUSIC-REVIEW-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOONDRUNK': A `PIERROT' LIGHTED BY MORE THAN THE MOON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BERNARD HOLLAND   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Any creative presentation of people and places has to
decide what to put in and what to leave out. ``Moondrunk'' at the
New Victory Theater on Friday night subscribed to the ``more''
theory rather than the ``less.''
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lunaire,'' the evening's
centerpiece, is not without encouragement for the art-by-addition
camp. The first performances in 1912 were sung/spoken by an
actress, and Albert Giraud's 21 poems, cruel and bizarre to begin
with, take on an even seamier graphic nature in German translation.
We are ready to picture Pierrot in his clown's suit and also the
object of his affection, the moon _ at the New Victory a suspended,
lit-up and balloonlike globe.
</P>
<P>
   The question was whether ``Moondrunk'' follows a natural path to
its conclusions or whether it jumps to them. All possible senses
are appealed to. Schoenberg's small ensemble sits to one side of
the stage and plays the exquisite instrumental part. Lucy Shelton,
with period headress and pasty face, delivers Schoenberg's
extraordinary mongrelization of speech and song either reclining on
her seedy chaise or posing and perambulating across the stage.
</P>
<P>
   But there is more: John Kelly and his associates Barbara Allen
and Jon Kinzel dancing their way from one song to the next. All of
these estimable performers were arguing that the more information
available to an audience the greater the sensuous experience.
Detail enriches. Two arts are better than one, and three an
unexpected blessing.
</P>
<P>
   There is, however, another kind of art: the art of omission, the
use of the small, incomplete gesture surrounded by little vacuums.
It is the imagination of the onlooker that rushes to fill them.
This is how three lines on a sketch pad can make us see a torso or
a chair; or how a line of a solo Bach sonata creates instantly
recognizable harmony even though no harmony is being played. We are
told a lot about Raskolnikov, but what Raskolnikov looks like will
differ according to each reader's inner vision.
</P>
<P>
   As to ``Moondrunk,'' the elements are splendid, but there may be
too many of them. Rarely have I heard five musicians play
Schoenberg with such refinement. Ms. Shelton was a model of eery
self-possession, far removed from her near-frantic performance of
``Pierrot'' two years ago at the Aldeburgh Festival. Couching Ms.
Shelton's singing in dark and shifting lighting (by Scott Pask) and
investing her delivery with long dramatic pauses work well. They
center our attention on the music rather than diverting it.
</P>
<P>
   But the dancing is too much. Kelly is an attention-getting
presence; but when he is at his best, Ms. Shelton and her musicians
are reduced to accompanists. When, on the other hand, we stick with
the music, we forget the dancers are on the stage. Sensory overload
is at work, an embarrassment of riches that the mind (at least this
one) has a hard time coping with.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moondrunk'' is part of a valorous attempt by Lincoln Center's
``Great Performers'' series to give classical concerts a new look
in different venues. One is thankful even while disagreeing with
some of the results. Mahler's ``Kindertotenlieder'' and an evening
of Bach cantatas, both for the eye and ear, are coming soon. They
are worth your attention.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The first half of Friday evening was devoted to finding out how
``Pierrot Lunaire'' got to be the way it is. There was Johann
Strauss' ``Kaiser-Walzer'' in Schoenberg's acid arrangement for
sextet and also Goethe's ``Erlkonig'' as read (by way of
recordings) by the 1920s actor Alexander Moissi. Sarah Rothenberg
played (beautifully) two of Brahms' richest and most ecstatic late
piano pieces, some boyhood Schoenberg and two items from his Op. 11
Klavierstucke.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, I am sure, was to prepare the listener for the
inspired lunacy to come, and in one way, ``Pierrot Lunaire'' does
have a past, being a little like traditional Viennese society with
the veneer of politeness scraped away. Yet this is one of those
works that more or less happened, like ``Le Sacre du Printemps'' or
the Beethoven Grosse Fuge. Its salient elements come from nowhere
and proceed no further. It sets no precedent; it is itself.
</P>
<P>
   The choreographed elements, often touching in ``Pierrot,'' did
less well before intermission. The three dancing janitors during
the Strauss begged for chuckles that were in no way deserved. The
silhouetted progress of the ``Erlkonig'' with horse, riders and
toothy monster was intentional naivete made to look embarrassingly
unintentional. The apparition of Pierrot pointing to the moon at
the end of Ms. Rothenberg's piano pieces was, on the other hand, to
the point: an affecting preview of the evening's coming attraction.
</P>
<P>
   The other musicians on Friday were Carol Wincenc, flutist; David
Krakauer, clarinetist; Guillermo Figueroa and Andrew Grams,
violinists; Toby Appel, violist, and Rafael Figueroa, cellist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
