<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6745 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-CONCERT-COUGHING-AR     01-17 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-CONCERT-COUGHING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN AMATEUR MUSICIAN'S EXPERT THEORY ON COUGHING IN AUDIENCES
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Resending to add photo note. No other changes.)  
 (ATTN: Ill.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By EDWARD ROTHSTEIN    
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The spate of coughing and hacking that caused the
conductor Kurt Masur to stalk offstage during a New York
Philharmonic concert last month was ascribed to the usual culprits:
inattentive audiences, rampant viruses and dull performances. But
the medical problem, which is widespread, may be more serious than
the absence of manners or cough drops.
</P>
<P>
   These convulsive paroxysms may have less to do with the failures
of the players onstage than with the lack of players offstage.
Coughing would diminish if audiences had more amateur musicians in
their midst.
</P>
<P>
   What does the absence of amateurs have to do with coughing? Some
hints can be taken from Wayne Booth, the literary scholar and
emeritus professor of English at the University of Chicago. For
more than 40 years he has been practicing the cello, creating
unusual counterpoint to his work as a teacher of rhetoric, irony
and fictional narrative. In fact Professor Booth has written a book
on the glories of amateurism, ``For the Love of It,'' to be
published this spring by his university.
</P>
<P>
   In the book, whose title plays on the Latin origins of the word
amateur, he makes effusive claims for the powers of playing chamber
music with friends, describing the infectious affection for the
music that spreads among them. He tells of grown men weeping at
Haydn and sober scholars sobbing with Beethoven. He writes about
``spiritual communion'' and about climbing a mountain that ``has no
top.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he speaks of what every amateur musician and not a
few professionals also know well: the sense of overwhelming
humility before something that is always beyond one's reach.
</P>
<P>
   The amateur path is pockmarked with the fear of failure, the
fear, as Booth puts it, of ``bare ruined choirs, where cellists'
boo-boos rang.'' Fellow amateurs may scorn one's weaknesses; others
might fail to measure up to one's own ``scale of tolerability.''
But despite it all the amateur's love grows. Such affection, if
more widely spread, might even provide a kind of musical
expectorant, a temporary cure for the common cold among concert
audiences.
</P>
<P>
   It might have some effect on the professionals as well. Booth
described the passions of the amateur on Friday at the conference
of Chamber Music America, the national society of professionals.
For many of those in attendance, he must have seemed a voice from
their past, bearing tales of an idyllic world almost eclipsed by
their struggles with marketing, grants and cranky critics. Booth
reminded earnest professionals of their amatory origins, suggesting
that the amateur spirit has much to offer professional life.
</P>
<P>
   I joined Booth in public conversation at that conference
session. I also recalled the thrills of amateur aspiration: a
Brahms piano quartet in which the massiveness of the chordal
pianism helped turn my body into the central axis of a breathing
organism, the almost painful strain of making the piano lines sing
simply in the midst of the swaying elegance of Schubert's ``Trout''
Quintet. I also recalled fears of not measuring up, of needing to
scramble to practice in the face of conflicting demands and of
wishing to find companions as tolerant of my weaknesses as I swore
I would be of theirs. Like much of Booth's audience, I ended up
leaving all this behind to turn professional. Except that I became
a professional listener, not a player. A critic, not a performer.
</P>
<P>
   But after 20 years of professional listening, I find the amateur
spirit even more important than it once was. It serves as a crucial
corrective to the cataloguing, collecting and comparing that mark
the professional listener. It has become a touchstone.
</P>
<P>
   How so? Amateur playing leads to what might be called amateur
listening. It means that nothing can be taken for granted. The
music can't be passively heard because it can't be passively
played. It is not ready made. It comes to be. The listener, in the
midst of hearing, actually helps it come to be, feeling it grow _
or fail to grow _ as if from the inside.
</P>
<P>
   The critic might take note of where gestures were stilted, where
the technical struggle became audible, where a sequence pointed
with all its might to a conclusion that was never reached. But the
professional is beholden to the amateur within, who is actively
involved, imagining alternatives, living in the midst of the sound
and sometimes even joining the performer as a co-creator.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur listening provides an almost Stanislavskian method for
musical enactment, except it is done silently, quieting one's body
so the mind and ears merge into those of the players. Even a bad
performance can inspire the amateur listener. The greatest
musicians make it easier. They are welcoming, enveloping,
demanding, sometimes wielding an almost erotic energy, turning a
vast public into avid amateurs. Lovers all.
</P>
<P>
   I like to imagine that in the days before recordings, radio and
MP3 downloads, when music heard was music played, when symphonies
were first learned in piano reductions, and kitschy pop songs were
sung around the keyboard in the parlor, this kind of amateur
listening to live music as it was being played was far more
