<SLUG> BC-TV-NIGHT-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`WHAT WE DID LAST NIGHT': RICK SCHRODER AS A BAD-BOY TOWNIE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rick Schroder is hot. Just a couple of months ago
critics and viewers alike were having a good laugh over the
prospect of his joining the cast of ABC's gritty police drama
``NYPD Blue.'' How was a baby-faced blond former child actor going
to fill the shoes of Jimmy Smits, who brilliantly had replaced
David Caruso, who had been pretty brilliant himself?
</P>
<P>
   But when Schroder turned up in his first episodes, older and
wiser than viewers remembered him and a little worse for wear,
those critics and viewers took it all back, and this week the young
star is on the cover of TV Guide, smiling just above the words
``He's great!''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night he's the star of an ABC movie, ``What We Did That
Night.'' Well, every career move can't be a winner.
</P>
<P>
   The first sign that this is going to be an obvious, predictable
(until the very end) film is the stick-figure characters. There's
Henry ( Schroder), the bad-boy townie who doesn't really belong
among his fraternity brother pals. He turns up eight years later as
a jailbird, smoking cigarettes, so you know he's no good.
</P>
<P>
   There's Doc (Jayce Bartok), the geek whose reaction to tragedy
is nausea. He grows up to be a respectable dentist. There's Ollie
(Jack Noseworthy), the loyal guy trying to be faithful to his
fiancee, who is away in Paris studying the cello. He grows up to be
a respectable lawyer. There's Charlie (Michael Easton), the
charmer, who grows up to be a nightclub owner and wears silk suits.
In the flashbacks he looks like Keanu Reeves.
</P>
<P>
   In college one of the four boys accidentally shoots a girl to
death on the night they were planning to make her part of a
gruesome fraternity prank. The four friends consider calling 911
but panic and bury the body in an out-of-the-way site called
Devil's Glen.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later real estate developers are about to break
ground in Devil's Glen. Henry gathers the other three young men by
making threatening telephone calls, and they head for the scene of
the crime to do whatever it takes not to be caught. The plot is
practically a genre to itself.
</P>
<P>
   The next sign that this movie may not be a masterpiece is the
dialogue, which never gets much more original than ``Now, if
anybody asks, we stick to the story'' and ``I can't stop thinking
about that night.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a lot of clumsy exposition. Instead of a scene in
which the boys devise the fraternity prank, Eric Harlacher's script
presents a scene in which they go over the details again. Instead
of having the pretty girl they pick up tell them about her
amazingly virtuous family, one of the boys later repeats what she
told him to the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``What We Did That Night'' has some redeeming features. Tara
Reid, as the girl who is the victim, does an amusing turn at the
beach party as a flirtatious but mean drunk. Some real suspense
builds in the final scenes. At the end there's a wonderful plot
twist, but it's dulled by having the characters overexplain it and
by a ludicrous death scene. When the character breathes his last,
his final words are, honest to God, ``Olly olly oxen free.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1706EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
