<HEADER>
A6749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIVIL-RIGHTS-PHOTOS-A     01-17 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVIL-RIGHTS-PHOTOS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHOTOS THAT CAPTURE THE TURMOIL OF THE CIVIL RIGHTS MOVEMENT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Germany; Mass., Miss., Tenn. and other Southern states.)   (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By FELICIA R. LEE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Life seldom offers epiphanies. Yet Steven Kasher, the
curator of the civil rights photography exhibition opening Monday
at the 92d Street Y here, can recall the slaying of three civil
rights workers in Mississippi as a turning point in his life.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Goodman, one of the three young men whose bodies were
found under an earthen dam in the summer of 1964, was a cousin of
the best friend of Kasher, who was then 10. The Goodmans and the
Kashers were close: two Jewish families in Manhattan, sharing
Thanksgiving dinners and idealism about America. What Kasher later
learned about the Goodman murder by white racists became the fruit
of a life that includes a book about the civil rights movement and
eight other exhibitions of images from that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a child, it was totally, totally vague to me,'' Kasher said
of the civil rights movement. ``I generally had a sense that there
was heroism and courageous things going on. All of a sudden, there
was this news that Michael's cousin Andrew was killed in
Mississippi. There was such terrible sadness.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I became very aware of anti-Semitism and racism and
intolerance and that we can't let this happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   After attending art school in Florence, he found work as an
artist, a writer and a photographer. At the Black Star agency
Kasher became a special projects coordinator and began documenting
the movement. His exhibitions have been shown in cities from London
to Los Angeles, and he now has a TriBeCa gallery bearing his name.
</P>
<P>
   The debut of the show at the 92d Street Y coincides with the
holiday commemorating the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. Called
``America and the Civil Rights Movement, 1954-1968,'' the
exhibition, which runs through March 19 at the Weill Art Gallery at
the Y, offers more than 50 images. Some are familiar, like those of
King marching or students with a Gandhi-like calm being harassed at
segregated lunch counters. Others are anonymous black faces:
dignified, enraged, defiant.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs are accompanied by text and information-laden
captions. Kasher says he believes that words as well as pictures
are necessary for the many people who still do not know why a civil
rights movement was needed.
</P>
<P>
   The pictures tell the story of a time when most blacks, by law,
went to separate schools, could not drink from the same water
fountains as whites and were denied the vote. They show how men
were killed because they stood up for those rights, and how women
and children had dogs and fire hoses turned on them. They also show
how the most disenfranchised Americans _ Southern blacks _
conceptualized and led a movement that changed the law of the land
and deeply entrenched customs.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilson, the director of the Y's School of the Arts and
the show's organizer, asserted that the civil rights movement owed
much of its success to the widespread publicity generated by
photographs. Those pictures embodied the inherent contradiction in
American life, he said, and captured the truths to which most
Americans had been oblivious.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, participants in the movement regularly staged
events for the news media and cultivated journalists, Gilson said.
They produced their own writers and photographers and were aware of
their legacy. The period from 1954, when the U.S. Supreme Court
outlawed ``separate but equal'' schools, to 1968, when King was
slain in Memphis and the movement began to splinter, was a high
point for photojournalism, Gilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Television largely has supplanted the role that photo magazines
like Life once played. But as the reaction to the videotaped
beating of Rodney King shows, he said, America remains a nation so
splintered by race and class that imagery can be used to stunning
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Gilson said his research for the exhibition had included reading
several histories of the movement, including Kasher's book, ``The
Civil Rights Movement: A Photographic History, 1954-1968''
(Abbeville Press, 1996).
</P>
<P>
   Many of the photographs come from the book with its bounty of
classic scenes, but Gilson said he deliberately had wanted to
include those less well known. He is aware that the show, part of
the Y's ``Project America,'' a multidisciplinary examination of
American culture, will introduce a new generation to what the civil
rights movement was about.
</P>
<P>
   ``This movement was the first widespread resistance and the
first to get widespread publicity,'' Gilson said. ``Previously,
there was a kind of invisibility of African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasher, in an interview in the apartment he shares with his wife
and daughter in the TriBeCa neighborhood, said: ``People have a
vague idea that Martin Luther King did something. But they have no
idea of the movement. That's why it's very positive to get it out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Kasher said he wanted the photographs to advance a broad view of
the movement that incorporates many aspects of what happened, from
the role of the church to white involvement to the violent
resistance to civil rights. One photograph, for example, shows a
speaker at a memorial service for Andrew Goodman, James Chaney and
Michael Schwerner _ the three young men murdered in Mississippi _
that takes place amid the ruins of a church torched by the Ku Klux
Klan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought about my daughter,'' Kasher said. ``What do I want
to teach her? What do I want to pass along? I felt this was as much
my heritage as the Holocaust. It was part of my life and my times
and my youth. This happened in America, and this movement
represents the crucial lesson about America in the post-war era.''
</P>
<P>
   It is significant that the exhibition takes place at an
institution founded by Jews in 1874 as the 92d Street Young Men's
and Young Women's Hebrew Association. Jews like Goodman, a
20-year-old student who had gone south to help register black
voters, played a key role as civil rights foot soldiers and
fund-raisers, many of them mindful of their own historical role as
despised outcasts. As a child, Kasher's mother and her family came
to New York from England, where they had gone to flee Nazi Germany
in the late 1930's.
</P>
<P>
   In a show of which he was the curator in 1991, ``The Art of
Hitler,'' Kasher showed a photograph of his mother and her sister
in 1938, shyly holding hands on a Frankfurt street as a panoply of
Nazi flags flap in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``A photograph is such a paradox,'' Kasher said. ``It's a frozen
moment from a river that never stops. There is still complete
belief that a photograph is a reflection of reality, something that
really happened. It's like a mirror. But it has a message because
there's a consciousness behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Through his years of assembling civil rights exhibitions, Kasher
met and befriended many of the movement photographers. Among them
were Ernest Withers, a 76-year-old black photographer who lives in
Memphis and whose work is showcased in the Y exhibition. Withers'
photographs include a famous one of the Memphis sanitation workers
on strike with the simple sign ``I Am a Man.'' The 1968 sanitation
campaign took King to the city where he was assassinated.
</P>
<P>
   Withers, whose great-great-grandfather was lynched in
Mississippi after running away to join the Union Army, recalled
striving for professional objectivity as he photographed the
organized resistance to that kind of violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a job because I'm the father of seven boys and one
girl, but it carried some pride to it, it carried some hope,''
Withers said in a telephone interview from Memphis. ``The young
people have been amazed to see those segregated bus signs, so those
shows that Steve does are important. It gives you a feeling that
your living has not been in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Moore, a 67-year-old white photographer who grew up in
Alabama and is also part of the show, said the movement had changed
his life. Moore made some of the first photographs of King. His
images of police dogs mauling protesters are some of the most
familiar in the genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Birmingham when I saw the dogs I don't think anything
appalled me more _ and I've been to Vietnam,'' said Moore, who now
lives in western Massachusetts. ``I photographed it, and the world
rushed in. I realized the power of even one image.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What changed was my awareness,'' he added. ``I wanted to show
how awful, how vulgar, how terrible this whole thing was.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the people who have seen his exhibitions, Kasher said
whites and blacks differed somewhat in their reactions. Many blacks
viewing the shows have some personal connection to the events of
that time, Kasher said. Many of the whites are surprised by the
depth of the hatred.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people see these photographs and they have a lot of
shame and embarrassment that this went on in America,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1711EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
