<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PATENTS-NYT &LR;      01-17 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PATENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHALLENGING PRICELINE.COM 
ONE SIZE DOES NOT FIT ALL 
CATCHING CUTLERY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Calif.)   (mk) 
 By TERESA RIORDAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; A Washington patent lawyer is challenging a fundamental patent
issued last summer to Priceline.com Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Thomas Woolston, contends that he filed for a patent
about 16 months before Priceline applied for its patent in
September 1996 covering an online auction system that allows
consumers to bid for items like airline tickets over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Woolston's patent, which was issued in December, in part covers
a computerized marketplace that enables ``the purchaser to
speculate on the price of collectibles in an electronic market for
used goods while assuring the safe and trusted physical possession
of a good.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Woolston, a baseball fan, first thought of his invention
as a way to buy and sell baseball cards over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Although that is very different from the business that Priceline
conducts _ it advertises widely, with the actor William Shatner
concluding ``I told you Priceline was going to be big, really big''
_ Woolston contends that his patent covers the buyer-driven auction
model of doing business on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His start-up venture, Mercexchange, is at this point little more
than a company name and a board in search of venture capital.
``We're defining our markets right now,'' Woolston said.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com operates a system under which consumers go to an
Internet site and name the price they are willing to pay for
airline tickets, hotel rooms and other items. Priceline then tries
to find an airline or other company willing to accept that price.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Walker, vice chairman and founder of Priceline, dismissed
Woolston's challenge. ``When you have a landmark patent, you have
to expect, as we did, that all kinds of people are going to come
out of the woodwork to claim that the Patent Office made a mistake
and that they really invented it first,'' he said. ``Our patent is
no exception.''
</P>
<P>
   Woolston said he discussed working with Priceline.com to develop
the auction technology but that the talks failed because the
company ``expressed no serious interest in cooperation.'' Woolston
has requested that the Patent Office conduct a proceeding known as
an interference. It could be months before the agency decides
whether to initiate such a review, which could then take several
years.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, such disputes over issued patents must be fought out
in the courts. But for technical reasons, Woolston is able to
challenge the Priceline patent through the Patent Office _ a far
less costly way to challenge a patent.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said it was ``not inconceivable'' that the Patent Office
would grant the interference, but expressed confidence that
Priceline.com's patent would survive such scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   Priceline was assigned patent 5,794,207. Woolston received
patent 5,845,265.
</P>
<P>
   TRUTH IN LABELING, WITH A VIEW TO SAFETY
</P>
<P>
   Frank Sadlo, a substitute high school teacher in Louisville,
Ky., received a patent last week for what he contends is a way to
encourage the practice of safe sex.
</P>
<P>
   Sadlo's idea? Sell condoms that fit to size.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you walk by the condom rack at the drugstore, you'll see
that there are just two sizes _ regular and medium,'' Sadlo said.
</P>
<P>
   Class A condoms are 7.1 inches in length, according to Sadlo,
while Class B condoms are 6.3 inches. ``But medical research of the
male anatomy shows that the length of an erect penis ranges from
about 3.5 inches to 13 inches,'' he said. ``Clearly, one size
cannot fit all.''
</P>
<P>
   Further, Sadlo said, 15 percent of men are unable to use the
latex condoms on the market because their circumference is too
small for the condoms to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people that the condoms just aren't going
to fit,'' he said. ``For lots of men it's too long, so there's an
unrolled portion at the base which can have a tourniquet effect and
restrict neurological and vascular functioning. And if it's not
long enough, it's going to have a tendency to pull off or break.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadlo has patented a system of selling condoms that vary in
length and width. Men could pick up a measuring strip at the
drugstore and then take their measurement at home in privacy, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned to the store, they would consult a coded
chart for the appropriate size. The chart would be similar to, but
a bit more complicated than, the weight-and-height charts that
women consult when they buy pantyhose at a store. But Sadlo said
the size of the condom would not be evident on the package.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be coded, so you would pick out, say, a J-M,'' Sadlo
said. ``The actual condom package would not indicate any length on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadlo said he hoped to license his invention. ``It can be a real
funny subject,'' he said. ``But it can help save a lot of lives
because it will be a lot more reliable and comfortable so a lot
more people will be willing to wear them.''
</P>
<P>
   Sadlo received patent 5,857,466.
</P>
<P>
   A TRAP DOOR OF SORTS FOR DISCARDED CUTLERY
</P>
<P>
   It can cost a cafeteria thousands of dollars a year to replace
flatware that has accidentally been thrown away. Richard Edwards
has come up with a solution: a trash can with an electronic metal
detector.
</P>
<P>
   The can described in his patent features a chute at the top. If
garbage passing through the chute contains a fork or a knife or a
spoon, an alarm sounds and a spring-loaded door closes the base of
the chute. Once the metal has been retrieved, the chute opens
again.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, of Long Beach, Calif., received patent 5,797,497.
</P>
<P>
   Patents are available by number for $3 from the Patent and
Trademark Office, Washington, D.C. 20231.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
