<HEADER>
A6758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VALENTE-MUSIC-REVIEW-     01-17 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VALENTE-MUSIC-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHAMBER MUSIC AMERICA BENEFIT: CELEBRATING BENITA VALENTE   
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  By ANTHONY TOMMASINI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like many other singers, the soprano Benita Valente
has worked with equal dedication in opera and song. But Ms. Valente
also has distinguished herself as a chamber music artist in
repertory ranging from Baroque cantatas to contemporary works.
</P>
<P>
   So she was a fitting choice for the Richard J. Bogomolny
National Service Award, given annually by the national association
Chamber Music America. Her achievement was marked by a gala concert
at the Juilliard Theater on Thursday night, also a benefit for
Classical Action, which raises funds for AIDS services.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Valente's involvement with chamber music was made clear at
the start, when the Juilliard String Quartet joined her for two
extended sections of ``The Rewaking,'' to texts of William Carlos
Williams, composed by John Harbison in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Though it was not organized as such, the concert also seemed a
fitting celebration of Ms. Valente as a model of sensible vocal
practices. At a time when so many promising young singers blow out
their voices through overly forceful singing of inappropriate
repertory, Ms. Valente, at 64, sounds remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   Early on she sized up her voice correctly: a lyric soprano with
a bright, clear, yet warm sound. With her faultless technique and
intelligence, she became an important recitalist, a notable singer
of Mozart and Handel opera, with forays into roles like Verdi's
Violetta. But no one ever talked her into Tosca or such, which is
why she is still singing.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously there has been some diminishing of her voice. But in
Harbison's highly charged work she sounded radiant. The music
captures the stormy weather of the poetic imagery in tormented
vocal lines, but it renders the calm after the storm in melodic
arcs of high, soft, sustained beauty, and Ms. Valente handled it
all impressively.
</P>
<P>
   Several colleagues were there to honor her. The mezzo-soprano
Joan Morris and her husband, the composer and pianist William
Bolcom, who has written several works for Ms. Valente, performed
four turn-of-the-century popular songs with elegance and wit. The
mezzo-soprano Marilyn Horne sang duets with Ms. Valente, her friend
of 47 years (they met as students in California), by Schumann and
Eric Thiman, sensitively accompanied by the pianist Ken Noda.
</P>
<P>
   Finally there was a performance of Brahms'
``Liebeslieder-Walzer,'' Op. 52, for vocal quartet and piano duo,
with twice the number of singers required, all taking turns. They
included Susan Narucki, Emily Golden, Marietta Simpson, Richard
Clement, Jon Humphrey, William Stone, Christopheren Nomura.
Stephanie Brown and Cynthia Raim were the musicianly pianists. When
her turn came, Ms. Valente sang beautifully. But she seemed even
happier when she was just listening to others perform in her honor
music she has loved all her life. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
