A6760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEWIS-MLK-SPEECH18-CO     01-17 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEWIS-MLK-SPEECH18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lewis urges U.S. to `choose between community and chaos'
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As the impeachment trial of the president continues
to roil the nation's Capitol, Georgia Democratic Rep. John Lewis
urged Sunday for ``a calming of the waters.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking before a packed audience at the Washington National
Cathedral, Lewis said the nation is ``tired'' of being ripped apart
by the partisan fight over whether President Clinton should be
removed from office for the way he concealed his affair with former
White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must choose between community and chaos,'' said Lewis,
invoking the words of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. on the eve of
a national holiday honoring the deeds of the former civil rights
leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a nation troubled by scandal and the politics of
personal destruction,'' said Lewis, who worked with King to promote
the civil rights of African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We as a nation are not at peace with ourselves,'' said Lewis,
his voice thundering throughout the gothic-style cathedral. ``Our
national community is sick and her heart is very heavy. Her soul is
aching and her spirit is low.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the chief democratic whip in the House, has
unsuccessfully sought a peaceful conclusion to the allegations that
the president lied under oath and obstructed justice.
</P>
<P>
   It was Lewis' hope that King's message of forgiveness would
bring some sense to the scandal engulfing Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge, Lewis said, is to take King's words and apply
them to the hate and divisiveness that has permeated Congress, as
well as society.
</P>
<P>
   ``The struggle is being waged in every nation, among every
people, by peaceful means, by propaganda, diplomacy, financial
pressures, bluffs, strikes, ballots, bullets and even by votes in
Congress where a battle is being waged over the shortcomings of our
president,'' Lewis said. ``We have seen men and women sacrifice
truth, deny truth, hide truth for a false and negative peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis told a story from his childhood about how he and his young
cousins held hands during a fierce storm. The storm rocked his
aunt's house, making them terrified that it might blow away. So
Lewis and his cousins went together from the corner of the ``shot
gun'' house to another in an effort to hold it down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends, the storms may come,'' said Lewis. ``The wind may
blow. The thunder may roll. The lightning may flash. And the rain
may beat down on this old house we call America. But we must never,
ever leave the house of faith.''
</P>
<P>
   Several people in the audience wiped their eyes. A hush fell
over the cathedral which took 83 years and several presidential
administrations to build.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took me back to an era of the 60's when there seemed to be
a heart beat type of hope,'' said Rosetta Robinson, a minister from
the Washington area sitting in the audience. ``It does make you
wonder where will there be justice (with Clinton) and whose justice
will it be?''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Reynolds, an usher at the cathedral, said he hoped that
Lewis' message would impact Congress. In all of his 42 years living
in Washington, he said he has never seen a Congress as divided as
the one deciding Clinton's fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hypocrisy of both sides, it is, well, just appalling,''
said Reynolds. ``I hope they hear him, I hope they listen to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
