<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Monday,
Jan. 18. If you have any questions, please call Shaune Jackson on
the Star's News Desk at (816) 234-4755. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEFECTIVE-HEATER (LEAWOOD, Kan.) The white chips clogging the
kitchen and bathroom faucets were a sign something was not right in
George McCollister's household. He learned from a plumber that the
chips were from a defective plastic tube in his water heater. Now
McCollister wonders why he had not heard of the defect, which also
has caused thousands of other people problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FIGHTING-FRED (IOLA, Kan.) _ When fire destroyed five businesses
on the west side of the courthouse square here in 1990, it left a
130-foot void and spawned a nickname _ ``The Ugly Gap.'' But Iola
is a progressive little city in Allen County, and eventually a
tourist center was suggested for the site. Of the names the town is
famous for, one name has a close link to the area. That name was
Frederick ``Little General'' Funston. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FUGITIVE-TRIAL (WAYNESVILLE, Mo.) _ Alis Ben Johns wasn't
running much Saturday morning. The former fugitive, who had dodged
dozens of searchers for months, arrived in Pulaski County Circuit
Court heavily shackled. He is on trial for the first of three
murder charges.
</P>
