A6769 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFECTIVE-HEATER-2ndT     01-17 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFECTIVE-HEATER-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAW THAT AFFECTS MANY WATER HEATERS HAS NOT BEEN WIDELY
PUBLICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the problem has been a mystery to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to customer complaints, Thornton, Musso and Bellemin,
a Louisiana consulting firm to several water utilities, in 1997 had
to use a microscope that takes the fingerprint of chemical elements
before discovering that the chips which came from the
disintegrating dip tubes were polypropylene.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many consumers with the problem initially assume it is a
problem with water quality and the fault of the water utility. Dan
Smith, director of distribution engineering for Johnson County
Water District No. 1, said the district began to get calls in late
1997 and had received 87 inquiries since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't figure out what it was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, working with the American Water Works Association,
the district traced the problem to the dip tubes. In a month or two
the district plans to distribute a bill insert alerting customers
to the water-heater problem.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Peugeot, the owner of the Roger the Plumber business in
Johnson County, said he had repaired about 200 of the tanks that
had defective dip tubes. He first saw the problem in late 1996 and,
like the water district, was initially stumped.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know exactly what it was,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some consumers have gotten repairs to fix shower valves and
dishwashers clogged by plastic chips. The dip tube was not
replaced, meaning that the valves and dishwashers had to be fixed
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been the weirdest thing in my career that has come
along,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue also has produced its share of drama in the
water-heater industry.
</P>
<P>
   State Industries, a water-heater manufacturer, sent a letter to
plumbing contractors in June 1998 stating that it was the only
company that had not sold any of the defective water heaters.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said millions of water heaters were likely to fail
because of the defective tubes. Perfection promptly sued State for
libel, saying there was no way it could show that millions of water
heaters would fail.
</P>
<P>
   A settlement was reached, with State paying Perfection's legal
fees. Evie Sommers, corporate counsel for State, said she could not
discuss the issue, because of the settlement's terms. State also
retracted its position that it had sold none of the defective water
heaters. It turns out it had bought some of the defective
Perfection tubes.
</P>
<P>
   Sommers said: ``All we can do is respond to people who call up
with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   By this time the water-heater companies had in place their
approach to fix the problem. Plumbers would detect and fix the
defective dip tubes when on service calls. The companies would pay
for repairs ``within reason,'' said one company spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the event an owner requests service and it is found dip
tube dissolution is the cause of a shortage of hot water, please
follow the attached procedures when servicing the unit,'' said a
letter that water-heater manufacturer A.O. Smith sent the plumbing
trade in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Foster, director of consumer affairs for manufacturer
Bradford White, said that dealing first with a plumber ensured a
proper diagnosis. Lukewarm water, for example, could also be caused
by other problems such as a faulty thermostat or sediment at the
bottom of the tank.
</P>
<P>
   That is not good enough for those who think there ought to be a
recall, or at least notification that a potential defect exists.
</P>
<P>
   Still, for some there has been a happy ending. McCollister, the
Leawood man whose faucets were clogged, was told by one plumber
that the problem was calcium deposits.
</P>
<P>
   A second company was aware of the defective dip tubes. Rheem,
the manufacturer of his water heater, approved the repairs that
were completed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel sorry for all those people who don't know what is going
on,'' he said.
(30)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
