<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6770 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEFECTIVE-HEATER-2TAK     01-17 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFECTIVE-HEATER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLAW THAT AFFECTS MANY WATER HEATERS HAS NOT BEEN WIDELY
PUBLICIZED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEAWOOD, Kan. _ The white chips clogging the kitchen and
bathroom faucets were a sign something was not right in George
McCollister's household.
</P>
<P>
   The Leawood resident assumed the problem was with the water.
Perhaps some calcium deposits. But recently he learned from a
plumber that the chips were from a defective plastic tube in his
water heater.
</P>
<P>
   Now McCollister wonders why he had not heard of the problem,
which also has caused thousands of other people in the country to
wonder why their faucets, dishwashers and showers were clogged, and
why their water heaters struggled to heat water.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should be a recall,'' McCollister said.
</P>
<P>
   People who know that the water-heater defect is causing their
plumbing problems usually can get them fixed for free, or at least
recover some of the cost. There has not been a recall, however, or
even any direct notice to water-heater buyers. That leaves an
unknown number of people with the problem _ and possibly hundreds
of dollars in repair bills.
</P>
<P>
   A manufacturing mistake caused the problem. The chemical
additives that stabilize the plastic tubes were applied improperly,
beginning in 1993, and the problem was not definitely remedied
until 1996. It is not known whether just a few batches of the tubes
were defective, or entire production runs.
</P>
<P>
   The tube manufacturer says the problem is small. Only about
11,000 claims have been filed for repairs or replacements so far.
About 8 million home water heaters are bought each year.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every company in the home water-heater business from 1993
to 1996 is thought to have sold some defective ones. At least a few
hundred have been fixed in the Kansas City area. And complaints
spring up whenever word of the problem circulates.
</P>
<P>
   ``From all reports this is nationwide, and it needs to be
addressed,'' said Michael J. McGuire, a former top executive with
the Metropolitan Water District of Southern California. He has been
helping the American Water Works Association examine the problem.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, everyone agrees, is with the plastic pipe called a
dip tube, which a water-heater company can buy for 50 to 85 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The tube is a pipe, 50 inches long in the most-common sized
water heaters, that delivers cold water to the bottom of an
electric or gas water heater's tank, where the burner is. Because
the cold water is delivered to the bottom, it does not dilute the
temperature of the hot water that has risen to the top of the tank.
</P>
<P>
   When the tube decays, so does a water heater's efficiency.
Eventually bits of the plastic tube can get into pipes and cause
other problems.
</P>
<P>
   The problem surfaced in May 1995 when 28 tubes failed
prematurely and were returned to the manufacturer, the Perfection
Corp. of Madison, Ohio. The tubes have a five-year warranty.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which provides more than 90 percent of the dip
tubes used in water heaters for the home, traced the problem to
1993, when the process for putting the additives into the plastic
was changed.
</P>
<P>
   Without the right chemical makeup, the polypropylene tubes can
break up and dissolve in two to three years, the company says. When
the problem was discovered, however, there was no way to tell how
many of the tubes made in the four years were defective, said Frank
Volgstadt, the company's vice president of research, codes and
standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no way to estimate it,'' he said. But with the
manufacturing problem corrected in 1996, Perfection thinks the
worst is over.
</P>
<P>
   Both Perfection and others in the water-heater industry said the
problem was being addressed with Perfection paying for the
water-heating and plumbing repairs after they were approved by the
water-heater manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to walk away from our customers,'' said
Vincent Debo, corporate counsel for Rheem Manufacturing Co., a
water-heater manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not so sure that the full extent of the problem has
emerged. The companies did not notify customers directly or
publicize the fact outside plumbers and the water-heater industry.
A search of the Lexis-Nexis database found no articles on the
subject in large-circulation newspapers or magazines for the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, critics say, the problem has been kept out of
public view and the number of complaints low.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've kept it hidden,'' said Joe Gagnon, who has a weekend
talk show about appliances on radio station WJR in Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Gagnon found out he had a water heater with a defective dip
tube. In late December he asked that his listeners and readers of a
column he writes for a small suburban Detroit newspaper send him
their stories of dip-tube problems. About 250 responded in two
weeks, with many saying they had already paid for the repairs, not
knowing about the defect.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Hutchins, the president of a water-quality consulting firm
in Michigan, sent a report to Opflow, a publication of the American
Water Works Association, in December about his work in tracking
down the dip-tube problem in a Clinton, Mich., apartment building.
Since the article was published, he has received 100 calls from
water utilities, plumbing inspectors and consumers from throughout
the country who say they have seen similar problems. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
