<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6771 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIGHTING-FRED-KAN &LR;      01-17 1185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIGHTING-FRED-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTEAD OF FINDING FAME, `FIGHTING FRED' HAS BEEN ALL BUT
FORGOTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IOLA, Kan. _ When fire destroyed five businesses on the west
side of the courthouse square here in 1990, it left a 130-foot void
and spawned a nickname _ ``The Ugly Gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Worse yet, residents feared that someone would put up slapdash
buildings, ones that would mar the square's pleasurable
architecture.
</P>
<P>
   But Iola is a progressive little city in Allen County, thank
you, and eventually a tourist center was suggested.
</P>
<P>
   That sounded like a winner. The area has had its share of famous
folk _ baseball Hall-of-Famer Walter ``Big Train'' Johnson from
Humboldt; 1968 Miss America Debra Barnes, reared in Moran; and the
movies' Buster Keaton, born in Piqua as his show-business parents
were passing through.
</P>
<P>
   Still, said lawyer Clyde Toland, when it came to ``famous,''
there was really only one name _ albeit one all but unknown to most
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   That name was Frederick Funston, born in Ohio but raised from
the age of 3 in a little white farmhouse north of here on what's
now U.S. 169.
</P>
<P>
   Funston was a farm boy and a voracious reader of adventure
stories who failed to get into West Point because of poor grades
and truly bantam size _ 5 feet 4 inches tall and 120 pounds; a
never-graduated botany major at the University of Kansas; and a
teacher at the Stony Lonesome grade school near here. Then his life
got interesting:
</P>
<P>
   He explored Death Valley in the 1880s. He did the same in
Alaska, making a solitary, 1,500-mile trip down the Yukon River by
canoe. He was a filibuster (mercenary) in Cuba, rising from
lieutenant to lieutenant colonel and fighting in 22 engagements
alongside insurgents. He commanded the 20th Kansas Volunteer
Regiment in the Spanish-American War. He won the Medal of Honor
almost a century ago (April 27, 1899) for bravery under fire in the
Philippine Insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   And more: He was a national hero as captor of Filipino rebel
Emilio Aguinaldo. By age 35 he was a brigadier general in the U.S.
Army. San Franciscans hailed him as their ``savior'' for his
effective use of troops and organization of relief efforts in and
after the 1906 earthquake and fire.
</P>
<P>
   By 1914, having survived an assassination attempt by a
disgruntled soldier, ``Fighting Fred'' was the highest-ranking
officer in the Army with promotion to major general. In 1916
Funston was the commander during the Mexican-American border
troubles and effectively wrote the book on the large-scale
deployment of troops, one that would be copied in World War I.
</P>
<P>
   In photographs taken in Funston's career, especially group
shots, he is easy to spot. He was the really short guy, the
``Little General'' to his devoted troops, and yet a man who loved
to make jokes about his diminutive stature. In short, he lacked a
Napoleonic complex.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in February 1917, two months before America entered World
War I, Funston, age 52, died of a heart attack while listening to
after-dinner music in a San Antonio hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Funston was the first person ever to lie in state at the famed
Alamo, which was draped in black; the train carrying his body
westward passed lonely crossings where people gathered in knots to
wave their farewells; his funeral at San Francisco's City Hall drew
thousands.
</P>
<P>
   Although he always called Iola home, he is buried at the
Presidio, the former military base in San Francisco. His wife was a
Californian.
</P>
<P>
   President Woodrow Wilson and Secretary of War Newton Baker wrote
later that had Funston lived, he, not Gens. John Pershing or
Leonard Wood, would have led American forces overseas in World War
I.
</P>
<P>
   In that war, Camp Funston, a recruit training center, was
established inside Fort Riley. Today it is remembered for, among
other things, being the locus from which the great influenza
pandemic of 1918-1919 originated and spread.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1920s there were occasional newspaper and magazine
articles recalling Funston. There was even a short-lived comic
strip dealing with his heroics in the Philippines. A street here
and one in Wichita were named after him. In World War II the
transport ship Frederick Funston was launched, did its duty and was
scrapped.
</P>
<P>
   But no definitive biography of Funston has ever been written.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the years Fred Funston was just forgotten,'' said Toland,
the lawyer, who has collected reams of documents on the old
soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lived at the right time _ Death Valley, Alaska, Cuba, the
Philippines.... What he did was to die at the wrong time,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   To Toland, Funston was part of a disappearing age, one in which
individuals could still make a positive difference _ Stanley in
Africa, Shackleton in the Antarctic, Edison in Menlo Park, Ford in
Dearborn, the Wrights in Dayton, Carry Nation in various saloons.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas remembered its adopted son for a long time. In 1955 the
State Historical Society bought the Funston home place, hired a
caretaker and opened the house to the public, advertising it as the
Boyhood Home of Frederick Funston.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the society could never get adequate funding from the
Legislature,'' said Toland, a former president of the Allen County
Historical Society. ``They cut back on the hours, and fewer people
would stop. Fewer stopping meant low attendance, so how could you
justify more hours being open, more money from Topeka? It was a
vicious circle.''
</P>
<P>
   Many who passed by asked, ``Fred who?'' Some tourists, said
Toland, mostly old soldiers who served at Camp Funston, would drive
into Iola and berate those at the Chamber of Commerce who had
nothing to do with the site that, over the years, took on a
shabbier and shabbier appearance.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s a new foundation was put under the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's the only thing that prevented it from falling
in on itself,'' said Toland.
</P>
<P>
   The house was saved by Iola's tourism idea. Through fund drives,
cajoling, pleas, occasional arm twisting and plain civic pride,
Toland said, more than $200,000 in local money was raised. The lots
on the square left empty by the fire were donated or bought; the
State Historical Society deeded the house to the Allen County
Historical Society, and a house mover hauled the structure to the
square. Then came a complete renovation.
</P>
<P>
   Since opening last year, more than 5,000 people have visited the
house with its period furnishings, toured the adjoining museum and
noted the six flags flapping outside that were key to Funston's
life _ Cuba, Alaska, Ohio, Texas, California and the Philippines.
They fly alongside Old Glory and the Kansas state flag.
</P>
<P>
   Toland said the Funston house was a perfect adjunct to the
square. Surprisingly, he said, several of the tourists have been
San Franciscans well-acquainted with the name Funston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funston is big out there,'' he said. ``Just go to the Museum
of the City of San Francisco and ask. Why, there's even a Funston
Boulevard near the Presidio. They know his name.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, better than a lot of us right here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
