<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUGITIVE-TRIAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER TRIAL OF ALIS BEN JOHNS BEGINS IN WAYNESVILLE, MO. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW SCHOFIELD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNESVILLE, Mo. _ Alis Ben Johns wasn't running much Saturday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The former fugitive, who had dodged dozens of searchers for
months, arrived in Pulaski County Circuit Court here heavily
shackled. He is on trial for the first of three murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   The surrounding hollows shrouded by thick mist and hilltops
covered by even thicker forest, seen through the courthouse
windows, made Pulaski County look like a perfect place to get lost
in the wild, to sneak away from civilization and escape to nature.
</P>
<P>
   Johns had tried that.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities contend that Johns pumped seven .22-caliber bullets
into Tommy Stewart on Oct. 1, 1996. Between that Oct. 1 and April
7, 1997, when a Missouri Water Patrol officer dropped Johns with a
single shot, he became a backwoods nightmare in central Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   For almost six months Johns evaded more than 400 law enforcement
officers searching for him on foot, on horseback and in
helicopters. He fled from house to house, mostly vacant summer
homes, in the rugged woods around the Lake of the Ozarks, taking
food and camping gear. He lived outdoors for days, maybe weeks at a
time. And his woodsman's skills managed to confuse even the
bloodhounds sent out to trail him.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, authorities say, he also killed Leonard Voyle of
Camden County and Wilma Bragg, in faraway Newton County. The trial
that began Saturday deals only with the Stewart slaying.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Johns' fame had spread to the point that last Monday,
when officials started choosing the jury in this trial, they first
moved the process hundreds of miles north to Kirksville. Even then
they had to question 588 potential jurors before finding 16 persons
_ 12 for the jury and four alternates _ suitable for the task.
</P>
<P>
   Moments before the trial was to begin Saturday, Johns stumbled
into the courtroom. He looked haggard; his legs were skinny, and
his face was gaunt, though partly hidden by facial hair.
</P>
<P>
   Despite suggestions from the judge that he find a nice outfit
and cover his shackles in front of jurors, Johns wore a baggy,
gray-and-black striped shirt and orange jail pants. The pants were
bunched about his legs by restraints _ similar to leg braces _
designed to stop him from moving with any speed or agility.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to get him to put the pants over the restraints,''
one courtroom guard said. ``But he refused. He said he just doesn't
care what people think.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the trial began, Johns entered the courtroom
ahead of the jurors and the alternates, glared at television and
press photographers, made an obscene gesture and said: ``Put that
on your TV.''
</P>
<P>
   After taking a seat at the defense table, he made the gesture
again when a television camera zoomed in for a close-up of his
face.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ahsens, an assistant Missouri attorney general, started the
trial by outlining the evidence against Johns.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart was found late Oct. 1, 1996, face down on county Route
KK, with blood pooling about his head and red stains spreading
across his white T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities discovered later that the .22-caliber cartridge
cases found 21 feet from the body matched cartridge casings found
at Johns' cabin, though they never would find the weapons that
fired them.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll hear from a couple who drove up on the scene that
night, saw the victim's pickup truck, saw the victim lying in the
road and were told by the defendant as they pulled up, `Go on, he's
just drunk,' '' Ahsens said.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the years since, Johns has confessed to law officers,
Ahsens added. Both times he claimed to have killed Stewart only
after Stewart had warned that he would kill Johns.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the evidence will show that there were no guns, no knives,
no clubs, no weapons found where all this was done,'' Ahsens said.
``And the evidence will be very clear that Tommy Stewart was an
unarmed man and will be more than sufficient to prove that Alis
Johns is guilty of murder in the first degree.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Chris Slusher conceded that the evidence would
show Johns shot and killed Stewart. He noted, however, that the
circumstances were such that the shooting was not only in
self-defense, but perhaps necessary.
</P>
<P>
   On the night of the shooting, Johns had been drinking at a
gathering with Stewart's ex-girlfriend, Slusher said. After leaving
in her car, they found themselves being chased at high speeds on
the twisting, sometimes unpaved roads of Pulaski County.
</P>
<P>
   The chase ended, Slusher explained, when Stewart zoomed in front
of the pair on Route KK and skidded his pickup to an angled halt,
creating a roadblock.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart then leaped toward their car, broke through his
girlfriend's window and proceeded to beat her. Johns tried to
intervene but was tossed aside and threatened. At some point in
this struggle the girlfriend handed a gun to Johns, who then shot
Stewart seven times, Slusher said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Johns had nothing to do with their violent relationship,''
he said. ``He was simply in the wrong place at the wrong time, a
time when the actions that followed had to take place.''
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last through the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
