<HEADER>
A6773 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-TABLOIDS-MEDIA-ART     01-17 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-TABLOIDS-MEDIA-ART-1150(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN TABLOID TV GOES PRIME TIME
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Text for a box listing last week's top stories from 2
tabloid shows is at the end of the 2nd take.) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time on television when Lorena Bobbitt, Joey
Buttafuoco and Amy Fisher and the boy accusing Michael Jackson of
sexual molestation were the special and overheated province of
early-evening tabloid news shows.
</P>
<P>
   Yet at the very moment when tabloid topics have become big news
in the most respected newspaper and television news programs, when
a tale of sex and betrayal is even being played out on the floor of
the U.S. Senate, the generation of shows that spawned the term
``tabloid television'' is dying. From a heyday when there were a
half-dozen, only three remain, ``Hard Copy,'' ``Inside Edition''
and ``Extra'' _ and all have lost a fifth or more of their viewers
in the past year alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Copy'' has even gone soft, focusing on first-person
stories, often about celebrities, and local stories about ordinary
folks.
</P>
<P>
   Television's cyclical nature is one reason _ a successful show
spawns many imitators, fragmenting the audience and eventually
diluting interest in that genre. Lurid talk shows, for example,
numbered 21 at their peak and are now down to a handful. But also,
tabloid news magazines have withered because certain kinds of
tabloid-style stories have migrated to the traditional news
organizations, which have so much more time to fill. There are
three all-news cable channels, and the broadcast networks produce
12 hours each week of news magazine programs (soon to be 14, with a
fourth night of ``20/20'').
</P>
<P>
   To put the competition in perspective, Diane Dimond, a former
reporter for ``Hard Copy,'' ``Extra,'' and ``A Current Affair,''
and now co-anchor of ``Upfront Tonight'' on the business-news
channel CNBC, recalled a story she pursued for ``Hard Copy'' in
late 1996. A single mother in Massachusetts had had triplets, gone
back to work to support them, and hired a nanny who somehow managed
to assume the woman's legal identity.
</P>
<P>
   A great tabloid story, Ms. Dimond thought, and it had been seen
only in the local newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I drove to her house and went and knocked on the door,'' Ms.
Dimond recalled ``and she said, `Oh! Diane Dimond! I watch you all
the time! But I'm really sorry _ I just promised my story to Diane
Sawyer.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever her own populist appeal, Ms. Dimond knew, it could not
compete with the fame, glamour and prime-time exposure associated
with Ms. Sawyer, co-anchor of ``Prime Time Live'' on ABC (now part
of ``20/20'').
</P>
<P>
   Maury Povich, the original host of ``A Current Affair,'' which
began in 1986, said the genre is evaporating because it is no
longer distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be vilified by the traditionalists for this, but the
network prime-time news magazines have co-opted the tabloid
genre,'' said Povich, now host of his own talk show, ``Maury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason for our success in the mid-'80s and early '90s was
we did stories that the traditional news divisions passed up,'' he
said. ``They never did stories like the Robert Chambers Central
Park murder story, or chasing down Mary Beth Whitehead, the
surrogate mom. These are stories that were staples in The New York
Daily News or New York Post, but they'd never put them on a
national broadcast.''
</P>
<P>
   They do now, he and several tabloid magazine veterans say. But
some mainstream television magazine executives say that _ aside
from the greater number of hours to fill _ nothing much has
changed.
</P>
<P>
   When ``60 Minutes'' and ``20/20''' began, the mix always
included stories of human drama and true crime, said Victor
Neufeld, the executive producer of ``20/20,'' who has overseen the
expansion from one show a week to four in the past year.
``Prime-time news magazines have always done these stories when
they have significance and they have a point.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference, '' he added, ``is that while syndicated
tabloid shows were doing stories in two days, we would take two
months, with significantly more time and effort invested in telling
a story to give it depth, impact and meaning.''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly more money is invested, too. A typical segment for
``Dateline'' or ``20/20'' can cost $500,000 to produce. ``A Current
Affair'' used to spend $70,000 or $75,000 an episode.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Shapiro, the executive producer of ``Dateline'' on NBC,
acknowledges that network programs do some of the same stories
tabloid show, or do.
</P>
<P>
   ``But they do half an hour, so they do three- or four-minute
stories, and often don't talk to the principal characters,'' he
said. ``We have an hour. We do longer stories. You meet the
characters, hear their words, and hear the larger story, the
context.''
</P>
<P>
   Even granting that to be true, tabloid producers say the
networks are digging deeper for the kind of stories only tabloids
used to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we go after stories, more often than ever before we find
our main competitor is either `Dateline' or `20/20,''' said Marc
Rosenweig, the senior vice president for programming and production
at King World Productions Inc., which syndicates ``Inside
Edition,'' whose anchor is Deborah Norville.
</P>
<P>
   But back when Peter Brennan, John Tomlin and Bob Young started
``A Current Affair'' for the Fox stations in 1986, only ``60
Minutes'' and ``20/20'' did magazine-style news programs in prime
time, and only CNN offered 24 hours of news. There was plenty of
room for offbeat stories.
</P>
<P>
   Prodded by the head of Fox's parent company, the News Corp.
chief Rupert Murdoch, who owned tabloid newspapers in Australia,
Britain and New York, the three producers tried to establish an
afternoon-newspaper approach to news, offering different angles and
more human-interest stories. As with tabloid newspapers, this
sometimes meant sensationalism and sleaze _ wet T-shirt contests,
lurid crimes like Mrs. Bobbitt's cutting off her husband's penis,
or grotesqueries like obese people who could not get out of bed.
</P>
<P>
   But it sometimes meant solid investigative reporting or dogged
pursuit of people trying to dodge exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Edition,'' in fact, won a prestigious George Polk Award
in 1994 for an undercover investigation of the exploitation of poor
people by some insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we were the only show in America to get a live interview
with Charles Keating, early in the Lincoln Savings debacle,'' Young
said of ``Inside Edition,'' which he and Tomlin started in 1988.
(Bill O'Reilly, who did that interview, is now an anchor on the Fox
News Channel.)
</P>
<P>
   Both ``A Current Affair'' and ``Inside Edition'' got excellent
ratings in the prime-time access time period, as the hour before 8
p.m. is known. So did ``Hard Copy,'' which began in 1989, until
recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``When our ratings went through the roof, they took notice,''
Povich said, referring to ABC, CBS and NBC. ``I think the O.J.
Simpson case never would have been such a huge story if tabloid
news magazines hadn't been there before and alerted audiences to
the power of these stories.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Frank Kelly, co-president of Time Warner Inc.'s Paramount
Domestic Television unit and the executive in charge of the
10-year-old ``Hard Copy,'' agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a seismic change with the O.J. story,'' he said.
``That's when all media came to the king of tabloid stories. That's
when it really changed. People asked, `How could you do O.J. for
four or five straight months?' Yet when they stopped, people went
away and sought out shows that were still doing O.J. stories. There
was this insatiable appetite, and the networks said, `This is
amazing, but people want this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But if one of the keys to tabloid success was alerting people to
stories they had never dreamed possible _ shocking people, in other
words _ then the increase in television channels, and in news
programs, and the wider latitude for reporting intimate details of
scandal, may have helped reduce the element of shock.
</P>
<P>
   And Kelly pointed out that tabloid magazine shows have new
competition from reruns of popular sitcoms like ``Seinfeld'' and
``Friends,'' since the recent relaxation of certain federal rules
that now allows stations owned by networks to buy network reruns.
Many are scheduled in that prime-time access hour of 7 to 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The same pressure of competition from mainstream news outlets
has affected supermarket tabloid newspapers like The National
Enquirer, Globe and The Star. All have seen circulation fall.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the face of this trend, The National Enquirer is
producing a television show, set to debut next fall. Marc Berman,
an analyst with Seltel Inc. who advises stations on what programs
to buy, said it would probably be more a gossip show than a tabloid
news magazine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tabloid reality show is not the hot ticket any more,''
Berman said. ``It used to be people said, `Omigod, did you see
``Hard Copy'' last night?' But not any more.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement? Court shows. The tremendous daytime success of
``Judge Judy'' spawned three imitators this season. Next season
there will be six, including one called ``Divorce Court.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Court is the hot ticket now,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL BOX FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   TALES FROM THE TABLOIDS
</P>
<P>
   Lurid features about murders and the underbelly of American life
were once almost the sole province of tabloid television news
magazines. But, with more competition for such fare from mainstream
news programs and more all-news networks, tabloid television is
weaving in more soft features and celebrity profiles. Here is a
sampling from ``Inside Edition'' and ``Hard Copy'' from last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Edition,'' Jan. 13
</P>
<P>
   Lead segment: An interview with the female fan who broke into
Brad Pitt's house. Other segments included Gunther, a dog who
reportedly inherited $65 million and is shopping for real estate in
Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Copy,'' Jan. 13
</P>
<P>
   Lead: A modern-day Noah stockpiles food in preparation for the
so-called millennium bug that some fear may disrupt the world's
computers. Other features included the ``Sinister Minister,'' a
Tennessee minister and his wife who have been accused of abusing
and raping their adopted daughters, and a behind-the-scenes look at
the making of the new Latin version of the hit 1970s show
``Charlie's Angels,'' which will run on the Telemundo network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside Edition,'' Jan. 14
</P>
<P>
   Lead: Michael Jordan's retirement is a gift to the two Mrs.
Jordans _ his wife and his mother. Also, the remains of a young
woman thought to be a 13-year-old girl are found; celebrities,
including Mariah Carey had appealed for her safe return. Also: a
segment dealing with claims that Gunther is a fraud, and that he
did not inherit millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard Copy,'' Jan. 14
</P>
<P>
   Lead: A young surgeon is slain by an unknown gunman and the
police suspect a love triangle. Other pieces included a profile of
Michelle Thomas, a young soap opera star who died of cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
