<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HITS-MEDIA-NYT &LR;      01-17 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HITS-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME MIDSTREAM HITS FOR THE NETWORKS 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ Maybe network television can still produce
hits after all. In five days, three networks started new series and
all of them scored ratings that would qualify them as significant
hits, by far the biggest new hits of what has been a woebegone
television season, if they hold up.
</P>
<P>
   What the shows _ ``Providence'' on NBC, ``The PJ's'' on Fox and
``60 Minutes II'' on CBS _ had in common was that they were not
introduced in the midst of the land-rush onslaught of new series
that marks every fall television season, but were singled out by
their networks for special handling during what is known as
television's midseason.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of each show was given the kind of devotion that
movie studios give to big-budget films: heavy promotion aimed at
maximum exposure. Almost no one in the country could have escaped
the fact that these shows were coming on for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   The entire television industry noticed, to the point that
numerous executives at both the networks and the studios that
produce television series said in interviews here that the system
of starting new series in the fall was fatally flawed. They said
that they foresaw an emphasis on holding shows for the midseason,
both to avoid the fall congestion and to gain the lavish promotion
attention that these three shows received.
</P>
<P>
   The midseason record for creating hits in recent years does
compare very favorably with that of the fall. In the last two
years, ``King of the Hill'' on Fox, ``The Practice'' on ABC and
``Dawson's Creek'' and ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' on WB have all
come on at midseason. The list of hits in the fall is much shorter.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors make January an especially good time to draw
attention to some new shows, one being the weather, which this year
had been especially cold and snowy in the East and Midwest, keeping
more people at home and thus forcing up viewing levels. Another
advantage for the networks that have football (two, in this case)
is the huge audiences that tune in to playoff games in January,
creating an extra-large pool of viewers to see promotions of new
series.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives said the most important development this
season was the focus that these networks brought to these three
shows: no other shows were being pitched to divert attention. In
addition, many of the promotions were adorned with special touches
like movie-style music and even, in the case of ``The PJ's,''
animated creatures walking across the screen during the games.
</P>
<P>
   Lloyd Braun, the president of Walt Disney's Buena Vista
Television, said he was a ``huge fan of midseason,'' citing the
handicaps created by the traditional system of program development.
Under this system, all the writing and acting talent is locked into
a short window of pilot creation, aimed at dishing up a batch of
new shows for the spring announcements of network schedules.
</P>
<P>
   These spring announcements serve as the kickoff to the network
advertising sales round known as the ``up front,'' when advertisers
commit several billion dollars a year to the network shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Grushow, the president of 20th Century Fox Television,
which produces shows for several networks, said, ``I think what
we're prisoners to is the network sales departments who all feel
that come May and June we've got to go into New York and we've got
to show the advertising community our wares and make sure their
up-front dollars are spoken for.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney owns ABC; Fox is a unit of the News Corporation and
General Electric owns NBC.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the swing of shows from the fall to the midseason has
to be limited. If too many shows switched, it could create a glut
in January that would make it impossible to give the shows the
favorite-son promotion treatment that the three new entries
received.
</P>
<P>
   But the executives emphasized that the timing was less important
than the special treatment. ``Maybe what the networks need to do is
pick one show a month and just go all out, pushing it everywhere
they can for the entire month,'' Braun said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
