<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6779 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-ARCTIC-ART-780     01-17 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-ARCTIC-ART-780(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGE COMES EVEN IN THE DARK AGE OF THE CANADIAN ARCTIC
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By ANTHONY DEPALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IGLOOLIK, Northwest Territories _ The time when the sun
disappears and day becomes night is known as ``the great darkness''
by the people who have lived on this island of ice high in the
Canadian arctic for over 4,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Stars shine at midday, and though violet bands brighten the
immense sky for brief periods around what would be high noon in
Toronto, 1,950 miles south, the sun does not appear at all for
seven weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The day the sun finally emerges from the horizon like the
nostrils of a bearded seal poking out of the ocean ice was once the
most important day of the year for Igloolik's Eskimos, who now
prefer to be known as Inuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first person who saw the sun would rush back to the sod
houses or igloos to tell everyone,'' Rosie Iqalliyuq, a 96-year-old
elder, said through a translator. A great igloo would be built.
Soapstone lamps that had provided the only illumination during the
long night would be ceremoniously extinguished, she remembered, and
relit from a single wick.
</P>
<P>
   Then the outsiders came from the south with their crosses and
their schools and their strange notions about chopping up the day
into small pieces called minutes, and the celebrations stopped.
Eventually, with electric lights, alarm clocks and calendars, ``the
great darkness'' meant almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   It was just one more loss in the cultural collision between
north and south that over the last century has stripped the people
of the Arctic of much of their tradition and culture.
</P>
<P>
   But a few years ago people here began systematic interviews with
elders like Mrs. Iqalliyuq (pronounced EE-kwal-ee-juk). Their vivid
memories suddenly made all that had been lost as clear as moon
shadows on new snow. A few leaders set their jaws and decided to
reverse the current.
</P>
<P>
   So on Saturday night, with the temperature outside low enough to
turn a man's breath to crystals of ice, about 400 people gathered
to watch three elders light traditional soapstone lamps filled with
lumps of pink seal blubber. Then, in a moment taken from the old
times, children who had seen the new sun came in to blow out the
flames. There was complete darkness for a minute. When the elderly
women relit the wicks, faces carved by the cold briefly glowed with
the light that represented new life.
</P>
<P>
   It is only natural the sun ceremony would be revived in
Igloolik. Throughout the arctic, Igloolik is famous both for its
fermented walrus meat and for the way the people of this stark and
spirited land survive.
</P>
<P>
   It is not that the 1,200 people in this hamlet roughly 1,200
miles from the North Pole have perfectly preserved their
traditional way of life. Snowmobiles buzz through the streets of
packed snow, and even though the temperature routinely hits 32
degrees below zero Fahrenheit, it is possible to buy a head of
lettuce at either of the two stores in town.
</P>
<P>
   But the appreciation of the ancient ways of life lies closer to
the surface here than in many other places in Canada's remote
north, in part because of the community's isolation and in part
because of the influence of a number of strong leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last 30 years we were busy learning other things,''
said Leah Otak, a resourceful woman who spans the two cultures by
working with both the Eskimo elders' society and the Nunavut
Research Institute, a federal program based in Igloolik. Under the
guidance of John MacDonald, a social anthropologist and star gazer,
the institute has transcribed interviews with more than 400 elders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were very much into other things _ silly games, dances _ to
the point where young people didn't know about their culture,''
Mrs. Otak said. ``It's only in the last few years that we really
tried to show our culture.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the seventh year since the sun ceremony was rekindled,
and it is an especially important year because on April 1, 770,000
square miles of ice and snow in the eastern portion of Canada's
arctic will become a separate territory named Nunavut that will be
governed by more than 25,000 Inuit who live here.
</P>
<P>
   While reviving ceremonies like this fosters a growing confidence
among the people at a crucial time, there is no pretense that
Igloolik or Nunavut can go back to the way things used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not real, what they do today,'' Mrs. Iqalliyuq said. She
sat cross-legged on her bed, with an Arctic trout thawing out on a
nearby hamper and The Simpsons on the television screen. But she
believes the sun ceremony ``will make people remember what it used
to mean.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This year's ceremony was to have been held inside a large igloo,
a splendid dome of lake ice like the kind Mrs. Iqalliyuq remembers.
Several men worked hard to complete it in time for Saturday's event
but when they got to the top they ran out of ice blocks, which had
been cut in the fall, before the ice got too thick.
</P>
<P>
   So the ceremony was held inside the school gym _ not on Jan. 14,
the day the sun actually reappeared, but on Saturday night, which
was more-convenient. Three women who had clearly lived through many
``great darknesses'' expertly placed cotton and moss wicks on the
edge of three soapstone platters brimming with seal blubber.
</P>
<P>
   Then they were lit, not with a piece of flint, as in the old
days, but with a plastic cigarette lighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tug of war going on between traditional culture and
southern culture,'' said George Qulaut, the Assistant Deputy
Minister of the new Department of Culture, Language, Elders and
Youth in Nunavut.
</P>
<P>
   Qulaut believes the Eskimos can win that tug of war if they are
able to learn more about their culture, while also adopting modern
advantages. He said the large wooden dog sleds that many hunters
use are crystal clear examples of how the two cultures can
comfortably accommodate each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``One hundred percent of the sled is southern material now, but
one hundred percent of the technology and knowledge that goes into
it comes from the ancestors,'' Qulaut said. ``Combining them
together makes the perfect sled.''
</P>
<P>
   It should be no surprise that two distinct worlds can learn from
each other _ especially not in a land where a familiar
constellation like the Big Dipper shines brightly in the midday sky
and people call it the great caribou.
</P>
<P>
   Change is occurring rapidly. Women in Igloolik carry their
babies in the traditional way in the hoods of their parkas, but
they also bring along disposable diapers. Men wear caribou breeches
while they zip around on snowmobiles.
</P>
<P>
   And while hunters drink seal blood to warm themselves on the ice
floes, they also like orange soda to cool themselves inside the
overheated gymnasium where they gathered to welcome back the sun,
chant over a ceremonial drum dance, and hoot and holler during the
big night's grand finale: a traditional Western-style square dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done both the drum dance and the square dance,'' said
Samueli Ammaq, a caribou hunter whose fancy dancing is sharp enough
to throw off sparks. ``And I like them both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6781 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HURRICANE-MIGRANTS-AR     01-17 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-MIGRANTS-ART-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPERATE HURRICANE SURVIVORS PUSH NORTH TO U.S. BORDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.M., Ariz., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAPACHULA, Mexico _ About every two days, a cargo train loaded
with fuel and other supplies arrives in this city near Mexico's
border with Guatemala. It departs back north after sundown, empty
but for the human cargo clinging to its sides.
</P>
<P>
   Since a hurricane struck Central America in the fall, leaving
thousands dead and millions homeless, officials say there has been
an alarming increase in the number of immigrants making this
harrowing journey, heading to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Central American immigrants have been jumping this creaking old
night train for more than a decade, embarking on a 15-hour ride
fraught with danger. Hundreds are ambushed and beaten by thieves.
Others suffocate after crawling inside the sealed box cars or are
mutilated when exhaustion causes them to lose their grip and fall
beneath the train.
</P>
<P>
   This latest group, driven by the loss of lives and livelihoods,
is more desperate and more determined to reach the United States,
say immigration officials and social workers who have talked with
them. Among those waiting for the train here earlier this month
were three men from the western Honduras province of Olancho.
Haggard and hungry, they said that their entire village of 500
people had been destroyed by the hurricane, which wreaked an
estimated $4 billion damage. They had left home two weeks earlier,
taking buses for pennies across Guatemala, and already they had
been robbed _ each had brought about $30 for food. One showed a
deep gash on his shoulder left by the thief's machete.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has to be the most sad experience a person could live,
leaving your children,'' said one, Jose Juarez, a farmer and father
of five. ``There are no words to describe that kind of pain. But I
must make this sacrifice for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Mexican officials worry that the increased number of immigrants
crossing the border of southern Mexico could indicate the beginning
of a prolonged and large-scale migration of Central Americans
through Mexico to the United States. Such a migration threatens to
place even greater burdens on border control systems in Mexico and
the United States and would put untold numbers of immigrants at
risk of being robbed, raped, murdered and even enslaved by
immigrant smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   The number of Central Americans detained and expelled at the
southern border has doubled in the last several weeks, Alejandro
Carrillo Castro of Mexico's National Immigration Institute said in
an interview in Mexico City. Institute officers caught 5,800
immigrants _ the overwhelming majority from Honduras, the country
most affected by the hurricane _ last month, compared with about
2,900 in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Border Patrol officials in Laredo, Del Rio and McAllen _
all Texas towns that are easily accessible from Tapachula _ report
significant increases in the numbers of Central Americans detained
in December.
</P>
<P>
   In Laredo, for example, officials report that some 583
immigrants known as ``other than Mexicans'' were detained last
month, compared with 123 in December 1997. And in Del Rio,
officials said the number of immigrants detained who were coming
from places other than Mexico rose to 221 last month, compared with
45 in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While the overall numbers are still low, U.S. officials said,
they are troubled by the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are watching it very closely, and we want to do everything
we can to avert a mass migration,'' said Doris Meissner,
commissioner of the Immigration and Naturalization Service,
referring to Washington's support of numerous reconstruction
efforts across Central America aimed at restoring infrastructure
and creating jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Carrillo said strategies to prevent mass migrations from Central
America would be discussed at a Jan. 26 meeting in San Salvador of
the Grupo Puebla, a gathering of leading immigration officials from
the United States, Mexico, Canada and every Central American
nation.
</P>
<P>
   In Mexico, law enforcement officers charged with protecting
immigrants' rights reported that they provided services to some
3,000 Central American immigrants last month, 10 times the number
in December of 1997. And at the Casa del Migrante, a shelter for
immigrants in Tecun Uman, a Guatemalan town adjoining the Mexican
border, social workers said they served close to 900 newly arrived
immigrants, compared with 200 in December 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other groups of immigrants, the people making the journey
across Mexico's southern border have had no time to plan their
trips, save money or contact relatives who might receive them. Most
travel only with the clothes they are wearing, a little money for
food, and wads of paper, about the size of gum wrappers, with phone
numbers of relatives whom they have not seen or talked to in years.
</P>
<P>
   Another unusual feature of this desperate group is that it
includes middle-aged men, like Jose Elias Perez, 47, who typically
put off notions of abandoning their countries in pursuit of new
lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am past the years where I want adventures,'' said Perez,
while a friend rubbed salve on his swollen ankle. ``I am doing this
because I have no options. In Honduras I had no way to make money.
I had no house. I had no transportation. And I had no food for my
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States,'' he said, ``if they pay me three
dollars an hour, it will be fine with me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   So far, Mexican officials say they have no plans to seal off
their southern border with more immigration agents. Now, 150 agents
are posted along Mexico's 650-mile border with Guatemala and
Belize.
</P>
<P>
   Most are posted here, the most common gateway for immigrants
coming from Central America because the Suchiate River that forms a
natural border between Guatemala and Mexico is low and calm; there
are shelters that provide free food and lodging to immigrants, and
there are accessible forms of mass transportation heading due
north.
</P>
<P>
   The border area near this city is so well known as a transit
stop for illegal immigrants _ as well as a den for smugglers and
others who prey upon the desperate _ that people refer to it as
``Little Tijuana.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent morning, the sun had only been up for a few moments
and already some 200 haggard and hungry immigrants had emerged from
their sleeping places, beneath bridges and in the municipal
cemetery, to gather along the railroad tracks that pass through
town.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was Julio Cesar Rodriguez, 28, a banana farmer and
father of two from El Progreso, who said the fields where he worked
were ruined. Perez, a taxi driver and father of two from Comayagua,
said his entire neighborhood and the car he used to make his living
were swept away in the flood. And Nery Sierra Ramos, 33, broke into
tears as he talked about losing his three children, ages 10, 5, and
1.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the men around him, Sierra said they were his family
now. He called them ``hermanos del camino,'' Spanish for ``road
brothers.'' And even though their journey had been tough _ they had
also been robbed of their money _ they refused to turn back.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are suffering here, but at least we have hope that there
might be a future for us in the United States,'' said Sierra, a
thin man who wore a jeans jacket that looked too small. ``In
Honduras, we have no hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether he thought more Hondurans would follow, he said,
``If they could, all of Honduras would come.''
</P>
<P>
   Another important factor contributing to the increase in the
numbers of immigrants from Honduras, officials and immigrants said,
was that many Central Americans mistakenly believe that the United
States had offered refuge to all victims of Hurricane Mitch. The
confusion apparently arose immediately after the storm, when the
U.S. government delayed deportations of undocumented Central
Americans for humanitarian reasons.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Clinton administration announced that it would
extend the amnesty for Hondurans and Nicaraguans who were in the
United States before Dec. 30 by granting them an 18-month temporary
protected status.
</P>
<P>
   People in Central America believed they had been given a green
light to immigrate. Most of the immigrants interviewed over three
days at different places along Mexico's southern border confirmed
the confusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``We read it in our newspapers,'' said Carlos Cabrera, 21.
``They said that Hondurans who are victims of Mitch will be allowed
to come and work in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are good people who just want to work,'' he said. ``Tell
your president to let us in.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Meissner said that a major thrust of the American
government's work with Central American governments was aimed at
spreading the word that people who immigrate to the United States
would not be given refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Lesbia Gabriel Maldonado, a social worker at the Casa del
Migrante, the immigrant shelter in Tecun Uman, said she had done
several interviews on Honduran radio in an effort to warn people
that they would not be given amnesty in the United States. She said
dozens of immigrants who had gone to her shelter carried ``letters
of recommendation'' from their town mayors or their parish priests,
verifying that their homes have been destroyed and that they
urgently needed refuge.
</P>
<P>
   When she tells them those letters are useless, she said, the
immigrants feel deceived, but not deterred.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say they are already here, and so they are going to go
on,'' she said. ``They have nothing at home. They have no reason to
go back.''
</P>
<P>
   Hugo Ayala Morales, chief of a law enforcement agency that
strives to protect immigrants from attacks, said: ``These people
seem more determined than other groups of immigrants I have seen.
They are more desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those determined to get to the United States was Carlos
Danilo Rojas Gomez, 35, a military sergeant from Tegucigalpa, the
Honduras capital. In what seemed like just a few seconds, he said,
he watched the Choluteca River swell and consume his entire house.
Two of his sisters drowned.
</P>
<P>
   He asked his superior officers to help him and his family find a
place to live. But, he said, they turned him away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I served my country for 16 years and when I went to them for
help they told me I was homeless just like everyone else,'' he
said. ``In that moment, I learned that we are nothing in our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Rojas said he began his journey out of Honduras on Dec. 28 and
made it to Tapachula before immigration agents arrested him on a
bus heading north. Mexican officials sent him back to Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   His skin was sunburned and his eyes were so bloodshot they
matched the pink T-shirt he was wearing. He was worried about his
wife, who was eight months pregnant when he left, he said. After
several collect phone calls to Honduras, Rojas still had not been
able to reach her.
</P>
<P>
   He was also worried about money. He said the $300 he had brought
with him was stolen by two men who held him up. But he refused to
go home. In Honduras, he said, he earned less than $150 a month,
hardly enough to rebuild his house and provide for his family.
International aid flowing into Honduras, he said, is going only to
help the rich.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easier for me to die of hunger trying to get to the
United States,'' Rojas said, ``than to watch my wife and child
suffer hunger.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he said, he would start out again for Houston,
where he hoped to get help from a friend of a friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they catch me 1,000 times,'' he said, ``I will try again
1,000 times until I succeed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
