<P>
   w/TEXAS-INAUG-BBQ _ AUSTIN _ Inaugural BBQ for 14,000 people is
not impossible. (Crider, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   MLKPOLL _ ATLANTA _ More than two of every three Americans
believe that the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. was killed as a result
of a conspiracy, according to a poll commissioned by The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution. Southerners and non-Southerners are in
virtual agreement: About 45 percent of poll respondents say James
Earl Ray conspired with others and about 24 percent say others
besides Ray were responsible for the murder. About 12 percent say
Ray acted alone when King was killed in Memphis on April 4, 1968.
Still, the poll reveals that the majority of Americans (55 percent)
say that nothing valuable is likely to come from further federal
investigation and it's time to move on. (ABrice, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/POLLSIDE _ ATLANTA _ For former FBI agent Donald Wilson, there
is some sense of vindication. In March, Wilson came forward with
two documents he said he retrieved from James Earl Ray's car in
Atlanta in April 1968 but had kept hidden for 30 years. At the
time, a bureau spokesman called the documents a ``total
fabrication.'' However, scientific examination of the documents
since then suggests that they could be legitimate, according to
federal authorities. (ABrice, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   CHILD-ABUSE-DEATHS _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ In the past month,
authorities believe two Western Slope children were killed and one
was seriously injured by men who were caring for them but who were
not their biological fathers. Local mental health and social
service professionals say the incidents reflect a dangerous pattern
among young parents who cannot control their anger. And if the
cases are proven in court, these incidences would parallel national
statistics that show when a child is abused by a person who is not
the biological parent, eight times out of 10 it's a man. (Joyce,
Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   TX-TOBACCO _ AUSTIN, Texas _ The great Texas tobacco case was
supposed to be over. The injured party _ the state of Texas _ has
been getting money from its judgment in the largest single legal
settlement in history. The state's lawyers have already received
their first $200 million paycheck. Squabbling and fighting and
hair-pulling over the attorneys' fees all was supposed to have
ended. Wrong. The $17.3 billion Texas tobacco litigation is
destined for another stop in federal court to find a way to settle
the festering dispute over how much the five private lawyers hired
by the state should be paid. (McCarthy, Austin American-Statesman)
MOVED
</P>
<P>
   ARABS-JEWELS _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ How do you persuade a
Midwestern businessman, to whom you're trying to sell millions of
dollars worth of allegedly fake jewels, that you're a world-class
wheeler and dealer with a pipeline to the world's richest man?
Dress up a 340-pound bearded mechanic in silk sheets, put Arafat
headgear and sunglasses on a couple of employees, hire two hookers
as harem girls and strip the logos off your own private plane.
That's what witnesses say jeweler Jack Hasson did to fool Detroit
broadcasting tycoon Aben Johnson into thinking he was meeting with
``Prince Akhmed,'' nephew of the Sultan of Brunei, at Palm Beach
International Airport. (McLachlin, Palm Beach Post). 40-50. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SATELLITE-FLARES _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Piercing the night
with sudden shards of light, a new globe-girdling array of 79
communications satellites called Iridium, lofted by Motorola Inc.,
is already arcing across the heavens, emitting brilliant ``flares''
from their super-reflective antenna-panels, bedazzling and
bedeviling astronomers by turns. The unexpected side effect of the
satellites _ brilliant solar reflections of light as they pass
overhead _ has caused concern among astronomers, some of whom see
the satellites as yet another source of light pollution in a world
where the magic and majesty of the star-sown night sky are already
under assault from myriad streetlights and neon signs. (Browning,
Austin American-Statesman) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   EVERGLADES-PLAN _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The federal
government's $7.8 billion Everglades rescue plan would provide more
water for suburbs while failing to restore South Florida's marshes
and bays, scientists at Everglades National Park say. But rather
than scrap the plan, park leaders say they want to help the U.S.
Army Corps of Engineers fix it. (King, Palm Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FLA-PREPAID-TUITION _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ With a couple of
weeks to go until the 1998-99 enrollment deadline, the Florida
Prepaid College Program got some unwanted publicity last week: A
respected national publication ripped the program as one of the
worst in the country. A look at the reasons why. (Horine, Palm
Beach Post) MOVED
</P>
