<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6793 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TAL     01-17 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TALKS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COURTSHIP OF AIRTOUCH, HEAVY DATES AND HEFTY STAKES
</HEADLINE>
   (See also AIRTOUCH-GINN-PROFILE) 
(ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The telephone call that Vodafone's chief executive, Chris Gent,
got on New Year's Day was the kind no executive wants on vacation.
His chief financial officer had tracked him down in his Sydney
hotel room to tell him that Bell Atlantic, the largest local
telephone concern in the United States, was close to buying
Airtouch Communications Inc. in a $45 billion stock swap.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's troubling,'' Gent said he told his colleague over the
phone. Vodafone Group PLC is Britain's largest wireless
communications company, and Gent had wanted to buy Airtouch
himself. Late last year, in fact, Gent had been in discussions with
Sam Ginn, the chairman of Airtouch, which is the largest wireless
carrier in the United States and has prime European operations.
Seeing his chance slipping away, Gent heeded the urgings of his
closest advisers and wrote a one-page letter reiterating his
interest in Airtouch. He faxed it to Ginn the next day.
</P>
<P>
   So began two weeks of all-night strategy sessions and telephone
calls between sleep-deprived executives in four time zones as
Vodafone tried to woo Airtouch from the embrace of Bell Atlantic.
In the end, Vodafone prevailed, and on Friday it announced a $60
billion Vodafone-Airtouch pact that would create the world's
largest wireless communications company and a powerhouse that could
become a serious rival to telecommunications titans like AT&AMP;T and
British Telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that Bell Atlantic was clearly going to make an offer
was the catalyst,'' Gent said on Saturday, recounting the events in
a telephone interview from London.
</P>
<P>
   For outsiders, the outcome recalled another recent international
telecommunications bidding coup: Worldcom's daring snatching of the
Wall Street darling MCI from the arms of staid British
Telecommunications in 1997. And for Airtouch, as for MCI in that
earlier deal, in the end the choice came down to the sought-after
company's vision of its own future.
</P>
<P>
   For the Airtouch board, that picture did not fully form until
directors met Friday in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going into the board meeting, the decision was not made,''
Ginn said in an interview Saturday. ``The board evaluated it on
price, and they tried to understand the strategic rationale of both
offers.''
</P>
<P>
   The call was so close that one Bell Atlantic spokesman said his
company even had a victory news release drafted in case Airtouch
went with the Bell Atlantic bid.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's outcome was one that hardly seemed likely after Gent
and Ginn held tentative merger discussions last fall. Those talks
quickly faltered because the chief executives could not agree on
various fundamental issues, people close to the negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   But the talks had the effect of prompting Bell Atlantic to step
up its own tentative discussions with Airtouch in the last month,
and soon they were heading toward what looked to be a conclusive
deal. ``We moved quickly to present Sam an option,'' Ivan
Seidenberg, chairman and chief executive of Bell Atlantic, said in
an interview Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   After that New Year's Day call, Gent said, he knew it would take
some convincing to prove to Ginn that his interest was real. So
bankers from Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co., which advised Vodafone, spent
the first weekend of the new year talking to representatives from
Airtouch's counsel, Morgan Stanley Dean Witter. The two sides
devoted two days to sorting out, among other things, how much
Vodafone might be willing to pay.
</P>
<P>
   One person close to the talks said Vodafone knew that it had to
be aggressive on price and that it had to lobby Airtouch's other
top executives, too, and not just Ginn. By the end of the weekend,
Vodafone came up with a two-page preliminary proposal offering to
begin discussions to buy Airtouch for about $55 billion in cash and
stock. The offer was faxed on Jan. 3 to Ginn, who had cut short his
vacation in Hawaii to return to San Francisco and monitor the
events.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Airtouch's discussions with Bell Atlantic had hit a
snag. There were still several unresolved issues, Seidenberg said,
and the two companies were reluctant to formalize a pact until the
problems were resolved. One hitch was that the companies would need
regulatory approval to use an accounting method that would enable
them to avoid hefty charges. Until there was at least a preliminary
ruling from the Securities and Exchange Commission, there was
little Bell Atlantic could do but wait and see how serious
Vodafone's offer was.
</P>
<P>
   That holdup gave Vodafone much needed time. On Tuesday, Jan. 5,
Vodafone publicly disclosed its interest in Airtouch. That day,
Gent dispatched a team including Vodafone's finance director,
Kenneth Hydon, from London to New York to begin exploratory talks
with Airtouch executives. Critics of Vodafone had warned that the
company's share price, which had been rising for months, was
unsustainably lofty and that Ginn would prefer a more stable
currency, like Bell Atlantic stock. ``We were trying to show them
that the synergies underpinned the stock's value,'' Gent said.
</P>
<P>
   The mood was relaxed at a private dining room at the Four
Seasons in midtown Manhattan that Wednesday night as Hydon met at
dinner with Airtouch's chief financial officer, Mohan Gyani, and
their negotiating teams. The conversation was cordial but hardly
substantive _ Vodafone's team was tired from the long flight _ and
after a few hours of amiable chatter, the two parties agreed to
spend the next day trying to figure out just how compatible the
companies might really be, people close to the discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   Ginn declined to comment on the timing or substance of any talks
he or his advisers had, citing various lawsuits by shareholders
filed after word of the negotiations became public. But people
close to the companies say that by this point, Airtouch negotiators
were keeping their cell phones on day and night or wearing pagers
so they could be kept aware of progress in both sets of talks.
</P>
<P>
   To complicate things further, other companies, including MCI
Worldcom, were calling to express interest in Airtouch, too. ``They
were in battle mode,'' one person, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said of the Airtouch teams.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
