</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATORS BATTLE OVER ISSUE OF WITNESSES IN IMPEACHMENT TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and Democrats drew new battle lines
Sunday over whether witnesses should be called in the impeachment
trial of President Clinton, with some senators threatening to
subpoena independent counsel Kenneth Starr and informant Linda
Tripp to question their motives in the case.
</P>
<P>
   Warning that efforts to turn the Senate floor into a full-blown
courtroom would lead to ``a spectacle'' that could ``go on and
on,'' Democrats said they are prepared to question Starr about why
and how his investigation grew from the Whitwater land development
deal to an inquiry on the president's private sexual behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to have witnesses,'' said Sen. John Kerry,
D-Mass, on NBC-TV's ``Meet the Press,'' ``I'd be very interested in
... having a whole host of people _ Linda Tripp, Kenneth Starr _
all of whom might shed enormous light as to how it is we got
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., speaking on CBS-TV's ``Face the
Nation,'' said he would focus his questions on ``prosecutorial
abuse'' if Starr is called.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, although admitting that the House prosecution
team had put on a fairly impressive case against the president,
said there was more than enough evidence and witness testimony in
the record now for senators to decide whether Clinton should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is accused of perjury and obstruction of justice
stemming from conduct in Starr's investigation of his extramarital
affair with former White House intern Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there needs to be witnesses. This is the most
thoroughly investigated, widely reported scandals in history,''
said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 13-member House prosecution team continued to press
its case for why they ought to be allowed to question witnesses in
the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you could obtain a conviction or I could clearly
ask for a conviction until we have testimony,'' said Rep. Asa
Hutchinson, R-Ark., on ABC-TV's ``This Week'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on NBC, both Senate Judicary Committee Chairman Orrin
Hatch of Utah and Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison of Texas, indicated
that they were open to having witnesses if Clinton's White House
lawyers offer conflicting information or fail to rebuff the charges
made by the House prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do need to wait until all the presentations have been
made,'' Hutchison said. But she reminded her colleagues that in the
end witnesses might be necessary to ensure that the Senate gives
``both sides a fair chance'' to make their case before the trial
ends.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's team of seven lawyers will begin its defense arguments
Tuesday afternoon and will continue Wednesday and Thursday. The
team, headed by White House counsel Charles Ruff, met Sunday to go
over its case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, spent the day preparing for his State of the
Union address to a joint session of Congress on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make the case that the allegations are not supported
by the facts or by the law, and they do not warrant nullifying the
results of a national election and removing the president from
office,'' White House spokesman Jim Kennedy said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Once the Clinton defense team wraps up its case, the senators
will be give a day or two to ask questions of both the prosecution
and defense teams. The questions will be submitted in writing
through Chief Justice William Rehnquist, who is presiding over the
Senate trial.
</P>
<P>
   When the question and answer phase has been completed, the
Senate will then begin making decisions on whether to allow
witnesses. Several House prosecutors said Sunday that they would
like to at least hear from Lewinsky, Clinton's private secretary
Betty Currie and his friend Vernon Jordan. Republicans contend that
Currie and Jordan conspired with the president to help him hide his
affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   It will take a majority vote by the senators to approve each
witness that testifies. But before senators get around to voting on
each witness, Democrats plan to offer a motion to dismiss the case.
If it passes, the trial will end and there will not be a Senate
vote on whether to convict Clinton and remove him from office.
</P>
<P>
   If the motion fails, however, the trial would probably continue
to a final vote for conviction or acquittal. If a final vote does
occur, it will take at least two-thirds, or 67 senators, voting in
favor of conviction for Clinton to become the first president ever
ousted from office for impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who is expected to offer the
first motion for dismissal, said Sunday that if it fails and the
Republicans succeed in summoning witnesses, the trial would likely
continue well into the spring or early summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you go that route,'' he said on ``Meet the Press,'' ``we
may be talking May or June before we finish this trial.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Paul Wellstone, D-Minn., said the prosecutors' demands that
they be allowed to call witnesses demonstrated how weak their case
against Clinton is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that the House has not made its case. I think that the
(perjury and obstruction) charges lack proportionality,'' Wellstone
said on ``Meet the Press.'' ``I think people in the country know
that the president's not been entirely honest ... But I think
people are also saying ... are these grounds for removing a
president from office, for overturning an election? I think the
answer is a resounding, `No.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats, however, did say they would be willing to support
a motion to censure the president for his actions.
</P>
<P>
   That idea was floated again by former Senate Majority Leader
George Mitchell, D-Maine, who has been advising Clinton during the
impeachment process. He agreed that Clinton's conduct had been
``seriously wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He deserves to be held accountable, but not removed from
office,'' Mitchell said, calling censure the ``appropriate
punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The House case is based on the principle that the underlying
circumstances don't matter ... But that's not true in life and it's
not true in the law, and it's not true in the law of perjury
itself,'' Mitchell added.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion, though, that Clinton get off with a public
reprimand from the Senate, was more than some Republicans could
bear.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Sen. Phil Gramm, for example, said on ``This Week'' that
censure, at least politically, would be an easy way out of the
impeachment dilemma for GOP lawmakers. He said he favors pushing
through to the end of the trial and having a vote on conviction,
even if it fails.
</P>
<P>
   ``Censure is to cover politicians,'' he said, adding: ``I don't
need any cover.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
