<HEADER>
A6795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TAL     01-17 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VODAFONE-AIRTOUCH-TALKS-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: Airtouch teams . 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Reporters, too, were hungry for any scrap of news, sometimes
with unexpected consequences. A week and a half ago, some news
outlets were reporting that MCI Worldcom was planning to bid more
than $55 billion for Airtouch in an all-stock offer that could be
announced within a few days. People close to MCI said that although
the company had talked to Airtouch, an offer was not planned.
Nevertheless, after those reports, Worldcom saw its stock drop 11.5
percent in two days before it released a statement saying it would
not pursue a bid for Airtouch.
</P>
<P>
   By the middle of last week, Bell Atlantic had received an
affirmative response from the SEC on the accounting matter. With
that, executives began weighing whether to raise the $45 billion
offer, people close to those discussions said.
</P>
<P>
   Seidenberg, who talked to Ginn almost every day, would not
comment on what the higher price would have been, except to say
there was a range as well as other considerations. People close to
the talks said Bell Atlantic might have been willing to increase
the amount of stock Airtouch shareholders would get _ to 1.6 shares
of Bell Atlantic stock for every Airtouch share owned, up from the
original 1.4 ratio that was initially reported, thus raising the
overall value of the bid.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Gent held his first telephone conversation with
Ginn since sending the fax 10 days earlier. ``I had to elicit from
Sam how he felt about all this,'' Gent said.
</P>
<P>
   The two discussed a variety of concerns, including whether the
new company would give each party an equal number of seats on its
board and how they planned to retain key executives and employees.
They also discussed what breakup fees would be paid to Vodafone if
another bidder intervened after a deal was announced; they settled
on $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the two talked by phone again. Gent, eager to wrap
things up, was prepared to increase his offer. ``But Sam said,
`Let's sleep on this and talk in the morning,''' Gent recalled.
</P>
<P>
   So at 7:30 a.m., California time, on Friday, Gent phoned Ginn
with the revised offer: Airtouch shareholders would still get half
a Vodafone American depository receipt for each Airtouch share, but
Vodafone would increase the cash portion of the offer from about
about $6 to $9 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Ginn murmured acknowledgment, Gent said, but did not say which
proposal Airtouch was likely to accept at the board's meeting later
that day.
</P>
<P>
   At 2 o'clock that afternoon, California time, it was Ginn's turn
to call Gent and tell him: ``We have a deal.'' The board had
accepted the offer, in which Airtouch stockholders would get $97 in
cash and stock for each of their shares, based on Friday's stock
prices. Gent would remain as chief executive in the combined
company, to be named Vodafone Airtouch P.L.C., and Ginn would
become nonexecutive chairman of the board.
</P>
<P>
   In London, where it was 10 p.m., Gent was relieved but not
wholly surprised. ``I sensed that this is the way it would go,'' he
said later.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic, receiving a consolation call a short time later,
released a statement that its discussions with Airtouch had ended.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview on Saturday, Ginn declined to discuss the
board's deliberations in detail. ``We had fiduciary issues to deal
with,'' he said, ``and I think we did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic's chief, for his part, reflected on the last two
weeks' events. ``The way we see this is this was more of a missed
opportunity,'' Seidenberg said. ``In the short term, the board
thought Vodafone was the better choice. In the longer term, it is
our job to prove that we would have been the best proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginn, meanwhile, suggested that the relationship with Bell
Atlantic was far from over. He said that Airtouch still had gaps in
its geographic coverage of the United States and that Seidenberg's
company might still play a role.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there is a way to sit down with Bell Atlantic and solve
on a partnership basis what we couldn't solve on a merger basis,''
Ginn said wearily. ``I will be working on that next week.''
</P>
</TEXT>
