u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-KNOCKOUT-NY     01-17 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-KNOCKOUT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TYSON'S RUST MAKES BOTHA CARELESS
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After often resembling an awkward amateur for nearly five
rounds, Mike Tyson upheld one of boxing's oldest truths on Saturday
night in Las Vegas, Nev.: One knockout punch is worth a thousand
punches that miss.
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe not a thousand, but Tyson missed with at least two
or three dozen wild left hooks and right hands _ many more than
even this now 32-year-old heavyweight was expected to miss in the
rusty resumption of his compelling career.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder Francois Botha, the self-proclaimed ``White Buffalo''
from South Africa who now lives in Newport Beach, Calif., dropped
his red gloves and stood in the middle of the ring, as if daring
Tyson to hit him. And then Tyson did. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I never saw the punch,'' Botha would say later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know I threw it,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   It's like that sometimes in boxing, as Tyson's latest trainer,
Tommy Brooks, explained in analyzing the short right hand that,
instead of missing, landed flush on Botha's jaw, mouth and nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you try for a knockout punch, you never get it,'' Brooks
said. ``If you start boxing, throwing your jab, that's when it
happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha bounced on his rump, somehow wobbled to his feet but then
flopped backward into the ropes that saved him from falling into
the ringside seats. By then the referee, Richard Steele, had waved
his arms, signaling that Tyson had won at 2 minutes 59 seconds of
the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Seeing that Botha was helpless, Tyson hurried across the ring
and wrapped his arms around him to prevent him from sliding through
the ropes anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a brother,'' Tyson said later of his sudden
sportsmanship. ``It's not that serious. It's just a boxing match.
There are some people I would like to let go through those ropes,
but they aren't fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the first round, however, Tyson had not resembled
a good samaritan. In a clinch at the bell and after a few punches
after the bell, he and Botha locked arms. Steele tried to break
them. So did their cornermen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike grabbed my arm, he was trying to break my arm, to twist
my arm,'' Botha would say calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Told later that Botha accused him of trying to break Botha's
arm, Tyson said, ``He's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few tense moments, it appeared that perhaps Tyson's temper
had snapped, as it had on June 28, 1997 in the same MGM Grand
Garden ring when he bit both of Evander Holyfield's ears. His
disqualification prompted the Nevada commission to revoke his
license. He finally was re-licensed here three months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very concerned,'' Marc Ratner, the commission's
executive director, said of the scrum after the bell. ``I told
Steele, `This is your fight. Take control. Take points away.' He
went to each corner and told them, `We don't want a DQ here.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the next round, Steele ordered the judges to deduct a point
from Tyson for holding, but Tyson was so rusty and Botha so
unafraid that the three judges would have Botha in command through
four rounds _ 40-35 on the cards of both Dave Moretti and Dalby
Shirley, 39-36 on that of Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started fooling around too much,'' Botha acknowledged. ``I
really thought this was going to be easy. I got careless. I got a
little too cocky and I paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tyson said: ``It was only a matter of time. I was telling my
trainer, `I'm working on him, I'm slowing him down.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, if Botha hadn't slowed himself down and left himself open
for that big punch that he never saw, Tyson might not have been
able to outpoint him over the 10 rounds of this nontitle bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't prove anything, I'm just trying to do well,'' Tyson
acknowledged. ``I feel great to do what I love to do, but I've got
to improve. I've got a long way to go.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's new manager, Shelly Finkel, mentioned late April as the
time frame for Tyson's next bout against contenders Vaughn Bean,
Axel Schulz or Lou Savarese.
</P>
<P>
   No matter who it is, Tyson's next opponent isn't likely to fear
the Tyson mystique that once turned good boxers, such as Michael
Spinks and Frank Bruno, into ice sculptures, frozen with fear.
Holyfield twice showed that if you're not afraid of Tyson, if you
hit him back, you can beat the bully out of him.
</P>
<P>
   And on Saturday night Francois Botha wasn't afraid of Tyson
either. He just got too cocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling Mike, `I'm going to hit you with a phantom
punch,''' Botha said. ``But he hit me with a phantom punch first. I
knew he had the punch. I just got careless.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Tyson got a little lucky, salvaging a one-punch
knockout when he might have lost a demeaning decision. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
