<HEADER>
A6797 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONLINE-ANTISMUT-LAW-A     01-17 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-ANTISMUT-LAW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE SMUT LAW HEADS INTO COURT
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Ohio, Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By PAMELA MENDELS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As general manager of Powell's Books, Miriam Sontz helps oversee
a successful retailer with seven stores in and around Portland,
Ore., and a growing international online book-selling business.
</P>
<P>
   But for several months, Ms. Sontz has had a worrisome
distraction: whether Powell's site (www.powellsbooks.com), by
including ``The Mammoth Book of Erotica'' and other sexually candid
books for sale on the World Wide Web, could run afoul of a new
Federal law intended to protect children from online smut.
</P>
<P>
   That is why Ms. Sontz is applauding her employer, which along
with the American Civil Liberties Union and 15 other groups and
businesses has filed a lawsuit to overturn the Child Online
Protection Act. President Clinton signed the act into law as part
of the huge budget bill in October, but the child-protection
measure was almost immediately challenged on constitutional grounds
and has never gone into effect. Hearings on the matter are
scheduled to begin Wednesday in Federal District Court in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a nutshell,'' Ms. Sontz said, ``this law aggressively
attacks one of the more financially profitable aspects of my
business _ and aggressively attacks my First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lowell Reed Jr., who issued a temporary restraining order
against the act last fall, will preside over an expected three days
of hearings this week to decide whether the court should issue a
preliminary injunction that would continue delaying the law's
taking effect, pending further courtroom proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   The law, with penalties of up to six months in prison and
$50,000 in fines, makes it a crime for the operator of a commercial
Web site to knowingly make available to those under 17 certain
sexually explicit material considered harmful to minors. It is a
successor to an earlier attempt to limit children's access to
online pornography, the Communications Decency Act. The United
States Supreme Court struck down that law in 1997, saying that it
was so vague and broad that it violated the First Amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the new law say it has one aim: to shield children
from smut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bill is narrowly written,'' said Peggy Peterson, an aide
to Rep. Michael Oxley, the Ohio Republican who sponsored the
legislation in the House. ``It applies only to commercial sites and
material that is harmful to minors _ explicit raw pornography.''
</P>
<P>
   The law's supporters are particularly incensed by teaser
photographs _ free and readily accessible sexually explicit images
that are used to advertise offerings that adult customers,
generally using a credit card, can pay to obtain from sexually
oriented sites.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Department of Justice, which is defending the
law, would not comment on the case. But in court filings, they have
argued that the statute is so much narrower than the Communications
Decency Act that it passes constitutional muster. For one thing,
they say, the old law applied to all online material , including
e-mail. The new law is aimed only at commercial Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the government's lawyers argue that the ``harmful
to minors'' standard of the new law _ which requires, among other
things, that the speech be prurient and lack scientific, literary,
artistic or political merit for young people _ is more precise than
the ``indecent'' standard of the earlier law.
</P>
<P>
   Government lawyers also note that the law would not outlaw
sexually explicit material altogether but require that it be put
behind a kind of electronic gate, like an online credit card
verification system, on the presumption that only adults would have
access to it. They say the law is analogous to retail laws in many
states that require that pornographic magazines be bound in
brown-paper wrappers or displayed out of the sight and the reach of
minors.
</P>
<P>
   But Christopher Hansen, a lawyer for the American Civil
Liberties Union and one of the lead lawyers for the group
challenging the law, contends that a virtual brown-paper wrapper
would undercut not just free speech on line but Internet commerce
of various sorts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The law will seriously stifle the creativity and new business
models that are starting to thrive on the Net,'' Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   He argued that credit card verification systems were expensive
and often technically unworkable. And perhaps most important to a
Web business, he said, such systems are an annoyance to customers,
who might be inclined to turn elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen's clients include a range of Web businesses concerned
that they may find themselves posting material that they consider
legitimate but that the law's advocates might nevertheless deem out
of bounds. Among them are Condomania, the online version of the
condom retailer; Artnet.com, which for a fee from artists and
galleries, displays artwork, including nudes, and the Internet
Content Coalition, a group of 23 publishers with online ventures,
including Time Inc., MSNBC and The New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   Hansen said that even though the law granted an exception for
work of political, scientific or other merit, Web publishers might
still have a hard time deciding what is legally suitable for
children. He cited the example of the Starr Report, with its
graphic descriptions of sex in the White House. Publication of that
report, he said, might have posed problems for online news outlets
had the new child-protection law been in effect.
</P>
<P>
   But Robert Flores, senior counsel to the National Law Center for
Children and Families, which has submitted a friend-of-the-court
brief in support of the law, contends that the Child Online
Protection Act is written carefully enough that it would zero in
only on Web enterprises clearly engaged in the smut trade. And he
said he was convinced that the law would not apply to any of the
plaintiffs in the case. ``None of them are out to produce material
designed to appeal to the prurient interest of children _ or adults
for that matter,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But such arguments do little to ease the mind of Ms. Sontz. She
wonders what enforcers of the law would make of such Powell's books
as ``Bisexual Option,'' ``Outspoken Role Models in the Gay and
Lesbian Community'' and one whose title contains a common
four-letter vulgarity. ``The key here is that I don't know what's
offensive or harmful to minors,'' she said. ``That leaves me in
purgatory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
