</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-HOLOCAUST-MEMORIAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGREEMENT REACHED ON HOLOCAUST MEMORIAL FOR BERLIN  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ After a bitter debate over how to commemorate the
Holocaust in the new German capital, Berlin, agreement has been
reached on a memorial that will include a vast field of stone
pillars, a 65-foot-high wall of books and a research center for
scholars.
</P>
<P>
   The accord already has been approved by Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder but is still subject to parliamentary review. It blends
longstanding proposals by the New York architect Peter Eisenman
with additions intended to satisfy the new government of Social
Democrats and Greens, whose initial declarations last year opposed
a vast memorial and caused an uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Over more than a decade, the proposed monument next to the
Brandenburg Gate, in central Berlin, has become a focus for
competing visions of how best to invite reflection on Hitler's
annihilation of European Jews. The fierce exchanges have, above
all, reflected Germany's search for a way to balance memory with a
growing desire to look forward.
</P>
<P>
   With the government and Parliament set to move to Berlin later
this year, the vacant 4.9 acre site and the lack of a plan to fill
it had become an embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told everyone involved a few weeks ago that they could
generate a lot more heat if they liked, but they could certainly
generate no more light,'' said Michael Blumenthal, a former U.S.
treasury secretary who is the head of the new Jewish Museum in
Berlin, a distinct project. ``It was time to decide this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a breakthrough mediated by Blumenthal and hammered out
between Eisenman and Germany's top cultural official, Michael
Naumann, the essence of the huge field of stone pillars _ to which
the government had objected _ is to be preserved.
</P>
<P>
   The number of pillars is to be reduced from about 2,800 to
somewhere between 1,800 and 2,100, and a building to be called
``The House of Remembrance'' _ consisting of an atrium and three
sandstone blocks _ is to be added.
</P>
<P>
   This building _ an archive, information center and exhibition
space _ is to be flanked by a thick, 100-yard-long wall that will
house a million books between an exterior made of patterned black
steel and a glass interior side.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Wall of Books.'' containing works that scholars will be
able to consult, is intended to symbolize the concern of the
Schroeder government that the memorial not be merely
backward-looking and symbolic but also educational and useful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am absolutely positive that this new project will now be
built,'' said Naumann. ``All statements pro and con have been taken
care of. This is a superb synthesis. It is not a compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   From the building, four glass-roofed tunnels are to lead out
into the field of pillars.
</P>
<P>
   ``My memorial has won _ it is intact, with the adjunct of a
Holocaust archive,'' Eisenman, who is in Berlin for the
presentation of the new plan, said Saturday. ``Beside it, you have
what a amounts to a nonbuilding, a proscenium for the monument.''
The project is due to be unveiled formally on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann appeared elated that an agreement had been reached. His
initial remarks last year about the monument _ including a
comparison of its monumentalism to the work of Hitler's architect,
Albert Speer _ provoked bitter opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Naumann had a first meeting with Eisenman that did
not appear to go well.
</P>
<P>
   Naumann came out with what seemed to be various half-baked ideas
for a genocide-watch center, a museum and a research center.
</P>
<P>
   But this time, after further talks between Naumann, Eisenman and
Blumenthal in New York on Dec. 30, the project seems to have been
well-prepared and to have broad backing.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal said agreement also had been reached that the
memorial would be administered by the Jewish museum, insuring that
there is no duplication _ an important breakthrough because it had
been unclear how the memorial and museum would relate to each
other.
</P>
<P>
   The government is particularly eager to settle the matter of the
memorial because a debate over memory of the Holocaust has been
raging in recent months between a prominent writer, Martin Walser,
and members of the small German Jewish community. Walser said last
year that Auschwitz had become a ``moral cudgel'' and a ``tool of
intimidation'' for Germans.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, the debate and the dithering over the memorial
became intertwined. But a breakthrough appears to have been made.
``This time,'' said Eisenman, ``It may even happen''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
