<HEADER>
A6799 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-FRENZY-MARKE     01-17 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FRENZY-MARKETPLACE-ART-668(2TAKES)NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: ANYTHING.COM LIKELY TO BE HOTTEST ISSUE IN CLASS OF
'99
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ms) 
 By DAVID BARBOZA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You want Internet companies? We'll give you Internet companies.
That's the message Wall Street is sending investors in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Class of '99 introduces a new crop of Internet-related
companies with initial public offerings that will surely test
investors' hunger for anything that hints at the World Wide Web.
The first of these, Marketwatch.com, came roaring onto the market
last Friday. And at least 15 more Internet initial offerings are
expected within the next few weeks and months.
</P>
<P>
   But after a frenzied run on Internet stocks, a run that has sent
the shares of dozens of as yet unprofitable ventures to dizzying
heights this winter, Wall Street analysts are warning that
investors could suffer huge losses by eagerly chasing these hot and
volatile issues.
</P>
<P>
   Speculators bent on riding Internet stocks higher may be
distorting the true value of these startup companies, some analysts
say. They also warn that, with the huge number of offerings coming
to market this year, investors' willingness to go after anything
with a ``dot com'' moniker may make it difficult to distinguish
companies with solid prospects from companies simply trying to cash
in on the market's exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what's called a herd mentality _ everyone's going in
the same direction not knowing what they're going after,'' said
David Menlow, the president of the IPO Financial Network, a company
in Millburn, N.J., that rates public offerings. ``How do you stop
to determine what a quality company is when Internet companies are
trading on vapors?''
</P>
<P>
   The first signs of a frenzy this year came Friday with the first
day of trading in shares of Marketwatch.com, a financial news Web
site partly owned by the CBS Corp. Wall Street underwriters had
priced the initial offering at $17 a share. But the stock soared as
high as $130 a share in early trading before closing at $97.50, up
$80.50, or 474 percent, for the day.
</P>
<P>
   That price run-up was not too different from the pattern that
emerged last year, when Internet stocks like Broadcast.com,
Theglobe.com and Ebay rocked Wall Street with some of the fastest
opening-day sprints in history. Theglobe.com, for instance, soared
a record 606 percent in its first day of trading. The Internet
enthusiasm has been further fueled by the recent surge of
Amazon.com and other electronic commerce stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Wall Street analysts say that underwriters have
been besieged by Internet-related companies seeking to go public.
``There's a pipeline chock full of deals,'' said Henry Blodget, an
Internet industry analyst at CIBC Oppenheimer. ``The market is
willing to fund anything right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those in the pipeline: Ivillage, a Web site that caters
primarily to women 25 to 49 years old; Healtheon, a
business-to-business health care information company founded by
James Clark, who is one of Netscape's founders, and Priceline.com,
an Internet auction site that enables consumers to bid for airline
tickets, automobiles and hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   While many leading Internet companies are preparing public
offerings _ including Barnesandnobles.com, the online operation of
the bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble Inc. _ some investment bankers say
that the quality of many prospective offerings is dropping.
``There's a lot of low-quality merchandise in the pipeline, and a
lot of companies with just `dot com' on the back of their names,''
said Scott Ryles, head of the technology investment banking group
at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also high-quality ventures coming public, he said,
including a growing number of companies involved in
business-to-business activity on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Investors should be forewarned that a majority of the offerings
still come from money-losing ventures. Almost every offering
prospectus reads as if the underwriters hit a computer key that was
programmed to spit out the words, ``The company expects to incur
losses for the foreseeable future.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Priceline.com, for instance, has had cumulative losses of $41
million; Ivillage has lost $65 million in three and a half years;
and Healtheon has had losses of $73 million since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Startup losses, however, have not prevented Internet companies
from winning over investors. The Class of '98 demonstrated that
Internet companies are hot, regardless of their profitability.
Initial public offerings of Internet companies gained an average of
119 percent last year, according to Richard Peterson, a spokesman
for the Securities Data Corp. in Newark.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of the activity came late in the year when a cool
market for initial public offerings quickly heated up after media
reports on the soaring popularity of the Internet and the rush of
retail business done over the Internet during the holidays.
``There's just huge mass media attention focused on the Internet,''
said Bill Burnham, an Internet industry analyst at Credit Suisse
First Boston. ``It's like a magnifying glass focusing the sun on
one little spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Day traders, who often trade in and out of stocks to ride price
trends and buying momentum, saw the rising demand for Internet
shares and pushed the volume of Internet trades to record levels.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts warn that the speculative frenzy has driven Internet
stock prices to irrational levels. As a result, they say, many
investors have lost considerable sums chasing volatile Internet
stock offerings, whose prices have occasionally fluctuated wildly
on their first day of trading, as Marketwatch.com did on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trading in some of those Internet stocks that go public is
totally irrational,'' said John L. Steffens, vice chairman of
Merrill Lynch. ``Some of the companies going public have been in
business two years and they're valued 10 times higher at the end of
the public offering; it doesn't make sense. Some of these issues
will have to come home to roost.''
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that the Internet offers promising business
possibilities or that many of these companies may eventually turn
out to be profitable enterprises. But everyone from Wall Street
investment bankers who take companies public to everyday investors
gleeful about big stock market profits is questioning the soaring
values of these young companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't fictional growth or tulips; these companies are
growing,'' Blodget, of CIBC Oppenheimer, said. ``But these
valuations are problematic. I don't think there's a sector in
history that's been valued at these heights. It's totally
frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, analysts and traders say, is that there are
so few Internet stocks available to eager investors, and so much
demand for those that are available that trading imbalances abound.
</P>
<P>
   One measure of the supply-demand imbalance is the huge amount of
daily trading volume in comparison with the total number of shares
available. Nearly 10 million shares of Marketwatch.com changed
hands Friday, for example, even though only 2.75 million were
issued. Dozens of other Internet companies have been similarly
traded.
</P>
<P>
   With a large new crop of Internet companies preparing to go
public, though, analysts say that the supply-demand imbalance may
ease, and that could lead to softening stock prices as money chases
many more issues. Analysts say investors may also alter their
habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are going to become more selective,'' said Lawton
Fitt, an investment banker at Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. ``There used to
be a lot of personal computer companies and now there are only a
handful.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are also concerned about a surge in the number of
company insiders who sold their shares in the fourth quarter of
1998, which some see as a sign that insiders believe the stocks are
near a peak. ``We continue to marvel at a veritable explosion of
insider selling at the Internet-related or E-trade companies,''
said Bob Gabele, the president of CDA Investnet, a company that
tracks insider selling.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
