<HEADER>
A6802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-OVERSEAS-NYT &LR;      01-17 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-OVERSEAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN PRESS JUDGES CLINTON, AMERICA AND WASHINGTON AND FINDS ALL 
 WANTING
</HEADLINE>
   (DUPLICATION NOTICE: Also filed in category `w') 
(See also: IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-UNION, IMPEACH-CASE,
IMPEACH-LEGAL) 
(DW) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ There he stood Sunday, on the back page of the
Munich-based Sueddeutsche Zeitung, the American president dressed
only in heart-adorned boxer shorts, clutching a glass of champagne
in his right hand and Monica Lewinsky in his left hand.
</P>
<P>
   The image, a photograph of a set of stamps just issued by the
self-styled Georgian state of Abkhazia, was given more prominent
play than the article inside on President Clinton's impeachment
trial in the Senate and appeared to sum up the amusement and
bemusement of most Europeans before what they see as America's
prolonged self-laceration.
</P>
<P>
   But beside the bewilderment and the familiar Gallic smirk at
what is portrayed in Paris as ``American puritanism,'' a new and
graver sentiment appears to have emerged with the start of
Clinton's trial. It is that the world's most powerful nation is
politically adrift, its capital marooned from its citizens, its
leader oddly cocooned.
</P>
<P>
   Noting the prosperity now enjoyed by many Americans, the
complacency such wealth can engender, and the relative lack of
interest in the trial, the French daily Le Monde wrote in an
editorial: ``When citizens feel themselves so little concerned by
public affairs, it is never a good thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, a correspondent for the daily La Repubblica reported
similar concerns for America's equilibrium in a piece from
Washington. Such European worries have mounted sharply since
Clinton's decision to bomb Iraq last month, an unpopular move here
that has been widely portrayed as futile, capricious and driven by
domestic politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to collective respect for the state, they have
played too closely with fire, gone too far in destroying what was
left of trust between voters and public officials,'' La
Repubblica's dispatch said. ``The senators of the new American Rome
seem to have understood. They appear to have understood that since
yesterday, in the court of the Senate, it is not just William
Jefferson Clinton on trial, but America itself.''
</P>
<P>
   That America is increasingly judged harshly or with bewilderment
by many Europeans for whom the trial is the culmination of a
process that has made the United States seem more foreign to them.
</P>
<P>
   Europeans have heard many time that this trial is about truth
and lies and that such matters may qualify as ``high crimes and
misdemeanors.'' But what many Europeans seem to see or sense is the
tawdry intertwining of a presidential sexual dalliance, the
relentlessness of a right-wing prosecutor, and furiously partisan
politics.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sueddeutsche Zeitung, in an article entitled ``One
Hundred for Justice,'' the trial amounts to the ``last chance to
save any American dignity.''
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, a daily newspaper, Slovo, the successor to the
official Communist Party organ Pravda, also said America's image
had suffered. It declared that Clinton's problems undermined the
image of ``citadel of law, high morals and morality that America
pushed on the world for decades.''
</P>
<P>
   Britain takes that morality more seriously than most European
countries, and its papers have been more inclined to judge Clinton
severely. The Republican rhetoric about the trial being in essence
about ``the rule of law'' and the place of ``honor'' in society has
found a deeper resonance in London than in Paris or Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The right-wing Daily Telegraph used the prosecution's words _
``His lies were not few or isolated, but pervades his whole
testimony'' _ as its banner headline in a dispatch from Washington,
and an editorial noted that, ``The longer the trial goes on, the
greater risk that Mr. Clinton's famous luck will break.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the center-left Sunday paper, The Observer, gave
considerable space to an opinion piece by Henry Porter, an
editorial writer, calling for Clinton's resignation. ``It's not
about sex any more but about his lying, and no sane person alive
doubts that he lied or that he tried to influence witnesses,''
Porter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But many continental Europeans greeted the trial with a yawn.
People feel they have already heard the story. The Lewinsky case
has been reported for many months, with successive sexual
revelations splashed on front pages. Most papers relegated the
start of the trial to inside pages.
</P>
<P>
   It seems that only if a conviction became more likely _ an
outcome that many European commentators feel may be more influenced
by a Wall Street tumble souring the American mood than by any
revelation in the Senate _ would the trial receive more prominent
coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the longer the trial goes on, the more European
concerns about the state of the American polity seem likely to
deepen. In its editorial, Le Monde suggested that the U.S.
Constitution may have been perverted by the partisan politics of
the impeachment process.
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans, the paper said, rightly saw the trial as ``the
engagement for partisan ends of a process of impeachment that
should remain exceptional, reserved only for the gravest crimes, as
the Constitution says.''
</P>
<P>
   This sentiment, it added, was likely to lead to further mistrust
of the political class. The headline on the editorial was
``Washington Guilty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
