<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6805 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BELARUS-JOURNALISTS-A     01-17 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELARUS-JOURNALISTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELARUS IS MUFFLING INDEPENDENT JOURNALISTS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINSK, Belarus _ It was a suspiciously finicky pack of burglars
who broke into the sardine-can offices of the little newspaper
Naviny one night in November.
</P>
<P>
   The thieves ignored television sets, computer monitors and
thousands of dollars in other business equipment. Instead, they
unscrewed the casings of four desktop computers and, after a few
minutes' work, departed with their innards _ memory banks holding
all the newspaper's photographs, archives and reference material.
</P>
<P>
   ``They only left the body,'' Igor Germenchuk, Naviny's editor in
chief, said not long ago, holding up one of the beige casings. ``We
accumulated information for eight years, and we lost everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Who ``they'' are is officially a mystery, but there is little
doubt as to the prime suspects. Naviny's editors have borne the
enmity of the Belarus president, Alexsander G. Lukashenko, since
they criticized his government a year ago in the newspaper Svaboda
and the police promptly shut the paper down.
</P>
<P>
   Lukashenko has not had to padlock another newspaper since. From
beatings to financial pressure to more subtle bumps in the night,
his government has deployed an ingenious array of methods to muffle
free-speaking journalists.
</P>
<P>
   The result is an independent press which, as the government
likes to boast, can say anything _ but which, as journalists
themselves agree, seldom speaks above a whisper.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the social and political publications have a
self-censorship situation,'' said Nikolai Inin, chairman of the
board of Belapan, which provides nonpartisan coverage of events to
local and foreign clients. ``Editors realize that if they print
materials that don't follow the state line, they may lose their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Those news outlets that refuse to toe that line often discover
that newsstands refuse to sell more than a handful of their
publications, that officials no longer speak to them, or that
printers are suddenly too busy to handle their work.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the variations are endless. Belapan, a rigorously
nonpartisan outfit, found that the state cut all its telephone
lines for ``routine maintenance'' at the height of 1996 elections,
which were widely regarded as rigged and which handed dictatorial
powers to Lukashenko.
</P>
<P>
   By statistical yardsticks, the Belarus press seems reasonably
robust. Only 285 of the country's 1,000 print publications are
officially state-controlled, and independent broadcasters
ostensibly compete for an audience with state-owned television and
radio stations.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say, however, that the numbers mask the real story. Of
the 716 independent publications, only 30 regularly critique the
government's actions; the rest are penny-savers, comics and other
apolitical journals. Only one of those 30 appears more than once a
week.
</P>
<P>
   Independent broadcasters uniformly avoid critical coverage of
the government for fear of losing their licenses. Russian broadcast
journalists whose coverage upset the government have been jailed.
</P>
<P>
   Watchdog groups like the International Helsinki Federation for
Human Rights and Human Rights Watch say the Belarus government has
systematically suppressed press freedoms that the nation's
Constitution supposedly guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   Human Rights Watch charged in a recent report that the
government has sought since 1994 to control the independent press
with the clear aim of driving such outlets out of business, for
instance by issuing orders to close independent radio and
television stations.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring the Committee to Protect Journalists, a New
York-based group, named Lukashenko one of the world's leading
opponents of press freedom. It later presented an award to a
Russian television journalist, Pavel Sheremet, who was jailed after
reporting on smuggling along the Belarus-Lithuania border.
</P>
<P>
   For journalists of lesser stature or smaller audience, a web of
government restrictions, fiscal penalties and a timely warning or
two may suffice. Independent publications are hard put to compete
with their state-owned rivals. Distributing independent journals
through official channels _ many news kiosks are government-owned _
can cost half again as much as is charged a state publication, and
the number of copies sold is often sharply limited.
</P>
<P>
   Obtaining information is no easier. A memorandum leaked last
year detailed a government-wide ban on providing information to
independent journalists. Last month, a new directive required all
news media to obtain a license before publishing any government
legal information.
</P>
<P>
   For some, the penalties are more severe. In June 1997, the
offices of Zdravy Smysl, a Minsk newspaper covering human-rights
issues, were ransacked and several computers and fax machines
destroyed. That fall, the government found the paper guilty of
breaking distribution rules, fined it $1,650 and ordered its press
run reduced from 23,000 to 10,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   Last June, the State Committee on the Press handed the editors
an official warning, charging the paper with printing false
information. The error consisted of identifying the government's
ban on contacts with the independent press as a decree, rather than
a directive. A second warning, the committee said, could lead to
the newspaper's closure.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those who still work for the nongovernmental press, it's
no longer just a profession; it's more,'' said an official of the
Belarusian Association of Journalists who asked not to be
identified. ``They're working out of their principles. Because any
moment, they could be closed.''
</P>
<P>
   That aptly describes Irina Khalip, editor of the weekly Imya, or
Name, an opposition journal whose hallmark is a weekly collage that
often features Lukashenko, usually in insulting situations.
</P>
<P>
   Imya has received two official warnings from the state press
committee. In 1997, Ms. Khalip and her father were among 40
pass-carrying journalists covering a protest march in Minsk when
the police surrounded and beat them. Ms. Khalip's father suffered a
concussion, cuts and a kidney injury. Later, he lost his job at a
state film studio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
