<HEADER>
A6810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AZERBAIJAN-ALIYEV-362     01-17 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AZERBAIJAN-ALIYEV-362&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AILING LEADER OF AZERBAIJAN IS FLOWN TO TURKEY
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ One of the key figures in the
multi-billion-dollar Caspian energy boom, President Heydar A.
Aliyev of Azerbaijan, fell ill and was flown Sunday to a hospital
in Turkey for treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Health Ministry in Azerbaijan said Aliyev,
75, was suffering from bronchitis and a viral infection.
</P>
<P>
   Reuters quoted an unidentified aide to Aliyev as saying he had
``a problem with his heart.'' That was disputed, however, by Mayor
Rafael Alakhverdeyev of Baku, the capital. He said Aliyev had ``a
bad cold'' and would remain in Turkey ``not more than one week.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev arrived in Ankara aboard a private jet sent to Baku by
President Suleyman Demirel of Turkey, a close ally. Demirel met him
at the Ankara airport and joined the convoy that took him to a
military hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a bout of influenza going around in Azerbaijan, and
I caught it and became pretty ill on the sixth day,'' Aliyev said
at the hospital, looking pale but standing unaided. ``My son called
my dear friend Suleyman Demirel, and he sent two teams of doctors,
but thanks to God, by the time they came I was not in a serious
condition any more.'' A statement issued by the Turkish foreign
ministry said that although his condition was not serious, ``it was
decided that to be sure, he should be given more tests.''
</P>
<P>
   Since rising to power in 1993, Aliyev has ruled Azerbaijan
virtually alone, making even the smallest decisions himself. His
departure or extended absence from the Azerbaijani political scene
could have profound consequences for the region.
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijan is the center of an oil and gas bonanza that has
brought tens of billions of dollars in foreign investment to the
Caspian region and made it the object of intense competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aliyev is the one who has created the fertile environment for
investment here, so should something happen to him, everyone is
going to hope that what he laid down will continue,'' Igor
Effimoff, president of Pennzoil Caspian Corp., said in a telephone
interview from Baku. ``People are likely to be very nervous until
things become clear.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In addition to his role in encouraging foreign investment,
Aliyev has shrewdly balanced pressures by outside powers. He has
favored the United States and the West, much to the displeasure of
some powerful figures in Russia, who would like to bring Azerbaijan
back under Moscow's control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Aliyev's replacement with a leader more amenable to Russian
interests would alter the strategic situation in the region almost
overnight,'' two specialists on Caspian affairs, Michael P.
Croissant and Cynthia M. Croissant, wrote in a recent study.
``Aliyev's departure would thus cast serious doubt on Azerbaijan's
prospects for remaining an independent state.''
</P>
<P>
   Azerbaijanis re-elected Aliyev to a second five-year term in
October. Foreign observers declared the election unfair because
opposition figures were denied free access to the news media, and,
in at least one case, assaulted by police when they sought to hold
a rally in Baku. Few, however, doubted that Aliyev would have won
even if the election had been completely free.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Baku said Sunday the president of the rubber-stamp
Parliament, Murtuz Aleskerov, would run the country while Aliyev
was away.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is unclear who might emerge if Aliyev is unable
to return to Baku soon. One opposition journalist, Shahin Abbasov,
predicted in an interview several months ago that the post-Aliyev
period would be characterized by ``a breakdown in national unity as
competing economic groups fight for power and access to the oil
wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Aliyev spent three months in a Moscow clinic in 1987, when he
was a member of the Soviet politburo. He said later that doctors
told him he had suffered a heart attack, but that he did not
believe them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely important, there's no doubt about that,'' Brian
Chipman, a Baku-based investment analyst, said in a telephone
interview. ``Before he came to power, you really had chaos and
disorder in Azerbaijan. The big issue is whether the prosperity and
peace that he's brought in his tenure has taken root to the extent
that no matter what happens to him, normal life will carry on here.
Everyone will be waiting and keeping their fingers crossed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
