<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 19:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6817 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GEN-SIDEWAY-COLUMN-LA     01-17 0288
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-SIDEWAY-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE STREAK EXTENDED, ANOTHER BROKEN AND, FINALLY, A SUPER BOWL
SHOW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As the year 2000 approaches, this space highlights
important dates in Los Angeles sports history over the last
century:
</P>
<P>
   __ Jan. 19, 1998: Chick Hearn broadcasts his 3,000th straight
game for the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jan. 19, 1974: UCLA's winning streak _ the longest in college
basketball history _ is snapped at 88 games when Notre Dame comes
back from an 11-point deficit with less than four minutes to play
and edges the Bruins 71-70.
</P>
<P>
   __ Jan. 20, 1980: Los Angeles' only appearance in a Super Bowl _
and the first time a team had a so-called home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In Super Bowl XIV before 103,985 at the Rose Bowl, the Rams
scrambled to take a 13-10 halftime lead. They managed a 19-17 lead
going into the final quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But game MVP Terry Bradshaw's 73-yard pass TD to John Stallworth
finally broke them. After a Franco Harris 1-yard TD run (set up by
a Bradshaw-to-Stallworth 45-yard pass), Pittsburgh had a 31-19
victory and its fourth Super Bowl title.
</P>
<P>
   Former USC star Lynn Swann also had a 47-yard TD catch from
Bradshaw that gave the Steelers a 17-13 lead just minutes into the
second half.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a trivia question: Who threw the Rams' only touchdown
pass in the game? It was Lawrence McCutcheon, on a halfback option,
for 24 yards to Ron Smith. Vince Ferragamo, who stepped in at
midseason for the injured Pat Haden, completed 15 of 25 for 212
yards but was picked off three times.
</P>
<P>
   __ Birthdays this week: Saturday: Former USC and Rams
quarterback Pat Haden (46).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1901EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6821 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DELAWARE-MURDER-420(2     01-17 0456
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELAWARE-MURDER-420(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAWARE JURY FINDS LAWYER GUILTY OF MURDERING LOVER
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By IRVIN MOLOTSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Thomas J. Capano, a lawyer and a member of
Delaware's political elite, was convicted Sunday of first-degree
murder in the death of a woman who had tried to break off their
romance.
</P>
<P>
   Capano, who denied killing the woman, Anne Marie Fahey, but
admitted in his trial that he had dumped her body in the Atlantic
Ocean, could face life in prison or the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The events in the case had transfixed Delaware for more than two
years and the announcement of the verdict, 934 days after Ms.
Fahey's disappearance _ her family had counted off each day _ took
on the tone of a civic event.
</P>
<P>
   The judge, William Swain Lee of Superior Court, had warned the
spectators in the courtroom against any outbursts, but a bailiff
slipped a note with the verdict through a crack in the locked door
to another official, and there were cheers in the hallway when it
was read to the several hundred people would could not get in.
</P>
<P>
   Capano showed no reaction as the foreman of the jury, which had
to believe the crime was premeditated to convict on the sole charge
of first-degree murder, said, ``guilty as charged.''
</P>
<P>
   Capano's mother, Marguerite, wept, and so did Kathleen
Fahey-Hosey, the victim's sister.
</P>
<P>
   There were cheers outside the New Castle County Courthouse when
all the participants except those connected to Capano walked
outside. There was even a loud cheer for Lee. The Wilmington
newspaper, The News Journal, printed an ``extra,'' a six-page
Sunday afternoon edition of 5,000 copies.
</P>
<P>
   The sentence will be imposed by Lee, but the jurors, who
deliberated three days after a three-month trial, will return to
court on Wednesday to recommend, but not mandate, the penalty.
</P>
<P>
   The judge told the jurors that the penalty phase would not
require a unanimous decision, as the guilty verdict did, but rather
a majority opinion as to whether the killing was aggravated or had
mitigating circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fahey, 30, had worked as the scheduling secretary to Gov.
Thomas J. Carper. Capano, 49, the eldest son of one of the state's
wealthiest real-estate families, had been the chief counsel to the
former governor, Michael N. Castle.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fahey disappeared on the night of June 27, 1996. Earlier
that evening, she had had dinner with Capano, who was married and
has since been divorced. Prosecutors did not have a body or a
weapon, and relied on circumstantial evidence to build a case that
Capano killed her when she tried to end their two-year affair.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, prosecutors introduced passages from Ms.
Fahey's diary. In the final entry, she described Capano as ``a
controlling, manipulative, insecure, jealous maniac.''
</P>
<P>
   After denying for 28 months that he knew anything about Ms.
Fahey's disappearance, Capano admitted in October that he had
disposed of her body by stuffing it into an ice chest and then
dumping it at sea but continued to deny that he had killed her.
</P>
<P>
   The real killer, he said when he took the stand last month, was
Deborah MacIntyre, with whom he had had an affair for 18 years, he
said, and who was jealous of Ms. Fahey.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debbie shot Anne Marie, and it was absolutely positively _ I'm
certain _ accidental,'' Capano said, telling of Ms. MacIntyre's
brandishing a pistol and of an accidental discharge as he struggled
to disarm her.
</P>
<P>
   He said that it was to protect himself and Ms. MacIntyre that he
did not call the police, decided instead to dispose of Ms. Fahey's
body.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. MacIntyre, who testified that she had bought a gun at
Capano's request and given it to him a month before Ms. Fahey's
disappearance, was one of those who conducted press conferences on
the courthouse steps Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very confident that the justice system would do the
right thing,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked her reaction when Capano had shifted the blame for
the shooting to her, Ms. MacIntyre answered, ``It didn't surprise
me.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Capano's brothers, Gerard Capano, told jurors that on the
morning of June 28, the two of them drove to Stone Harbor, N.J.,
lugged the ice chest onto his 25-foot fishing boat and sailed 60
miles out to sea, to a spot known for sharks, and emptied the
contents.
</P>
<P>
   The cooler was soon recovered by a fisherman and ultimately
traced to Capano.
</P>
<P>
   Another of Capano's brothers, Louis, testified that Capano had
discarded a sofa and a rug that might have been stained with blood.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers are expected to plead guilty to minor charges in
connection to the slaying. In exchange for their cooperation, they
have been promised they will not receive jail sentences.
</P>
<P>
   One of Capano's lawyers, Joseph S. Oteri of Boston, said in a
news conference: ``The jury was a serious jury. They've spoken.
We're not happy, but that's the process. We'll go on to the
appellate process.''
</P>
<P>
   Oteri looked out on to the dozens of television and newspaper
photographers and dozens more reporters with microphones and
notebooks drawn to the courthouse on a day in which downtown
Wilmington would otherwise have been deserted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a feeding frenzy,'' he said of the coverage of the
case. ``This is O.J. Jr., but with the opposite verdict.
</P>
<P>
   About 150 people were able to crowd into Lee's courtroom. One
was Edward Lafferty, a telephone repairer for Bell Atlantic in
Wilmington, who said, ``We've been here since quarter to 6 this
morning. I was third in line.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he was so intent on seeing the verdict handed up,
Lafferty said: ``We've been following the trial very extensively
and we're here to see that justice is done. I've been here three
times before. So far as I'm concerned, the man is guilty. I have no
question about that at all.''
</P>
<P>
   David C. Weiss, a lawyer for the victim's family, told a
cheering audience outside the courthouse: ``We're real pleased and
satisfied. It is not a time for celebration, of course. Nothing can
bring Anne Marie back.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter how privileged you may be,'' Weiss added, ``justice
applies to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss lamented that the killing and trial had ``disturbed'' what
Ms. Fahey actually was because it emphasized her weaknesses, not
the loving role she played in her family.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne Marie was more than Tom Capano's mistress,'' Weiss
declared.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fahey's family did not participate in the consecutive
statements on the courthouse steps. Instead, a sister and four
brothers held a subdued news conference in the cafeteria of the
Chase Manhattan Center nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The repeated applause at the courthouse, said one brother, Brian
Fahey, was ``surreal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a surprise,'' he said. ``It's odd, but I understand
their reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Another brother, Robert, said that the family had no opinion of
whether Capano should be sentenced to death or to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, life in prison can be a cruel punishment,'' he
said. ``It doesn't matter. It's up to the jury and the judge to
decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The family was to gather Sunday night, he said, but not to
celebrate the conviction. ``If we celebrate anything, it will be
Anne Marie's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fahey-Hosey said that in the trial, Capano's ``true
personality became very clear. He was manipulative.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the verdict, she said: ``I am relieved. I'm numb. We learned
that Anne Marie was shot, but we don't know what happened to her.
It's very sad. It's a hollow victory. We all miss Anne Marie, and
she's not coming home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
