<HEADER>
A6832 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-TRASH-VIRGINIA-2TA     01-17 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-TRASH-VIRGINIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIRGINIANS INDIGNANT AT GIULIANI'S TRASH TALK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)  (mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RICHMOND, Va. _ Virginians are struggling to decide what odors
wafting out of New York City smell more foul _ mushrooming mounds
of garbage or uppity pronouncements from Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Nostrils flared across the Old Dominion last week at news of a
possible tripling of deliveries of New York City garbage. Up to 2.2
million tons a year, Virginians learned, could be heading up the
James River, bound for landfills in a state that already is
embarrassed to place second (behind Pennsylvania) as America's top
garbage destination.
</P>
<P>
   Noxious as the news was _ Gov. James Gilmore III called it
``highly unacceptable'' and spoke of his ``duty'' to ban garbage
barges on state rivers _its perceived toxicity was quickly exceeded
by the mayor's statement about why non-New Yorkers have garbage
obligations.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for the top-drawer culture that visitors soak up in
New York, the mayor argued, they should be willing to bury some
trash back home. A ``reciprocal relationship,'' he called it.
</P>
<P>
   In this state where people take pride in their manners, the
mayor's reasoning has incited widespread outbreaks of incivility.
Long-simmering suspicions about Yankees _ their arrogance, their
pushy politicians and the unspeakable nature of their garbage _ are
suddenly boiling over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now let me see if I got it right,'' said state Sen. William
Bolling, a Republican and longtime critic of out-of-state trash.
``I come up to New York and I spend my hard-earned money and
somehow in exchange for that privilege, I am supposed to take your
trash? This represents a certain arrogant attitude that is not
consistent with the way we do business in Virginia. I can't think
of a single issue that has made my blood boil more than this.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Sunday at the governor's mansion, Gilmore, a
Republican, said he was ``offended'' by the Republican mayor's
reasoning on garbage, which he described as ``really an outrageous
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To come out and basically try to further the discussion by
saying we had a moral obligation because some Virginians from time
to time visit New York is not proper,'' said Gilmore.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he was concerned that the image of Virginia,
which he described as ``one of the top technology states in the
country,'' with more than 1,000 high-tech companies, including
America Online, was being unfairly maligned by the trash issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very much on the rise and we don't want anyone to get
the impression that Virginia is only good as a garbage
repository,'' Gilmore said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's office has dismissed such comments, which resounded
here in the state capital during last week's opening of the General
Assembly, as mere carping from ``pandering politicians trying to
achieve their own agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just politicians are peeved. Business leaders with
multimillion-dollar investments in garbage importation speak
bitterly of the public-relations disaster they say the mayor has
created.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this past week, when people here say Yankee trash, they
think it's redundant,'' said Charles Carter III, an 11th-generation
Virginian whose family owns Port Tobacco at Weanack, a
state-of-the-art facility for containerized garbage on the James
River.
</P>
<P>
   Carter finds it hard to believe that Giuliani is entertaining
thoughts of running for national elective office.
</P>
<P>
   ``Giuliani couldn't have said anything that could have harmed
his own cause more. He is definitely not presidential material,''
Carter said.
</P>
<P>
   If Virginia's governor and the Legislature follow through on
last week's threats to ban garbage barges on the river _ and there
are constitutional reasons why such a state ban might not hold up
in court _ Carter stands to lose lots of money. He says his family
does not have the resources to take the state on in a long court
battle.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's advice to the mayor: ``We'll take the trash, but keep
your mouth shut.''
</P>
<P>
   The largest company that disposes of New York's garbage in
Virginia is Waste Management Inc. of Houston. It has invested $15
million in Port Tobacco and had planned to begin barge shipments
there in April. Asked if the mayor had helped Waste Management in
its delicate negotiations with the governor and the Legislature, a
company spokeswoman, Christine Meket, who has been dispatched to
Richmond for damage control, said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   For years, environmental groups, investigative reporters and a
few lawmakers in Virginia have tried to raise public awareness of
what they see as the ecological and road-safety risks of the
state's rapidly increasing importation of garbage. The business has
boomed here in the last decade, creating giant landfills located
mostly in land-rich, cash-poor African-American communities in
central Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   New York City, driven by the legal deadline to close its
landfill at Fresh Kills on Staten Island by Dec. 31, 2001, has
become Virginia's fastest-growing source of garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Garbage-truck accidents, complaints about putrid odors and state
records documenting the arrival of untreated syringes and vials of
human blood have all raised public awareness here about trash
rolling into this state from New York. A poll released last week by
Virginia Commonwealth University's Center for Public Policy found
that 87 percent of Virginians want to cap trash shipments into the
state.
</P>
<P>
   But Matthew Higgins, a spokesman for Giuliani, said Sunday that
at least some Virginians welcomed New York's trash. ``Simply put,
this is a business that creates jobs and generates economic
activity,'' he said. ``New York City has already been contacted by
a number of communities in Virginia that want this trade.'' He
would not say which communities wanted the city's garbage. But he
said the city had no choice but to find alternatives to Fresh
Kills.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But judging by comments this weekend from shoppers at a mall
outside Richmond, Giuliani has been uniquely effective in
crystallizing attitudes toward big-city garbage in the minds of
average Virginians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had not been thinking about it until Giuliani made his
remarks,'' said Kitty Jones, 55, a school secretary from Henrico
County who was having lunch on Saturday outside the Chick-Fil-A
booth in the food court at Virginia Center Commons mall.
</P>
<P>
   Since reading about the mayor in the papers and watching him on
television in the past week, Ms. Jones said she had found herself
wondering why Giuliani would say such a thing and what kind of town
would support such a man.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think of New York, you think of arrogance,'' Ms.
Jones said, adding that it was probably unfair to judge a whole
city on the basis of its mayor's behavior. ``I'm sure they are all
not like that, are they?''
</P>
<P>
   In the Virginia Legislature this year _ an election year here _
garbage is emerging as the hot-button issue. On one side, there are
quality-of-life complaints, especially from lawmakers in affluent
northern Virginia, where highways in the Washington suburbs are
inundated with out-of-state garbage trucks.
</P>
<P>
   On the other, there is the deepening dependence of central
Virginia counties on revenue from landfills. In Charles City County
south of Richmond, $32 million in revenue from a landfill that
takes New York City garbage has allowed county supervisors to build
a new school system and an industrial park and to cut property
taxes by 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the legislative mix, according to state records, is an
increasing flow of campaign money from waste industry companies.
</P>
<P>
   Given the volatility of the garbage issue, state legislators on
both sides of the aisle here said they were stunned by both the
content and the timing of Giuliani's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor should realize that this is a hot political topic
and the general approach should not be to fan the flames,'' said
Delegate Kenneth Plum, chairman of the state Democratic Party.
``But this is effectively what he has done.''
</P>
<P>
   Down in Charles City County, whose 934-acre landfill is operated
by Waste Management Inc., school leaders and county planners
reacted more in sadness than in anger to the mayor's theory of
interstate garbage-culture reciprocation.
</P>
<P>
   They said the county, which has a population of about 7,000
people, many of whom are among the poorest residents of Virginia,
simply cannot afford a huge, politics-driven reduction in the
amount of garbage coming into the landfill. It is ready to begin
receiving New York garbage from the new port on the James River _
if the barges are not banned by the state Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landfill is the biggest boon to Charles City County in
modern times,'' said Bill Britton, the county planning director.
``Every tax since 1988 has either stayed the same or has been
lowered. At the same time, we have been able to build a whole
school system _ not just one school _ but a $21 million school
system.''
</P>
<P>
   The county's school board chairman, Charles Giles, agreed
wholeheartedly with Giuliani's statements last week that any
attempt by Virginia to ban barge shipments of garbage would be
overturned by federal courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want anyone to interfere with interstate commerce,''
Giles said. ``It is a constitutional right.''
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Britton declined to comment on the mayor's
invocation of a garbage obligation in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, managing director of the family-owned port on the James
River, had no such reticence.
</P>
<P>
   He said that before last week's comments by the mayor, he had
heard sketchy reports of a similar public-relations debacle in New
Jersey. In December, the mayor surprised and infuriated Gov.
Christie Whitman with a plan to ship trash to transfer stations in
her state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had thought that brouhaha must have been exaggerated,''
Carter said. ``But it sounds like the mayor has apparently got a
big enough mouth that he not only can get his feet in it, but
several other people's feet in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter then allowed himself to ask what he described as a
sarcastic question: ``Is the mayor always such a wonderful and wise
person in all his comments?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
