<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 19:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6848 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SANFRAN-SPCA-ART-925&AMP;     01-17 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SANFRAN-SPCA-ART-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVING CATS AND DOGS, IN A `NO-KILL' NATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)   (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When Richard Avanzino leads a tour of the
headquarters of the San Francisco Society for the Prevention of
Cruelty to Animals, he cannot help sounding terribly pleased.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no shelter like this in the world,'' he said the other
day as he ushered guests through the society's Maddie's Pet
Adoption Center. He was not really bragging. Under his direction,
the San Francisco SPCA has become the envy of humane societies
across the country, a place where tourists go and one out of three
city households donates time or money.
</P>
<P>
   In this $7 million shelter, abandoned dogs live in airy,
glass-walled ``apartments'' with doggy futons, televisions and
throw rugs. Cats have elaborate jungle gyms to play in, potted
grasses to munch on and fish videos to watch on their televisions.
The rooms are so spacious that the SPCA offered to shelter some of
the city's many homeless people in them, though most people decided
it was not a great idea.
</P>
<P>
   But the society's biggest accomplishment, Avanzino said, is
pushing San Francisco to become the first no-kill city in the
United States _ one where no adoptable animals are put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Avanzino is now taking this philosophy on the road. Known as a
brash pioneer among animal protectors, Avanzino is launching his
biggest, most ambitious project: He wants to make every shelter in
the country no-kill within 10 years, and he has $200 million from
the owners of PeopleSoft, a $5.5 billion Silicon Valley software
company, to help reach his goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that killing is not an acceptable management tool
for us to use as stewards of our nation's animals,'' he said.
``Given that, we're going to do everything we can to provide a
creative resource to help shelters develop their goals of finding
homes for every adoptable animal.''
</P>
<P>
   About 700 of the country's 5,000 shelters call themselves
``no-kill.'' Still, in a country where nearly 5 million dogs and
cats are euthanized each year in overcrowded shelters, and the
human society mantra to spay and neuter seems lost on the wider
public, the notion of a ``no-kill nation'' sounds rather
far-fetched, even with $200 million in seed money. Avanzino insists
it can be achieved shelter by shelter, city by city. The San
Francisco SPCA last year saved 4,897 dogs and cats, finding 82 so
diseased or ill-tempered that they had to be put to death.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, Avanzino said, when Dave Duffield started
PeopleSoft to create software for human resource applications,
people laughed at that, too. ``All revolutionary ideas,'' Avanzino
said, ``are rejected at first.''
</P>
<P>
   Duffield and his wife, Cheryl, who have a personal worth of $1.9
billion, had already given the San Francisco SPCA $1.5 million _ $1
million to help build Maddie's, named for their late miniature
schnauzer _ when they lured Avanzino away from the presidency of
his beloved SPCA after 22 years with their $200 million offer to
use in heading the Duffield Family Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ``And there's more to come,'' said Duffield, who calls the money
a pledge they made to Maddie, who died of cancer in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``My wife couldn't have children,'' he said, ``and at a tough
time in our lives, we got Maddie, and she was a tremendous friend
to us. We told ourselves that if we ever had money, we would return
some back to her kind.''
</P>
<P>
   In theory, the plan for a no-kill nation is simple: Animal
shelters receive hefty grants that increase each year as they start
achieving a five-year goal of finding homes for every adoptable
animal, regardless of age, appearance or physical disability.
Within five years, when its goal is met, the shelter is rewarded
with $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will help them continue to launch creative ways to adopt
out animals,'' Avanzino said. ``And when other shelters see what
the first is doing, they'll want to try it. Success brings more
success.''
</P>
<P>
   The concept of a no-kill nation has critics. Some animal welfare
organizations question how ending euthanasia is possible when the
number of unwanted animals far exceeds the number of people willing
to adopt them. They also say that labeling a shelter no-kill could
make the public think ill of struggling shelters that do kill
animals to make room for others that might suffer and die slowly on
the streets as strays.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Newkirk, president of People for the Ethical Treatment of
Animals, lauds the goal of a no-kill nation, but doubts it can be
attained. ``The people who are coming to fund the no-kill shelters
obviously have high hopes and big hearts _ and deep pockets,'' Ms.
Newkirk said. ``But every day, I pray that some of that money will
go to the unpopular roots of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   That, she said, includes the failure of pet owners to spay and
neuter their animals. In fact, a component of the no-kill nation,
Avanzino said, would be reducing animal birth rates, as well as
helping people keep their pets and increasing adoptions. But Ms.
Newkirk said she was still skeptical that no-kill could be achieved
on a wide scale.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they're doing in San Francisco is all absolutely
praiseworthy,'' she said. ``But I do think that we cannot condemn
the shelters that do euthanize, when there are animals who would be
suffering on the streets if shelters couldn't bring them in because
they had no room. I don't think there will ever be world peace, and
I don't think we'll ever have a no-kill nation.''
</P>
<P>
   Avanzino deflects all criticism with a wry smile. ``It's not
only doable,'' he said, ``it's not even hard.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Bolstering his confident claims is the success of the San
Francisco SPCA. When Avanzino, who has a doctorate in pharmacology
and a law degree, joined the organization in 1975, it was operating
at a deficit. Its annual budget is now nearly $12 million, making
it one of the richest shelters in the country. He raised membership
to 87,000 from 3,500, increased annual donations to $4.5 million
from $47,000 and increased the SPCA's volunteer roster from zero to
2,287 _ and counting.
</P>
<P>
   The society has also started one program after another _ some
now common in shelters throughout the country _ to help its
abandoned animals find and keep homes. They include three-month
training programs that pair dogs with deaf people, a mobile
adoption program, doggy day care for working people, an animal
behavior program, an elaborate program that helps older people
adopt older animals and pays for routine veterinary care, and a
program that lobbies landlords to allow tenants to own pets.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who say how can you spend $200 million on
animals when there is all this human suffering,'' Avanzino said.
``But animal philanthropy represents a very small amount of the
work that is being done in this country for those who need it.
We're doing it as a life-saving measure.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate his point, he stopped at an ``apartment'' at
Maddie's to visit Ashton, a graying 7-year-old Australian shepherd
mix who has been in the shelter since early November, longer than
any other animal. At another shelter, the dog might have been
killed by now. Instead, the society is spending hundreds of dollars
on Ashton _ teaching him new tricks, giving him expert medical care
and lots of loving attention, all in the hopes that the dog will
become more adoptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why shouldn't Ashton get a chance?'' Avanzino asked. ``We know
someone wonderful out there will bring Ashton home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
