<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, Jan. 18, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Several inches of windswept snow will fall from central
Wisconsin to southwestern Ontario as a potent low pressure system
draws colder to the south along its western flank. Meanwhile, rain
showers will accompany a frontal system as it moves east from the
eastern part of the Great Lakes and Ohio Valley Monday morning.
During the afternoon and Monday night, colder air will sweep in
from the northern Ohio Valley to the western slopes of the
Appalachians. Scattered snow showers and flurries will occur as the
colder air arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Rain will be locally heavy from the Middle Atlantic coast to
central New England as gusty winds from the southeast bring
moisture from over the Atlantic Ocean. As the rain spreads north,
it may begin as a period of freezing rain in some of the valleys of
central and northern New England. A few rumbles of thunder are
possible as a cold front arrives over the Middle Atlantic states
Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and showers will precede a front as it moves toward the
Southeast coast. In the wake of the front, drier breezes from the
northwest will foster ample sunshine from the southern Plains to
the lower Mississippi and Tennessee Valleys.
</P>
<P>
   In the West, frequent showers will dampen the Pacific Northwest
coast where stiff onshore breezes prevail. Locally heavy snow will
fall above 4,000 feet in the Cascades and Bitterroot Mountains.
Farther south, a frontal system will bring showery rain from
central California to northern Nevada and Utah. Intermittent snow
will occur along west-facing slopes in the central and northern
Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Ice Jams
</P>
<P>
   After frequent Arctic chill this month, the current thaw
combined with expected rain is raising concern about ice jam floods
on creeks and streams around Pittsburgh. While widespread flooding
is not expected Monday, the situation offers a glimpse of what
sometimes occurs in early spring when seasonal downpours and
melting snow lead to ice jams on major rivers that can pose a
serious threat of flooding. Chunks of ice can choke waterways
pushing water backward beyond the river banks. Also, sudden
releases from ice jams that abruptly dislodge can send flood waters
rushing downstream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
