<HEADLINE>
TINY STATE GETS BIG ROLE ON SMALL SCREEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's mid-January, but Rhode Island is hotter than a Tabasco
sandwich. The buzz began last season with an occasional mention on
``Ally McBeal'' and ``Dawson's Creek,'' both of which are set in
Massachusetts. Then came ``Providence,'' a new drama on NBC, and
next is ``Family Guy,'' one of three new animated comedies with
midseason launches on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Though it could be Anyburg, U.S.A., the setting of ``Family
Guy'' is the Ocean State because creator Seth MacFarlane went to
college at the Rhode Island School of Design. When ``Family Guy''
joins the Fox lineup in March, viewers will be treated to
MacFarlane's impression of the Providence skyline, along with
references to Pawtucket's minor league baseball team and
Providence's colorful mayor, Vincent ``Buddy'' Cianci, who has a
junior high school named for him in the series.
</P>
<P>
   If early indications are anything, viewers also may see a
prime-time cartoon show with enough wit and irreverence to match
the best of ``The Simpsons.'' At first blush, ``Family Guy''
resembles a ``Simpsons'' photocopy _ it's about a somewhat
unconventional family of five living in the 'burbs _ but
MacFarlane's humor is gentler and more rooted in middle-class
reality. Never mind that the youngest child, an infant named
Stewie, is constantly plotting his mother's demise.
</P>
<P>
   MacFarlane, all of 25, says his mom is OK with that and all the
other subversive humor in ``Family Guy.'' ``Really,'' MacFarlane
insisted, ``she laughs at the most potentially offensive stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Family Guy'' will get a special preview Jan. 31 after the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   __ If MacFarlane is the next Matt Groening, you might think
Groening, creator of ``The Simpsons,'' is ready for enshrinement in
some sort of hallowed hall.
</P>
<P>
   You might think right.
</P>
<P>
   ``Futurama,'' Groening's new sci-fi animated comedy for Fox,
also premieres in March, complete with something called The Head
Museum in New New York City. With the series set in 3000, Groening
told TV critics in Pasadena that The Head Museum, featuring the
disembodied heads of contemporary celebrities kept alive in jars,
was the only plausible way to create guest spots for the stars of
today. Among the first, uh, headliners scheduled to appear: Leonard
Nimoy, Dick Clark, Pamela Anderson Lee (ironically, from the neck
up) _ and Groening himself.
</P>
<P>
   __ ``Becker,'' the new CBS series in which Ted Danson plays a
good doctor with a bad 'tude, has had mixed reviews, but you've got
to give the set decorator high marks for authenticity. The waiting
room of Dr. Becker's office in the Bronx _ actually Paramount
Studios _ has a National Geographic magazine from 1986.
</P>
<P>
   You might think twice about making an appointment, though.
Buried under some other publications is a copy of the Journal of
the American Veterinary Medical Association. This may explain the
fate of some of Becker's patients. In the appointment book kept by
office manager/head nurse Margaret Wyborn (Hattie Winston) are the
names of dozens of luminaries, some of whom apparently failed to
respond to treatment. Among them is the late Ingrid Bergman. Some
still-living patients in the book, all entered on Winston's whim:
Quincy Jones, Jessica Lange, Molly Ringwald _ and Ted Danson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1945EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0144 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
