A6863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT     01-17 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE PUNCH, AND TYSON'S COMEBACK SURVIVES
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With one electrifying shot, Mike Tyson jolted his career as a
heavyweight boxer back to life at the MGM Grand in Las Vegas, Nev.,
on Saturday night. Now comes the hard part: Keeping it going.
</P>
<P>
   After a 19-month exile imposed by the Nevada State Athletic
Commission for biting Evander Holyfield's ears, Tyson showed
considerable ring rust. Tyson was roughed up and taunted by
Francois Botha, until he landed a crushing right hand that ended
the fight at 2 minutes 59 seconds of the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   One punch. Knockout.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson (46-3) caught Botha (39-2) with a short, snapping counter
right hand that landed flush on Botha's chin. Botha crumpled, went
down on his rear end, tried to get up, but lurched face forward on
the canvas. He made it to his feet at the count of seven, but
stumbled into the second rope. Referee Richard Steele quit counting
and declared the fight over as Tyson went over to help Botha.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't prove anything,'' Tyson said after the fight. ``I'm
just trying. I have a long way to go. We're working on it.''
</P>
<P>
   His veil of invincibility and intimidation is gone. Botha even
taunted Tyson in the fourth round, drawing laughter from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson is to become a world champion again, he will have to go
through boxers who are more skilled than Botha. Tyson at least
proved that he still has a big right-handed punch. And it's a good
thing because he was behind on all the judges scorecards before he
landed the knockout punch.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's handlers were happy he was able to keep his cool, and
accused Botha of trying to Tyson to snap as he did on June 28,
1997, when he bit Holyfield's ears, was disqualified and
subsequently had his boxing license revoked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those first couple of rounds, Botha was doing everything he
could to get him crazed,'' said Shelly Finkel, Tyson's manager.
``But Mike went back to the corner and composed himself. He did a
good job of keeping his cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The first round was punctuated by an ugly scene. After the bell,
Tyson and Botha were locked up in a corner and Steele could not
part them. Tyson had Botha's left arm clamped under his right arm
and was twisting it. Both fighters exchanged punches as both
corners, MGM Grand security and Las Vegas police flooded into the
ring. Tyson was dragged back to his corner by his new trainer,
Tommy Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks had warned Tyson that Botha's manager, Sterling McPherson
and his trainer Panama Lewis, who is banned from boxing because he
removed the stuffing from the gloves of one of his fighters in a
1983 bout, might encourage Botha to try to provoke Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   But Botha said dirty tactics by Tyson prompted the first round
altercation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike grabbed my arm, he was trying to break my arm, to twist
my arm,'' Botha said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about that Tyson said, ``He's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ring was being cleared, Marc Ratner, the executive
director of the Nevada State Athletic Commission, entered the ring
to talk to Steele. If Steele had disqualified Tyson and stopped the
fight, Tyson's career could have been finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him just to take control, take a deep breath,'' Ratner
said. ``I think Richard did take control and I think he did a good
job under some trying circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele deducted a point from Tyson in the second round for
holding Botha's arm and hitting on the break. Not only was Steele
back in control of the fight, Botha was gaining control over Tyson
and building confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's timing was off. He missed with a lot of wild looping
shots. He was loading up on every punch and catching a lot of shots
to the face from Botha. But Tyson was walking through most of the
punches.
</P>
<P>
   Botha even resorted to taunting Tyson in the fourth round, but
Tyson did not lose his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I would knock him out,'' Tyson said. ``It was just a
matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a crushing defeat for Botha. A former International
Boxing Federation heavyweight champion, Botha was noted for his
durability and his ability to take a punch. But he couldn't take
Tyson's best shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just walked into that punch,'' Botha said. ``Mike is a great
hitter. I just got careless. I was trying to psyche him out. We
really said some bad things to each other. I feel I was in control
of things until I walked into that punch. It was a punch I didn't
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said that he will go back to training in two weeks for
another bout in April.
</P>
<P>
   He also has a court date in Maryland on Feb. 5 to be sentenced
on a plea of no contest to two charges of misdemeanor assault that
resulted from his involvement in an incident following a traffic
accident in Gaithersburg, Md., on Aug. 31. Two men alleged that
Tyson struck them following a chain reaction car crash, in which
Tyson's wife, Monica Turner, was hit from behind and pushed into
another car.
</P>
<P>
   There is an outside chance that Tyson's probation on a 1992 rape
conviction could be revoked and he could wind up back in prison in
Indiana, but that seems unlikely at this point.
</P>
<P>
   Finkel said his preference for Tyson's next opponent is Axel
Schulz, another tough brawler who has more boxing skills than
Botha, but lacks the firepower to level Tyson. Botha defeated
Schulz in a 12-round decision in 1996 for the IBF title, but was
stripped when he tested positive for steroids after the bout.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll fight anybody,'' Tyson said. ``If the price is right,
I'll fight a lion.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
