<HEADLINE>
JONSSON, ISLANDERS' ALL-STAR, WORRIES ABOUT INJURED KNEE
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Kenny Jonsson limped out of the National Car Rental Arena
late Saturday night in Sunrise, Fla., his right knee supported by a
brace, the Islanders defenseman felt a wide range of negative
emotions.
</P>
<P>
   He was worried, confused, frustrated. And even considered
himself a little snakebit.
</P>
<P>
   Jonsson twisted his knee as he fell near the Florida Panthers'
goal only 5 minutes 20 seconds into the Islanders' 1-0 loss. He was
helped off the ice, never to return.
</P>
<P>
   Now the question arises: how serious is his injury?
</P>
<P>
   An early examination classified it as a sprain of the medial
collateral ligament, the seriousness of which is to be determined
by the Islanders' director of medical services, Dr. Elliott
Pellman.
</P>
<P>
   The problem was, Pellman was in Denver Sunday. He also is a
medical liaison with the Jets, who played the Broncos for the
American Football Conference championship.
</P>
<P>
   So Jonsson will have to wait until Monday to learn if he will be
able to play again this season, much less next weekend in the
National Hockey League All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still planning on playing,'' he said of the All-Star Game.
``But everything will be settled by Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he felt he would be missing a chance to get more
recognition if he can't play in the All-Star Game, Jonsson said:
``I think I got the recognition already, when I was picked for the
team. I don't know if it's going to change a lot with my
recognition.''
</P>
<P>
   The twisted knee is only the latest injury to befall the
23-year-old Jonsson this season. He has missed eight games because
of two concussions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough break,'' he said. ``I mean, I was starting to
feel good after the concussions I've had.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he was trying hard to think positive. ``The good news I
guess is that I can walk on the knee,'' Jonsson said.
</P>
<P>
   It was more difficult to find any silver lining in what is
happening to the Islanders. Saturday's loss extended their streak
without a victory to 10 games (0-9-1), completed an 0-5 trip and
left them with a 13-28-3 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't really know what to do,'' Jonsson said. ``It seems
like we try and try and try, but we don't get any breaks. We just
have to keep working hard and look to ourselves, what we can do for
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   His thoughts were complicated by the throbbing in his right
knee. Sunday _ and Pellman's return from Denver _ seemed a long
time coming as he left the arena Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have other doctors,'' Jonsson said. ``But for something
like this, it's best that I wait.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he turned and hobbled alone toward the team bus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1948EST &QL; 
