</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-ANDERSEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS' ANDERSEN WINS THE BATTLE OF THE PLACE-KICKERS
</HEADLINE>
  (ms) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Gary Anderson and Morten Andersen had their fates,
the fates of the Minnesota Vikings and the Atlanta Falcons and an
invitation to the Super Bowl decided on the same piece of
artificial turf at the Metrodome Sunday. Thirty-eight yards from
the western goal post is where a field-goal kicker named Anderson
floundered and a field-goal kicker named Andersen flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Vikings' Gary Anderson gagged on a 38-yard attempt
with just over two minutes remaining in the fourth quarter _ his
first miss on a field-goal or extra-point try this season _ the
Falcons stayed within 7 points and managed to tie the score less
than a minute later. Because the Falcons' Morten Anderson made a
38-yard attempt from the same spot in overtime, Atlanta shocked
Minnesota, 30-27, in the National Football Conference championship
game.
</P>
<P>
   Two kickers with almost the same last name. Two kickers kicking
from the same spot on the field. Two thirtysomething kickers who
have each been in the league for 17 years and are among the most
precise in the National Football League. Two kickers, two very
different results and two very different directions for their
teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of destiny, I guess,'' Morten Andersen said.
``That's part of it being meant to be like that. I feel bad for
Gary, but I'm so happy for this football team. He had a great
season, so he ought to be proud. We're certainly proud of the way
we came back today and kept fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Anderson may be proud of a season in which he was 39 for 39
on field-goal tries and 64 for 64 on extra-point attempts before
Sunday's kick narrowly sailed to the left, but he was sullen after
the loss. Anderson was crammed into the corner of the muggy locker
room, and quarterback Randall Cunningham gently reached over and
moved the kicker aside to get to his locker. Then Cunningham patted
Anderson's stomach, like a father consoling a son.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no words to describe how bitterly disappointing that
is, with the season we've had,'' Anderson said. ``We had a lot of
chances out there today, and we didn't get it done. This team had
very high expectations, and that's what makes it 10 times more
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Morten Andersen said he did not even realize he had made the
field goal from the same place where Gary Anderson had botched the
chance to give the Vikings a comfortable 10-point cushion. He
shrugged, smiled and said, ``That's just destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Anderson had been so automatic that some fans were probably
using their cellular telephones to confirm reservations to Miami
for the Super Bowl as he trotted onto the field. But something went
awry in the dream season Anderson was having within Minnesota's
dream season. Somehow, the perfect kicker missed, and he could not
explain why. Anderson said the snap was perfect, the placement of
the ball was solid and he thought he had produced 3 points with his
right leg.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was hit after the attempt and tumbled to the turf, but
he did not blame the contact for the miss. Some fans cheered before
realizing Anderson's kick was no good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it goes to show you that no one is perfect,''
Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Gary Anderson, anymore. The 39-year-old native of South
Africa patiently and professionally answered waves of questions
about the missed field goal. It is a miss that might be remembered
more than anything else Anderson has done in his career, a notion
that he did not dispute.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's part of field-goal kicking,'' Anderson said. ``You have
to be a man about it. When you're a field-goal kicker, that's part
of the job. To line up and fire those field goals. Unfortunately,
that one didn't go through. Most of them have. That's what made it
so, so bitterly disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   When Morten Andersen had the chance to give the Falcons a
stunning victory in overtime, it felt like another practice to him.
Coach Dan Reeves tested the 38-year-old from Denmark throughout the
season by asking him to imagine there were five seconds left in a
game and he had to kick a 40-yard field goal for Atlanta to win. If
Andersen drilled it, his teammates did not have to run sprints. If
he missed, they did. That is pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We practice tense situations all the time,'' Reeves said.
``When you tie the conditioning to a kick, that's almost as much
pressure as in a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen, the lefty kicker who holds seven league records, said:
``I just had to stay automatic and hit the ball. It's something we
have rehearsed so many times before. Once I'm ready, we let the
skills take over. We just react.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Anderson and Andersen reacted differently after the
winning field goal. Andersen sprinted to the Falcon bench and was
buried under his teammates. Anderson watched the celebration
unfold, tried to find his counterpart to congratulate him and then
gave up because he could not see through the maze of delirious
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've still got one game to go, but I'm so elated,'' Morten
Andersen said. ``I'm the happiest guy in here right now.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hundred yards away, a kicker named Anderson was the
saddest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
