<HEADER>
A6868 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT &LR;      01-17 1116
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-RDP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS PARTIES BICKER OVER CASE, DEMOCRATS WARN ABOUT WITNESSES
</HEADLINE>
  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-OVERSEAS,
IMPEACH-UNION, IMPEACH-CASE) 
 (ko) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With the White House set to open President
Clinton's defense before the Senate on Tuesday, Republicans and
Democrats sparred Sunday over the strength of the prosecution's
case, and Democrats stepped up their warnings that calling
witnesses would lead to a prolonged impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Robert Torricelli, a New Jersey Democrat who speaks
regularly with Clinton, warned that if the Senate called witnesses
sought by House prosecutors it would also have to approve witnesses
sought by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Front and center is going to be Kenneth Starr,'' Torricelli
said on CBS's ``Face the Nation,'' ``and we will go through
prosecutorial abuse, how he came by the information, who he talked
to, and we are going to put the system of justice on trial.''
</P>
<P>
   The competing assessments of the impeachment case, after three
days of opening arguments by the House prosecutors, came on a day
when senators demonstrated precisely how they differed from a jury.
Instead of being forbidden to discuss the case, 19 lawmakers,
nearly a fifth of the Senate, blanketed the Sunday talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   In a demonstration of the uncertainties surrounding the
impeachment process, several lawmakers even raised the possibility
Sunday that the Senate had the leeway to convict Clinton on
articles of impeachment but not remove him from office, even though
the Constitution says that the president ``shall be removed from
office on impeachment for and conviction of treason, bribery or
other high crimes and misdemeanors.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the lawmakers raising that possibility, Rep. Lindsey
Graham, R-S.C., one of the House managers, said on ``Face the
Nation'' that there was ``historical precedent'' dating to before
1936 that the Senate could take separate votes on conviction and
then on removal from office. ``That's, I think, a constitutional
option,'' the South Carolina Republican said.
</P>
<P>
   Graham did not elaborate further. Sen. Mitch McConnell, R-Ky.,
called the idea ``an interesting possibility,'' and Torricelli said
the Senate could find that perjury had been commited by the
president but not remove him.
</P>
<P>
   A memorandum from the Senate Office of Legal Counsel sent to
senators in December by Trent Lott, the majority leader, and Tom
Daschle, the minority leader, says, ``Removal from office follows
automatically from conviction.''
</P>
<P>
   In a footnote, the memorandum noted that in the impeachment
cases of three judges dating from before 1936 there were two
separate votes. But legal scholars say that since the impeachment
trial of Judge Halsted Ritter in 1936, the separate vote on removal
was abandoned by the Senate in recognition that the Constitution
requires removal from office upon conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republicans said Sunday that the 13 House prosecutors in
their three days of opening arguments had made a strong case that
the President should be removed from office. They said the
president's own lawyers, who open the president's defense Tuesday,
have to rebut the evidence, not just argue that the charges do not
rise to the constitutional level for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can just sweep away the House's case,'' said
Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, on NBC's ``Meet the Press.'' ``I think a
lot of people were very impressed with the case that they made.
It's a prima facie case; in other words, it's a case that would go
to the jury. The judge could not keep it from the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the White House had a ``heavy burden'' ahead of it in
rebutting the House presentation. Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said,
``Frankly, I think if the president does not put on a defense,
House prosecutors have proved a case, both on perjury and
obstruction of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   But none of the Democrats who appeared on television showed any
sign that they were leaning toward Clinton's conviction. ``We've
sat for three days and haven't heard anything new,'' Sen. Byron
Dorgan, D-N.D., said on ``Fox News Sunday.'' ``I don't think we'll
hear anything new when the White House makes a presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the trial procedures agreed to by the two parties, the
Senate will take two votes in late January after opening arguments
on whether to dismiss the case and whether to depose witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   A few Republicans set the stage for blaming the White House if
the Senate takes a majority vote to hear from witnesses. Sen. Jon
Kyl, R-Ariz., said the question of whether to call witnesses
depends ``on the degree the White House challenges the facts.'' He
added, ``If they say you can draw a conclusion that supports the
president, I think the House managers will have a stronger argument
for the proposition they need witnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had their own mantra of the day: that opening the door
to witnesses would lead to a prolonged proceeding. Sen. Christopher
Dodd, D-Conn., said that if witnesses were called ``you're going to
have the White House demand all exculpatory evidence from the House
managers, you're going to have discovery and depositions.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the trial could go on to May or June.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said that if witnesses were allowed he
would be interested in questioning not only Starr but ``Linda
Tripp, maybe having a whole host of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans quickly pointed out that depositions would require a
majority vote in the Senate and that another majority vote would be
needed if any witness was to testify on the Senate floor. ``We are
not going to let this spin out of control,'' McConnell said. Kyl
said ``I can't imagine more than a couple or three witnesses at
most and perhaps a week in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Senators also debated whether the Senate should have a different
standard for removing a president from office than it used in
removing Federal judges. In 1989 the Senate removed Judge Walter
Nixon Jr. of Mississippi for lying before a grand jury. Judge Alcee
Hastings of Florida was also removed from office that year for
lying in a bribery trial in which he was acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who voted to convict both judges, said that the standards
were different for removing a president and judge because
presidents are elected for a four-year term and judges serve for
life on good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that the case involving Nixon concerned whether he had
tried to intervene in a drug investigation. ``Now'' he asked, ``how
can you have a judge who's lying with respect to a drug
investigation which it is the purpose of the courts to
investigate?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 1954EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6869 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MISLEADING-MORTGAGES-     01-17 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISLEADING-MORTGAGES-ART-920(3TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ABUSES FOUND IN HIGH-INTEREST LENDING TO LOW-INCOME HOMEOWNERS
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Calif., Ga., Miss.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ To all appearances, the loan agreement Gloria Knight
signed in 1995 was a classic transaction between savvy mortgage
salesmen and an unsophisticated borrower in a poor Brooklyn
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Knight, a 55-year-old retired teacher, said she was
persuaded by the salesmen who knocked on her door to put her house
up as collateral for an $88,000 loan at 13 percent interest, even
though she had no income and no way to make the $973 monthly
payments.
</P>
<P>
   But when she defaulted on her loan, leading to eviction notices
last year, it turned out that she was in the grip of something far
larger than Delta Funding, a relatively obscure Long Island
mortgage company that solicits business among low-income
homeowners. Delta's partner in trying to take Ms. Knight's home is
Bankers Trust Co., America's eighth-largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   High-interest lending in poor neighborhoods has long produced
high profits for lenders and, often, equally high burdens for
homeowners. But the entry of big banks like Bankers Trust has
changed the equation. Over the last several years, Delta has
converted hundreds of millions of dollars' worth of its mortgages
into securities much like bonds, which it sells to investors
through Bankers Trust.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Bankers Trust has provided Delta with hundreds of
millions of dollars from the investors, allowing it to make more
and more loans and become a major player in high-interest lending
in New York and in 21 other states.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a problem: a high percentage of the homeowners
cannot afford the mortgages they are getting through Delta. Many
say they were deceived into getting the loans and now risk losing
their homes, as Delta and Bankers Trust seek to reclaim the money
for their investors.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Knight, who has since been found to be delusional by a
psychiatrist for the city's Protective Services for Adults, cannot
even afford electricity. She keeps warm with a kerosene heater and
cooks over a makeshift grill in her backyard. But despite being
poor, she had something that made her attractive to lenders like
Delta: her rowhouse in East New York, which was fully paid for and
which served as security. Legal Services lawyers say she will now
almost certainly lose it.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's business has recently produced civil lawsuits in three
states and has drawn the attention of low-income housing advocates
and social-services agencies, who say the company has generated
more complaints of abusive lending than any other high-interest
lender in New York City. They contend Delta has taken advantage of
scores of homeowners and violated federal and state laws.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Chief Judge Charles P. Sifton of the Federal Court
for the Eastern District of New York stopped the foreclosure sales
of homes of three people who defaulted on Delta loans, because, he
wrote, the mortgages ``on their face'' violated federal law.
</P>
<P>
   The homeowners have sued Delta and Bankers Trust, claiming they
violated, among other laws, a federal prohibition on making loans
based solely on equity in a house and not on a homeowner's ability
to repay a loan. The suit seeks to represent tens of thousands of
other Delta borrowers whom lawyers say are caught in similar
circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Bankers Trust, which is being acquired by the
German banking giant Deutsche Bank, declined repeated requests for
interviews. On Friday, William McBride, a bank spokesman, said:
``Bankers Trust's sole responsibility in these situations is to
safegaurd the interests of investors. We have no other connection
to these actions.''
</P>
<P>
   Marc E. Miller, Delta's general counsel and a son of its
founder, vigorously denied that the company engages in deceptive
lending, saying it made no sense financially for the company to
make loans it knew would fail. ``There is sometimes this myth
that's spread around that lenders do make money'' from foreclosed
properties, Miller said. ``And it is a myth.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to comment on cases that are in litigation, he
added that ``if a loan simply doesn't make sense for a borrower, we
won't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But city real estate records show high foreclosure rates on
Delta mortgages in some neighborhoods. In Brooklyn, where the
company is most active in the city, a search of records found that
48 of 363 loans made by Delta in 1995 _ or about 13 percent _ have
ended up in default, and Delta has begun foreclosure actions. For
1996 loans, the records show, the figure is 99 of 923 _ or about 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   In its annual report to the Securities and Exchange Commission
last year, Delta reported that 4.65 percent of all its loans were
in foreclosure, calculated by the dollar amount of the loans.
</P>
<P>
   According to Inside B&AMP;C Lending, an industry newsletter that
reports statistics from several large lenders, about 2.65 percent
of the amount of high-risk loans nationwide were in foreclosure as
of September 1998, the most recent date for which information was
available. An additional 1.9 percent were 90 days delinquent and in
danger of foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's critics contend that the company has devastated the
lives of many working-class homeowners, most of them elderly.
``These folks not only lose their homes, but lose every dime of
equity they have built up over the years, and in most cases this is
all they have to show for years of hard work,'' said Josh Zinner, a
lawyer with the Foreclosure Prevention Project for Seniors, a
branch of South Brooklyn Legal Services set up last year to pursue
claims of abusive lending.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Anna Dawson, a 67-year-old Brooklyn widow who is fighting Delta
and Bankers Trust in state court for her home, may get help from
prosecutors. The Brooklyn district attorney's office is
investigating an independent broker who, she contends, falsified
her mortgage application without her knowledge to make it appear
she could afford a $99,000 mortgage with monthly payments of $1,017
</P>
<P>
   In reality, her only income was roughly $700 a month in
survivor's benefits from her late husband. But her application
included a letter saying she was an office manager at United
Equities in Brooklyn and a lease that made it appear she rented out
a floor of her home. The company does not exist at the address on
the letter, and Ms. Dawson said she has not worked in more than two
decades. She has no renter. In addition, the signature on the lease
does not appear to be hers.
</P>
<P>
   Her loan became part of $340 million worth of 1997 Delta
mortgages put into a trust managed by Bankers Trust and sold to
investors.
</P>
<P>
   In a lawsuit filed in State Supreme Court in Brooklyn, her
lawyers contend that the mortgage broker and a home-improvement
contractor came to her house uninvited several times, persistently
pushing her to get a loan for repairs to her house.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, she was unable to make her payments, and Delta and
Bankers Trust have begun to foreclose against her. Meanwhile, like
many other Delta borrowers who claim to have been deceived, she
said she was left with almost no proceeds of her loan _ after
paying Delta's fees, settling a previous low-interest loan and
paying the same home-improvement contractor, who she said did
little work.
</P>
<P>
   High-interest lending became a big business in low-income
neighborhoods nationwide after 1986, when a change in the federal
tax code gave a tax break to homeowners who took out second
mortgages.
</P>
<P>
   But complaints about abuses began almost immediately.
Unscrupulous finance companies often singled out homeowners, many
of them elderly, who had substantial equity in their homes; in case
of default, lenders could recoup the loan by taking possession of
the home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, New York City's Department of Consumer Affairs reported
that finance companies, usually working with crooked home
improvement contractors, had ``fleeced thousands of lower-income
and minority New York City homeowners'' out of equity in their
homes by tricking them into loans for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Many finance companies resold their mortgages to big banks. But
Delta _ founded in 1982 in by Sidney A. Miller, a former planner
for insurance companies _ was one of the first to see a vast
untapped resource beyond the banks: the investment market. By
converting loans into securities and selling them to investors,
finance companies could generate a faster profit and have access to
much more capital, and make many more loans.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last decade, the market in asset-backed securities like
those issued by Delta has grown from $9 billion to more than $140
billion, as investors pursued the rapidly expanding trade in
high-risk auto loans, credit cards and home-equity loans.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the high-risk home-loan industry alone reached more
than $120 billion in loans issued nationwide in 1997, according to
industry estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Delta began selling its loans as securities in 1991, giving
investors the right to share in mortgage interest payments, and
Bankers Trust's California branch soon began to manage the trusts
that held these securities. Delta's business zoomed. In 1994, it
made about $100 million in loans. By last year, according to its
federal securities filings, its loans increased to more than $1
billion. It grew from about 150 employees to more than 1,000. In
1996, the company went public, on the New York Stock Exchange, and
in 1997 it reported profits of more than $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   William J. Brennan, a lawyer for the Atlanta Legal Aid Society
who specializes in lending abuse cases and is familiar with
lawsuits against Delta, criticizes Bankers Trust as Delta's
``enablers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bankers Trust would never make these kinds of loans
themselves,'' he said, ``but they put themselves in the position of
enhancing the power of Delta Funding to engage in abusive lending.
And they do it because there's lots of money to be made.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the view of Marc Miller, whose family runs Delta, based
in Woodbury, N.Y., ``there are many people who want and need a loan
and can't get one. From that standpoint we fill a very legitimate
niche in the consumer finance field.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Menzel, an elderly Queens woman who had lived in her
two-story rowhouse in Ridgewood since she was a teen-ager, took out
an $81,000 Delta mortgage in the summer of 1994, when she was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, Bankers Trust and Delta say Ms. Menzel owes
more than $123,000 in principal and interest, and they are trying
to take her house.
</P>
<P>
   There is no dispute that Ms. Menzel signed the loan papers. But
little else is clear, including her motivation, since her first
mortgage was paid off and she appeared to have no debts. Her lawyer
said that she was talked into the loan by an acquaintance who had
previously taken financial advantage of her and ended up taking the
proceeds of her loan for himself.
</P>
<P>
   But questions remain about whether she was competent when she
closed the mortgage in Delta's offices. Workers at a Queens center
for the elderly, who saw her almost daily, said they noticed memory
lapses and confused behavior well before the summer of 1994.
</P>
<P>
   By Thanksgiving, six months after she got the mortgage, she
``was wearing house slippers out into the cold and was not taking
care of herself,'' said Thomas Crossman, who ran the Ridgewood
Older Adult Center at the time.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, according to court papers, two psychiatrists hired by
the center found symptoms of dementia and memory loss, indicating
Alzheimer's disease. One reported that she ``does not have any
knowledge of her assets or income.''
</P>
<P>
   By May 1995, Ms. Menzel was ruled legally incompetent in State
Supreme Court, and she later defaulted on the mortgage.
</P>
<P>
   But Bankers Trust argued in court papers that her mortgage was
valid because Ms. Menzel had not been ruled incompetent before the
closing. Partly for that reason, a State Supreme Court judge, Edwin
Kassoff, declined to let Ms. Menzel out of the mortgage. Bankers
Trust and Delta continue to fight her in court.
</P>
<P>
   Delta's critics say that the company commonly works with a
network of aggressive, often unscrupulous mortgage brokers and
home-improvement contractors who canvass poor neighborhoods,
looking for elderly homeowners willing to put up their homes as
collateral for loans to help with bills or home repairs.
</P>
<P>
   A search of court records and Delta loan documents found that at
least two people who have referred loans to Delta _ John Gizze, the
owner of a mortgage consulting firm in Hempstead, N.Y., and Gary
Feldman, a Queens home improvement contractor _ have pleaded guilty
to conspiracy to commit bank fraud in Federal court in cases
unrelated to Delta.
</P>
<P>
   Both men admitted in court that they had falsified papers to
exaggerate the income of borrowers.
</P>
<P>
   Gizze's lawyer, Allen Drezin, said Gizze has subsequently had
``some dealings with Delta Funding,'' but they ``have been up to
the standards of the industry.'' Feldman is now a defendant in a
federal civil suit filed by Mary Lewis, a Queens woman who claims
he and Delta deceived her when she took out a home equity mortgage
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview, Feldman said he has closed few loans
with Delta, and denied engaging in any deceptive lending practices.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials said they were unaware of the criminal pasts of
either man, but they added that they do not routinely perform
criminal background checks on brokers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with thousands of different brokers,'' said Marc
Miller, the general counsel, ``it would, frankly, be impossible for
us to stay on top of every broker at every instant.''
</P>
<P>
   The company is now the target of at least four Federal civil
suits, three of which seek to represent classes of thousands of
homeowners whom lawyers allege were deceived or mistreated by
Delta.
</P>
<P>
   The suit filed late last year in federal District Court in
Brooklyn accuses Delta of consistently lending to people based on
the equity of their homes and not on their ability to pay, a
practice the plaintiffs' lawyers say has led to scores of
foreclosures.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also accuses Delta of breaking federal law by charging
exorbitant extra interest once a loan goes into default. (A review
of Delta loan papers for several borrowers found that the interest
commonly jumps to 24 percent after default. In New York, interest
rates over 25 percent are prohibited by criminal usury laws.)
</P>
<P>
   Delta and Bankers Trust, represented by a single law firm in the
case, have not yet responded to the allegations in court.
</P>
<P>
   In Mississippi and Georgia, two federal civil suits allege that
Delta is one of many high-interest mortgage lenders paying fees to
mortgage brokers. The suits allege that these fees are, in reality,
a kickback to brokers for steering borrowers to the lenders, even
though it may not be in the borrowers' best interest.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials deny the accusations. But in a similar federal
class-action case in New York, Delta recently settled with the
plaintiffs in a confidential agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, the company's general counsel, said in a written
statement that all such suits contain ``accusations, rather than
fact'' and have been filed ``solely for the purpose of delaying or
preventing Delta Financial from protecting its rights.'' But Delta
has not always been successful in challenging borrowers' claims of
abuse. In October 1991, Theresa Leonardi's husband of more than 50
years had just died. In November she went into the hospital with
thyroid and heart problems.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after she was released from the hospital, she was
taken to Delta's offices, then in Great Neck, N.Y., by a
stockbroker who later pleaded guilty to mail fraud against her in
connection with the loan and served time in federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Leonardi took out a $95,000 mortgage on her home in
Sheepshead Bay, Brooklyn, but she said later in a lawsuit against
Delta that she had no idea what kind of papers she was signing.
</P>
<P>
   The papers described her as a 68-year-old self-employed investor
making $7,000 a month. In fact, she was almost 73 and was living
mostly on Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   In giving the loan to Mrs. Leonardi, according to court
documents, Delta waived its written policy stating that income tax
returns should be used to verify the income of loan applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, her lawyers say, all her mortgage proceeds went
directly to the stockbroker, and Mrs. Leonardi never made a single
loan payment. By December 1992, the bank began a foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Felsenfeld, a former Citicorp vice president who was an
expert witness for Mrs. Leonardi, said in a deposition that the
case showed ``clear and convincing evidence of Delta's
participation in the fraud perpetrated on Mrs. Leonardi.''
</P>
<P>
   Delta denied the accusations and pointed out that Mrs. Leonardi
had chosen the unscrupulous stockbroker herself. ``It is a sad
commentary on our society,'' a Delta vice president, Marie Klasa,
wrote in a letter in February 1995, ``that people must seek to
blame others for their own errors in judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   But as the trial approached last summer, Delta agreed to pay
Mrs. Leonardi $200,000 _ more than twice the amount of her mortgage
_ in a confidential settlement in which Delta admitted no
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said the company settled because it believed it would be
less costly than pursuing an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The actual facts,'' he said, ``are that Delta made a loan that
made sense at the time to a woman who knew what she was doing at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Leonardi remembered it differently. ``At no time did any of
these people explain to me that I was signing papers for a mortgage
on my home,'' she stated in court documents. ``They merely pointed
to the lines, and I signed or initialed as directed. At the time I
was so weak that I couldn't walk without assistance and could not
read any of the papers that I was asked to sign.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
