<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6880 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-CASE-1020(2TA     01-17 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-CASE-1020(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFENDERS TO INVOKE LAW, FACTS, CONSTITUTION AND HISTORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.D., Wis., Fla., Ohio, Utah, Ill., S.C., Ark.)   (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-LEGAL, IMPEACH-OVERSEAS,
IMPEACH-UNION) 
(jw) 
 By JILL ABRAMSON and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton's lawyers are preparing a defense
to the Senate on Tuesday that broadly attacks the prosecution case
presented by the House managers on the facts, on the law, on the
Constitution and even on history.
</P>
<P>
   According to several White House advisers, the heart of the
president's defense will remain that the charges against him fall
far short of the high constitutional standard for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This impeachment is a direct affront to that constitutional
standard,'' George Mitchell, the former Senate majority leader,
said Sunday on NBC's ``Meet the Press.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the president are likely to use aspects of the House
prosecution case to defend him and to show that his accusers have
misread both the facts and the law. ``We will point out the
significant holes in the presentation of the House managers,'' said
Jim Kennedy, a White House spokesman, ``as well as their misleading
and overreaching characterizations of the evidence and testimony in
the record.''
</P>
<P>
   In presenting their case, the House managers also employed this
tactic, by anticipating, incorporating and debunking Clinton's
defense before it had been heard by the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The evidentiary case presented by the House managers outlined an
unlawful scheme orchestrated by the president to get Monica
Lewinsky to file a false affidavit in the sexual misconduct lawsuit
brought by Paula Jones, and to conceal their relationship from the
Jones lawyers by hiding gifts the president had given to Ms.
Lewinsky. The House prosecutors claimed that Clinton helped find a
job for Ms. Lewinsky in order to silence her, and tried to
influence the testimony of other witnesses. Then, they charged, the
president went before a federal grand jury and lied about these
activities, including the nature and details of his relationship
with Ms. Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's legal team is well aware that it faces new and
significant hurdles as the impeachment trial turns to the defense.
Senators have already sat through three days of uninterrupted
evidence and argument imploring them to go the ultimate step in the
impeachment process and remove the president from office. And even
some Democratic senators conceded that the House managers had
presented their case clearly and effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any fair-minded person would have to say they made a powerful
presentation,'' Sen. Kent Conrad, D-N.D., said Saturday after the
House's final arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Senior Democrats in Congress and White House advisers remain
confident that the House managers still face extremely stiff odds
in persuading the required two-thirds of the Senate to convict the
president. But the prosecution's coherent presentation of the
evidence and law on perjury and obstruction of justice, the central
charges contained in the two articles of impeachment passed by the
House, made it far more likely that a simple majority of senators
would favor hearing from witnesses, an issue to be decided after
the White House makes its case.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, senators will hear more about events with which they
have become all too familiar: the president's deposition in the
Jones trial, his testimony before the grand jury and his
interaction with White House aides and friends, including his
secretary, Betty Currie, and Washington lawyer Vernon Jordan Jr.
This time, however, they will hear about these subjects from a
different vantage point.
</P>
<P>
   Where the House managers placed the president at the heart of a
conspiracy to lie and obstruct justice, his lawyers will, if their
trial brief is an accurate road map, show him in a very different
light. After trying to conceal an embarrassing and illicit affair,
they will say, the president admitted to the grand jury that he had
had an ``inappropriate, intimate'' relationship with Ms. Lewinsky
and did nothing unlawful in his earlier efforts to hide their
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   The White House legal team, relying heavily on the president's
grand jury testimony as well as the testimony of Ms. Lewinsky and
Ms. Currie, will most likely challenge every assumption and many of
the facts on which the House case was premised. In several
instances, the lawyers will argue that the House's recitation of
evidence was purposely misleading.
</P>
<P>
   For example, instead of encouraging Ms. Lewinsky to lie in the
Jones case, the president said in his grand jury testimony that he
believed Ms. Lewinsky could execute a truthful affidavit, since
they had never had sexual intercourse. Ms. Currie testified that it
was Ms. Lewinsky who initiated the retrieval of gifts, while the
House managers claimed that Clinton had instructed Ms. Currie to
get the gifts back from Ms. Lewinsky. Finally, the president's
lawyers will stress that he helped Ms. Lewinsky in her job search
before she became embroiled in the Jones case, undercutting the
House managers' allegations that the job help was a quid pro quo
for her silence in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders were particularly rankled by the
presentation of two Republican managers, Rep. James Sensenbrenner
Jr. of Wisconsin and Rep. Bill McCollum of Florida. Sensenbrenner
mischaracterized earlier testimony from the White House counsel,
Charles Ruff, and misstated facts from the Jones case, claiming
that Ms. Jones was denied merit pay raises.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum focused heavily on the president's statements in the
Jones case, even though the House rejected an impeachment article
charging him with perjury in the civil case. McCollum also insisted
that the president committed perjury before the grand jury by
saying he did not lie in the Jones case. The president's lawyers
have repeatedly stressed that he was not asked to reaffirm all of
his testimony in the Jones case when he went before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Broadly, the president's case is likely to follow the same
outline as the House case. It is expected to deal separately with
the evidence and law on perjury and obstruction of justice but move
more quickly to a core argument that the allegations against the
president, even if they are proven, do not rise to the
constitutional standard of impeachment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The House managers outlined four separate areas of perjury,
which they illustrated with video clips from the president's
deposition in the Jones case and his testimony before the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   In presenting the perjury case to the Senate, Rep. Steve Chabot,
R-Ohio, said it was ``undeniably clear'' that the president had
fulfilled a crucial element of perjury, the intent to testify
falsely. He cited as evidence Clinton's statements and those of
Ruff, that the deposition testimony was designed to mislead Ms.
Jones' lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he cited Clinton's conversations after the
deposition with Ms. Currie, a kind of question-and-answer session
in which the president suggested to her a version of his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. ``This is not the conduct of
someone who believed he had testified truthfully,'' Chabot said.
</P>
<P>
   The president's statements to the grand jury were material,
another important legal measure of perjury, Chabot said, ``because
the grand jury was investigating whether the president had
obstructed justice and committed perjury in the civil deposition,''
in the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   The White House will argue that the president's testimony before
the grand jury was truthful and differed only in trivial ways from
Ms. Lewinsky's account.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Christopher Cannon, R-Utah, outlined for the Senate seven
instances in which he said Clinton obstructed justice. With
easy-to-follow charts, Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., showed a
suggestive sequence of events that he used to support the managers'
case that the president was at the center of a scheme to hide his
affair with Ms. Lewinsky from the Jones lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   Central to the obstruction case presented by the House managers
were gifts the president gave to Ms. Lewinsky. They cited Ms.
Lewinsky's testimony that Ms. Currie called her and then came to
her apartment to retrieve them. They also insisted that Ms. Currie
would have done so only at the president's suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   The president's lawyers will emphasize that the testimony of Ms.
Lewinsky and Ms. Currie is at odds with the House case and that he
gave Ms. Lewinsky additional gifts on Dec. 28, the day the House
managers assert he plotted with her to conceal the first batch of
gifts. That means, the president's lawyers argued in their brief,
that ``on the very day the president and Ms. Lewinsky were
conspiring to hide the gifts he had already given her, the
president added to the pile. No stretch of logic will support such
an outlandish theory.''
</P>
<P>
   The managers argued that the president's job search for Ms.
Lewinsky was moribund until the president and Jordan learned she
had been subpoenaed in the Jones case. The president's lawyers,
Jordan and Ms. Lewinsky have all said there was no job quid pro
quo.
</P>
<P>
   Another pillar of the House obstruction case was the allegation
that the president engaged in witness-tampering when he asked Ms.
Currie to come to the White House the day after the Jones
deposition and he asked her a series of questions about his
relationship with Ms. Lewinsky. The managers have essentially
accused Clinton of coaching Ms. Currie, feeding her answers that
were helpful to him and ``corruptly influencing'' her future
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers ridiculed Clinton's testimony that he was
merely trying to refresh his memory with the colloquy, but the
White House will continue to emphasize that Ms. Currie testified
she did not feel influenced in any way. At the time, she was not a
witness in any legal proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Where the two cases diverge most is on whether any of these
charges are impeachable. This is the least legal and most political
of the issues and is being argued against a backdrop in which most
people believe Clinton may have lied but do not believe his actions
warrant removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   The House managers, led by the Judiciary Committee chairman,
Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., wrapped up their opening with arguments
that the president's actions amounted to the high crimes and
misdemeanors outlined in the Constitution and required his removal
from office.
</P>
<P>
   Given the murky area of what precisely qualifies as a high
crime, the managers have invoked recent and ancient history and
analogies that are homespun and academic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a high crime?'' Lindsey Graham, R-S.C., asked before
the Senate on Saturday. ``How about if an important person hurts
somebody of low means? It's not very scholarly, but I think it's
the truth. I think that's what they meant by high crimes. Doesn't
even have to be a crime. It's just when you start using your office
and you're acting in a way that hurts people, you've committed a
high crime.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the White House case will be that none of the
actions alleged by the House are serious enough to warrant removal
of an elected president from office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will make the case that the allegations are not supported
by the facts or by the law and that they do not warrant nullifying
the results of a national election and removing the president from
office,'' said Kennedy, the White House spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   White House lawyers have asserted in their brief that ``our
system of government does not permit Congress to unseat the
president merely because it disagrees with his behavior or his
policies.''
</P>
<P>
   That is why, they argued, the framers of the Constitution listed
the specific crimes of treason, bribery and other high crimes and
misdemeanors that would allow or require removal from office. House
managers, meanwhile, cited the same history, emphasizing that
perjury was deemed on the same level of seriousness as bribery.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has said that the only acts that would warrant
removal are those that ``are profoundly serious and malevolent'' to
the Constitution. Only offenses against the system of government
qualify, they assert, and the president's offenses, even if proven,
do not rise to that level.
</P>
<P>
   The White House lawyers have argued that the failure of the
House Judiciary Committee in 1974 to include an article on tax
fraud against President Richard Nixon demonstrated that impeachment
should be reserved for official and not personal actions that cause
harm to the country. The House managers have responded that the tax
fraud count was not included only because it was not sufficiently
proven.
</P>
<P>
   The managers asserted that the president's conduct was not
private or personal but affected the workings of the judicial
system. They repeatedly cited the impeachment and removal from
office of Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr. in 1989 for having tried to fix
a case in state court involving the son of a business partner.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's lawyers have argued in their filings that the standard
for impeaching a president should be higher than that for a judge
because the president uniquely embodies the head of the executive
branch and can be voted out of office, while an individual judge
has lifetime tenure and does not hold the equivalent role.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
