<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6882 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLICY-KOSOVO-ART-590     01-17 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLICY-KOSOVO-ART-590(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO AMBASSADORS CONDEMN MASSACRE IN KOSOVO
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(ms) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Confronted with escalating violence in Kosovo and
an increasing sense that it is almost impossible to halt the
bloodshed, divided NATO ambassadors meeting in Brussels Sunday
night called on Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic to respect a
ceasefire, but backed off reviving NATO plans from last fall to
bomb Serbian targets in Kosovo and Serbia itself.
</P>
<P>
   The massacre of 45 ethnic Albanian civilians by Serb forces
under the control of Milosevic on Friday refocused Western
attention on Kosovo, but also served to underline the lack of
appetite for the measures needed to halt all-out conflict, Western
diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before NATO ambassadors convened their unusual Sunday
night meeting, fighting broke out in the very village where the
massacre occurred on Friday, forcing Western monitors and mourners
to flee before they could even bury the slain.
</P>
<P>
   NATO condemned the massacre and described it as a ``flagrant
violation of international humanitarian law.'' An alliance
statement stressed that Milosevic must allow investigators from the
International Criminal Tribunal for the former Yugoslavia to visit
the site, a move that the Yugoslav leader has consistently refused,
and called him ``personally responsible for the behavior of his
security forces.''
</P>
<P>
   A Clinton administration official said the presence of NATO
troops in Kosovo was probably the only way to keep the Serbian
security forces and ethnic Albanian rebels apart, but that this was
an unlikely prospect. There was little interest within the
administration to insist on a NATO presence in Kosovo, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some European NATO allies have also made resolve on Kosovo more
difficult because of growing opinion before the massacre,
particularly in France, that the ethnic Albanian guerrillas were
more to blame for recent outbreaks of violence than the Serbian
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian police and the guerrillas fought in the village of Racak
Sunday where dozens of mutilated bodies, some with gouged eyes and
one decapitated, were found by Western diplomats Saturday morning.
Mortar and machine gun fire erupted from police positions on a hill
above the village and a dozen Serbian armored vehicles were seen by
Western monitors entering the village.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest fear following the massacre is the likelihood of the
Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for the independence of
the Serbian province, seeking retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   This in turn could provoke Milosevic to order a crackdown of
much larger proportions than seen so far, a NATO diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic has seen he can push it very, very far,'' the
diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
   The options facing NATO Sunday ranged from the most rigorous _
the reactivation of an order authorizing the use of force _ to
issuing a stern statement of the kind that resulted.
</P>
<P>
   James Steinberg, deputy director of the National Security
Council, said that the administration was satisfied with the NATO
statement and the dispatch of the two top NATO military officials
to see Milosevic in Belgrade. ``We got everything we wanted,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement reiterated that the order authorizing the use of
force by NATO's supreme allied commander, Gen. Wesley K. Clark,
still stands from last fall when NATO announced it would strike
Serb targets but then pulled back. Javier Solana, NATO's
secretary-general, has, in fact, been repeating this for the last
several weeks as the Kosovo violence has increased.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carrying out the order either now or in the near future would
require another vote of the 16 NATO ambassadors, diplomatssaid.
</P>
<P>
   Given the different opinions within NATO as to who is most to
blame for the growing violence of the past three weeks, any
consideration of air strikes was unlikely Sunday, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said Washington remained firm in the
view that Milosevic's forces were mostly responsible for the
conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   There was ``unhappiness'' at the provocative acts taken in the
past few weeks by ``extremists'' in the Kosovo Liberation Army,
including the hostage-taking of Yugsolav Army soldiers as hostages
and the shooting of Serbian policemen, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have not lost perspective of who is at the root cause
of this,'' the official said, referring to Milosevic and his
slash-and-burn offensive last summer and fall that created 250,000
Albanian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   The administration, which has traditionally dispatched its
special envoy, Richard C. Holbrooke, to meet with Milosevic in
times of real tensionin the Balkans, publicly slammed Milosevic for
the first time last month as a man who was part of the ``problem''
and not part of the ``solution'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   NATO decided Sunday night to send Clark and German Gen. Klaus
Naumann, head of the alliance's military committee, to see
Milosevic in Belgrade, probably on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's harsh critique of Milosevic would not deter
Washington from dealing with him, the administration official said.
``Milosevic is the president of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia
and the security services follow his directions. If you want to get
things done you have to interact with him. There is not much
choice,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic, meanwhile, unleashed a propaganda campaign on Serbian
television, breaking into programs every hour with messages
deriding the West.
</P>
<P>
   A statement by the Serbian president, Milan Milutinovic, a close
ally of Milosevic, was read, accusing the chief Western diplomat in
Kosovo, William Walker, of being ``a liar'' and a ``protector of
terrorists,'' the Serbian way of referring to the ethnic Albanian
rebels. Serbian television also played up support for the Serb
cause from Russia.
</P>
<P>
   A shaken Walker, who served as U.S. ambassador in El Salvador in
the 1980s, said after seeing the Albanian bodies on Saturday that
he had never seen such deliberate carnage and called it a ``crime
very much against humanity.'' He unequivocally blamed the Serb
forces.
</P>
<P>
   The high-decibel denials by the Milosevic regime that its forces
had done anything wrong was particularly disturbing, a U.S.
official said, because it was among several signals that Milosevic
intended to forge ahead with squashing the guerilla insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Milosevic believes they're going to do what they want no
matter what anyone says,'' the official said. ``They say that
Kosovo is part of Serbia and they're going to vanquish the Albanian
terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief prosecutor of the international war crimes tribunal in
the Hague, Louise Arbour, reiterated Sunday her intention of going
to Kosovo to investigate the massacre. In the past, she has been
denied all requests for a visa to Kosovo, and Milosevic does not
recognize the authority of the tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said they understood Ms. Arbour planned to fly to
Skopje, the capital of Macedonia, on Monday, without a visa and
then drive the short distance to the Kosovo border. There, armed
with NATO's paper demands that she be allowed to investigate the
massacre and be given the names of those who participated in the
killing, she would face Serbian immigration officials who would
have to decide whether to let her in or not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
