<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCHOOP-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA-STANFORD WAS LESSON IN BASKETBRAWL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It began as an important Pac-10 clash between
Stanford and UCLA. But early in the evening, a Big East game broke
out.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford beat UCLA 72-59 Saturday in a game that featured all
the notorious ingredients of Big East brawlball. There was enough
clawing, grabbing and holding to last a Pac-10 season. The Bruins
committed 35 fouls, lost five players to disqualifications, and
Stanford shot 49 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably the roughest game I've ever played in my
life,'' Cardinal guard David Moseley said. ``That includes
streetball, where you call your own fouls.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA guard Baron Davis, who played Pop Warner football, was
assessed one technical foul and had two verbal exchanges _ one with
the Stanford coaching staff, another with Cardinal guard Art Lee
after what Davis called a ``frustration foul'' in the final
seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Why the rough stuff? Coach Steve Lavin's limitless energy and
Davis' natural aggressiveness has dramatically altered UCLA's
psychology this season. The Bruins play harder and tougher than
they have in recent years, and they have the size and depth to
execute the approach. It's working: Opponents are shooting 40
percent from the field, and Stanford committed a season-high 25
turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you put that energy with that athletic ability, watch
out,'' Cardinal coach Mike Montgomery said.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bruins must learn to play tough defense without fouling.
Instead of grabbing and holding, they must use their feet and their
heads and sound fundamentals. They have solid depth, with a 10-man
rotation, but no team can survive five disqualifications against
elite competition _ especially on the road. If UCLA plays like that
in Maples Pavilion next month, Stanford might shoot 70 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was brutal,'' Montgomery said. ``I've never seen anything
like it. You couldn't dribble.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as in the Big East.
</P>
<P>
   __ Fronting up front: One noticeable difference in UCLA's
defense in recent weeks is the manner it defends opposing big men.
Like Duke, Kansas and other teams that specialize in pressure
defense, the Bruins are using a strategy called fronting the post.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how it works: Instead of playing on the opponent's
backside and allowing uncontested entry passes into the low post,
UCLA's big men are playing in front of their opponents (ie: on the
ball side).
</P>
<P>
   The technique cuts off entry passes and leaves offenses with one
option: to make a difficult lob pass over the defense and into open
space under the basket. If the defense rotates properly, someone is
waiting for the offensive player when he catches the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Lavin has employed the fronting strategy because freshmen Jerome
Moiso and Dan Gadzuric are steadily improving their footwork.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's supposed to cut down (the opponent's) comfort zone,''
Lavin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins do not execute with Duke's precision, obviously, but
the change has disrupted opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to apply as much pressure as possible and make teams
play one-on-one,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Swoosh or stripes: Yes, UCLA is a Reebok school. But several
Bruins have Nikes on their feet. Davis and Earl Watson are wearing
Nikes because, they say, the Reebok models hurt their feet.
</P>
<P>
   According to the players, Reebok has been slow to respond to
their requests because the school's contract expires June 30. At
that point, UCLA becomes an Adidas client _ a $19 million client.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough ticket: Stanford alumnus and Orange County native Tiger
Woods attended the game, but finding tickets was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Woods called Fox, but the network couldn't help.
</P>
<P>
   He called Stanford, but the alma mater claimed to have no
tickets available. (So much for that $10 million endowment.)
</P>
<P>
   He tried UCLA several times. Sorry.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, Woods' management team secured two tickets from an
unknown source, according to a UCLA official, and he sat behind the
Cardinal bench.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
