<HEADER>
A6886 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-2TAKES-     01-17 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-LEGAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPERTS GIVE GOOD GRADES TO HOUSE MANAGERS' PRESENTATIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn., Fla., N.Y.)  (See also IMPEACH-RDP, IMPEACH-OVERSEAS, IMPEACH-UNION,
IMPEACH-CASE) 
(mk) 
 By WILLIAM GLABERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After three days of impeachment arguments from the House
managers, constitutional and impeachment experts said the
presentations last week gave the strongest legal arguments yet
against President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews over the weekend, the experts _ professors at
law schools around the country _ generally agreed that if the
Republican managers had made legal headway in their case against
the president, it was in subtly shifting the emphasis.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the Republicans want the question to be is: Did the
president do what is alleged in the articles of impeachment?'' said
Cass Sunstein, a professor of constitutional law at the University
of Chicago Law School. ``If that is the question, they're in better
shape than if the question is: Should the president be removed from
office? I think in the last few days the ball was moved a little
bit in the direction of what the Republicans want the question to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   The legal specialists also said the managers' arguments could be
neutralized when Clinton's lawyers made their case, and noted that
the Senate's decision is likely to be as much political as legal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, nothing was new here, but it was packaged
better,'' said Susan Low Bloch, a professor of constitutional law
at Georgetown University Law Center in Washington. She added, ``It
was rhetorically polished. But I suppose after the president has
had his three days, we'll be back to where we were before.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the experts generally agreed that the managers'
statements were more effective than previous arguments in favor of
impeachment, several said the presentations were far from the
dramatic break the Republicans might need to change the momentum in
the impeachment battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good opening statement in a trial is when you say, `My God!
These people deserve to win,''' said Eric Freedman, a law professor
and expert on impeachment at Hofstra University School of Law.
``That certainly didn't happen here.''
</P>
<P>
   The law professors said the legal quality of the managers'
statements varied widely. But several of them said some of the
managers' statements grappled more seriously with the fundamental
constitutional questions in the case than any prior presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Akhil Reed Amar, a professor of constitutional law at Yale Law
School, said that in arguing that Paula Jones' civil rights might
have been violated by the president, the House managers made the
case that Clinton's acts were ``an assault on the idea of
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a much better job this time of saying it's an assault
on the idea of justice,'' Amar said.
</P>
<P>
   Sunstein said the managers also demonstrated that perjury was an
offense taken very seriously by the nation's courts. Throughout the
debate over Clinton's actions, Sunstein said, some of the
president's supporters have made it appear that, even if Clinton
had committed perjury, that was a mere technical offense.
</P>
<P>
   Sunstein said it has not been established that Clinton did
commit perjury. But he said the managers demonstrated that the
question of whether Clinton lied under oath was an important one,
not just for the impeachment debate but for the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they showed,'' he said, ``is that perjury is an extremely
serious offense and if the president perjured himself _ and if
people think that's OK _ then there's a real problem for the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ackerman, a Yale authority on impeachment law who
presented testimony before the House Judiciary Committee against
impeaching Clinton, also praised some of the House presentations.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said the presentations had not changed his view of the
case against Clinton. But he singled out the statement of Rep.
Charles Canady, R-Fla., as one of the first that, as he put it,
``raised the level of constitutional argument.''
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman and other legal scholars have argued that
constitutional law and history make it clear that a president
should be removed from office only for misdeeds concerning the
functioning of government. The Constitution's declaration that a
president can be impeached for ``high crimes and misdemeanors,''
they have said, refers to such presidential actions as abuse of
official power, not lies to cover-up a sexual relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Ackerman said Sunday that Canady presented an argument to depart
from that legal tradition. In his statement, Canady argued that the
Senate's power to remove a president should not be narrowly
defined. Instead, Canady said, the removal power ``should be
understood as a positive grant of authority to the Senate to
preserve, protect and strengthen our constitutional system against
the misconduct of federal officials when the misconduct would
subvert, undermine or weaken the institutions of our government.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   If the Senate adopted that position in Clinton's case, Ackerman
said, that would represent an important change in the understanding
of the law of impeachment. He said he strongly disagreed with
Canady's argument, but added, ``After many, many hours of
repetitive rehearsal of the arguments, we had a guy standing up
there trying to speak to a fundamental issue. I say: Good job,
Charles Canady.''
</P>
<P>
   Several experts said the most important presentation by the
House managers was their analysis of impeachment cases involving
federal judges. Because there has been only one prior Senate trial
of a president _ Andrew Johnson _ the cases involving judges are
being carefully parsed by both sides. One case involved Walter
Nixon Jr., a federal judge who was impeached for lying about
whether he had used his influence to have a prosecutor dismiss drug
charges that had been filed against the son of a friend of the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the experts said the Constitution suggests that
judges and presidents are not subject to the same rules in
impeachment proceedings, but, even if they were, Bloch of
Georgetown said, the cases of Nixon and other impeached judges
would not necessarily dictate a conclusion that Clinton should be
removed from office.
</P>
<P>
   In several of the cases mentioned by the House managers, some of
the experts noted, the judges had already been convicted of federal
felonies but were still on the government payroll when their
impeachment cases came to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   That, Bloch and other experts said, was a distinction from the
case of Clinton. There is still debate about whether Clinton would,
if charged, be convicted of perjury or obstruction of justice under
the technical requirements of the law.
</P>
<P>
   Bloch, who said she did not favor removing Clinton, acknowledged
that the judicial cases raised a legal issue the president's
lawyers will have to counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been judges impeached and convicted for things that
looked sort of personal,'' Bloch said. ``That has a ring to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts went even further, describing the judicial cases as
among the most persuasive legal arguments yet in the impeachment
battle.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are precedents,'' said Roger Cramton, a professor at
Cornell University Law School who is an expert on impeachment law.
``Clearly, Congress has, and could, consider perjury _ for any
reason _ as an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Cramton, who was a member of a federal commission studying
judicial impeachment law, said he thought the case for removing
Clinton was strong.
</P>
<P>
   But whether the House managers changed minds or not, some of the
professors said, several of the managers presented provocative
arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They tried to connect the dots and offer a coherent
narrative,'' said Amar of Yale, ``and frankly, I thought they did a
much better job than we had seen before.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
