<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-NYT &LR;      01-17 1250
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER HURDLES THE JETS AND RUSHES BACK TO THE SUPER BOWL
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For more than half of Sunday's American Football
Conference championship game, the Jets could see all the way to
Miami and the Super Bowl, the game that they had helped turn into
one of the biggest spectacles in sports 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But in a 10-minute splurge after halftime, the Denver Broncos,
the defending Super Bowl champions, rallied for 20 points and
defeated the Jets by 23-10 to earn the trip to Super Bowl XXXIII on
Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by the high-powered Broncos was not a surprise, but
their Super Bowl opponent is: the Atlanta Falcons, who shocked the
heavily favored Minnesota Vikings for the National Conference
championship, winning by 30-27 in overtime in Minneapolis.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons _ led by a coach, Dan Reeves, who had heart bypass
surgery a month ago _ will play in the Super Bowl for the first
time in their 33-year history, and will again be underdogs, this
time to the Broncos, Reeves' former team.
</P>
<P>
   On the best of days it would have been difficult for the Jets to
halt a Denver team that had won 18 straight games at Mile High
Stadium, and which knew that this could have been 38-year-old
quarterback John Elway's last home game. But the Jets, who led by
10-0 early in the second half, could not overcome their mistakes:
six turnovers, including four lost fumbles, and a botched kickoff
that set up a Denver field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Terrell Davis once again led the Broncos, rushing
for 167 yards and a touchdown. For the Jets, Curtis Martin gained
just 14 yards on 13 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who won his fifth AFC championship in his 16th season and
is expected to announce his retirement after the Super Bowl, was
not at his best, completing 13 of 34 passes for 173 yards. But his
11-yard touchdown pass to Howard Griffith in the third quarter
started the Denver comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, how sweet, and how near it had seemed for more than half
the game for the Jets, who had become symbols of football failure
following their Super Bowl moment 30 years ago. This was their
first appearance in a championship game since 1982, when they lost
to Miami 14-0.
</P>
<P>
   All the surprising good things they had accomplished this
season, in winning the American East Division title, seemed to be
gaining even more momentum. They had the lead despite losing the
ball a few times.
</P>
<P>
   But even as they came apart near the end, with Vinny Testaverde
intercepted for the only time in the game after starting it with 13
straight completions, it was apparent that the franchise had gone
into a new era. It just wasn't going to Miami just yet.
</P>
<P>
   The sole score in the first half was John Hall's 32-yard field
goal as time expired, and it was positioned, in a mistake-filled
half, by a Broncos penalty on a punt. That put the Jets in good
field position after they had misfired repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   The game's opening drive _ which took place in a foot-stomping
atmosphere which threatened to shake the looming Rockies, and also
with wind gusts that hit 32 mph and sent flags snapping to
attention _ ended with a failed 42-yard field-goal attempt by Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets had other chances on offense and failed, while their
defense held the Broncos, the American Conference's most powerful
offense, to small gains.
</P>
<P>
   On one Jets drive, Martin fumbled and lost the ball. It was the
second straight playoff game in which he had done so, after a
regular season in which he lost the ball once in 369 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Another drive stopped when Keith Byars lost the ball after
catching Testaverde's 13th straight completion.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan of the Jets defensive coach, Bill Belichick,
seemed to have anticipated much of the Broncos' offense. Elway did
not have a completion in his first three drives. The Jets took away
the middle, double-teamed dangerous tight end Shannon Sharpe and
did not seem concerned about Elway throwing the ball deep.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also batted down three Elway passes in the opening
half, while Chad Cascadden sacked him once. Davis amassed 75 yards
on 14 carries in the half, but Elway, remarkably, completed only 4
of 14 passes for 33 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde, though, connected on 17 of 26 attempts for 217
yards. He connected with Wayne Chrebet 5 times for 86 yards.
Martin, the focus, naturally, of the Broncos' front seven, was held
to 11 yards on 8 rushing attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, early in the second half, the Broncos heard their first
boos _ for all anyone knows, their first of the season here _ when
they went three-and-out and Tom Rouen launched a 29-yard punt.
</P>
<P>
   Two drives later, a Jets rookie tight end named Blake Spence,
who had not even put on a uniform for 10 straight games, loomed out
of obscurity to block a punt that Fred Baxter recovered to put the
Jets only 1 yard out. One play later, Martin found the end zone,
and the Jets led, 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   But just as suddenly, Elway and the Broncos discovered their
quick-strike heritage. It took 93 seconds, included a 47-yard
strike from Elway to Ed McCaffrey _ who earlier had dropped two
passes _ and ended with an 11-yard touchdown toss to Howard
Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Jets' turnovers finally cost them points. Elam's
kickoff, held by the wind, bounced in front of the returner, David
Meggett. The Jets' James Farrior tried to snare it, but fumbled it
away to Keith Traylor on the Jets' 32.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a 44-yard field goal by Elam to tie the score at
10-10. Soon, again helped by good field position, Elam cut through
the dangerous winds for a 48-yard field and a 13-10 lead, Denver's
first of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The seemingly inexorable turnaround continued later in the third
quarter when Davis, who came in averaging 145 yards a post-season
game in his career, churned out a 31-yard touchdown run. It
extended the lead to 20-10 with 18 seconds left in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets soon were in a hole again. Alex Van Dyke, a seldom-used
wide receiver, fumbled after catching a pass, the fourth time in
the game the Jets lost the ball.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Win or lose, the Jets' appearance here was nothing short of
remarkable. The last time the Jets played in Denver they opened the
1996 season believing there was a new era with Neil O'Donnell at
quarterback. By season's end the Jets were 1-15, the opening-game
loss, by 41-6, a perfect precursor of how badly things would go.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells joined the team for the following season, and after
that the Jets charted a different course. Their East Division title
was their first such crown in 30 years. Their playoff run included
their first post-season victory since 1986, and first playoff game
since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells on Sunday became the first coach in the NFL to take a
third club to a conference championship game; he also is the only
coach in Jets history to have a winning record in his first season,
let alone his second. The Jets' 21-11 record the last two regular
seasons is sixth-best in the league over that span. It is also
better than any other team in the American Conference East.
</P>
<P>
   The team that Parcells has shaped _ there was a bit of whipping
into shape, too _ may have absorbed the cornerstone of his
philosophy: Until you understand what it is that causes you to
lose, you will never understand how to win. In other words, avoid
dumb plays, fumbles, mental errors. The Jets did none of those
things on Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
