<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-BRADLEY18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Out from the realm of improbability, Falcon's win `so
unbelievable'
 &HT;    By Mark Bradley
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Thirty-three years in the football business, and
finally Taylor Smith got to stand on a podium and be handed a
trophy. Thirty-three years of working various jobs in the family
shop, from locker-room attendant to team president, and here was
the payoff, so dearly deferred.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we hadn't thought this day would come, we wouldn't have
been it,'' Smith said, speaking for his long-suffering father, dead
15 months now. ``But sometimes you wondered.''
</P>
<P>
   Their audience had stopped wondering. Their audience simply knew
that everything this franchise tried would blow up like a trick
cigar. How could such an unassuming organization come to be so
cursed? What football gods had the callow Falcons affronted?
</P>
<P>
   And then, from beyond the blue, there came an enchanted season
when all curses became blessings, when every single wrong turned
absolutely right. ``It's destiny,'' said Chuck Smith, the defensive
end. ``It's got to be.''
</P>
<P>
   A kicker who hasn't missed anything all year fluffs the
clincher. An offense that can't be stopped manages seven points on
its last 10 possessions. A coach steers his team through an
excruciating championship game 34 days after having his chest cut
open. The Atlanta Falcons go to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``So unbelievable,'' Dan Reeves said. He sat in a Metrdome
cubbyhole, pulling off his socks but mostly staring at the floor.
``It makes you so humble and so proud in one swift motion.'' He
looked up. ``I don't have the words. I'm not very good with
words.''
</P>
<P>
   For everything this NFC title game was _ frustrating,
fulfilling, draining, uplifting _ there was about the improbable
victors a mood that transcended exultation. After seeing Randy Moss
burn and fizzle, after watching Gary Anderson miss his kick and
Morten Andersen make his, the Falcons seemed to grasp that this
championship wasn't just for the team that won it but for all those
Falcon assemblages that hadn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought much about getting to the Super Bowl,'' said
Chuck Smith, who forced the Randall Cunningham fumble that changed
this game. ``Deion (Sanders) and Andre (Rison) _ they had to go
elsewhere to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   But now one precedent has been broken, another set: It is
possible to be a Falcons player and reach the Super Bowl. It is
possible for wearers of this uniform to do surpassing things. Chris
Chandler turned into Johnny Unitas. Ronnie Harris, cut by Seattle
in November, caught a vital pass. Eugene Robinson, who can't run,
broke up a throw to Moss, who assuredly can. Said defensive tackle
Shane Dronett, released by Detroit two summers ago: ''Unbelievable,
isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   It is, and it isn't. Fortune favors the prepared, but this much
good fortune on the heels of so much bad? ``All the things I've
been taught, from the seventh grade on,'' Reeves said. ``About how
you keep working. About doing the fundamental things. About a bunch
of guys coming together and sacrificing for one another...''
</P>
<P>
   He stopped. Every bromide had just been made real. The Atlanta
Falcons were NFC champions. Said Dan Reeves, describing the
indescribable. ``It just blows you away.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
