<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6903 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-BISHER18-COX     01-17 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-BISHER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler, Falcons tough birds
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Let me savor the moment. Can it be real, or am I
giddy in the head? It must be true, for they're dancing in
Peachtree Street back home, they tell me. I trust Atlanta isn't
burning again.
</P>
<P>
   Let me try to run it through my mind one more time: The Falcons
are going to the Super Bowl. That's the Atlanta Falcons,
understand. Thirty-third year in the National Football League, 33rd
Super Bowl. There seems to be the fine hand of destiny here.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons of Ernie Wheelwright. Of Junior Miller. Of Randy
Johnson, first quarterback. Gary Barnes, who scored the first
touchdown. Of Tom Pridemore. Of Greg Brezina. Of Dave Hampton. Just
think of them, all those guys who passed through those grungy
uniforms and left some of the best days of their lives behind, with
no glory. And Hecker, Van Brocklin, Campbell, Glanville and Jones,
all those coaches who couldn't get it done before. Through all
those dismal years, when the Falcons became the national bird of
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   For years, they had company. The Braves were just as futile.
They ran through managers like an embezzler runs through money.
They changed owners. But nothing changed until Ted Turner turned
baseball over to baseball people. Now the Braves are a symbol of
nouveau prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Falcons wallowed behind. Leeman Bennett had them
within a few minutes of a championship game one time, but they were
steamrolled by Dallas. The Cowboys scored 20 points in the last
quarter, on the Falcons' own ground. Same score then as this score
that shall be hallowed forever: 30-27. The last time there was an
overtime in one of these championships, Denver topped Cleveland.
Dan Reeves was the winning coach. Same score: 30-27.
</P>
<P>
   This was not supposed to happen. They didn't have to beat
Minnesota to be adored. Look at all the joy they had brought to
their people. Winning 14 games of 16 and bringing the missing
persons back to their seats in the Georgia Dome. Just ``being
here,'' as they say, was enough to feed the flock. Here was a coach
with a heart on rehab. Here's a quarterback who's the target of
every defense. Get Chris Chandler out of the game, the Falcons are
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Then, there is the noise for which the Metrodome is notorious.
They were testing the sound system before the game, ``Referee mike
check, one, two, three ...'' It rattled your earbones. Vikings
players shamelessly stand on the field waving their arms like
cheerleaders when the other team has the ball. They should wear
skirts and join the dancing girls.
</P>
<P>
   Well, ``noise'' turned out to be seriously over-valued. The
price took a big drop in the Metrodome on Sunday. Once Chandler
tied the game on his goal-line pass to Terance Mathis, the voices
lost some of their peal. And as the Falcons were making the drive
to the winning field goal, thousands of noise-makers were leaving
their pews, looking neither right nor left, jaws set like the
condemned walking the last mile. It's fun to see the suffering in
another precinct when it has been part of your autumn life since
Lyndon Johnson was president.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Falcons and Vikings tried to give the game away. What
gave you a hint that this might be a better than common day for the
Falcons was the first possession. They drove the ball from kickoff
to end zone in a tedious set of 15 plays. The Vikings came back
like a rocket, like all the football scientists had said they
would. In two minutes, 48 seconds they were on the board, as
foreseen, on a pass from Randall Cunningham to Randy Moss.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Morten Andersen kicked the winning field goal, all
that was lost in the warp of time. Moss was never a real factor
thereafter. Gary Anderson missed his first field goal this season.
I never knew there could be so much difference between an ``o'' and
an ``e'' in an Anderson's name.
</P>
<P>
   If there is to be one hero raised above all others in this, let
it be Chandler, who came to us like an orphan left on a doorstep.
``Journeyman'' was stamped all over him, moved about like a gypsy
quarterback, never in one place for long. He has survived injury
and critique, and attempts to take his head off. Twice he limped
off and twice he came back and never did he give an inch of ground.
</P>
<P>
   He is one tough sonofagun, which pretty much represents what
these Falcons are.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
