<HEADER>
A6904 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-CHANDLER18-CO     01-17 0506
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-CHANDLER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chandler's part in `all or nothing' play a big score
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ More than a decade ago, Dan Reeves watched in
disbelief as Denver quarterback John Elway drove the Broncos 98
yards for a game-tying touchdown in the final seconds, forcing
overtime in the 1987 AFC Championship Game at Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Reeves watched his latest pupil, Atlanta quarterback
Chris Chandler, lead the Falcons 71 yards in only 1:18 to tie
Minnesota 27-27 with 49 seconds remaining, forcing overtime in the
NFC Championship Game in the Metrodome.
</P>
<P>
   And, like the Broncos, the Falcons reached the Super Bowl with a
game-winning field goal in overtime in the 30-27 upset.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Chris after we went down there and tied the score, that
it ranked right up there with any of the big-time quarterbacks,''
Reeves said. ``He's done it with the pressure on him. When we
signed him, I talked to him and told him we're going to stick our
neck out to sign him because I thought he could win a Super Bowl
for us. Now he's one game away from doing that, and I think he's
good enough to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler threw for 340 yards and three touchdowns on 27-of-43
passing against the Vikings, who stacked the line of scrimmage with
as many as eight players to stop tailback Jamal Anderson, who
rushed for only 67 yards on 23 attempts.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, in his second season with the Falcons after a
journey-man career that included stops with five other teams, was a
steadying force for Atlanta in its final drive of regulation,
completing four of six attempts for 56 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's biggest completion in the series was a 29-yarder to
Ronnie Harris on a corner route. Chandler's 16-yard touchdown to
Terance Mathis five plays later came after a tipped pass was nearly
intercepted by safety Robert Griffith in the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a do-or-die thing,'' Chandler said. ``It was all or
nothing. In a way, it makes it easier because you know you have to
score a touchdown. You don't have to worry about it being third or
fourth down, you've just got to make the plays. You get so wrapped
up in the game that you don't actually think about what is
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler's play in overtime was even bigger. He opened Atlanta's
second series of the extra session by completing two long passes to
tight end O.J. Santiago to move to the Minnesota 48. On
second-and-6 at the Vikings' 44, he hit Mathis with a seven-yard
pass. On first down, Chandler gained seven yards on a keeper. After
three runs by Anderson, Morten Andersen nailed the game-winning
38-yard field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``All week, we'd been hearing about how they were going to stop
our running game and beat us,'' Chandler said. ``I think Terance
and Tony (Martin) and O.J. took it personally. I know I did. We've
been making big plays with our passing game all year. I think to
overlook our passing game is a mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
