<HEADER>
A6905 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-LEDEBAR18-COX     01-17 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-LEDEBAR18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A drive toward victory
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The opposing quarterback is sacked and fumbles
just before halftime, your team scores a touchdown on the next play
and suddenly the game's not a blowout, anymore. A safety just
missed an interception, the heretofore perfect placekicker suddenly
becomes imperfect, and there you are. Still hanging around.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all we had to do was hang around,'' Falcons tackle Bob
Whitfield said with a sweaty smile Sunday. ``You know the saying:
If you let a dog hang around long enough, sooner or later he's
gonna bite you in the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   A miracle season appeared over for the Falcons with just over
two minutes remaining in their NFC championship game against
Minnesota. The Vikings led 27-20 and Gary Anderson, who had made 37
straight field goals this season, was lined up for a clinching
38-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was the biggest sign of fate the Falcons franchise
has ever experienced: Anderson missed, giving Atlanta one final
chance to tie the game and send it into overtime. ``When he missed
that, our sideline erupted as if we had just won the game,''
quarterback Chris Chandler said. ``That excitement just carried
over into the huddle on the next drive.''
</P>
<P>
   Denver had a ``Drive.'' San Francisco had a ``Drive.'' Now the
Falcons can embrace their own moment.
</P>
<P>
   They began a possession at their own 29-yard line with 2:09
remaining. Eight plays and 1:18 later, the game was tied after
Chandler threw a 16-yard touchdown pass to Terance Mathis. From
beginning to end was a string of improbabilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a magical thing _ fate, destiny, all that stuff,''
Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   It started quietly, Chandler hitting fullback Brian Kozlowski
for a two-yard gain, leading into the two-minute warning. On second
down, Chandler, from a shotgun formation, connected with Mathis for
9 yards down the right sideline. Before the catch, Mathis was still
thinking about a touchdown pass he dropped earlier in the fourth
quarter that would've cut Minnesota's lead to 27-24.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have an opportunity to make plays, you have to take
advantage of it,'' he said. ``I let the guys down.''
</P>
<P>
   On first down from the Falcons' 40, it was Ronnie Harris's turn.
Harris, who was signed in mid-season after being released by
Seattle, found himself the centerpiece of the next play, finding a
seam in the Vikings' zone defense on a corner rout and making a
catch just in front of Vikings strong safety Robert Griffith for a
29-yard gain to the Vikings' 31 with 1:48 left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hoping we'd call that play _ it worked great in
practice,'' Harris said.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler tried to go back to Harris on the next play but it was
near disaster. The pass was tipped, blooped over the receiver and
Griffth dove and just missed an interception.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see that,'' said center Robbie Tobeck, ``your heart
drops into your stomach.''
</P>
<P>
   Second and 10 from the Minnesota 31. Chandler drops back, sees
his receivers covered and scrambles 9 yards. He's belted by Vikings
linebacker Dwayne Rudd and comes up limping. ``No big deal,'' he
says later.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's only 1:27 remaining but the Metrodome is getting
quiet. On the third and one from the 22, Chandler hands the ball to
Jamal Anderson, who starts over left tackle, then bounces outside
and runs 6 yards for the first down. ``I felt like I could break
that thing and take it to the house,'' Anderson recalled.
</P>
<P>
   No problem. The Falcons were at the Vikings' 16 with 1:15 left.
On first down, the Falcons ran a play called, ``78-wing-8-Y6.''
Translation: Mathis was to line up wide right and run a post route.
No Viking followed Mathis, but Chandler's pass was tipped by
cornerback Corey Fuller, and Griffith again had a potential
interception bounce off his finger tips.
</P>
<P>
   On second down with 57 seconds left, the Falcons came back with
the same play. This time Chandler was pressured. But as he
scrambled, Mathis crossed over the middle into an opening. Chandler
drilled a pass that Mathis caught as he dropped to his knees for
the tying TD with 49 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to make the play,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to compare a lot of things to golf,'' Chandler said.
``A lot of times when the other guy has a two-foot putt and you
have to make a miracle shot from the rough, you make the shot.
You're not thinking about first downs and all that stuff. You're
just thinking, 'We have to score a touchdown.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
