<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6906 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-MINNSCENE18-C     01-17 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-MINNSCENE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dome thunders, gives way to sudden silence
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ They'd surrounded themselves with giant stereo
speakers during practices, lodged mild complaints with the NFL, and
generally made enough noise about noise it almost could have been a
separate section in the playbook.
</P>
<P>
   But when all was loudly said and done Sunday, the Atlanta
Falcons had found the best way imaginable around the Minnesota
Vikings' supposed earsplitting home-field advantage: They beat
them. And the loyal band of Atlanta fans who'd followed them here
to the so-called ``Thunderdome'' finally got to have the last word.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a half hour had passed since veteran kicker Morten
Andersen's 38-yard field goal iced a thrilling overtime victory for
the Falcons and still some 50 fans couldn't bring themselves to
leave the field-level seats they'd clambered down to almost as soon
as the ball sailed through the uprights. Chanting ``Super Bowl!
Super Bowl!'', brandishing signs reading ``Miami Bound,'' and in
one case, waving a giant Falcons flag, they stared almost
unbelievingly at the field where only a few local TV reporters
solemnly filed reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``After everything that was said about the noise, I don't think
(quarterback Chris) Chandler was affected one bit,'' said Jimmie
Ann Davis, as her husband and two adult children found themselves
exchanging high-fives with whooping strangers clad in the suddenly
hip Falcons red-and-black. ``And if he was, he somehow pulled it
off anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few hours earlier, it never would have seemed possible.
Then, it was nearly impossible to pick out the Atlanta fans, so
overwhelming was the presence of Vikings fans both inside and
outside the Metrodome. Their hair or beards dyed purple, their
horned helmets accessorized with long yarn braids or fake swords,
they wore their Vikings player jerseys with nearly as much
confidence as the sense that their famed loudness would somehow
carry the day.
</P>
<P>
   And why not? The previous week, the vanquished Arizona Cardinals
had claimed it was too loud inside the Dome for them to possibly
audible plays _ let alone win a playoff game. Meanwhile, the local
media had spent the past few days pooh-poohing Falcons coach Dan
Reeves' complaints about the Dome's supposedly dangerous noise
level, and then _ oops! _ sort of confirming the problem. One
newspaper, the St. Paul Pioneer-Press, reported that noise levels
reached 128.4 decibels during last Sunday's playoff game against
the Arizona Cardinals, equivalent to the sound of a jet on takeoff
and some 43 decibels above where OSHA regulations begin to take
effect.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, longtime Vikings fans said it was all just so much,
um, talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a dome; Atlanta's got a dome,'' said Rick Lewis, who
was one of four ``Mossheads'' here from Moose Lake, Minn., some 100
miles to the north.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing horned helmets covered with remarkably fresh-looking
2-week-old grass _ one of their party, a mortician, confessed it
was the stuff used on top of graves _ they were paying homage to
Vikings phenomenal rookie receiver Randy Moss. ``The Falcons ought
to be able to take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe they should just have ``taken it'' like Lewis' cohort
Ray Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earplugs,'' Arnold confided, lifting his helmet to reveal
serious looking stoppers stuffed into both ears. ``I may be a
`Mosshead,' but I'm not an idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, he'd been here before. For two hours before the game
began, music and announcements blared out of the Dome at
unbelievably high levels, exhorting fans to ``SHOW YOUR PURPLE
PRIDE!'' Once the game began, Minnesota fans, players and stadium
staff all conspired to raise the noise level whenever the opposing
team was trying to do anything but hide in the showers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't even hear the music anymore,'' said onetime Marietta
resident Stephen Anderson, a diehard Minnesota fan who was sitting
about halfway up the stadium in front of the press box. ``I took
two aspirin before I came here. I should have brought along the
bottle.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, maybe the Falcons fans were just tougher. You manage
to grab a $125 ticket and enough warm clothes to withstand a
game-time temperature of 32 degrees, said Atlantan Traci Cameron,
and the prospect of hearing nothing but ringing for the next few
days was no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, tens of thousands of Vikings fans headed for
their cars and dreams of what nearly was. Said one, Plymouth,
Minn., resident Jim Miller, softly:
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never heard it so quiet here.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
