<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-MORT18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mortensen kicks it off
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Morten Andersen played on teams so bad with the
New Orleans Saints in the 1980s, that he was widely considered the
teams' best player. It was a distinction, however, that spoke more
to Andersen's skill than the Aints' ineptness. And although mired
in the Bayou abyss, Andersen still managed to establish himself as
the premier kicker in the game, one who performed in the clutch
with icy perfection.
</P>
<P>
   So, considering Anderson's background, it should come as no
surprise that when the time came for the 17-year NFL veteran to
boot the Falcons into the Super Bowl _ and to erase the memories of
the bad old days _ he approached it with business-as-usual calm.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just another kick,'' Andersen said.
</P>
<P>
   He was talking about the way he approached it, not its
magnitude. Someone had the audacity to ask Andersen if it was the
most important field goal he'd ever kicked. ''Come on,'' he said.
''For the Super Bowl? You've got to be kidding. It's been 17 years
for me. After so long, you kind of think that you might not ever
get that chance. But one of the attributes of a kicker is to be
patient. I've been patient.''
</P>
<P>
   He was patiently watching and pacing as quarterback Chris
Chandler directed the Falcons from their 9 yard line in overtime.
When Chandler hit O.J. Santiago for a 26-yard gain, Atlanta was in
Minnesota territory _ and close to Andersen territory. Finally, on
third down, coach Dan Reeves sent in the field goal unit.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings burned a timeout in an attempt to freeze Andersen.
But how can you freeze ice? All it did was give Andersen more time
to visualize the celebration that was to come.
</P>
<P>
   He and punter/holder Dan Stryzinski went through their usual
pre-kick routine, which means they did not say much.
</P>
<P>
   ''Another day at the office,'' Stryzinski said. ''I knew he
would get it done. He's the best clutch kicker in the game. And I'm
not lying.''
</P>
<P>
   Andersen not only made the 38-yarder to win the game; he drilled
it. ''Right down the pike,'' he said. It touched off a celebration
on the Metrodome field that was sustained and unrestrained.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a great team effort,'' Andersen said. ''This was a game
and a kick that gives me some closure. Big time.''
</P>
<P>
   At 38, Andersen said he does not know if he'll play an 18th
season. Like the basketball player from Chicago who retired last
week, Andersen has conquered his sport. Individually, he's been
consistently reliable over the years, with bad teams, not so bad
and now with a Super Bowl team.
</P>
<P>
   His kick Sunday gave him 26 game-winners, which is phenomenal
considering how awful most of the teams he played with were. Unlike
Jordan, however, Andersen does not have a championship ring. But,
thanks to his left foot, he has a shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's all you can ask,'' he said. ''It's an honor to play in
the Super Bowl. I know _ after 17 years _ how hard it is to get
there. It's unbelievable to finally get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, he got into the position of hero on Gary Anderson's
only missed field goal of the season, with 2:07 left in regulation.
Chandler deftly took the Falcons down the field for the game-tying
and overtime-forcing TD.
</P>
<P>
   Not much later, Andersen got his turn. ''One kick doesn't define
you,'' said Andersen, who also had field goals of 27 and 24 yards.
''The ramifications on that last kick are huge. The unit did its
job. All I had to do was do my job, let my skill take over. ... And
now, after all this time, I'm going to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
