<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-OLDFALCONS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elder Falcons `never stopped fighting for it'
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ He's been with the Falcons the longest, which
means he's suffered the most, which means Jessie Tuggle will enjoy
the trip to Miami the best. But even in the euphoric aftermath of
the Falcons' overtime victory, something was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to hug and kiss my wife and my kids,'' Tuggle
said. ``I can't wait to do that. They've been with me through all
the years. They've kept me going. I want to enjoy this with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12 years of service Tuggle has put in with the Falcons were
worth experiencing the joy of Sunday. Going into this season, the
teams Tuggle played admirably with had a cumulative record of _
hold your nose _ 64-111. Seldom was there any hope for anything
like this season: 14-2 regular season, playoff victory over nemesis
San Francisco at home, NFC Championship Game victory on the road
over record-setting Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   So, excuse Tuggle as he relishes the moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud,'' he said. ``This is a long time coming. I've been
around here a long time, but I never stopped wishing for this,
never stopped fighting for it. And now that it's here, it's hard to
put into words.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Falcons arrived here Friday, Tuggle talked boldly about
the Falcons' chances. Sunday, he was not through.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came here to win,'' he said. ``We weren't going to quit.
We've faced adversity all year long, but we always overcame it.
Now, we're going to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Tuggle offered the first prognostication of what promises
to be many from pundits and fans alike. ``And we're not finished
yet,'' he said. ``We're going to win this thing, too. We're not
going to Miami just to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tight end O.J. Santiago, who made two significant catches in the
game-winning drive, said he's been to Miami once in his life. ``But
not like this,'' he said. ``I'm only in my second year, and I feel
great about it. So you know how Jessie must feel. Hey, I know what
it's like to struggle. I played on a college team (at Kent State)
that won five games in four years. I know what it's like to think
every year you're rebuilding, that you're going to turn it around.
And it doesn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, I know this moment is very special to Jesse. Twelve years
he's been here with a team that was struggling. Now he's going to
the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They said all week that we couldn't play with Minnesota,''
said Tuggle, who had a team-high 11 tackles. ``We're a team with no
superstars. But we showed the nation what we're about.''
</P>
<P>
   What they are about is the very elements that Tuggle possesses:
grit, perseverance and will.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not all about raw talent,'' said defensive tackle Chuck
Smith, who's suffered with the Falcons for seven years. ``I've been
in a lot of battles with this team over the years. I look into
every guys' eyes before the game. I could see we were ready. We
kept fighting. Now, we're proud of ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
