<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-VIKEREAX18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vikings loss `is going to hurt for a while'
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ It was not the losing. It was the method. The
toast of the NFC, the most multifaceted offense in the game today,
collapsed upon itself like a fourth-grader that forgot his lines in
the school play.
</P>
<P>
   ''This,'' nose tackle Jason Fisk said, ''is going to hurt for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings lost a game they had been dominating
Sunday, fiddled away a 10-point lead in the last 13:41. Randy Moss,
the NFL's Next Great Thing, caught only once pass the whole second
half. Randall Cunningham, one of the season's great stories,
completed just four of his final 11 passes and played the overtime
as in a fog.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than even attempt to score in the last 49 seconds of
regulation, owing two time outs and needing some 50 yards to give
the game's most consistent kicker a chance to win, the Vikings gave
it up. Cunningham kneeled down with the third down snap to let time
run out. Incredible.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing I'm disappointed in is the lead we had,'' Moss said.
''Our explosive offense didn't let it happen. As a whole, I'm
feeling kind of low.''
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings locker room was a morgue afterward. Running back
Robert Smith walked as in total body cramp, due to knee and thigh
bruises. Linebackers Dixon Edwards, Ed McDaniel and Bobby Houston
were all knocked out of the game. Minnesota scored just seven
points in the final 37:44 of play. It had committed the offsides
penalties _ four offsides, one enroachment _ that opponents at the
Metrodome usually make.
</P>
<P>
   They might have had everything going for them, but the Minnesota
Vikings eventually had nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not easy,'' cornerback Jimmy Hitchcock said. ''It's not
easy for anybody. We knew we were going to win the whole thing. We
felt we were the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a solid season,'' coach Dennis Green said. ''It wasn't
the great season we really wanted. I think all of our guys are
feeling the way they should feel.''
</P>
<P>
   What had been a season of celebration for Cunningham ended with
him having to explain away an awkward conclusion. He completed nine
of his first 10 passes and by early in the fourth quarter was
25-for-37 for 266 yards with a pair of touchdowns. Then the Vikings
fell silent.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we tightened up,'' Cunningham said. ''I think we
didn't make the plays that we needed to make at the end,
offensively and defensively. You can't really look at one play and
say that of we had done this. ... It's a game of inches and a game
of timing and at the end, we just didn't have what we needed to get
the ball in the end zone. They did at the end and they won the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Atlanta played a perfect game,'' tight end Andrew Glover said.
''They came in with a game plan and they stuck to it. I think we
got a little excited in the end when we couldn't make it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
