</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-FOLO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Botha fight exposes a rusty `Iron Mike'
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In the best-case scenario for Mike Tyson,
consecutive losses to Evander Holyfield and a dramatic career slide
in this decade have taught him that giving his ring techniques an
overhaul is mandatory if he hopes to get back into the title
picture.
</P>
<P>
   There's only one problem. Francois Botha is exhibit ``A'' that
those same losses to Holyfield taught everybody else something,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, a light-punching, soft-bellied heavyweight, mimicked the
heavyweight champion in his fight against Tyson Saturday night at
the MGM Grand. He didn't crumble at the thought of Tyson's vicious
right hand. He jabbed and moved away every time Tyson telegraphed a
punch. He tied him up whenever Tyson got close, showing no concern
for Tyson's inside skills, then beat him to the punch on the break.
Botha beat Tyson to the punch?
</P>
<P>
   ``I really expected more from him,'' the South African said.
</P>
<P>
   All Tyson proved in his latest comeback fight was he still has
the ability to be a one-punch wonder when a mediocre opponent gets
careless. Trailing by a wide margin on points, Tyson dropped Botha
with a right hand with 11 seconds remaining in the fifth round.
When Botha didn't make it up before referee Richard Steele's
10-count, Tyson had his first victory in two years and four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to improve _ I've got a long way to go,'' said Tyson,
who through four rounds won only one round combined on the cards of
the three judges. ``I wanted to shine tonight, but it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's last visit to the MGM was not pleasant. He was
disqualified for biting Holyfield's ears in their title rematch
June 28, 1997, and had his license revoked. The bout ended with
Tyson going bonkers in the ring and a near melee breaking out
between the two camps.
</P>
<P>
   The Botha bout picked up where that one left off. Botha used his
jab with surprising effectiveness in the first round. But as the
round ended and the two were in a clinch, Tyson attempted to twist
Botha's arm (''I told the ref, 'He's trying to break my arm.''')
and Botha responded by throwing an overhand right after the bell.
Tyson fired back, and when Steele was unable to separate the two,
camp members from both corners and security personnel leaped into
the ring in an attempt to restore order. There was a delay of
several minutes before the fight continued.
</P>
<P>
   Steele apparently began to focus on Tyson, because he deducted a
point from him early in the second round for the repeat holding
foul. That infuriated Tyson. For the next two rounds, he seemed
puzzled how to penetrate the defenses of the lightly regarded Botha
and was loading up for one shot, rather than throwing combinations
as trainer Tommy was loading up for one shot, rather than throwing
combinations and as trainer Tommy Brooks had promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a work in progress,'' Brooks said. ``It's going to take
time. He wasn't following the game plan. I was disappointed. All he
was trying to do was land one good shot. That's not how he's going
to get any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Tyson, overconfidence creeped in with Botha. He
taunted Tyson, dropping his gloves, even smiling at him and saying,
``Is that all you have?'' That was a mistake. Tyson began pressing
the attack and caught Botha coming in with a short right on the
chin. Botha dropped. It was several minutes before the cobwebs
cleared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just walked into a punch _ a punch you don't see,'' Botha
said. ``I was controlling it real easy and keeping away from Mike's
power. I started fooling around too much, probably. I got
careless.''
</P>
<P>
   His trainer, Panama Lewis, concurred: ``He dropped his hands.
But I can't take anything away from him. He was sticking to the
game plan until he got too cocky.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson seemed to take his performance well, and his handlers were
in full spin control after the fight. Promoter Dan Goosen said, ``I
don't think Mike fought poorly _ I think Botha just fought great.''
Shelly Finkel, Tyson's manager, actually praised his fighter for
``keeping his composure'' _ odd, considering Tyson was yelling at
Steele and it took security officials to calm him down after the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson was candid about a couple of things. Told of Botha's
charge that Tyson was trying to break his arm, the former champion
said, ``He's correct. He got rough with me, I got rough right
back.'' Asked if he felt he proved anything with his performance,
he said, ``No, I'm just constantly trying to do well. We're working
on it.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tyson, at 32, has time to work on things, it's only because
of the sad state of the heavyweight division. But when a Francois
Botha gives him this many problems, so can others. His next fight
is tentatively scheduled for April 24, possibly against Axel
Schulz. Schulz will watch tapes of the Botha fight _ just as Botha
watched Holyfield's.
</P>
<P>
   Botha said, ``I would like to have a rematch. But I know there's
probably other people who want a chance against Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
