<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6913 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-HUMMER18-COX     01-17 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-HUMMER18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kicking criticism, doubt out of the dome: The Falcons are going
to the Super Bowl
 &HT;    By Steve Hummer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The falcons are going to the Super Bowl. Such a
simple sentence. Such an unfathomable concept.
</P>
<P>
   You could write it a year ago, a month ago, a week ago and still
risk ridicule. To have spoken it before a grand jury might have
been an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   There it is now, in plain fact, made real by a game that will be
the shining point of reference in Atlanta sports. In fact, I think
Sid Bream's little jog around the basepaths just got some real
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Let us break down that eight-word declaration into its two major
components, shall we class?
</P>
<P>
   ''The Falcons.'' A football tragedy. Wretches, the way that
Dickens used to make them. A collective noun usually modified by a
sigh and a mumbled ''same ol'. . .''
</P>
<P>
   No more. Sunday's overtime subduing of Minnesota for the NFC
championship put all that was previously known about this franchise
through a wood-chipper. It is time to redefine. The accumulated
sins of 33 seasons were forgiven because, well, the Falcons are
going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ''It means a dream come true,'' said Taylor Smith, head of the
family so often treated as failure's fertilizer. ''This is
something we've always wanted to do for our people our fans. For
me, that's just overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   ''So long. So much criticism,'' said linebacker Jessie Tuggle.
''No one imagined that we could play at this high a level or beat a
team like we just beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's game was dangerous hike over a high, narrow, twisting
plot. Past editions of Falcons would have been thrown off by the
first switchback. This one endured, counting on the fact that the
16-1 Vikings had never faced a real trial this season.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, the Vikings were the ones who stared into the
bright possibilities and blinked. Their kicker hadn't missed in a
year-and-a-half, yet pushed the 38-yard, fourth-quarter kick that
would have finished the Falcons. When Morten Andersen had the
chance to win it from the same distance, he was pure. ''I didn't
have the perfect season, but I had the perfect Sunday,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When these Falcons needed a touchdown drive with just over two
minutes left in regulation, quarterback Chris Chandler delivered.
He was 3-for-3 on the drive to the winning overtime field goal.
''That ranks right up there with any of the big-time
quarterbacks,'' Dan Reeves told his man.
</P>
<P>
   When these Falcons needed someone to keep the phenom Randy Moss
in check, there was 35-year-old safety Eugene Robinson swatting
away the bomb in overtime. The kid caught but one pass for four
yards in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as Andersen aligned himself for the winning kick, an
old-fashioned tent revival broke out on the Falcons bench. Instead
of watching the kick, most of those not directly involved huddled
in prayer. These Falcons call on all powers. ''I know there are
Christians on both sides, that God will favor both of us,'' said
cornerback Ray Buchanan. ''We wanted Him to favor us just a little
bit more, that's all.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the second part of the simple, yet astounding sentence:
''Super Bowl,'' the place promised to every player who buys into
football's ethic of work and faith. The place that seemed
unreachable, almost fictional, to those of Falcons persuasion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it gives everybody in this league hope,'' said Reeves,
underestimating the wonder of the Falcons going to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
