<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6914 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NFC-LEDE18-COX     01-17 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFC-LEDE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons suddenly super
 &HT;    WITH PHOTOS, SEVERAL SIDEBARS
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Amid the bedlam of the Atlanta Falcons locker
room, William White was yelling, ''We shocked the world, we shocked
the world!'' and Eugene Robinson was yelling, ''They can't believe
it, they can't believe it!''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons safeties were right.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are going to Super Bowl XXXIII. As participants.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible no words will ever sufficiently describe what
happened Sunday afternoon, when the Falcons came from behind to
beat the Minnesota Vikings 30-27 in overtime at the Metrodome, not
only because it was so amazing, but because so much happened in one
game.
</P>
<P>
   As the Falcons danced and hollered as they gathered on stage to
receive the NFC Championship trophy, running back Jamal Anderson
was pointing to people, saying, ``I told you all.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, though, could have predicted that a Falcons team that
was 1-7 in the middle of last season _ having won just four of it's
previous 24 games _ would turn around and win 22 of it's next 26.
</P>
<P>
   Morten Andersen's 38-yard field goal with 3:08 left in the extra
period was the game-winner. The native of Denmark has won an
NFL-record 26 games with kicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was automatic, man,'' he said. ``Right down the middle,
baby. It's all destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it is.
</P>
<P>
   Now this improbable season moves on to the Super Bowl in Miami,
where in two weeks the Falcons face the Denver Broncos, who
defeated the New York Jets 23-10 Sunday in the AFC Championship
Game.
</P>
<P>
   After Andersen's kick, Falcons president Taylor Smith and other
team officials yelled in the press box, and bedlam reigned on the
field, as Falcons players and coaches went running in every
direction.
</P>
<P>
   At the trophy presentation, coach Dan Reeves, who five weeks ago
today underwent quadruple heart bypass surgery, tried to do the
``Dirty Bird'' dance, something he said at midseason he would do if
the Falcons made it to their first ever Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stand today, my heart's going to be in great shape,''
Reeves said. ``It can't get much tougher than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room, backup quarterback Steve DeBerg was
videotaping everything. Wide receiver Terance Mathis _ whose
16-yard touchdown catch with 49 seconds left sent the game to
overtime _ smoked a big cigar.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as beautiful as it gets,'' Mathis said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody played better, or harder than quarterback Chris Chandler,
who completed 27 of 43 passes for 340 yards and three touchdowns.
He got sacked three times, but in general had time most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder he was going around kissing his linemen on the cheek
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just kept giving me time to throw,'' Chandler said. ``It
was hard today, unbelievably loud, but we didn't have a single
false start penalty. That's how focused we were.''
</P>
<P>
   As big as Andersen's kick was, there were many other moments
nearly as important as the Falcons (16-2) rallied from deficits of
20-7 in the second quarter, and 27-17 in the fourth quarter to win
for the 11th straight time.
</P>
<P>
   What was biggest?
</P>
<P>
   Was it the 38-yard field goal missed by Minnesota's Gary
Anderson that gave Atlanta the ball back with just 2:07 left in the
game? Anderson this season became the only kicker in NFL history to
go all season without a missed field goal, hitting on all 37 of his
attempts before that fateful attempt sailed barely left, leaving
Atlanta within 27-20.
</P>
<P>
   Or was it the lightning quick, eight-play, 71-yard drive that
ended with a game-tying pass from Chandler to Mathis, who was
barely in the end zone?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it was it a defense that gave up just seven points in the
final 44:37 to a team that set an NFL record this season by scoring
556 points.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is for certain, few in the crowd of 64,060 in the
Metrodome, or back in Atlanta were sitting down when the Falcons
took their second possession of the overtime.
</P>
<P>
   On the first play, Chandler hit tight end O.J. Santiago, whose
fumble in the first half helped the Vikings (16-2) score 10 points
off Atlanta turnovers. That 15-yard play was the first of 10 on the
70-yard drive, and Santiago wasn't finished.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, he caught a 26-yard pass, moving the ball to
the Minnesota 48.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a bad feeling when I fumbled,'' he said, ``but I
couldn't let it take me out of the game. I went out to make plays.
I just joined the party. Everybody else was making plays, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson didn't have his usual stellar game, rushing 23 times
for a modest 67 yards, his 9-yard run behind left guard Gene
Williams moments later took the ball to the Minnesota 22.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson gained 1 yard on the next two carries, and Reeves opted
to kick the field goal on third-and-9 from the 21.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, who took three Denver teams to Super Bowls in the 1980s,
losing all three, went to five Super Bowls as a player and coach
with the Cowboys in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, this one already is more rewarding.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's incredible when you think about it, coming from 1-7
halfway through our first year,'' he said. ``All my life, every
football coach I ever played for preached the same things that we
try to, and when you have a football team that believes in those
things and executes them. ... I couldn't be prouder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing tougher than (Sunday's game) is going to be
dancing in downtown Atlanta, the dirty bird. That ain't going to be
a pretty sight.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh yes, it will be.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
