<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INAUG-BBQ18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Barbecue for 15,000, please
 &HT;    By Kitty Crider
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four years ago Eddie Deen served plates to
15,000 people in 48 minutes, his personal best barbecue record. At
five to six people a second, that's faster than the average Texan
can say ``barbecue plate, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning today, he will again turn Colorado Street into a giant
outdoor kitchen to feed 12,000 to 15,000 guests attending the
second inauguration of Gov. George W. Bush on Tuesday. A $3 ticket,
purchased in advance, will get folks about a half-pound of meat _
the choices are brisket, smoked turkey breast, ham and sausage _
beans, cole slaw, potato salad, condiments, a big ol' homemade
yeast roll and a slice of chocolate fudge pecan or vanilla
buttermilk pie. Thank ya, kindly, sir. We need a nap now.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Deen &AMP; Company will cook the 800 briskets _ that's 400
steers _ at his headquarters in Terrell. ``But we will smoke the
turkeys fresh in Austin next to the Capitol. I have a 20-foot
smoker that will hold 200 turkeys,'' he adds. To accomplish this
mega 'cue, the cooking team will leave North Texas before daybreak
today en route to the Capitol grounds with trucks, trailers,
portable generators for cooking and the smoker in tow. (Tickets for
the barbecue may already be sold out. Call 494-1999 to check.)
</P>
<P>
   Much of the food for the inauguration day barbecue has been
donated: the sausage from football legend Earl Campbell, turkey and
ham from Hormel, beans from Ranch Style, water from Anaya, soft
drinks from Coca-Cola.
</P>
<P>
   Deen, speaking in a calm, slow drawl early one morning this
month, did not sound like a man sweating the big barbecue. ``We
catered over 3,000 parties last year. We've done the Cowtown Ball
in Fort Worth, the Cattlebaron's Ball in Dallas and Tyler,''
enumerated the 1979 A&AMP;M grad.
</P>
<P>
   To feed Texans as fast as a Nolan Ryan pitch, Deen will bring
100 or so people and set up 60 nonpartisan serving lines.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bush's inauguration in 1995, when Deen says he was a
small company and went without sleep for a couple of days for this
event, this year's barbecue won't be a snooze loser. ``We were a
very small company four years ago,'' says Deen. But he snagged the
contract in a catering menu taste-off conducted by the inaugural
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Six or seven times larger now in space, volume and sales, he
averages eight parties a day and has done as many as 27 events at
the same time. This barbecue is just another big party.
</P>
<P>
   And it's not the only one he will be doing that day. There's
also a luncheon for 500 at Prestonwood Baptist Church in Dallas and
a Taste of Texas dinner for 2,500, also in Big D, with a more
complex menu encompassing different foods and flavors from the
various regions of the Lone Star State. Seafood. Mexican food.
German dishes.
</P>
<P>
   That little shindig down in Austin on Tuesday?
</P>
<P>
   Why, it's just a barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
