<HEADER>
A6920 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEXAS-INAUG-LOGISTICS     01-17 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-INAUG-LOGISTICS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Security officers to keep watchful eye during inauguration
 &HT;    By Claire Osborn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When he was 4 years old, Mike Cox sat on a
granite windowsill upstairs at the state Capitol, watching the 1952
gubernatorial inauguration of Alan Shivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Times were simpler then and security was less of an issue,''
said Cox, who is now a spokesman for the Texas Department of Public
Safety.
</P>
<P>
   That's for sure. It's best not to think of planting yourself on
a windowsill at the Capitol to watch Tuesday's inauguration
festivities or dream that you can park a few steps away from the
parade route. It's all part of the plan to make sure that Texans
peacefully celebrate the swearing-in of their state leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of watchful eyes belonging to DPS troopers, Austin
police, Capitol police and Secret Service agents will be scanning
the crowds to make sure participants leave with only pleasant
memories.
</P>
<P>
   Officials declined to say how many law enforcement officials
would be present. ``We never discuss security during an
inauguration or other major events,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Officers will be ready, however, just in case. ``Everything is
thought of, every possible security arrangement is made and every
possible scenario is thought through,'' said David Wilkinson, an
Austin Secret Service agent.
</P>
<P>
   The Secret Service agents, of course, will be protecting former
President George Bush and former first lady Barbara Bush. Their
son, George W. Bush, will be inaugurated for his second consecutive
term as governor.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson said he doesn't expect security to face any new
challenges in guarding the ex-president.
</P>
<P>
   ``With former President Bush we have not had more extra threats
than usual . . . nothing has escalated,'' Wilkinson said. He
declined to say what the ``usual'' threats against Bush entailed.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested three anti-war protesters who heckled former
President Bush in November, when he read from his book about the
end of the Cold War at the Capitol during the Texas Book Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Cox, who said he has attended every Texas inauguration since the
1950s, said he couldn't remember any large protests in the past
decade. Officials would not say if they expected any protesters
during Tuesday's festivities.
</P>
<P>
   It is not illegal to protest, but complaints might be drowned
out by all the groups marching down Congress Avenue in the
inaugural parade, which starts at 2:30 p.m. at Third Street and
Congress Avenue. There are 81 entries in the parade, including more
than 20 marching bands, a ``Texas Technology'' float, the ``Chinese
Golden Dragon Club,'' several divisions of soldiers and the Kilgore
Rangerettes.
</P>
<P>
   The swearing-in ceremony, scheduled for noon on the south steps
of the Capitol, and a 1 p.m. barbecue on the Capitol's south lawn
will precede the parade.
</P>
<P>
   Parking, of course, is prohibited along Congress Avenue and near
the Capitol along 11th and Colorado streets. Plenty of streets,
however, will be open downtown, including Fourth through 10th
streets except at their intersection with Congress Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Officials had no specific advice for best viewing of the
festivities. ``Get there early and get a high place,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
