A6923 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLOBAL-CITIZENS18-COX     01-17 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-CITIZENS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nobel prize winner says mercy is key
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO
 &HT;    By Charles Walston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Belfast, Kosovo, Rwanda, and the tough inner cities of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Each place is the site of strife that may seem unique, but the
conflicts actually have much in common, a Nobel Peace Prize winner
said Sunday in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``All conflicts are about differences, whether it's your
religion, nationality or race,'' said John Hume, a 1998 Nobel
laureate for his role in forging a peace agreement in Northern
Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Hume, leader of Northern Ireland's Social Democratic and Labor
Party, is in Atlanta today to receive the 1999 Martin Luther King
Jr. Non-Violent Peace Prize as part of the King Week celebration.
Sunday, he participated in a roundtable discussion on peace and
reconciliation at the Omni hotel in downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the panel were King's widow, Coretta Scott King; retired
Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu of South Africa, the 1984 Nobel
Peace Prize recipient; and former United Nations ambassador and
Atlanta mayor Andrew Young.
</P>
<P>
   They emphasized respect for differences as a key to resolving
conflicts, and wrestled with the question of whether those who
commit atrocities during wars or civil unrest should be made to pay
for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   Hume said people who are ``sucked into'' violence are victims of
long-simmering hatreds, and he urged forgiveness as the only way to
heal old wounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've reached resolution of your conflict, the best thing
you can do is draw a line over your past,'' said Hume. ``If you
keep bringing in the past, you're re-creating the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Hume invoked King's name to support his view, saying the civil
rights leader ``wasn't looking for victory over people who had
committed injustices, he was looking for equality.''
</P>
<P>
   Tutu, who headed a commission on Truth and Reconciliation in
South Africa after the nation rejected apartheid, offered a
somewhat different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   After years of repression of the black majority and armed
struggle to overthrow their government, Tutu said it was important
for South Africans to acknowledge that horrible acts had been
committed.
</P>
<P>
   Although the commission offered amnesty to most people who
admitted their role in crimes during apartheid, Tutu said that was
not the same as pretending the acts had never occured.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get amnesty unless you accept accountability,'' said
Tutu.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to know what our past is,'' he added. ``We say, 'We
did these things.' Having done that, we can now say we close the
chapter.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel was sponsored by the Global Citizens Circle, a
nonprofit organization based in New Hampshire and founded by the
Dunfey family of hotel fame. Prior to the roundtable discussion,
Coretta Scott King was presented the Walter J. Dunfey Lifetime
Award for Peace and Reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe, as Martin believed, that the road to true
reconciliation must begin with a values transformation in our
hearts and souls,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
