<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6932 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     01-17 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORAL OF THE FALCONS' STORY: `YOU CAN TURN IT
AROUND'
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN, FBN-ARATON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS) 
(ms) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS  &UR; _  &LR; The more you think about what unfolded here
Sunday afternoon, the more incredible the feat becomes. The noisy
Metrodome was quieted, millions of Minnesota hearts were broken,
the powerful Vikings were disposed of and the Atlanta Falcons, a
team with dreary history and little tradition, were headed to the
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what is most incredible. Sunday's stunning
overtime victory goes slightly beyond football and into the heart,
literally, of the Atlanta Falcons' coach.
</P>
<P>
   In mid-December, Dan Reeves was being wheeled into the
intensive-care unit after undergoing quadruple-bypass surgery. The
operation was a success, and the burning sensation in his throat
that had driven him to the doctor in the first place was gone. Five
weeks later Reeves was here, winded, slightly drawn, watching his
Falcons complete one of the most dramatic turnabouts in the
National Football League: 3-13 two seasons ago, 7-9 in Reeves'
first season and now a Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Robinson, the Falcons' veteran safety, who is making his
second Super Bowl trip in three years, said of Reeves: ``The Lord
has shown favor to our coach, because he had a quadruple bypass,
and look at him. He's going to the Super Bowl again.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson sensed fate in Atlanta's victory. He said: ``My wife
said, `Wouldn't it be great if your coach goes to the Super Bowl
and has to play his old team, Denver?' I said that would be a nice
dream. She said, `It could happen.'''
</P>
<P>
   For all the praise placed at the feet of Bill Parcells and the
Jets, Reeves is amazing in his own right. He took three Denver
teams to the Super Bowl, then left after friction with John Elway.
In 1993 he took a reeling Giants team that had finished 6-10 a
season earlier and led them to an 11-5 record and a playoff berth,
and Reeves was voted coach of the year. He left after an impasse
with a rigid Giants hierarchy that refused to relinquish control.
</P>
<P>
   But what Reeves accomplished in Atlanta in two short seasons _
what Reeves accomplished Sunday _ was stunning. ``That was a great
game,'' said Reeves, who was once again selected coach of the year.
He clearly was drained from a game that had seen him burst with
intensity over bad calls and exhort his team in the face of
adversity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five weeks ago I'm in the operating room,'' he said. ``I just
thank the good Lord for allowing me to witness an awesome football
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is incredible when you think about it: to come from 1-7
halfway through your first year, then be in the Super Bowl your
second year. This is great for the league, when a team like the
Atlanta Falcons can be in the Super Bowl. It gives everybody in
this league hope, that regardless of what your situation is you can
turn it around.''
</P>
<P>
   Few people _ and I was not one of them _ gave Atlanta a chance
to reach the Super Bowl. Not because the Falcons aren't good, but
because, well, because they are the Falcons. Each time the Vikings
scored Sunday, especially in the fourth quarter, when they went
ahead by 27-17, you figured the Vikings' scoring machine was about
to grind Atlanta's dreams to dust.
</P>
<P>
   But the Falcons have their coach's resolve, and the Vikings, at
the moment of truth, performed as if they were walking on egg
shells: very careful, very delicate. Very different from the
bombs-away team that had scored more points during the regular
season than any team in National Football League history.
</P>
<P>
   Things happen: Gary Anderson missed his first field goal in 46
attempts for Minnesota _ his first miss since Dec. 15, 1997, with
San Francisco _ and Atlanta scored with 49 seconds left to tie at
27-27. After taking one shot at a touchdown, the Vikings opted to
let the clock run out in regulation with 37 seconds left and take
their chances in sudden death.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Falcons are perched to win the organization's first
Super Bowl. The high-scoring Vikings, whose defense was ground to
powder, is left to consider an axiom that Reeves embodies: It is
not how much you can hand out that matters, but ultimately how much
you can endure.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had their chance,'' Reeves said. ``All you can say is
that they didn't get the job done, and we took advantage of the
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   When someone asked how he felt, Reeves, who turns 55 on Tuesday,
said: ``If I can stand today, my heart's got to be in great shape.
I found out today that I can't control my emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   After Morton Andersen's 38-yard field goal ended a fantastic
battle, Coach Dennis Green of the Vikings trotted over to the
Falcons sideline to offer congratulations, saving Reeves a trip he
didn't need to take. ``That showed a lot of class,'' Reeves said.
``There's exhilaration for yourself at times like this, but you
also understand that when there's excitement for you, there's
someone else who's really dying.''
</P>
<P>
   The news conference finally broke up. Reeves shook hands with
well-wishers and was about to jump into a cart for the ride back to
Atlanta's jubilant locker room when Randall Cunningham, the
Vikings' quarterback, passed by. They hugged. I think I overheard
Reeves say, ``Sorry.'' Cunningham said, ``God's taking care of
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves shrugged. ``I don't understand it,'' he said climbing
into the cart. ``But I'll take it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
