<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6938 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT     01-17 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS :  WITH FOREIGN RESERVES DOWN, BRAZIL HAD TO FLOAT THE
REAL
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Md.) (See also BRAZIL-IMF) 
 (DW) 
 By DIANA JEAN SCHEMO  
  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ On the trading floor of the Sao Paulo
stock exchange, it led to a breathtaking buying spree. In
Washington, officials were relieved. But in Brazil, the
government's decision to stop protecting the currency that beat
hyperinflation signaled the end of a celebrated monetary plan that
promised to transform Latin America's biggest country into a modern
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The dream has been personified by President Fernando Henrique
Cardoso, a multilingual former sociology professor and finance
minister who has roamed world capitals and financial centers for
the last four years, selling his vision of a modern Brazil, intent
on reform and backed by a stable currency, the real.
</P>
<P>
   He told Brazilians, most of whom had never lived without runaway
prices, that inflation was the cruelest tax of all, striking the
poor whose salaries lost value by the hour.
</P>
<P>
   It complicated long-term investments and planning, so industry
failed to modernize, relying instead on trade barriers to keep out
cheaper imports. Brazilians rewarded Cardoso for his Real Plan's
success in beating hyperinflation by voting him president twice _ a
first for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors signed on, seeing in Brazil huge, untapped
market of 160 million for everything from telephones to
refrigerators, and potential base for exports to the rest of South
America. Direct foreign investment, $2 billion at the Real Plan's,
totaled $36 billion by last year.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Cardoso stood before his nation on television for two
and a half minutes, to say that he had done all he could to protect
the real by intervening on currency markets, but could no longer
spend foreign reserves that had dwindled to $30 billion from $75
billion in five months. The real would be free to float on world
markets.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate reaction was frenzied buying, which gave the Sao
Paulo Bovespa index its second-biggest rise in a single day: 33.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only higher increase, 36.05 percent, occurred on Feb. 4,
1991, when the second phase of former President Fernando Collor de
Mello's economic plan was announced. He left office one step ahead
of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Now, while economists and industrialists debate the size of
price increases likely to hit stores this week and the possible
nature of ``Real Plan II,'' there is little disagreement about the
cause of the current failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Real Plan foundered on the same rocks that sank a half dozen
other plans to transform Brazil over the last 15 years: the
government's inability to maneuver reform past vested interests
that enjoy benefits and breaks Brazil cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso said a year ago that his predecessor, Collor de Mello,
was drummed from office not so much for corruption as for angering
the elite by going too fast with reform. This president learned the
lesson, and navigated reform measures through Congress cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months into office, he turned his attention to winning a
constitutional amendment to permit his re-election, a complicated
process that cost political capital needed he would need later. In
doing so, he put off the further economic and political change
needed to make Brazil the modern nation of his vision.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Cardoso has been brought up short by the refusal of a
political rival, Itamar Franco, governor of the second-largest of
Brazil's 26 states, to make his state's payments to the federal
coffers. Franco's default has whipped up a wave of discontent among
opposition governors, who are now demanding that the federal
government renegotiate the terms of their debts.
</P>
<P>
   Much as Cardoso and his government may try to portray Friday's
move as a simple shifting of gears to juggle the concerns of those
who favor growth, and those who want a stable currency, there is
little sign that the president had any option but to surrender
stability he could no longer sustain.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the financial markets appeared pleased that Brazil
would no longer drain foreign reserves to bolster its currency. But
there was a sense of betrayal among those who had believed Brazil's
leaders when they repeatedly ruled out devaluation. What other
elements of his vision will Cardoso surrender?
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's the emperor has no clothes syndrome,''
said Riordan Roett, director of the Western Hemisphere Programs at
the Johns Hopkins School of Advanced International Studies.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the Cardoso administration has made important
progress.
</P>
<P>
   It pushed through measures to force government to lay off public
workers if a state's payroll exceeds 60 percent of its budget, and
has had partial success adopting laws that should trim the deficit
left by pensions that are more generous than the state can afford.
It has privatized state-owned mining, telecommunications and
utility companies, and cleaned up state-owned banks notoriously
used as political kitties by state governors.
</P>
<P>
   But the heart of the Real Plan, its raison-d'etre, was its goal
of curbing inflation that topped 2,500 percent a year before the
plan's creation in July 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Controlling the real's value in relation to the dollar, the
Brazilian government told the International Monetary Fund last
fall, was crucial to encouraging fiscal responsibility and fighting
inflation. With last week's 18 percent devaluation, the government
is likely to be urged to print money to ease a building recession
and pay off dollar-denominated debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has become a group of characters in search of a
play,'' said Alexandre Barros, a political consultant based in the
capital, Brasilia. ``They had the play of the Real Plan, based on
some premises, but those premises are not valid anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the level of government indebtedness now will be
exposed.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso's dream for Brazil grew more expensive each year that it
remained unrealized, because _ without the fig leaf of inflation _
the government has had to borrow to cover its overspending.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Real Plan began in 1994, the Brazilian government had
no deficit to speak of, Demosthenes Madureira de Pinho Neto, the
Central Bank's director for International Relations, said in
October. Government agencies would rely on inflation to cure any
shortfalls, delaying adjustments in salaries for inflation and
using the money saved to cover overspending elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Without inflation, the budget deficit has ballooned, lumbering
now toward $65 billion, or 8 percent of the gross national product.
Brazil owes some $285 billion in domestic debt, much of it dollar
denominated, and $228 billion abroad, according to Brazil's
November letter to the IMF.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
