<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6941 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      01-17 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: CAST OF CHARACTER
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Theodore Kheel, the great New York labor mediator,
dropped by the other day to tell me about the ``industry
university'' movement. Ted's in his 80s now, cheerfully vigorous as
ever, and is getting unions and corporations together to help his
foundation finance at-home ``distance learning'' for workers via
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``You did a good job of public relations for me once,'' he
recalled. ``Remember the Lawyer's Committee for Civil Rights?''
</P>
<P>
   That was about four decades ago. I was a hotshot press agent in
my late 20s. Kheel, big in the Urban League, called to ask me to
publicize a meeting of lawyers to support an outfit that was having
its troubles in the South. It would have to be a freebie, but Ted
assured me I'd make some good contacts.
</P>
<P>
   I checked with a young lawyer pal with some political
experience. He made a few calls and reported back that the guy
Kheel was pushing was suspected by the FBI of being manipulated by
a Communist backer. Did I, a true believer in the presidential
prospects of Richard Nixon, want to risk being labeled, at the
start of my career, as a commie dupe?
</P>
<P>
   I ran this past another lawyer pal in my age cohort. He said
that my fears were unworthy, and that Kheel's list of attorneys
supporting civil rights included such legendary lights as Sol Gelb.
Not only should I handle it, he advised, but to show how strongly
he felt about it, he said I should put his name down on the
letterhead and he'd come with me to the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   I told the first lawyer that is what I would do. He said to
relax and go ahead and help Kheel publicize the guy's cause; he'd
loyally vouch for me if anybody said I was a pinko.
</P>
<P>
   We had a so-so turnout at the press conference following the
organizing meeting. The civil rights leader was civil and not very
militant. Because I felt presumptively guilty at what would be a
tepid response in the New York City media, I told the civil rights
leader I would follow up with a release.
</P>
<P>
   That meant I had to write up the formation of the group with a
little bit about what the rights outfit was doing. The leader _ a
fellow my age, short, serious _ filled me in as we stood on a
corner of Fifth Avenue in the Sixties.
</P>
<P>
   In my mind's eye, I could envision the FBI's secretly
photographing a black militant and his white flack conspiring to
overthrow the government, while some redneck on the other corner
got ready to take a pop at us. My agitator ``client'' sensed my
discomfort and told me, smiling, he got that creepy feeling often.
</P>
<P>
   The astute reader will have figured out some of the characters
in today's essay.
</P>
<P>
   The first lawyer was Roy Cohn. As a legman for the Tex and Jinx
McCrary column in The New York Herald Tribune, I covered his early
success in getting narcotics convictions at the U.S. attorney's
office; it had been his first press clip and he never forgot it.
Cohn's sources had been dead right about the FBI suspicion of my
civil rights leader. Roy's friend, FBI Director J. Edgar Hoover,
later persuaded Attorney General Robert Kennedy to authorize a
wiretap, its renewal signed by his deputy, Nicholas Katzenbach,
which gave the color of law to subsequent bugging of the leader's
hotel rooms by state agencies seeking to besmear him. (Ironically,
Katzenbach was chosen by Democrats for expert testimony in the
House's impeachment inquiry.)
</P>
<P>
   My other lawyer-friend was Morton Janklow, now the literary
agent for every best-selling author from Danielle Steel to the
pope. Still a civil libertarian, he's remained my lawyer and agent
through the years _ not least because of his good, gutsy judgment
to call attention to a passionately peaceful man seeking to improve
America.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leader filling me in on the corner was, of
course, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. No pretense herein intended
that I did anything of substance in the civil rights revolution; I
did not do nearly enough. But in retrospect, I'm glad to have
ushered Jackie Robinson in to urge Nixon to call Dr. King in jail
in 1960, which the candidate mistakenly declined as
``grandstanding.'' Eight years later, after the assassination, I
reminded the candidate of that omission, as he was debating whether
to attend the King funeral; Nixon went.
</P>
<P>
   I still think of him as ``Martin''; we were the same age, all of
us. The lesson to today's ambitious young networkers: Do not fret
about associating yourself with a dedicated dissident, and one day
you may have a personal reason to celebrate a national holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
