<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MILLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVEY MILLER, 63, COMEDY WRITER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)   (ko) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harvey Miller, a film and television comedy writer who was
nominated for an Academy Award for his collaboration on ``Private
Benjamin,'' died on Jan. 8 at his home in Los Angeles. He was 63
and had a second home in East Hampton, Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was heart failure, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   While working as a social director for a hotel in the Catskills,
Miller liked to say, he became fascinated that men could attract
beautiful women simply by telling jokes. Eager to try his hand, he
pitched a three-page routine to comedian Vaughn Meader, who paid
him, to his amazement, $300. His talent was confirmed by stand-up
comedians like Dick Gregory, Shecky Green, Alan King and Sandy
Baron, who hired him to write their jokes.
</P>
<P>
   Miller moved to Hollywood in 1967 to work with Baron on the
``Hey Landlord!'' television series. With that show, he began a
longstanding relationship with the writing-producing team of Jerry
Belson and Garry Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1973, he became the writer, producer and director of ``The
Odd Couple,'' for which he received two Emmy Award nominations. He
also was nominated for an Emmy for ``Love, American Style,'' and
wrote and directed other hit series, including ``Taxi'' and ``The
Tracey Ullman Show.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, with Nancy Meyers and Charles Shyer, Miller wrote and
produced ``Private Benjamin,'' starring Goldie Hawn. The picture
was a box office success and earned the trio an Academy Award
nomination for best original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   His other film credits included writing and directing ``Getting
Away With Murder'' and ``Bad Medicine.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller is survived by a brother, Stanley Howard of Delray Beach,
Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2129EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
