<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-YOUNG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAYLE YOUNG, 63, BALLET DANCER IN LEADING ROLES AND AS PARTNER 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.H., N.Y., Ky, Calif.)   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gayle Young, a principal dancer with American Ballet Theater who
partnered such leading ballerinas as Margot Fonteyn and Cynthia
Gregory, died on Jan. 8 at Cottage Hospital in Woodsville, N.H. He
was 63 and lived in Haverhill, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was emphysema, said Darryl Dodson, his companion.
</P>
<P>
   Young was a tall, lean dancer whose quietly sympathetic manner
made him a natural lead dancer and partner in Antony Tudor's
dramatic ballets.
</P>
<P>
   He performed many of those roles during his 21-year career with
Ballet Theater, which he joined in 1960 as a corps dancer. He also
danced lead roles in ``Giselle,'' ``Swan Lake,'' ``Coppelia'' and
``The Nutcracker,'' and in ballets by Agnes de Mille.
</P>
<P>
   He played the father in a television version of ``The
Nutcracker.'' The ballerinas Young partnered also included Sallie
Wilson, Marcia Haydee, Lupe Serrano, Lynn Seymour and Maria
Tallchief.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Lexington, Ky., Young studied dance with Dorothy Prince
while a student at the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Joffrey Ballet in 1958 and performed with the New
York City Ballet in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Young was a professor of dance at the State University of New
York at Purchase for the last 16 years. He also staged ballets for
companies throughout the world, most recently Bronislava Nijinska's
production of ``Les Noces'' for the National Ballet of Holland, the
Paris Opera Ballet, the Vienna State Opera Ballet and the Berlin
Opera Ballet.
</P>
<P>
   He also restored historic homes in New England and ran an
antiques business in Haverhill. In addition to Dodson, Young is
survived by a brother, Eugene, of Tenafly, N.J. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
