</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWING-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SWINGING BRIDGE TO SPAN THE GENERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mich., Calif., Texas, Fla., N.Y.)   (jw) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Madison Avenue is learning to sing, sing, sing _ with a swing.
</P>
<P>
   Swing sounds are becoming the music of choice in an increasing
number of campaigns for mainstream advertisers. Television and
radio commercials are reverberating with the voices of such vintage
vocalists as Louis Prima, Tony Bennett, Cab Calloway, Ella
Fitzgerald and Frank Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   Marketers are also showing interest in the big bands of
musicians like Glenn Miller, Count Basie, the Dorseys, Duke
Ellington, Artie Shaw and Benny Goodman _ whose ``Sing, Sing, Sing
(With a Swing)'' may be the unofficial anthem of the trend _ as
well as in contemporary bands that reinterpret the swing music of
the 1930s and 1940s. Among them: the Brian Setzer Orchestra, Big
Bad Voodoo Daddy, Royal Crown Revue and Squirrel Nut Zippers.
</P>
<P>
   One agency, Devon Direct Marketing and Advertising in Berwyn,
Pa., even sent out holiday cards last month that resembled old
swing record albums and made swing the theme of its annual employee
party.
 &UR;  &LR; The ad boom comes after the recent revival for everything swing,
from dance clubs to hats for men to cocktails, fueled in part by
the 1996 film ``Swingers.'' That is indicative of the magpie nature
of consumer marketing, which raids popular culture for bright,
shiny objects to feather its nest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, myriad music genres have always been sources of
soundtracks to peddle products by, as evinced by campaigns set to
rock 'n' roll, Motown, folk, opera and rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that swing is popular makes it relevant,'' said
Gunnar Wilmot, executive vice president at McCann-Erickson
Worldwide Advertising, who is also managing director at
McCann-Erickson Detroit in Troy, Mich., the longtime agency for the
Buick division of the General Motors Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``And the fact it's a resurgence makes it relevant to our older
Buick buyers as well as to the young,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   For Buick, McCann-Erickson Detroit _ part of the McCann-Erickson
World Group unit of the Interpublic Group of Companies _ created a
promotion carrying the theme ``Swing Into '99.'' Commercials
presented images of couples dancing to swing music, which were
echoed in an accompanying print campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for us to get both traditional buyers and
nontraditional buyers to respond to the same message,'' Wilmot
said. ``This really bridged the gap.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of which, Gap Inc. and its in-house agency are the
kings of ad swing, a result of a widely praised television
commercial that began running in April to promote khaki pants sold
at Gap stores. The spot, titled ``Khakis Swing,'' featured a group
of young, khaki-clad dancers performing acrobatic maneuvers to the
Prima recording of ``Jump, Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   Swing is ``very energetic,'' said Michael McCadden, executive
vice president for global marketing at Gap in San Francisco. ``Its
ebullience calls you in from the next room.''
</P>
<P>
   The volume of letters, calls and e-mails hailing the commercial
was ``pretty unprecedented,'' he added, so it was brought back in
late summer for a second run.
</P>
<P>
   McCadden agreed with Wilmot about the multigenerational appeal
of swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For young people who are not that familiar with it,'' McCadden
said, ``it sounds faintly `retro' but at the same time new. And for
their parents' generation, it's bringing back the past in a new
light.''
 &UR;  &LR; That dual appeal influenced the Seagram Americas unit of the
Seagram Co &UR; .  &LR;  to sponsor ``Chivas Swings,'' a promotion for its
Chivas Regal brand of Scotch whisky centered on a mobile stage,
which brings a troupe of swing dancers dressed in period garb _
baggy pants and twirling skirts _ to perform on city streets and in
bars and lounges in markets like Dallas, Houston, Miami and New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting dressed up and going out again, dancing and
drinking the classic cocktails,'' said Bob Dubin, Scotch category
manager for Seagram Americas in New York. ``That's where Chivas
Regal fits in.''
</P>
<P>
   Setzer, leader of the Setzer Orchestra, has also been signed to
an endorsement agreement with Chivas Regal that includes
sponsorship of his coming tour and a print campaign by the New York
office of TBWA/Chiat/Day, owned by Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``One reason we decided to go with Brian and not another swing
band is the staying power he brings to the party,'' Dubin said,
referring to Setzer's previous musical incarnation with the Stray
Cats rock group. ``We did not want to be caught up in a fad.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, marketers' keenness for swing has waxed and waned
through the decades. During its first go-round, big brands
sponsored the radio shows of the big bands and swing singers. They
included Camel cigarettes for ``Benny Goodman's Swing School,''
Lever Brothers and Max Factor for ``The Frank Sinatra Show'' and
Lucky Strike cigarettes for ``Your Hit Parade.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, cigarette marketers are unlikely partners for swing
musicians. But the ties between swinging and swigging have inspired
Seagram Americas to promote a drink named after the Setzer
Orchestra's hit album, ``The Dirty Boogie,'' which features
Setzer's version of ``Jump, Jive an' Wail.''
</P>
<P>
   The cocktail, the Chivas dirty boogie, is a concoction of
Scotch, club soda and cherry juice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
