<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6952 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHILLY-POLITICS-ART-N     01-17 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLY-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PHILADELPHIA, MAYORAL FREE-FOR-ALL
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(jw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Appearing here recently as the Wizard in a stage
show of ``The Wizard of Oz,'' Mickey Rooney stopped in at City Hall
to present Mayor Edward Rendell with a special souvenir.
</P>
<P>
   As he accepted a ceremonial key to Oz, Rendell took a moment to
congratulate the 78-year-old actor for a lifetime of charitable
work. Rooney was taken aback by the mayor's remarks. ``I'm not
through yet,'' he insisted, prompting Rendell to cut him off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I keep telling people here I'm not through yet, either,''
Rendell said.
</P>
<P>
   Embarking upon the last of his eight years as Philadelphia's
mayor and foremost cheerleader, a period of major economic and
psychological turnaround for the city, Rendell, a Democrat, hardly
seems ready to relinquish his reputation for drawing a spotlight to
cities as the economic engine of a metropolitan region. (Rendell
cannot run for re-election; Philadelphia has term limits.)
</P>
<P>
   There is a budget to balance. Policing strategies under a new
commissioner are still evolving. Thousands of untrained and
illiterate people are coming off the city welfare rolls this year.
Public schools need more money. And the city still needs to attract
businesses to sustain seven years of economic development.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the five things I want to do this year,'' the mayor
said in an interview the day after Rooney's visit.
</P>
<P>
   But if Rendell's achievements reflect a job well done, they also
stand as a formidable challenge for his potential successors.
</P>
<P>
   Five Democrats and one Republican are searching for issues to
run on this year while not appearing critical of a politician so
popular and effective that investors who watch municipal bond
ratings are beginning to wonder if his successor can match his
performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to distance themselves from what has happened
over the last six or seven years,'' said John Street, who resigned
as City Council president last month, after 18 years on the
council, to run for mayor.
</P>
<P>
   For all the candidates' desires to continue the momentum built
by Rendell, the election comes at a critical time for Philadelphia,
whose population, 1.47 million, reflects the loss of nearly 90,000
people to the suburbs and beyond since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   Like other big cities with eroding populations and constant
social-service needs, Philadelphia is learning to do more with
less. It also finds itself competing with cities in the same
predicament for new industries, federal grants, even conventions.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's successful pitch for the Republican convention in
2000, beating out New York and several other cities, was considered
a major victory for a city with a strong Democratic mayor, a
Democratic majority in the City Council and more than three times
as many registered Democrats as Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia won the prize in part because of its enormous
economic development in recent years: the new hotels, restaurants
and cultural institutions that have bloomed throughout the downtown
and waterfront areas. This year alone, 13 big hotels are scheduled
to open.
</P>
<P>
   But with those projects in the works, along with others like a
planned Disney entertainment complex and renovations for
Independence Mall, Rendell's successor is not likely to have as
many glamorous ventures to promote. The next mayor is almost
certain to confront decidedly unglamorous issues like revamping the
schools, expanding downtown development into neighborhoods and
figuring how to accommodate the 60,000 city residents who will
begin to lose welfare benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ed Rendell needed to be part cheerleader,'' said Charles
Pizzi, president of the Greater Philadelphia Chamber of Commerce.
``But now the ship is under wind, and the next mayor is going to
have to go below the deck to make sure it's still sailing.''
</P>
<P>
   As Rendell's partner on countless initiatives over the years,
Street has won the mayor's endorsement, which makes him one of the
favorites in the Democratic primary in May.
</P>
<P>
   But just as Rendell conceded that ``any of the candidates would
make a good mayor,'' the Democrats, at least, are expecting a
lively battle over the next few months. As the lone Republican, Sam
Katz, an expert on municipal finance, has no opponent in his
party's primary.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, all the candidates are focusing on improving
schools and public safety and on lowering a hated wage tax. And the
ways they approach those challenges are not altogether different.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, they are largely selling experience and leadership
qualities as much as solutions.
</P>
<P>
   Street, 55, who was council president for the last six years,
presents himself as Rendell's partner in the city's leap from an
accumulated deficit of more than $200 million in 1991 to six
consecutive years of surpluses, each a city record, including the
current $169 million. Street shepherded through many major pieces
of legislation that changed the city's physical as well as fiscal
condition.
</P>
<P>
   But other Democratic candidates contend that they have skills
that are just as valuable. Happy Fernandez, 59, the only woman
running, has been a member of the council since 1991. She describes
herself as ``a valued member of the Rendell-council team''
responsible for the city's fiscal recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Weinberg, 61, is a former city solicitor and was a close
adviser to former Mayor Frank Rizzo. Now the head of a large law
firm, he has made the overhaul of the school system a priority,
proposing that the school board become more accountable to the
mayor. He also wants to give police officers more training and
educational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   As the only state legislator in the Democratic field, Dwight
Evans, 44, has also made schools a priority. He claims to have the
best leadership skills, pointing to his role in inviting the former
New York City police commissioner William Bratton to Philadelphia
to discuss crime fighting. The invitation ultimately led to the
city's hiring last year of John Timoney, Bratton's deputy, as
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The other Democrat, John White Jr., 49, has served in a variety
of public service roles. He has been a member of the state
Legislature and the City Council and most recently was executive
director of the Philadelphia Housing Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Now an executive with a real estate development firm, White has
made improvements to the school system a cornerstone of his
campaign, promoting safety, after-school programs and an education
guaranteed to prepare students for a job or college.
</P>
<P>
   Katz, 49, who was a financial adviser to Rendell in his first
term, is facing the daunting task of becoming the city's first
Republican mayor since Bernard Samuel won election in 1947.
</P>
<P>
   Katz is an enthusiastic supporter of Rendell. But he points out
that the city's population decline reflects problems that have to
be corrected, especially the crime rate and the underperformance of
children in the public school system.
</P>
<P>
   Katz lost in previous races for mayor and governor. But,
pointing to Republican mayors like Rudolph Giuliani in New York and
Richard Riordan in Los Angeles, he contends that the time is right
for a Republican in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say all the time that a Republican can't win here,'' he
said. ``That's silly, self-serving Democratic poppycock. You put
the better candidate out there, and it won't matter what the party
label is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
