<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6955 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-DENVER-JETS18-COX     01-17 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-DENVER-JETS18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Broncos earn a return
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Of the 14 Denver Broncos quickly surveyed following
their 23-10 victory over the New York Jets in the AFC Championship
Game here Sunday evening, none was even remotely cognizant of the
Branch Rickey suggestion that luck is the residue of design.
</P>
<P>
   No matter, since Denver wide receivers Ed McCaffrey and Rod
Smith demonstrated on the game's signature play that it doesn't
require familiarity with axioms that are four decades old when you
know coach Mike Shanahan's game plan well enough to overcome what
should have been a forgettable formation faux pas.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-yard grab by McCaffrey on the botched play revived the
slumbering Broncos and sparked a 20-point third-quarter explosion
that lifted them into Super Bowl XXXIII in two weeks against the
Atlanta Falcons. In a matchup certain to dredge up the lingering
acrimony between the Shanahan-John Elway tandem and Falcons coach
Dan Reeves, the Broncos can become the seventh franchise to claim
consecutive Super Bowl titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that big pass play, though, I didn't think we had a
chance,'' said Broncos tailback Terrell Davis, who rushed for 167
yards on 32 carries. ``Put a big red circle around that play,
because it turned everything around for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The play came with the Broncos trailing 10-0 and 11:45 remaining
in the third quarter. Shanahan and offensive coordinator Gary
Kubiak signaled in a deep play-action pass in a desperate attempt
to jump-start a moribund attack that had totaled just 120 yards to
that point and been overwhelmed by another clever game plan from
Jets defensive coordinator Bill Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   But Smith, who was to run a post pattern from the left side of
the set, lined up right. McCaffrey, supposed to clear ou the deep
middle of the secondary with an intermediate crossing route,
aligned to the left side of the formation. With the play-clock
close to expiration, Elway didn't have time to flip-flop the
receivers. Instead, he looked over to Smith, who nodded that he
understood he now had to run McCaffrey's route.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the snap, Elway whispered to McCaffrey to run the
post-route. The result was a little Mile High magic in what almost
certainly was Elway's last appearance at the raucous stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could have been an incredible (screw-up) had we let it
be,'' said McCaffrey. ``Instead it turned out to be just the kind
of play we needed to get us going.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Broncos had run Davis off-tackle most of the
afternoon from the same set _ two tight ends, two wideouts and just
a single back _ the Jets defense anticipated another rushing play.
When strong safety Victor Green ill-advisedly moved forward to
defend Smith on the crossing route, McCaffrey sneaked behind
everyone by five yards.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Denver got on the scoreboard on Elway's 11-yard
rocket to fullback Howard Griffith. The ice was broken and so was
the New York defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Games can turn on one play and we saw that today,'' said Jets
strongside linebacker Mo Lewis, the former University of Georgia
standout who had six tackles and a pair of passes defensed. `` They
set the trap, we took the bait and . . . the next time we looked
up, they had a 20 on the scoreboard where the zero had been.''
</P>
<P>
   The final score certainly overshadowed a brutal performance by
Elway, who completed just 13 of 34 passes for 173 yards and had
four attempts batted back in his face. At the behest of Shanahan,
the future Hall of Fame quarterback took a victory lap around the
track ringing the field. As he started his slow jog, McCaffrey
noted a crowd of fans who might delay the moment and pointed Elway
in the opposite direction. ``Good thing I didn't go the way I had
started,'' Elway agreed afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, luck and design had struck again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
