<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL: JACKSON LEAVES PROSE TO PROS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not coming soon to your local B. Dalton: ``Whoa Nellie! The
Keith Jackson Story.''
</P>
<P>
   The now-retired ABC college football play-calling legend calls
the next part of his life a ``blank page,'' but it won't be filled
with autobiographical gobbledygook.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been approached a few times, but I've chosen not to do a
book,'' he said. ``Don't think I know how to. I've seen old friends
start 'em and when they get to the end, they're staring at the
typewriter until their fingers bleed trying to get the last chapter
done.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides, in today's marketplace, it's hard to do one without
hurtin' someone, and I have no desire to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of shoot out a book, he's more apt to shoot his age on
the golf course.
</P>
<P>
   Last week at Valencia Country Club, the 70-year-old carded an
even-par 72 _ that's scratch, 66 with his handicap _ during the
SCGA Team Play Match. Jackson was on the Los Angeles Country Club
contingent. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Don't have the heart to tell Dan Reeves he's about to lose
his fourth Super Bowl, and John Elway's about to win his second in
a row. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Had the Jets won, Bryan Cox would've seen what a real dirty
bird looked like. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ IOC chief Juan Antonio Samaranch says he has no intention of
resigning because of the current Salt Lake City bribery
controversy. But for a couple of shiny trinkets, he might
reconsider. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ The IOC's next investigation will be into cable guys who have
_ egads! _ received cash payments to hook up people with better
reception to watch the Games on their TV sets. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ There's been no reason to believe organizers for the '84 Los
Angeles Summer Games were equally as bribe-crazy when it was their
turn to sell the IOC on So Cal. But because those Games were so
financially successful, it definitely raised the bar for everyone
else after that to do whatever possible to receive the IOC's
blessing. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ You're still tellin' me Atlanta was the more legit choice for
the '96 Centennial Olympics than Athens? . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Laila Ali, the 21-year-old daughter (and eighth of nine kids)
of Muhammad Ali, told writers in Las Vegas over the weekend at the
Tyson-Botha fight that she's been boxing the last four months while
attending classes at Santa Monica City College. The 5-foot-10 and
175-pound knockout might find a promoter and fight professionally.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ If my nickname's the ``White Buffalo,'' I'm keeping it quiet.
. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ If you want a resourceful hitting coach for your team, hire
someone who knows how to switch hit. The Lancaster JetHawks hired
Greg Harris, the former major-leaguer who could pitch with both
arms, as their new throwin' coach. Which makes you wonder why more
teams don't find guys like him. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Pitchers and catchers report to Dodgertown in one month. . .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ Warning to Ken Brett: If new Dodgers bullpenner Greg Cadaret
survives April, he'll be pitching for only his ninth team in his
11th major-league season. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Adrian Beltre was the Dominican Winter League's MVP, hitting
.300 (fourth-best overall) with a league-best 10 home runs and 37
RBI. Probably didn't make an error, either. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Based on who's (not) showing up for workouts at Southwest
College, the Lakers already have that winnin' way. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Both the Lakers and Clippers had MLK matinee games today at
home on the original NBA schedule. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Miami Heat coach/motivational speaker Pat Riley isn't the
least bit choked up about the prospects of having Latrell Sprewell
join his club. Riles told the Palm Beach Post: ``We all make
mistakes in our life. He is being totally branded by an incident I
think he regrets incredibly. I'm willing to give players a second
chance.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Fox's Super Bowl pregame show starts in about an hour.
</P>
</TEXT>
