<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6957 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX     01-17 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-TEX </SLUG>
 
In land of unlikely, Falcons pull off `unthunkable' (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ This is, after all, the land of the unlikely.
Around here, logic usually ends up buried in a snowbank.
</P>
<P>
   Like how can an ice hockey team fail in Minnesota only to become
an NHL success way down there in Texas?
</P>
<P>
   Or how can the state's new governor, who took the oath of office
on Saturday, be a cheesy former pro wrestler? At his inauguration
party, Jesse (The Body) Ventura once again reminded all of
Minnesota that him being elected ``shocked the world.''
</P>
<P>
   It was just 24 hours later, however, when even the flashy
Ventura was totally upstaged. Sunday at the Metrodome, the Atlanta
Falcons provided a more proper example of ``shocking the world.''
</P>
<P>
   In the state house, Minnesota will certainly survive Jesse. Hey,
it's only politics. But in the life-and-death world of the NFL
postseason, there may never be recovery for this part of the globe
after the beloved Vikings took such a mighty and unexpected fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who would have thunk it. . .who indeed would have thunk it,''
screamed Falcons safety Eugene Robinson after Atlanta's outrageous
30-27 overtime upset in the NFC Championship Game.
</P>
<P>
   As an 11-point underdog, this Falcons victory was
``unthunkable.'' But if beating the Vikings ranked as one of those
against-all-odds propositions, it still doesn't compare to the
Falcons' Super Bowl hopes back in late August. Jesse Ventura had a
better chance of being elected president than Atlanta playing in
Miami on the final Sunday in January.
</P>
<P>
   But the ``Dirty Bird'' will now migrate far south. For the first
time in franchise history the forever-futile Falcons are no more,
because they're going to the Super Bowl. And, by gosh, it's no
fluke, either, not after a 14-2 regular season, a win over the
49ers in the playoffs, and now ``this.''
</P>
<P>
   In 72 minutes of all-action-all-the-time football, what happened
here Sunday will be remembered as one of the greatest games ever
played, not to mention producing one of the most improbable
winners.
</P>
<P>
   Until overtime, both teams were constantly role-playing. The
Vikings gave repeated indications, starting in the first half, of
using their nuclear offense to blow this one open. In contrast, the
Falcons appeared to be doing a Francois Botha imitation _ hanging
around, but still knowing the knockout punch was coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had all those chances to put it away, and couldn't,'' said
Minnesota coach Dennis Green, who had his can't-win-the-big-one
reputation expanded. ``Our guys wanted to win very badly. There is
no question of 100 percent being given at all times.''
</P>
<P>
   True. This was hardcore playoff effort on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   But offensive frustration, the most unlikely of all negatives
for the Vikings, started to build in the fourth quarter, and
certainly prevailed in overtime. Which, of course, is a huge credit
to coach Dan Reeves' defensive staff and players.
</P>
<P>
   Except for one drive at the end of the fourth quarter, Vikings
running back Robert Smith was erased as a weapon. To do this was
considered highly unlikely because Atlanta couldn't consistently
use a safety to shore up the front seven. The safeties had to help
in coverage due to the duo of Randy Moss and Cris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Except super-rookie Moss also disappeared, as did his loud
mouth. After a big first half, Moss had one catch in the last 42
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, meanwhile, was held to 71 yards on 21 carries, and 44 of
them came on that one drive in the fourth quarter. It should have
been enough to salt down the win, except Gary Anderson shanked a
38-yard field-goal attempt with just over two minutes left in
regulation. That was an indication the football gods were smiling
on Atlanta. Anderson hadn't missed a kick all season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a 10-point lead, and a celebration, the Vikings held
a 7-point margin, 27-20. Chris Chandler, six times a reject of
other teams during his career, became Roger Staubach at that point.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler whipped the Falcons downfield for the tying score, and
in overtime, launched a long drive to set up Morten Andersen's
clutch 38-yard game winner.
</P>
<P>
   The Vikings' unheralded defense kept Minnesota in the game
throughout the second half, but couldn't hold off Chandler and Co.
forever.
</P>
<P>
   It was assumed the Falcons wouldn't win if running back Jamal
Anderson didn't carry them. That assumption was wrong. Anderson was
roadblocked, getting 67 yards in 23 carries. That left it up to
Chandler and his receivers to match the Vikings on the scoreboard.
And finally surpass the Falcons on the scoreboard.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves, an all-time favorite in Dallas, has done miracle
coaching work in Atlanta, and, by the way, the surgically corrected
heart apparently pumps better than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thank the Lord I was here to watch this,'' said Reeves,
who had by-pass surgery five weeks ago. Laughing, Reeves added,
``if I can handle this, I can handle anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what his Falcons are thinking for the Super
Bowl.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
