<HEADER>
A6964 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAMES-SFCHRON-GAMES &LR;      01-17 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAMES-SF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISERS GET INTO THE VIDEO GAME 
</HEADLINE>
 CHRON - GAMES   By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR; In the video game Cool Boarders 3, the characters swoosh past
Butterfinger candy bar banners, riding Burton snowboards and
wearing Levi's jeans while attempting to beat opponents' times
recorded on Swatch watches.
</P>
<P>
   In NFL GameDay 99, Minnesota Vikings wide receiver Cris Carter
can haul in a touchdown pass in front of a banner for Upper Deck
trading cards.
</P>
<P>
   And in the X-Files computer game, agents Scully and Mulder track
down aliens with the help of the latest Nokia cellular phone.
</P>
<P>
   Video and computer gamemakers aren't just trying to make the
games look realistic; in some cases, they're selling advertising
space.
</P>
<P>
   This advertising scheme _ paying for product placement _ already
has invaded movies and television shows. Now, it's becoming more
common in electronic games as advertisers try to reach teens and
twentysomethings who are spending less time watching TV and more
time playing games.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day we released Cool Boarders 3, sponsors were lining up
saying, `How do we get into Cool Boarders 4?''' said Jeff Fox, vice
president of marketing for 989 Studios, a Foster City computer
gamemaker.
</P>
<P>
   In a few cases, companies actually pay video gamemakers to
showcase their products or logos. More often, the companies enter
cross-promotional deals.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Psygnosis of Foster City released a game last year
for the Sony PlayStation and the PC titled G-Police in which
characters wear Diesel apparel. &UR;  &LR; Diesel, in turn, marketed G-Police
jackets and had in-store kiosks where people could play the game.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Brand names have been showing up in electronic games,
especially sports-related ones, for years to add a touch of
realism. In the past, however, gamemakers had to beg well-known
companies to use their logos and sometimes even pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tables are turning as companies see games as a new
advertising medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're moving away from the big-bang, big-budget media and are
trying to talk to the consumer more directly,'' said Barth Ballard,
digital marketing manager for San Francisco's Levi Strauss.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors are catching advertisers' eyes.
</P>
<P>
   First, sales of computer and video games in North America were
projected to hit $6.3 billion in 1998, a 32 percent increase from
1997, according to the marketing research firm NPD Group of Port
Washington, N.Y. More than 20 million PlayStation and Nintendo 64
game consoles alone were in U.S. homes, NPD said.
</P>
<P>
   Electronic games have become the fastest-growing segment of the
entertainment industry, according to the industry trade group
Interactive Digital Software Association.
</P>
<P>
   Second, game graphics have become so good that company logos and
products now can be faithly reproduced.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Psygnosis released a Sony PlayStation game in
November called Psybadek in which the main characters are decked
out in shoes and athletic wear from Vans Inc., a Southern
California sportswear company. The resolution is so good, you can
even make out a tiny Vans logo on a shoe.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, Nokia Corp. wanted to substitute its latest-model
cellular phone for an older one used in the X-Files game, figuring
that players would be able to read the model number. Gamemaker Fox
Interactive held up production for a few days so that it could make
the switch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Third, the demographics of video game users are appealing to
certain advertisers. Most are males ages 12 to 35 who don't spend a
lot of time with traditional media. Certain games, such as
snowboarding or jet skiing, appeal to fans of extreme sports _ just
the type of customer that companies like Burton Snowboards, Diesel
and Nokia are trying to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike product placements in movies, which usually are seen just
once, placements in video games can provide more impressions
because they are played over and over, said David Cole, president
of DFC Intelligence, a computer-game industry magazine in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, even multiple impressions on a video game can't match
the exposure on a network television show like ``Seinfeld,'' which
was famous for product placements. About 108 million viewers
watched the last episode of ``Seinfeld,'' while a video game is
considered a big hit if it sells about 200,000 units.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; But the potential is there, especially with advertisers
changing how they allocate their marketing dollars.
</P>
<P>
   `'Product placement used to be a tiny part of the mix, but now
it is a very big part of the mix, and it's only natural for it to
go forward into video games,'' said Dabney Day, president of
Catalyst Corp. of Burbank, a marketing firm that specializes in
product placement.
</P>
<P>
   A report by the U.S. Chamber of Commerce said companies like
Catalyst charge clients $500 to $20,000 a year for help in getting
product placements.
</P>
<P>
   Cole and other game industry experts don't expect product
placement to become a primary source of income for game companies
but said it eventually may help offset production costs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Fox of 989 Studios declined to say how much his company has
received for product placements, but an executive for a competing
gamemaker who did not want to be identified said he has been told
by advertisers that 989 Studios has been seeking fees between
$5,000 to $50,000 per product placement.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are drawbacks to charging for product placement in
games.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Roach, an executive vice president with Accolade Inc. of
San Jose, said doing so could tempt gamemakers to cross the line
between realism and the crass commercialism that would be a turn
off to players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Product placement is not an end to itself,'' &UR;  &LR; Roach said.
``You put (products) in there to extend the fantasy, so people will
like your product and buy more. The moment you take your eye off
that and get greedy, it can backfire.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, ads don't make sense in certain games, especially science
fiction and fantasy titles. Players would recoil if they saw Link,
the hero in Nintendo's best selling Legend of Zelda game series,
stop to sip a Coke.
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, a company like Levi's would be loathe to have
its products show up in a violent or risque game.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Day expects more real-world products to show up in the
virtual world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We live in a world of brands,'' Day said. ``We don't live in a
world of generics. I'm not a believer in gratuitous product
placement. But if a kid is bouncing a basketball in a video game,
to us it makes sense that it should be a Spalding basketball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
