<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6966 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON-MIC     01-17 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - MICROSOFT  
 Should Gates Take The Stand?  &HT;     By Benny Evangelista 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates is a brilliant programmer. Now he's faced with the
task of reprogramming his own image, which has been tarnished by
his appearance so far in the antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Gates' videotaped deposition was widely seen as hurting his
reputation and Microsoft's defense. He came off as evasive,
forgetful and defiant.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Now that it's Microsoft's turn to present its case, there's
speculation that the software giant might call Gates as a late
witness to undo the damage he's done.
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea, say legal and public relations experts. That would
give government attorneys even more ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd be dead meat,'' said Rich Gray, an intellectual property
and antitrust attorney with Bergeson, Eliopoulos, Grady &AMP; Gray in
San Jose. ``If Microsoft tries to put him on the stand, they're
just painting a bull's-eye on his heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Others say Gates would be better off doing another Barbara
Walters interview (he gave one a year ago, before the trial
started) or a ``60 Minutes'' appearance to repair a public image
that has changed from whiz-kid tycoon to scheming monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being one of the great entrepreneurs of the
century, he's going to be (seen as) one of the great
entrepreneurial robber barons of the late 20th century,'' said San
Francisco public relations executive Sam Singer.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Justice and 19 states sued Microsoft in
May, claiming that the Redmond, Wash., firm was using its monopoly
on computer operating software to crush Internet software rivals
like Netscape Communications Corp. Microsoft has denied the
charges, and last week began its defense in a trial that started
October 19 in Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Gates is not on the list of 12 witnesses Microsoft plans to
call, but could come in as one of the two rebuttal witnesses
allowed each side.
</P>
<P>
   The government has played videotaped excerpts of 20 hours of
deposition taken from Gates this summer in Redmond. The tapes
showed Gates claiming that he did not remember writing e-mail the
government said proved Microsoft was out to harm competitors like
Netscape and Sun Microsystems.
</P>
<P>
   At points, Gates stubbornly debated the meaning of common words
like ``we'' and ``concerned.'' His testimony seemed to fly in the
face of his image as one of the sharpest business tycoons the world
has ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft has lost significant credibility because of Gates'
videotaped deposition,'' said Hillard Sterling, an antitrust
attorney with the Chicago law firm Gordon &AMP; Glickson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gates appeared to be over-prepared and over-coached,''
Sterling said. ``Gates, if he testifies (in person), would be
steamrolled by his own deposition. The more Gates says now, the
deeper his foot will slip into his mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Gray, however, had a slightly different view. He said Gates
showed the type of restraint and nervousness that's typical of a
legal deposition, similar to how President Clinton behaved in his
own deposition.
</P>
<P>
   The betting in legal circles is that Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson will find that Microsoft did violate some antitrust laws.
The only questions are whether Jackson's rulings will survive the
appeals process in higher courts, and what kind of sanctions will
be imposed on Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what happens in the court of law, public relations
experts say Gates should start some spin control now to sway the
court of public opinion. One way would be to try to project an
image of sincerity and contriteness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't need to wholly admit everything,'' said Singer,
president of Kamer Singer &AMP; Associates, which has taken on some
tough public relations issues like labor strikes and the 49ers
stadium campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Bill Gates could do outside of this trial is have
Microsoft adopt and promote standards of practice, codes of conduct
on how they treat competitors, how they conduct business,'' Singer
said. ``Even if people held strong feelings against Bill Gates and
Microsoft, it would bring them a great deal of credibility right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Historically, tycoons like Charles Crocker, Andrew Carnegie and
John D. Rockefeller were reviled when they were accused of
monopolistic practices. But the public can be won back if they are
seen as sincere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like Bill Clinton reluctantly admitted (indiscretions),
Bill Gates and Microsoft need to find some way to clarify to the
public that they made some errors in their business practices,''
Singer said.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of MICROSOF (58764 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``The president still has a great deal of believability when he
talks to the public,'' Singer said. But, he added, ``Bill Gates is
no Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   However, another public relations expert believes that win or
lose, Microsoft and Gates will emerge largely unscathed because the
public usually pays little attention to the intricacies of
antitrust cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average Joe or Mary Consumer is not going to understand
it,'' said David S. Margulies, president of Margulies
Communications Group of Dallas. The firm has specialized in
devising public relations strategies for companies hit with serious
issues like antitrust violations, pollution problems and sexual
harassment lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People see him as a hard-nosed businessman,'' Margulies said
of Gates.
</P>
<P>
   Gates, if well coached and prepared, could take the stand and be
a winning witness, Margulies said. But Gates doesn't have to
testify, ``and my strategy is (don't) do anything that will screw
up the case,'' Margulies said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If, after this is over, he wants to get his point out, he can
write another book, he can go on the `Today' show. He's got plenty
of money. He has lots of ways to control his image if it really
becomes a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of MICROSOF (58764 ) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
