<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0207 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6967 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-TYSON-ARCH-FOLO18     01-17 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-ARCH-FOLO18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tyson's tricks reflect lapse in skills
 &HT;    By Tom Archdecon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ The answer tells you a lot about Mike Tyson and who
he has become.
</P>
<P>
   It was some 90 minutes _ and a few stitches _ after he'd come
from far behind on the judges' scorecards to knock out Francois
Botha with one, short, jack-hammer right hand in the fifth round of
a fight marred by extra-curricular thuggery and now Tyson was being
asked to respond to his opponent's assertion:
</P>
<P>
   ``Botha said you were trying to break his arm.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson, surprisingly, was candid:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's fans, his handlers and much of the press gathered at the
MGM Grand Garden, all laughed, though, in reality, the joke is on
Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   So much for that invincible warrior of old. Tyson is starting to
look more and more like those cartoonish World Wrestling Federation
characters with whom he aligned himself while in exile last year.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Tyson was in a boxing ring _ the June, 1997 bout
now called the Bite of the Century _ he ended up banned by the
Nevada State Athletic Commission for gnawing on both of Evander
Holyfield's ears.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, until Tyson landed that vintage KO punch, the
only time he had Botha hurt was when he pinioned the South
African's left forearm at the end of round one and, using his own
forearm for leverage, literally tried to break the bone.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout that first round, Tyson had been out of sync. The
fight plan he'd prepared with new trainer Tommy Brooks _ movement,
throw combinations _ was out the window 20 seconds after the
opening bell. From then on, Tyson, who looked trim, but weighed a
career-high 223 pounds, was standing flat-footed, trying to land
one punch and missing badly.
</P>
<P>
   The 233-pound Botha, it seemed, had traded that shaggy white
buffalo skin he wears as a robe _ to go with the ``White Buffalo''
nickname _ for a cloak of confidence. From the outset, he not only
showed he wasn't intimidated by Tyson, but that he could push the
smaller heavyweight around.
</P>
<P>
   And so just before the bell, Tyson latched onto Botha's arm
during a clinch. Botha bellowed in pain and, as the bell sounded
and Tyson continued to twist while referee Richard Steele pushed
in, Botha crashed a right hand into Tyson's head.
</P>
<P>
   More punches were thrown, the fighters refused to break and soon
it looked as if there would be ring anarchy reminiscent of the Bite
Fight. Handlers from both sides jumped into the ring, as did
security guards. Instantly, Las Vegas police crawled up on all
sides of the ring apron and provided a uniformed barrier between
the crowd and the chaos behind them. No one wanted a repeat of the
post-fight riot after the June 1997 bout.
</P>
<P>
   Once both fighters were shoved to their corner stools, Marc
Ratner, executive director of the NSAC, met with Steele. ``It was
very frightening,'' Ratner said. ``All the elements were there. It
was definitely scary.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele went to each corner and issued a warning: ``You can't win
on a foul.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson didn't listen. In the second round, Tyson again worked on
Botha's arm and then tried to follow through on a punch with an
elbow to the throat. Steele deducted a point from Tyson on all
scorecards for what he called ``unnecessary roughness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was doing so much,'' Steele said. ``I had to get him calmed
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The old Tyson never needed all the illegal tactics and tricks.
He just walked in and knocked guys out. But Saturday, whether it
was the rust of a 19-month layoff, the lack of confidence that
first surfaced against Holyfield, or the growing proof that his
skills are eroding dramatically, Tyson feels he needs something
more than he's got in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, he may be right.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's fight was to be his first step at redemption, but for
the first 4 1/2 rounds it was more of a back-pedal from the boxer
he once was. After four rounds, Dalby Shirley and Dave Moretti had
Botha winning, 40-35. Bill Graham had it 39-36, as did the Dayton
Daily News scorecard.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 12,512 was stunned by what it was seeing.
</P>
<P>
   In a collision of heads, Botha had opened a small cut above
Tyson's right eye. Then in the third round - with Tyson often
looking pleadingly at Steele as if the ref could get him out of
this mess _ Botha backed the former two-time heavyweight champ to
the ropes and in comical Three Stooges fashion, boxed both of
Tyson's ears at once.
</P>
<P>
   By the fourth round, Botha was dropping his hands, daring Tyson
to hit him and once even tried something of a fancy shuffle. ``I
think he thought he was the white Muhammad Ali,'' Tyson joked. ``I
wasn't worried though. I knew it was just a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Botha started round five talking incessantly to Tyson, who had
been jawing back most of the night. ``I don't want to say what we
said all fight, it was really some bad words,'' Botha said. ``I was
trying to psyche him out. I told him, 'All America is watching you.
You better start boxing because you're losing.'''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson took the advice and soon capitalized on a Botha confidence
that led to carelessness. Fighting with his hands down _ ``I got
careless and started fooling around,'' _ Botha tried to land a slow
wide right that Tyson countered with a short textbook right hand
flush to Botha's nose.
</P>
<P>
   Botha melted instantly, landing butt first on the canvas. He
rolled over and twice tried unsuccessfully to push himself upright.
Counted out by Steele at 2:59 of the fifth, Botha finally got to
his feet only to stumble sideways and fall halfway through the
ropes.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson rushed across the ring and helped Steele pull Botha to
safety. It was one of three good things Tyson can take from this
bout. The most important, as was noted by new manager Shelly
Finkel, was that he didn't ``totally lose his composure'' after the
first shaky moments. And then there was the reaffirmation that a
puncher _ as Tyson has shown in 46 of 49 fights _ always has a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if Tyson can just keep from tripping over his psyche.
Coming out of the ring, he ranted to pay-per-view microphones that
he needed respect. That everybody was writing trashy articles and
trying to assassinate his character.
</P>
<P>
   Later, though, he was more subdued: ``I feel a little crappy. I
didn't prove anything and I wanted to shine tonight. I tried to do
well, but I've got a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's handlers know this is going to be a rebuilding process _
though, it's doubtful the 32-year-old heavyweight ever will become
the dominator he once was. The talk now is of a fight in April with
Axel Schulz, Lou Savarese or Vaughn Bean. First, though, comes a
sentencing in a Maryland court after his no-contest plea on an
assault of two motorists who rammed his wife's car. That could have
bearing on a Feb. 5 parole hearing and the worst case scenario for
Tyson would be a return to prison.
</P>
<P>
   Botha, meanwhile, praised Tyson's punching power and wished him
luck in his climb back toward the title. ``I think Mike Tyson will
go and get what he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   It was meant as a compliment, but that might not be the case.
</P>
<P>
   What's coming _ as much in the ring, as out _ could be bad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
