<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRTOUCH-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - AIRTOUCH  
 AirTouch Still After Deal With Bell Atlantic  &HT;     By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Despite its agreement on Friday to sell out to Britain's Vodafone
Group PLC, AirTouch Communications Inc. still wants to negotiate a
deal with Bell Atlantic Corp. to create a national wireless network
in the United States, AirTouch chief executive Sam Ginn told The
Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Pairing with Vodafone, which outbid Bell Atlantic in a
high-stakes battle for control of San Francisco's AirTouch, is
important for creating a global company, Ginn said, but the merger
doesn't solve a crucial problem in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to solve the footprint problem in the U.S. to stay
competitive,'' Ginn said. ``What I would hope to do is negotiate an
agreement with Bell Atlantic because our assets fit so naturally
together. We fit like hand-in-glove.''
</P>
<P>
   Ginn said the two companies had ``preliminary conversations''
about a joint venture in the United States, but those talks ended
when Vodafone won the battle for AirTouch. He said he plans to
resume those conversations with Bell Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch operates mainly in the West. In the Bay Area, it sells
cellular phone service through Cellular One, a joint venture with &LR; 
 &LR; AT&AMP;T, and paging service under its own name. Bell Atlantic's
territory is mainly in the East. Both companies need a nationwide
network or ``footprint'' so they can eliminate `'roaming''
agreements they must sign with other companies so their customers
can use their cell phones in every state.
</P>
<P>
   The costs of those agreements are passed along to customers, who
must pay roaming fees when they use their phones outside their home
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors with national networks, like AT&AMP;T Corp. and Sprint
PCS, have eliminated those fees and are luring away customers with
lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   While Vodafone is the No.1 carrier in the United Kingdom and has
9.1 million customers overseas, it does not have a presence in the
United States. AirTouch has more than 11 million customers in 25
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do (a national network) with Bell Atlantic, we've
got to do it some other way,'' Ginn said.
</P>
<P>
   If a strong domestic network is so important to AirTouch, some
may wonder why the company accepted an offer from Vodafone, rather
than Bell Atlantic. The answer, Ginn said, came down to price and
strategy. Bell Atlantic was reportedly offering between $73 and $80
a share, as opposed to Vodafone's $97 per share stock-and-cash
offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, the board looked at the price and $97 per share
was a pretty good offer,'' Ginn said. ``The board had two excellent
alternatives. One was pointed at solving a footprint problem in the
U.S. and the other opportunity allowed us to create the premier
wireless company in the world. We were looking strategically at how
we positioned our direction.''
</P>
<P>
   But AirTouch's shunning of Bell Atlantic, which pulled out of
the bidding after realizing it would not win, may have had an
unwanted effect.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the New York phone company filed a lawsuit to void a
noncompete clause in its joint venture agreement with AirTouch. The
two companies jointly own PrimeCo Personal Communications LP, which
offers digital wireless service in 30 major cities, and the
agreement prohibits the companies from competing in the same
territory.
</P>
<P>
   Bell Atlantic is in the process of acquiring GTE Corp., which
competes with AirTouch's Cellular One in San Francisco. If Bell
Atlantic had acquired AirTouch, the noncompete clause would have
been irrelevant because Bell Atlantic would have owned all of
PrimeCo. Now that AirTouch is merging with Vodafone, Bell Atlantic
wants to be able to keep competing in San Francisco and other GTE
cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ginn, who said he had not seen the lawsuit, said he hopes to
resolve the problem without going to court.
</P>
<P>
   If Vodafone AirTouch PLC, as the new company will be known, does
work out an agreement with Bell Atlantic, it could be good for Bay
Area wireless customers, who pay some of the highest cell phone
rates in the nation, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   That's because the two companies could eliminate roaming fees
and price their service to stay competitive with other national
carriers.
</P>
<P>
   Even if a deal with Bell Atlantic doesn't happen, Ginn said, the
agreement with Vodafone will be good for customers and employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``What customers ought to know is that we are going to keep our
competitors in our gun sights and offer prices that are competitive
with anybody in the nation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   AirTouch employees, including Ginn, stand to make a substantial
sum off the deal because almost every one of them has stock
options, said AirTouch spokesman Jonathan Marshall.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Ginn, who built AirTouch into the world's largest
wireless carrier after spinning it off from Pacific Bell, said he's
``sad in a way'' that AirTouch has been sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am immensely proud of what we've been able to achieve,''
said Ginn, who will become chairman of the joint company.
Vodafone's chief executive Chris Gent will run the combined
company. Ginn said it was the right time to sell AirTouch because
of consolidation in the industry and other trends.
</P>
</TEXT>
