A6970 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-AFC-MOORE18-COX     01-17 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-MOORE18-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stay tuned for behind-the-scenes hostility between Dan, John and
Mike
 &HT;    By Terence Moore
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Uh' oh. We're already prophetic. Let's just say that
the soap opera we'll see over the next two weeks involving Dan
Reeves, John Elway and Mike Shanahan began just moments after
Sunday's final gun shot through the chilly air inside Mile High
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   That's right. To the surprise of absolutely nobody who knows the
difference between Vinny Testaverde and John Elway, the most
persistent questions in the home locker room after the Denver
Broncos' 23-10 snoozer over the New York Jets weren't about the
Broncos sitting four quarters away from repeating as world
champions.
</P>
<P>
   They also weren't about the golden boy of the Rockies hinting at
playing his last game around here after 16 seasons. Oh, and there
was that matter of Terrell Davis chewing through the Jets' normally
staunch defense for 167 yards rushing and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Well, forget all of that. You can forget about everything
between now and the end of the month, except what we recently told
you would happen with a Super Bowl between the Atlanta Falcons and
the Broncos: Dan, John and Mike. Dan, John and Mike. Dan, John and
Mike.
</P>
<P>
   We're not talking about Peter, Paul and Mary here. Try something
like Bill, Linda and Monica.
</P>
<P>
   After Reeves spent his dozen years with the Broncos through the
1992 season, Elway described working as Reeves' quarterback as
``hell.'' As for Shanahan, the Broncos coach, all Reeves did to his
former Broncos assistant of seven years was fire him for
insubordination. That's because Reeves thought Shanahan and Elway
were working in collusion behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, it took two quarters, four minutes and a bunch of
ugliness by the Broncos and the Jets before Elway realized he was
so close to battling his arch-enemy again. Elway pushed the Broncos
past the Falcons in the Georgia Dome last season, but that was
before the Falcons became the Dirty Birds, and it definitely wasn't
the Super Bowl. Even then, Elway sprinted away in the aftermath to
keep from shaking Reeves' hand.
</P>
<P>
   So Elway got busy against the Jets. With Reeves already grabbing
that thriller in Minnesota to give the Falcons the NFC
Championship, Elway finally became Elway before a normally spirited
crowd that was as lifeless as the defending world champions.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Elway went from the goat who was 5 for 18 on his
previous throws to the hero who was rallying the Broncos from a
10-0 deficit. In the end, Elway did a victory lap around the
stadium. He thanked the fans. He praised the organization. This was
after Shanahan did the same, but neither could escape the only
questions that mattered to the masses.
</P>
<P>
   So, Mike, do you think Dan is responsible for the Asian
financial crisis, global warming or the Clinton trials in Congress?
</P>
<P>
   ``At times, we were best friends, '' Shanahan said. Then he
added, trying to keep his smile from fading, ``He's done a great
job with that football team, and we look forward to playing them in
Miami. It's really going to be a great game, and we're just happy
to be there.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway said of Reeves, ``He's done a great job with the Falcons,
and you have to give him credit.''
</P>
<P>
   Uh-huh. Stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
