<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0211 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS &LR;      01-17 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMPEACH-TRIAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS CONFIDENT ON WITNESSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House managers who are prosecuting the impeachment
case against President Clinton expressed hope Sunday that they had
changed enough minds in the Senate to allow witnesses to be called,
a move that Democrats said might stretch the trial into June.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, two Republicans said that it might be possible for
the Senate to vote to convict the president but then vote not to
remove him from office. But neither said he favored such an
outcome, and many constitutional scholars have said a convicted
president would be removed automatically.
</P>
<P>
   After three days of opening arguments in the Senate trial,
several House managers said on television talk shows that they
hoped their statements had persuaded the necessary 51 Republicans
to stick together to vote for witnesses, including Monica S.
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've changed some minds in regard to witnesses and
that was a big part of the case,'' Representative Asa Hutchinson,
an Arkansas Republican manager, said on ABC's ``This Week.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hutchinson said that senators won't make a final
determination on witnesses until after the White House presents its
defense this week, he expressed confidence that there would be
enough votes in favor. ``I think we made a strong case . . . for
witnesses,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, as they have since the trial began, said Sunday that
there is no need to call witnesses. But Senator Christopher J.
Dodd, a Connecticut Democrat, said that if Republicans push for it,
the White House would be compelled to respond with a call for
witnesses who could testify on the president's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not an exaggeration if you go that route _ and you can
make a case for it _ we could be talking May or June before you
finish this trial,'' Dodd said on NBC's ``Meet The Press.'' ``And I
think the Senate ought to think seriously before it goes that
length of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Lindsey Graham, a South Carolina Republican,
speculated on CBS's ``Face The Nation'' about whether it would be
possible for the Senate to convict Clinton but not vote to remove
him. Many constitutional scholars have said the president would
automatically be removed upon conviction, but some have suggested
that the Constitution is vague enough to leave open the option of
letting the president remain in office.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some historical precedent they could do that,''
Graham said. But he added that since 1936, ``the practice . . . has
been that a finding of guilty automatically results in removal. I
guess there's two ways you can do this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Graham, however, has been among the most forceful in arguing for
the president's removal.
</P>
<P>
   Another guest on the CBS program, Senator Pete V. Domenici, a
New Mexico Republican, agreed that it might be possible to convict
but not remove the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``That could happen,'' Domenici said. ``I had not heard of it
until recently, and I hear nobody talking about it. But I assume,
in a sense, the United States Senate could do what it wanted in
that regard.''
</P>
<P>
   The appearance by the House managers and senators on the
television shows highlighted the split-screen nature of the
historic proceedings. On Thursday, Friday, and Saturday, the House
managers presented solemn arguments for conviction, while the
senators were required to sit silently and listen.
</P>
<P>
   But as both groups took to the airwaves, the partisan split was
evident, as the managers insisted they had made the case for
conviction and some Democrats argued the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   If the television questioning is an indication, Democrats are
being pressed to explain why some of them voted in 1989 to convict
US District Judge Walter L. Nixon Jr. on perjury charges in a
Senate impeachment trial, but may not be willing to make the same
vote on similar charges against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Senator John F. Kerry of Massachusetts did not
answer directly when ``Meet The Press'' moderator Tim Russert asked
whether he would vote to convict Clinton on the charges against him
if the president were a federal judge. The following exchange
between Russert and Kerry illustrated how the Nixon case has
affected the Clinton trial:
</P>
<P>
   Russert: ``If Bill Clinton was a federal judge, would you vote
to remove him from the bench based on what you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry: ``Tim, I mean, those are the kinds of hypothetical
questions that just sort of get you into, I think, a bad place. And
I'm not trying to avoid you. Let me just try to draw the
distinction here. He's not a federal judge, he's president of the
United States, and we're dealing with a different set of facts. . .
. It is not a question of having a lower standard. The standard
should be high for both. It is a question of having a different
standard.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry explained that there is a different standard for Clinton
because judges ``serve on good behavior'' in a lifetime term.
Democrats frequently have pointed out that presidents are elected
by the people and serve four-year terms.
</P>
<P>
   Another guest on the program, Senator James M. Inhofe,
Republican of Oklahoma, disagreed, saying that he has never heard
any justification for ``having a lower standard for the president
of the United States than a federal judge. I mean, after all, the
president appoints the federal judges,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
