<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6974 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ONTECH-SFCHRON-ONTECH     01-17 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONTECH-SF </SLUG>
 CHRON - ON TECH  
 The Trials and Tribulations of PC Installations  &HT;     By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1998 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
In the past few months, I've heard Bill Gates and Craig Barrett _
the chief executives of computer giants Microsoft and Intel _ give
speeches exhorting the industry to make personal computers easier
to use.
</P>
<P>
   In the past few weeks, as I helped my mother-in-law buy and set
up a new PC, I learned that Gates and Barrett still have some work
to do.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing about the endeavor was easy. Not the purchase, not the
setup, not even filling out the rebate forms.
</P>
<P>
   Although selling to my mother-in-law, a self-described computer
illiterate, is a challenge, she is precisely the type of person the
industry needs to win over if it is to continue to grow.
</P>
<P>
   My in-laws are great, but technologically, they're stuck in a
time warp.
</P>
<P>
   I heard a computer consultant tell my brother-in-law last week
that his company now had e-mail and that a Web page would be up and
running soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great,'' my brother-in-law replied. ``What's the
difference between e-mail and a Web page?''
</P>
<P>
   Suffice it to say, his parents are not too far ahead of him. In
fact, the most active e-mailer in the family is grandma, who just
traded up to an iMac.
</P>
<P>
   Intel CEO Barrett knows the problem. A month after he turned 59,
he told an industry gathering in Palm Springs, ``The main reason
people my age don't want to use a computer is they're afraid
they'll break them.''
</P>
<P>
   That's my mother-in-law. She's 62 and has the time and the money
to own a computer but fears crashes and error messages.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of people, she just wants it to work.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 years, she's used a PC with a 286 MHz processor.
It ran DOS, had no graphics and used near-obsolete 51/4-inch floppy
disks. But it worked. She was happy.
</P>
<P>
   She recognized, though, that her computer at home should be
compatible with the Windows 95 machines at her office, and she also
wanted to tiptoe into e-mail and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   I told her she probably didn't need to spend more than $1,000
for a computer, and I said she should ask for a 56K modem, Windows
98 and Microsoft Word _ basic stuff.
</P>
<P>
   She asked a family friend, a retiree who spends hours on end
chatting away online in his basement.
</P>
<P>
   He sent her to a small firm in the Portland suburbs that
custom-builds computers.
</P>
<P>
   She went to that store. She might as well have gone to Ulan
Bator, Mongolia, for all she understood. She faxed me the specs.
</P>
<P>
   It was virtual gibberish: gigabyte 100 MHz P2/ATX motherboard,
64 MB 100 MHz SD-Ram Dimm memory, ATI 8 MB 3D AGP Xpert'98 video
card, and on and on. Is a normal person supposed to understand
this? In deciphering the list, I saw it was actually a heck of a
deal: a 350 MHz chip from Advanced Micro Devices, a 17-inch
monitor, 64 megabytes of RAM and a 4.3 gigabyte hard drive _ even a
separate 51/4-inch floppy drive, so she could transfer her old
files _ all for under $1,200.
</P>
<P>
   So I said, ``Buy it.'' So she bought it.
</P>
<P>
   When I got to her house, I took everything out of the boxes and
tried to hook it up. It seemed to go fine, except they had
forgotten to add the 51/4-inch drive, and there was no place to
plug in the keyboard.
</P>
<P>
   We called. They said, ``Oops.''
</P>
<P>
   We took it back to the store. They installed the drive, gave us
a quick tutorial and shoved us out the door.
</P>
<P>
   We took it home, hooked it up and _ because I had already
ordered her an Internet account _ tried to get online. It started
to dial, and the screen froze.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, every time we tried to connect, even to Microsoft to
register the software, the screen froze and the dialing stopped.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the system did not have Microsoft Word _ the only
reason she really needed a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, because it was a custom-built computer, it came with no
manuals. No support.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, I left town for a week of skiing and my
mother-in-law returned the computer. When I returned, I had one
afternoon to help coordinate the purchase of a new machine for her.
</P>
<P>
   A sales clerk at Office Depot was very helpful. He taught us
some vagaries of the computer we were eyeing: It comes with
Microsoft Works. If you wanted to upgrade to Microsoft Office 97
(even though it's now 1999), that's $200. If all you want is
Microsoft Word, that's also $200, so you might as well upgrade
because Word is part of Office. (Ah, Microsoft.)
</P>
<P>
   We bought a Hewlett-Packard 4450, with an HP monitor (because
that way you get a rebate) and an HP printer (because then you get
an even bigger rebate). In picking a printer, we kept in mind that
my mother-in-law didn't care about color cartridges or dots per
inch but that she just wanted no paper jams.
</P>
<P>
   Back home, my wife and her father were able to un-box it and
plug it all in. Things seemed to be getting easier. Yellow cords
went into yellow plugs. HP had included a manual and a big colored
map.
</P>
<P>
   (I couldn't be there because, in my burgeoning career as a
computer consultant, I was at grandma's, trying to sift through all
the little drawings on America Online.)
</P>
<P>
   I stayed up late, loading Office 97 and getting the Internet
service provider configured.
</P>
<P>
   My wife sought to assemble the rebate material, which turned out
to be a scavenger hunt for receipts, serial numbers and labels
carved off of the giant cardboard boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, just before I headed to the airport, I showed
my mother-in-law the machine. ``Let's send an e-mail,'' she said
excitedly.
</P>
<P>
   The machine dialed in. She wrote her e-mail. She hit send. The
program quit, the modem disconnected, the screen froze, and I
taught her the magic of control-alt-delete.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's it,'' she said. ``I'm just going to use it as a word
processor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
