<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-GUNSALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L . A. WEIGHS GUN SALES LIMIT AND A SUIT AGAINST MANUFACTURERS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ko) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The City Council is considering legislation to
restrict handgun purchases, while officials debate whether to join
a growing movement among cities to sue gun makers for contributing
to handgun violence.
</P>
<P>
   The city ordinance would prohibit individuals from buying more
than one handgun a month in Los Angeles, which has 87 registered
gun dealers and firearms stores.
</P>
<P>
   The intent is to reduce the flow of handguns to criminals
through ``straw purchasers'' who legally buy several weapons at one
time and then resell them on the street. Supporters of the measure
say Los Angeles had 27,000 incidents of gun violence in 1996. The
incidents cost the city an estimated $35 million in police and
firefighter time.
</P>
<P>
   A City Council committee approved the proposed ordinance on
Wednesday and voted to send it on to the full council, which has
approved several gun control measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible to imagine somebody who, seeking
self-protection, would need more than a gun a month,'' said Mike
Feuer, the councilman who drafted the measure. ``This is a
common-sense measure that will have a meaningful impact on public
safety in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation is based on new research suggesting a link
between the legitimate retail gun market and the secondary black
markets where criminals obtain guns, contrary to the traditionally
held belief that most guns used in crimes are stolen.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms has reported
that as many as half of the guns it has traced from crimes were
sold by a dealer in the previous three years.
</P>
<P>
   A study conducted for the Los Angeles Police Department found
that more than half the handguns recovered by the police had been
sold by legitimate retailers within the previous two years and that
only 10 percent to 15 percent of the recovered guns had been
stolen.
</P>
<P>
   City officials are also considering a variety of legal theories
for potential suits against gun manufacturers. Strategies include a
product liability claim, like the one being pursued by New Orleans,
and a public nuisance claim, like the one being pursued by Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   California's new governor, Gray Davis, and the new attorney
general, Bill Lockyer, have also voiced more support for gun
control measures than their predecessors, and Lockyer has agreed to
help Los Angeles enforce the one-gun-per-month limit by giving
dealers in the city access to a state data base that would show
whether a customer had bought a gun anywhere in the state in the
previous 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The measure is opposed by gun-rights advocates as an unfair
restriction on the rights of gun buyers who may want to buy several
guns for sport or collecting. They say federal law already protects
against gunrunning through multiple purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us believe we have a right to keep and bear arms, and
it's an undue burden on our Second Amendment right,'' said Alan
Gottlieb, the founder of the Second Amendment Foundation, which
successfully sued the city of San Francisco to overturn a ban on
possession of handguns.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles legislation would not prevent individuals from
buying a whole cache of handguns in another California city without
a limit.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with local jurisdictions' limits on sales, said
Franklin Zimring, a law professor at the University of California,
Berkeley, is that the measures can have no comprehensive effect.
``All you do is export the gun trade,'' Zimring said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
