<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-COLTEN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRINDA HOLDS OFF KUKAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   THOUSAND OAKS, Calif. _ Jean-Noel Grinda takes pride in his
French heritage. When it comes to tennis, that means the red clay
of Roland Garros, or any French red clay.
</P>
<P>
   His love of hardcourts isn't as high on his list, even though
Grinda possesses a powerful serve and forehand that helps on the
fast surface. Still, the UCLA sophomore's ability paid off Sunday,
when he defeated USC's Roman Kukal 6-3, 6-4 to win the 23rd
National Collegiate Tennis Classic at Sherwood Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Grinda became the first UCLA player to win the tournament in
eight years.
</P>
<P>
   In women's singles, Stanford freshman Marissa Irvin, a
Harvard-Westlake graduate and top seed, overcame a sluggish start
to beat third-seeded Anita Kurimay of Cal 4-6, 6-2, 6-1 for her
first collegiate tournament title.
</P>
<P>
   Grinda, the tournament's No.4 seed, has the tennis pedigree. His
father, Jean-Noel, played for the French in Davis Cup competition
from 1958-62. At one time, the elder Grinda was ranked No.2 in
France.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the elder Grinda used his name to help his son get
the best tennis instructors. Father only coached son through age
12. Then he became too busy with his various real estate projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't have been in my best interests,'' Grinda said.
``He would not have been able to follow me enough, and my game
would have suffered.''
</P>
<P>
   Clay play came more naturally, but his father had the sense to
instruct Grinda in the ways of serve and volley, the style of
choice on other surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I hadn't been my father's son, I would have been a
grinder,'' he said. ``He taught me to come in. When I was a kid,
he'd advise me to serve and volley. On my natural side, I'd sit
back and hit from the baseline. It made me a complete player.''
</P>
<P>
   Kukal, who made an unexpected run to the final, last faced
Grinda five years ago in the Australian Open junior doubles
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Kukal won that day, but Sunday was different. His best chance
came in the second set, when he broke Grinda to pull to 3-3. But
Grinda, using ground strokes, broke back for a 4-3 lead. The two
held serve the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``He served better than I did,'' Kukal said. ``I didn't start
too well. I felt tired. I couldn't move well.''
</P>
<P>
   Irvin never thought she moved well against Kurimay but received
a break when Kurimay pulled a hamstring muscle and required a
massage in the second set. Irvin was up 5-2 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it was Kurimay who said she had problems moving.
</P>
<P>
   For Irvin, the victory took away some of the pain of losing the
doubles final earlier in the day. Cal's Amanda Augustus and Amy
Jensen, the second seeds, overcame a 5-1 deficit and beat Irvin and
Teryn Ashley 8-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played well in doubles. I didn't feel at any point I started
to play well here,'' she said. ``It's really exciting, but 10
minutes from now, I'll be like, `Oh, OK.' I think it stays with you
longer if you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's K.J. Hippensteel and Ryan Wolters won the men's
doubles final, 8-6 over USC's Ryan Moore and Nick Rainey.
</P>
<P>
   Texas' Brandon Hawk won the men's consolation singles title,
beating teammate Jack Brasington 7-6 (7-2), 1-6, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's Gabriela Lastra won the women's consolation singles
title, 6-3, 6-2 over Laresa Marinova of Arizona.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2211EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
