<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-N     01-17 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JETS' CONSOLATION IS PARCELLS' COMEBACK
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ARATON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS) 
(ms) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ When the Jets were rolling toward the American Football
Conference championship game, Bill Parcells' face told you all you
needed to know about how he felt. His eyes glowed, his smirk had
mischief in it. But Sunday night, after the 23-10 loss to the
Broncos, the coach's eyes were flat and he had forgotten how to
smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players I was proud of a lot of things they
accomplished; they did a good job in many areas,'' he was saying
now. ``But it would've been foolish to tell them they can pick up
next season where we left off. They have to go back to where we
started and they've got to get to where we were this season with a
different perception of what it takes to win it.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells then talked about ``making a few changes'' for next
season, but he didn't sound like he was including himself among the
changes.
</P>
<P>
   So if there's any consolation to the Jets not qualifying for
Super Bowl XXXIII, it's that Parcells surely will remain to finish
his job.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Jets somehow won the Super Bowl against the Atlanta
Falcons on Jan. 31 in Miami, it's not unreasonable to think that
the 57-year-old Parcells might have decided to stop being the Jets'
chief of football operations, retire to his Sea Girt, N.J., home
and let Bill Belichick take command as head coach.
</P>
<P>
   But not now. Not after this loss.
</P>
<P>
   Parcells knows why Leon Hess gave him all those millions _ to
win the Super Bowl, as he had with the Giants twice. He didn't get
all those millions just to make the Jets presentable; he got those
millions to make the Jets champions.
</P>
<P>
   But all that the Jets are champions of right now is the AFC's
Eastern Division. That is two levels shy of the standards that
Parcells demands _ conference champions, then Super Bowl champions.
</P>
<P>
   And after the way the Jets let Sunday's conference title get
away after holding a 10-0 lead, Parcells isn't about to depart
without continuing to meet those standards. The Jets sabotaged
themselves with four lost fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed a field goal and we turned it over three times in
the scoring zone,'' he said. ``That's a potential 24 points. You
can't do that in a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also reminded his listeners of what he called the
franchise's ``quantum leap'' in getting to the conference
championship game with a 13-4 record, an improvement over the 9-7
turnaround in his first season after taking over a team that had
been a 1-15 disaster in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it compares favorably with anybody in history,'' he
said. ``And I'm not saying that from an egotistical standpoint, but
from the accomplishment standpoint from the players' part.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he asked to leave the interview area, saying, ``I'm a
little tired right now.'' And more than a little disappointed.
Don't forget that this is a coach who must continually monitor his
heart since undergoing bypass surgery in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   If the Jets had won Sunday, Parcells would have joined another
coach who has had bypass surgery _ Dan Reeves of the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Several days after Reeves' emergency surgery on Dec. 14,
Parcells phoned to tell the Falcons' coach what it was like during
his own recuperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as anyone in this country, Dan can identify with me
and I can identify with him,'' Parcells said at the time. ``There
aren't too many coaches that have been through bypass. I told him
what it was like for me. I told him some of the problems I had in
the convalescent period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `Here's what it took me to do this' or `I was
doing this by this day.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I ran lightpoles on the boardwalk to get better. I'd run one,
walk one at first. If I didn't get to the next lightpole, it was,
`Parcells, you're weak,' then I'd have to go to the end of the
boardwalk. Or, it was `Parcells, you're a fat wimp.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Dan, `You're not going to be happy until you can run
around that Falcons' complex 15 times. When you can do that, then
you'll say, `I'm back.'''
</P>
<P>
   But even if Reeves hasn't yet run around the Falcon complex 15
times, he's back. And during the Jets' warmup, Reeves was even back
in Denver: On the video screen on Mile High Stadium's scoreboard,
he storming the sideline as his Falcons upset the Vikings, 30-27,
in overtime for the National Football Conference title.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever the Falcons made a big play, the Bronco fans cheered.
They know Reeves from when he took the Broncos on three Super Bowl
trips, even if he lost all three.
</P>
<P>
   And now Reeves, who feuded with John Elway in their last few
seasons together, will be going against Elway and the Broncos in
the Super Bowl about six weeks after his heart-bypass surgery. More
than anybody else, Bill Parcells would appreciate Dan Reeves'
comeback. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
