<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6982 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     01-17 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: SECOND HALF, LOOKING GRIM: ELWAY'S TIME TO SHINE
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS) 
(ms) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ The aura of greatness seemed to be gone from John
Elway, as missing in action as his passing touch. The rumored grand
exit from his hometown stage was blowing in the wind, a mile high.
</P>
<P>
   For one mistake-plagued half and a few minutes of another
Sunday, Vinny Testaverde looked like the future Hall of Famer,
piling on the yards, if not the points. Elway, slow dropping back,
throwing on the move, failing to so much as complete a pass for 20
minutes, fired low-angled balls that the Jets' defensive line
played paddle ball with.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was tough, I was getting balls batted, we were just
out of sync,'' Elway said after the Broncos had grounded the Jets,
23-10, for the American Football Conference title. ``It was ugly,
that first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came one play-action call, one butchered formation, and one
display of timely improvisation that reminded the Jets of a
fundamental tenet of sports. Greatness eventually shows up. It is
as easy to bring down, to bury in the soil beneath the natural
grass, as Terrell Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos were losing, 10-0, and they had, as Elway said, done
nothing you would expect of defending Super Bowl champs. Dropped
passes. A fumbled pitchout. Bad snaps. A blocked punt. Then they
came out of the huddle three minutes into the third quarter,
first-and-10 from their 36, with their receivers lined up wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Ed McCaffrey, who was supposed to line up on the left, lined up
on the right. Rod Smith, who was supposed to line up on the right,
lined up on the left. Elway looked at this mistake, and calmly
transformed it into the Broncos' wake-up call.
</P>
<P>
   He looked over at Smith, who nodded, letting Elway know he would
change his route from a post pattern to a cross. Elway shouted over
at McCaffrey to make sure he realized to run the post. ``They're
bright men,'' Elway said. ``They knew what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The play-action fake froze the Jets' safeties just enough.
McCaffrey got into the secondary, behind Corwin Brown. Elway would
later admit that his pass, in the wind, was not the best he has
made in 16 years. It was a completion, though. It was for 47 yards,
to the Jets' 17-yard line. It was a play champions make when they
are down, and just about when they seem on the verge of being out.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who would make few memorable plays in the AFC title game
he called ``the ugliest one'' of five, threw the pass that lit Mile
High Stadium, that set up a touchdown pass to Dwayne Carswell and
set off an explosion of 20 Denver points. In 11 minutes 38 seconds
from Bill Parcells' worst nightmare, the Broncos were the Bulls
blowing away the Utah Jazz in Game 3 of the NBA finals. They were
the Yankees loading up on the Padres in the first two games of the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to get out of a funk, to get the fans back into
it,'' Elway said. ``It perked everyone up.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway wound up throwing for 173 yards Sunday, that total more
than doubled by Testaverde, who deserved better from his team than
he got. A missed field goal by John Hall wasted a game-opening
drive. Fumbles by Curtis Martin, Keith Byers and Alex Van Dyke
short-circuited others. With no running game, in the biggest pro
game of his career, Testaverde at times dominated the Broncos'
defense. Three points, ultimately, is what the Jets' offense
produced on its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept my focus,'' Testaverde said, sadly. ``I won't be
satisfied until I win the championship.''
</P>
<P>
   He had a storybook year, was a prince of a guy, and the only
consolation was that he was beaten by the king. By the quarterback
with the star over his head. Elway won his first Super Bowl last
year, but made it to the game three times much earlier in his
career. Some guys have the supporting casts, the looks, the luck.
Very few play 16 years in one city, as Elway has in Denver, and get
to finish _ as Elway will if he does retire _ by taking his coach's
advice to address the hometown fans, on national TV. By looking
into the camera and telling them, ``I love you.''
</P>
<P>
   By carrying a championship trophy above his head, leaving the
field.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, in fact, could not have scripted a better finish, except
for the pass to McCaffrey in the end zone, as the game wound down.
Mike Shanahan claimed it made sense for the Broncos to go for a
touchdown, ahead by 13, on fourth down from the Jets' 25. That it
may have been Elway's last pass at Mile High had nothing to do with
the play call, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan, just last spring, set the standard for the
dramatic superstar exit, but Elway's pass was inches too long, off
McCaffrey's outstretched hand. Incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``My decision on retirement won't be made until after the next
game,'' Elway said.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, right. There remains one more game, one more finish, one
more chance for the perfect, Jordanesque goodbye.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2217EST &QL; 
