<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0218 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-KEYPLAY-N     01-17 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-KEYPLAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BUSTED PLAY MAKES THE BIGGEST GAIN FOR THE BRONCOS
</HEADLINE>
   (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ARATON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS, FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(ms) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ It was a busted play that gave Denver life at the start
of the third quarter, but it was a Broncos running back who busted
open the American Football Conference championship game, and with
it, the Jets. John Elway got the victory lap around Mile High
Stadium. The man who made it possible, Terrell Davis, got bags of
ice around his powerful legs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the National Football League's leading rusher and only
the fourth running back in league history to gain 2,000 yards in a
season, finished the day with 167 yards on 32 carries. But it was
his third-quarter performance that allowed the Broncos to return to
the Super Bowl and defend their title. He carried nine times for 78
yards and propelled the Broncos to four consecutive scores for 20
points.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you see how hard-nosed he runs,'' said Denver tackle Tony
Jones, ``how he tears people up and keeps bruising away at them, it
really gives you a boost. They had stopped us, but we knew it was a
matter of getting T.D. untracked.''
</P>
<P>
   Down by 3-0 _ shut out in the first half for the first time
since 1993 _ and down by 10-0 early in the second half, the Broncos
started the second half with these dire words from Elway: ``We
aren't going to win with no points.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he backed them up by finding Ed McCaffrey for a 47-yard
pass play to the Jets' 17-yard line early in the third quarter, on
the possession after the Jets had scored their touchdown. Elway
could laugh afterward about how McCaffrey and Rod Smith came out of
the huddle on the wrong side. How they switched assignments at the
line of scrimmage, with McCaffrey running the post instead of the
deep cross as he was supposed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both are bright enough guys to make the adjustment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the one long strike softened the Jets up enough to turn the
game back into Davis' &UR;  &LR; hands. He had galloped for 75 yards in the
first half, but the Broncos had failed to convert on third downs
and could &UR;  &LR; not get him into the end zone on third &UR; - &LR; and &UR; - &LR; goal from
the 2. In fact, they were only 21 percent efficient in that
category for the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hadn't stopped Terrell all day,'' said Broncos tight end
Shannon Sharpe. ``We just hadn't given them any help.''
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, he was on his way to his sixth consecutive post-season
game over 100 yards. After Elway hit Griffith for an 11-yard
touchdown pass to cut the score to 10-7, Davis and his undersized
line went to work. Jets Coach Bill Parcells said before the game
that his team could play perfect defense against Davis and the
running back could still gain 5 yards on a carry. He did. Often.
</P>
<P>
   He had runs of 5 and 15 yards to set up Elway's second touchdown
pass and to set up Jason Elam's 44-yard field goal to tie the
score. The next time Davis took the field, he cut back to the
middle for 20 yards and down to the Jets' 21-yard line to set up
another Elam field goal.
</P>
<P>
   And, finally, he did it all by himself. On third-and-3 from the
Jets' 31- yard line, Davis swept left and broke down the sideline
until he reached the end zone. In just nine carries, he had powered
the Broncos to a 20-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pitch play and the backside was open,'' Davis said of
his touchdown run. ``I just told myself to be patient. I saw the
flow of the line, cut back and saw a seam. I thought a lot of our
players were over anxious. We just wanted to go back and start
playing our game and executing better. We wanted to go back to the
basics. It was just one of those game, but we came out and played a
great second half and wore them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
