<HEADER>
A6988 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-SPECIALTEAMS     01-17 0882
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-SPECIALTEAMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS' SPECIAL TEAMS FALL APART IN THE WIND
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ARATON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS, FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN) 
(ms) 
 By TIMOTHY W. SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DENVER _ Special-teams play is the pet project of Jets coach
Bill Parcells. He believes it is the area that can provide the
margin of victory in certain games and in certain situations.
Sunday was one of those games, and the unusual situation was a
swirling wind that gusted at unpredictable times.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a scary thing,'' said Broncos kicker Jason Elam. ``I
don't think the Jets knew what to do. I don't think they know what
hit them.''
</P>
<P>
   Early on, it looked as if the Jets' special teams were going to
be a factor in a New York victory. But the Broncos' special teams
aren't too shabby either. And when it was over, and Denver had
clinched a 23-10 victory and another American Football Conference
championship, the Broncos' special teams were standing tall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to hang in there, because we didn't really play
that well in the first half,'' said Broncos linebacker Keith Burns,
who recovered a fumbled kickoff that led to Denver tying the score
at 10-10 on a 44-yard field goal in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being on special teams sometimes you don't feel like you get
the credit you deserve, that the guys on offense and defense get
all the credit,'' Burns said. ``But we have a veteran group of guys
on special teams and we know how special we are to our offense and
defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was one of those days and it couldn't have happened in a
bigger situation.
</P>
<P>
   Elam kicked field goals of 44, 48 and 35 yards in the swirling
wind. Punter Tom Rouen had a punt blocked, which led to the Jets'
only touchdown, and fumbled a punt snap. But he handled the
unpredictable wind, kicking three other punts inside the Jets' 20
yard-line (one at the 6, one at the 7, and another at the 17) to
give New York poor starting field position. Kickoff returner Vaughn
Hebron had a 28-yard return right before quarterback John Elway hit
receiver Ed McCaffrey on a 47-yard pass that helped set up the
Broncos' first touchdown, in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Darrien Gordon had a 36-yard punt return that set the Broncos up
at the Jets' 36-yard line and led to a 31-yard run by running back
Terrell Davis that helped give Denver a 20-10 lead near the end of
the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Things didn't start out that rosy for either of the
special-teams units.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' John Hall missed a 42-yard field goal with 9:20 to
play in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing so hard on that field goal that he didn't
have much of a chance at making it,'' said Elam, who used that
miss, which went wide right, to gauge his field-goal attempts.
</P>
<P>
   But Hall nailed a 32-yarder at the other end of the field with
the wind at the close of the first half to give the Jets a 3-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   On his fumbled punt in the second quarter, Rouen said that the
wind caught the ball as it was snapped by linebacker Glen Cadrez.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball just started rising up,'' he said. ``I caught the tip
of it with one hand and then as I squeezed the ball it just shot
out of my hand. The ball was moving all over the place. It was
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Near the beginning of the third quarter, the Jets' punt-return
team exploited a weakness in the Broncos' cover team at the line of
scrimmage. Blake Spence, a third-string tight end who was active
for just his second game this season, came in free from the right
side of the line and blocked Rouen's punt. The Jets recovered at
the Broncos' 1 and running back Curtis Martin ran it in for a
touchdown to put the Jets up by 10-0.
</P>
<P>
   But the tide turned for the Broncos' special teams in the second
half. Elam got a better idea of which way the wind was blowing and
he began to use it to his advantage. Elam estimated that at certain
levels of the stadium the wind was gusting between 50 and 60 mph.
</P>
<P>
   On the two field goals that he hit heading into the north end of
the stadium, Elam said he aimed the ball 15 to 20 yards wide right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would aim to the right and the wind would pull it back in,''
he said. ``I'd just try to keep the ball low, like a line drive and
hope nobody got a hand on it. I was just trying to hit the heck of
it every time.''
</P>
<P>
   The one time that Elam got the ball up in the air was on a
kickoff. It rose and then dropped as if it had hit a brick wall.
That was the kickoff that fell about 20 yards short of the Jets'
return man, Dave Meggett, was mishandled by James Farrior and was
recovered by Burns at the Jets' 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was no one else's responsibility,'' said Meggett. ``I have
to take it wherever it goes. The previous kick came to the 4, but
the wind held the second one in the air and I didn't get a good
read on it. The wind was very tricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Parcells said it was a lucky break for the Broncos, remarking,
``You can't tell me they intended to kick it that short.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that Meggett was too far back, and I'm not sure whether
their front guys saw that the ball just hit the wind and dropped,''
Burns said. ``I knew it was a live ball. I was pretty lucky,
because it hit the ground and just bounced right back to me. It was
a good bounce for me.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
