<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6989 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     01-17 1203
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON MYSTIQUE HAS VANISHED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Tyson is no longer Mike Tyson. That was clear on Saturday
night in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, he was rusty after a 19-month layoff. And, yes, Francois
Botha put up a good fight before he was knocked out by one
monstrous punch with one second left in the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Let's be honest, though: The Mike Tyson who fought Saturday
didn't remotely resemble the tornado who swept through the
heavyweight division and captured the imagination of the public in
the '80s.
</P>
<P>
   This Tyson has one weapon: a big punch. Two long layoffs and age
_ he's 32 _ have sapped his once-remarkable skills and at least
some of his quickness. Even the fury that was a cornerstone during
his peak was subdued on Saturday at the MGM Grand.
</P>
<P>
   It's to a point where he's losing his appeal. Oh, fans are still
intrigued by the power and his unpredictable nature but not to the
extent they once were.
</P>
<P>
   The Tyson act is getting old. The pay-per-view numbers for
Saturday's card are expected to reflect that and it might get even
worse the next time out.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson insists he's not through and asks for patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be back in the gym in two weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fact is, it's too late for Iron Mike. Clever trainer Tommy
Brooks might be able to lift Tyson's performance to a somewhat
higher level in his coming fights, but he can't resurrect the dead.
And the Mike Tyson we've come to know is dead.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks' mission during training was to correct Tyson's ``bad
habits.'' The goal: Get him to jab, to move his head, to throw
punches to the body and in combination as he did during the first
and most successful installment of his career.
</P>
<P>
   What'd Tyson do? None of the above.
</P>
<P>
   He was all the things that twice made him such easy prey against
Evander Holyfield: He jabbed only minimally, he was a stationary
target, he didn't try to find Botha's substantial stomach and he
threw single punches with a knockout on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, he was dominated by Francois Botha _ Francois Botha _
before the big right hand saved his career. He took many more
punches than he landed, which was reflected in the scoring: Botha,
a 7-1 underdog, won all but one round on the card of one judge.
</P>
<P>
   It appears the only thing Tyson got out of training camp was
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Is Brooks worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``He learned his lesson tonight, he
learned his lesson tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   That's right, Tommy. Say it over and over again and you just
might begin to believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Brooks, who worked with Holyfield the past several years before
becoming Tyson's main man shortly after he regained his boxing
license in October, said before the bout that Tyson would beat
Holyfield if they were to meet again.
</P>
<P>
   That was ludicrous even then. Now? No way Brooks could say it
again with a straight face. He knows it, Tyson knows it, we all
know it: This is a new but hardly improved Mike Tyson who remains
better than most heavyweights but is really nothing special.
</P>
<P>
   But his career moves on. His next battle is against a familiar
foe: the justice system. He will learn next month whether an
altercation with two men on a Maryland highway constitutes a
violation of his conditions for parole on his rape conviction.
</P>
<P>
   If so, he could return to prison and his career could be over.
</P>
<P>
   If not, he'll fight again in April, once more perhaps in July
and then _ if all goes well _ face Holyfield for a third time in
November or December in what could be the richest matchup in
history.
</P>
<P>
   And he'll probably get there. Those guiding his career will
continue to put mediocre opponents in front of him so he won't lose
the big payday against Holyfield. Such names as Axel Schulz, Vaughn
Bean and Lou Savarse keep popping up as possible opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly mouth-watering, is it?
</P>
<P>
   Tyson will get Holyfield again and all the money. And, again,
Holyfield will pummel an inferior fighter even though the champion
will be 37 years old when it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Tyson even knows it. He said he plans to retire after
his fourth bout _ against Holyfield _ and fighters almost never
retire after a victory.
</P>
<P>
   __ Scary moment: The mini-riot at the end of the first round
Saturday was frightening.
</P>
<P>
   As the round ended, Tyson had Botha's left arm locked under his
and refused to let go. When referee Richard Steele was unable to
free Botha, handlers from both camps and then security personnel
rushed into the ring to restore order as police officers lined the
apron to contain the mayhem.
</P>
<P>
   It took only a few minutes to sort things out and, after Steele
warned both fighters, the bout continued.
</P>
<P>
   Nevada officials, fearful that Tyson might snap again as he did
when bit Holyfield's ears in his last fight, were relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I was worried,'' said Marc Ratner, director of the
Nevada State Athletic Commission. ``I just talked to Richard
(Steele) and told him, `It's your fight. Take control.' And he did
a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Tyson being Tyson: Tyson was relatively gracious after the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to help Botha up as he was sprawling against the ropes
after the knockout and he hugged his opponent warmly a few moments
later.
</P>
<P>
   And, at the post-fight news conference, he kept his swearing to
a minimum.
</P>
<P>
   However, he made one comment that surprised no one. Asked to
comment on Botha's contention that Tyson tried to break his arm at
the end of the first round, he said with a smile:
</P>
<P>
   ``That's correct.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Huge mistake: Botha squandered an opportunity to make a
fortune and his place in history when he became overconfident in
the fifth round.
</P>
<P>
   Had he continued to keep his distance and fire punches from long
range, while tying up Tyson when danger approached, he might've
won. Instead, he became brave. He exchanged punches with his much
more powerful opponent and ultimately paid a very expensive price.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really thought it was going to be easy,'' said Botha,
referring to a conclusion he reached a few minutes into the fight.
`` . . . I got careless. I knew I was in control. I was slowly but
surely getting a hand on the fight. I just walked into the punch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I got a little cocky _ and I paid for it.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, Botha proved what many knew going into the
bout: He's a good fighter who will have other opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Unbeaten heavyweight Lance ``Mount''
Whitaker's victory over Alex Stewart was a positive step in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   However, he's too cocky in and out of the ring for his own good.
</P>
<P>
   In it, he needs to keep his hands in front of his face _ not at
his sides _ and fight with more urgency. Outside it, he made
comments to the effect it wasn't a difficult or important fight. In
fact, it was both. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how Julio Cesar Chavez does with
Joe Goossen as his trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, even at 36, has a lot of fight left in him if he can
keep his focus.
</P>
<P>
   Goossen might be just the trainer he needs. He's a fun-loving
guy, but, in the gym, he demands a tremendous amount of his
fighters. Chavez will learn this quickly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
