<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SPEECH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMBITIOUS STATE OF THE UNION IS PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The high drama of the Senate impeachment trial will
give way to the high purpose of the State of the Union Tuesday
night when President Clinton goes before a joint session of
Congress to deliver the annual presidential address.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republican House members are planning not to attend the
speech, for a variety of reasons. Some House Democrats, who plan to
be there, said the GOP leadership has not given members much
incentive to return to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   With the House not in session and no votes scheduled until
February, the only reason most House members would travel is for
the State of the Union address.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after his lawyers begin presenting the case to senators
for why he should not be removed from office, Clinton will go to
the House chamber, where he became the first elected president to
be impeached, and lay out what his aides say is the most ambitious
policy agenda of his presidency.
</P>
<P>
   The last State of the Union by a president in the 20th century
will also be the first delivered in person by a president who has
been impeached.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress, Republicans and Democrats, had wanted
Clinton to delay the address, while some White House officials had
wanted to postpone his lawyers' opening presentation in the Senate
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   But the speech will be given as scheduled. Clinton will deliver
his seventh State of the Union address before members of Congress
who have impeached him and others who are considering whether to
oust him from office.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to his colleagues Friday, House Speaker Dennis
Hastert, a Republican from Illinois, said, ``These are
extraordinary times.'' While he did not explicity urge lawmakers to
attend the address, he offered some advice for how they should act
if they do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of respect for the office of the presidency and for the
state of our union, we will listen to the president's remarks
soberly and with the dignity that befits the United States,'' he
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said he does not intend to mention impeachment in
his address. ``Tuesday night, I'm going to ask the country to go
back to work because we've still got a lot to do,'' he said before
a gathering of Democrats on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   A senior White House official involved in the planning for the
speech reported on the prevailing mood: ``People who listen to the
State of the Union want to hear what we have to say that makes a
difference in their lives, not ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will take advantage of the spotlight to promote a host
of poll-tested policy initiatives focused on aging baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the agenda has been previewed through a series of
carefully orchestrated news leaks and staged White House
ceremonies, though aides have hinted at something new.
</P>
<P>
   One big unknown is how Clinton will advance his call of last
year to ``Save Social Security first,'' a mantra to Republicans not
to use the budget surplus for tax cuts. White House communications
director Ann Lewis said Clinton will tell Congress and the American
public that ``this is the year we should get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposals include increasing military spending,
tripling money for after-school programs, creating tax credits and
health care grants to help disabled Americans go to work, improving
food safety, and extending funding for community policing.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton will also renew his effort to restrict teenage smoking,
calling this year for a new 55-cent-a-pack cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   He will also recycle proposals that did not go anywhere last
year, including raising the minimum wage, modernizing schools, and
allowing Americans as young as 55 to buy into Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a president who is looking backward in the seventh
year of his presidency,'' Lewis said. ``He is looking forward. In
fact, these are ideas that you might see in a first year.''
</P>
<P>
   The fate of those proposals and others, however, hangs in the
balance of an increasingly uncertain relationship between the White
House and Congress that has been strained by the weight of
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans, including Henry J. Hyde, the chairman of the
House Judiciary Committee and a prosecutor in the impeachment
trial, said they will not attend the president's speech.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde told ABC's ``Nightline'' last week that he would watch the
address from home ``mostly because it's not fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Tom Coburn, a Republican from Oklahoma, said he
will not attend because he does not think it is appropriate for
Clinton to deliver the speech while the Senate is conducting his
impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now is not the time for a presidential moment,'' he said
through his press secretary, John Hart.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican leadership aide said, ``There will be a handful who
won't come. I don't think it will be a colossal amount.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Democrat from Lowell and a
member of the House Judiciary Committee, said he was disappointed
that no House floor votes had been scheduled for Tuesday or
Wednesday to ensure that lawmakers, who are on recess, get back to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``When there are no votes, my experience has been that some of
the members don't come to Washington,'' he said, adding that he
wasn't assigning ``motives'' to the Republican leadership's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Fields, author of ``Union of Words: A History of
Presidential Eloquence,'' said members of Congress have long
preferred that presidents not deliver the State of the Union in
person and that this year the problem is heightened by Clinton's
impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is awkward tension between being a participant and
performer,'' said Fields, who also directs American culture studies
at Washington University in St. Louis. ``He's up there giving the
speech, but they are part of the act. And that's always awkward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
