<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Companies
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-SHOPPING SURVEY SHOWS MIXED REACTIONS
</P>
<P>
   Amid post-holiday giddiness about the stellar drawing power of
Web merchants and portals, a survey to be released Monday by
Jupiter Communications, a new-media research company, found that
while record numbers of Americans tried Internet shopping, they
were not always happy with their experiences.
</P>
<P>
   The number of consumers who expressed satisfaction with online
shopping dropped by 14 percentage points from six months earlier,
although 74 percent still considered it a positive experience. The
No. 1 reason consumers voiced dissatisfaction was a problem as old
as retailing: The product they wanted was out of stock. Unhappiness
about high shipping costs was a close second.
</P>
<P>
   NETWORKS NURTURE MIDSEASON HITS
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the land-rush congestion of the fall television season,
three networks started new series this month, and all of them
scored ratings that would qualify them as hits. The shows _ NBC's
``Providence,'' Fox's ``The PJ's,'' and CBS's ``60 Minutes II'' _
received heavy promotion aimed at maximum exposure. Executives at
the networks and the studios that produce series said they foresaw
an increased emphasis on holding back shows for midseason to gain
such lavish promotion.
</P>
<P>
   THE MURK IN THE MICROSOFT CASE
</P>
<P>
   While the government contends that Microsoft has a ``choke
hold'' on software distribution and that consumers will be harmed
unless the software giant is reined in, Microsoft replies that the
government has produced no real proof on either front. The
challenge for the courts is that how antitrust doctrine and the
case law apply to the Microsoft case is by no means clear cut.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY NEWS REVAMPS ITS PAGE 2
</P>
<P>
   The transformation last week of page 2 at the Daily News of New
York _ prime real estate for news in a tabloid _ into a column
about what's happening around town did not go over very well in the
newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   HEARINGS ON INTERNET SMUT LAW
</P>
<P>
   Court hearings will begin this week on the Child Online
Protection Act, which was signed into law in October but has never
gone into effect because of legal challenges. Supporters of the
act, which makes it a crime for a commercial Web site to knowingly
make certain sexually explicit material available to those younger
than 17, say it would shield children from smut. Critics say the
measure would undercut free speech and Internet commerce.
</P>
<P>
   THE CUSTOMER AS AN AFTERTHOUGHT
</P>
<P>
   Few industries have gorged themselves on digital commerce with
greater appetite than telecommunications companies, but the result
has been a wired world that seems to care little about providing
additional value for customers.
</P>
<P>
   HOFFMAN SUES MAGAZINE OVER PHOTO
</P>
<P>
   Actor Dustin Hoffman is pressing a lawsuit against Los Angeles
magazine for its use of his face in a fashion spread. In the March
1997 issue, the magazine superimposed an image of Hoffman's face
from his role in ``Tootsie'' _ in which his character disguised
himself as a woman to get an acting job _ on a model wearing a gown
and high heels. The suit centers on an area of law called right of
publicity, which is supposed to give celebrities the right to
control their names and images for commercial purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Markets
</P>
<P>
   MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States are closed Monday in observance of Martin Luther King Jr.
Day. They will reopen Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
