<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-HORSES-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANISTIQUE WINS FEATURE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. Manistique's narrow victory over Gourmet Girl in
Sunday's El Encino Stakes at Santa Anita wasn't pretty. But trainer
John Shirreffs and jockey Gary Stevens knew the result could have
been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-5 favorite stumbled badly out of the gate in the $150,000
Grade II race for 4-year-old fillies. She then had to run for her
life to hold off outclassed Gourmet Girl by a head.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just hoping Gary would stay on,'' said Shirreffs of the
Manistique's start. ``He did a great job of riding her.''
</P>
<P>
   Manistique had only two horses to beat in the 1 1/16-mile event
but, according to Stevens and Shirreffs, the temperamental filly
was never really relaxed after a short delay in the tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not one to stand still,'' Shirreffs said.
</P>
<P>
   Manistique, however, did right herself and led from the
quarter-pole en route to her fifth victory in six career starts.
</P>
<P>
   Manistique finished the 1 1/16-mile race in 1:43.10 and paid
$2.80 to win. There was no place or show wagering because
Tranquility Lake was scratched.
</P>
<P>
   Second-choice Magical Allure, who was stretching out, faded
badly in the stretch and finished three lengths back in third, even
though she had a perfect opening along the rail.
</P>
<P>
   But Manistique's first race at Santa Anita was made interesting
as Gourmet Girl, an unlikely challenger, battled all the way to the
finish. Shirreffs admitted he was worried about Gourmet Girl
``because Manistique isn't the kind of horse that has a big closing
charge.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't intimidated by Manistique,'' said Gourmet Girl's
trainer, Pico Perdomo. ``This is a tough filly. Like I said before,
thank God they don't teach horses to read the (Daily Racing) Form.
Because then she'd know she was a $3,500 horse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to face (Manistique) again in the La Canada
(Stakes on Feb. 7). We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She ran a winning race,'' said jockey Kent Desormeaux of
Gourmet Girl, who has won four of 11 races. ``There was no shame in
defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   There was also no shame in a close victory, according to
Shirreffs and Stevens, even for a highly regarded filly who is
expected to be a factor in the 1999 Breeders' Cup Distaff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent's filly ran the race of her life and this is the first
time my filly has ever really been in a battle,'' Stevens said.
``She showed her talent and how game she is today. I was proud of
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely wasn't one of her better races, and that's why
I'm not discouraged. If she had run one of the best races of her
life and won by a head, then I might be discouraged. Believe me, on
a scale of of 1-10, this rates about a 3 or a 4. And that's not too
bad if she's still able to win a Grade II race.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainer Bob Baffert had been pointing Magical Allure to the
Grade I seven-furlong Santa Monica Handicap on Jan. 23, but plans
were changed and the El Encino turned out to be little more ``than
kind of a good workout,'' said jockey David Flores.
</P>
<P>
   Magical Allure had won seven of her previous eight races, but
only two of the victories were in races of a mile or more.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish Prize and Laffit Pincay Jr. held off longshot Fearless
Pirate by a nose in the second feature, the $100,000 Sensational
Star Handicap for Cal-bred 4-year-olds and up at 6{ furlongs on the
turf.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always tries hard,'' trainer Richard Mandella said.
``Laffit always seems to get him in the right place.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was Turkish Prize's fifth in 10 starts, and he paid
$5.20, 3.40 and 2.60.
</P>
<P>
   Fearless Prize returned $9.80 and 5.60. Naval Academy, which led
much of the race, paid $3.40 to show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
