<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS HURDLE THE JETS AND RETURN TO THE SUPER BOWL
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds: SUBS to add quotes, integrate game stats into the story; now
in 2 takes. ) 
(ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ For more than half of Sunday's American Football
Conference championship game, the Jets could see all the way to
Miami and the Super Bowl, the game that they had helped turn into
one of the biggest spectacles in sports 30 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But then they began to drop the ball, turning it over six times
on a day when the Denver Broncos needed the gifts. And in a
10-minute splurge after halftime, the Broncos, the defending Super
Bowl champions, rallied for 20 points and defeated the Jets by
23-10 to earn the trip to Super Bowl XXXIII on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The victory by the high-powered Broncos was not a surprise, but
their Super Bowl opponent is: the Atlanta Falcons, who shocked the
heavily favored Minnesota Vikings for the National Conference
championship, winning by 30-27 in overtime in Minneapolis. The
Falcons _ led by a coach, Dan Reeves, who had heart bypass surgery
a month ago _ will play in the Super Bowl for the first time in
their 33-year history and will again be underdogs, this time to the
Broncos, Reeves' former team.
</P>
<P>
   On the best of days it would have been difficult for the Jets to
halt Denver, which was 14-2 in the regular season and had won 18
consecutive games at Mile High Stadium. But the Jets, who led by
10-0 early in the second half, could not overcome their mistakes:
the six turnovers, including four fumbles, and a botched kickoff
that set up a Denver field goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you can do the things we did in a championship
game against a team like this,'' said a subdued Bill Parcells, the
Jets' coach, who in two breathless seasons had rebuilt the National
Football League laughing stocks and brought them within 60 minutes
of the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   While Parcells held his post-game news conference, Elway was
busy running a victory lap around Mile High Stadium after what was
probably his last game in Denver. The quarterback, who was
energized by the fans and by the Jets' mistakes in the second half,
is likely to retire after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-year-old Elway, who won his fifth AFC championship in his
16th season, was not at his best, completing 13 of 34 passes for
173 yards. But his 11-yard touchdown pass to Howard Griffith in the
third quarter started Denver's comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Davis once again led the Broncos, rushing for 167 yards
and a touchdown. The Jets' failures, meanwhile, were punctuated by
the startling fact that Curtis Martin, their leading runner and one
of the best in football, was held to 14 yards on 13 carries. It was
the worst day of his pro career, and it included a lost fumble, his
second in the playoffs. During the regular season, he had lost the
ball only once in 369 carries.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were making their first appearance in a conference
championship game in 16 years, and their upset victory 30 years ago
in Super Bowl III remains their only Super Bowl visit. But into the
second half Sunday, their surprising run to the playoffs seemed to
be gaining even more momentum. Vinny Testaverde, who had come to
symbolize the Jets' resurrection under Parcells, completed his
first 13 passes and would finish 31 of 52 for 356 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fantastic,'' Jets guard Todd Burger said. ``There was
so much optimism. But then you think you've got almost 250 yards by
halftime and you've only got 3 points, and Denver must be thinking,
`All we're behind is by 3 and we're playing lousy.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets, one of the NFL's best-conditioned teams, had not
collapsed like this in a game this season. Reasons for Sunday's
failure could be found, perhaps, in the mile-high altitude or the
atmosphere in the tumultuous stadium, where more than 75,000 people
stomped their feet so hard it seemed that the looming Rockies might
quiver.
</P>
<P>
   But even as the Jets came apart near the end, with Testaverde
intercepted twice in the fourth quarter, it was apparent that the
franchise had gone into a new era. It just was not going to the
Super Bowl yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a team we came a long way,'' Testaverde said. ``A longer
way than people expected us to.''
</P>
<P>
   Keith Byars, one of the ``good hands'' people with whom Parcells
had surrounded Testaverde, produced a rare fumble after a reception
to stifle a drive deep in Denver territory in the second quarter.
The game was scoreless, and mistakes like that kept Denver hoping.
In fact, the Jets lost the ball to Denver three times within the
20-yard line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the ball tucked,'' said Byars, the leading career
receiver among NFL running backs. ``If I had to do it over again,
I'd do it the same way. I must have made that play hundreds of
times.''
</P>
<P>
   He just didn't make it Sunday. Nor did other Jets.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams combined for more than 900 points during the
regular season. But it took almost the entire first half before
anyone scored even 3 points. That turned out to be the Jets, who
finally put up points after dominating for 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That sole score was John Hall's 32-yard field goal as time
expired, and it was positioned, in the mistake-filled half, by a
Broncos penalty on a punt. That put the Jets in good field position
after they had misfired repeatedly themselves. Indeed, the game's
opening drive ended with a failed 42-yard field-goal attempt by
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it was kicked amid gusts that hit 32 mph and sent
orange balloons swirling, flags snapping to attention and stray
pieces of paper flying. Whatever the reason, a Jets drive deep into
Denver territory was wasted.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos went three-and-out and the Jets got the ball again,
but Martin lost the ball and Tyrone Braxton recovered at the Denver
44.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' defense troubled Elway for much of the game. He moved
his team to the 1-yard line after Martin's fumble, but the Broncos
were halted. On fourth-and-goal from the 1, Mo Lewis tipped away
Elway's pass.
</P>
<P>
   But the Broncos weren't only stopped close. Repeatedly, they
could not solve the defense orchestrated by Bill Belichick. The
Jets, using a 3-4 alignment that relied on a coordinated rush and a
pass-defense alignment that took away the center of the field,
simply looked better than Denver. Elway did not have a completion
in his first three drives. The Jets took away the middle,
double-teamed the Pro Bowl tight end Shannon Sharpe and did not
seem concerned about Elway throwing the ball deep.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second half, the Broncos heard their first boos _
quite possibly their first here of the season _ when they went
three-and-out and Tom Rouen botched a 29-yard punt.
</P>
<P>
   Two drives later, a Jets rookie tight end named Blake Spence,
who had not even put on a uniform for 10 straight games, loomed out
of obscurity to block a punt that put the Jets only 1 yard out of
the Denver end zone. Spence, a fifth-round draft pick, suited up
because Parcells was unhappy with free safety Jerome Henderson. So
Spence blocked Rouen's punt from the end zone. The Jets' Fred
Baxter recovered on the 1.
</P>
<P>
   One play later, Martin found the end zone, and the Jets led by
10-0.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The Jets could not build on that momentum. In fact, the Broncos
smothered it immediately. Vaughn Hebron returned the kickoff 28
yards, and then Elway connected with Ed McCaffrey, who had earlier
dropped two passes, for a 47-yard completion over a fooled Victor
Green.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Elway and the Broncos had rediscovered their
quick-strike capability. The drive took 93 seconds and ended with
an 11-yard touchdown toss to Howard Griffith.
</P>
<P>
   And then the Jets' turnovers finally cost them points. Jason
Elam's kickoff, held by the wind, bounced in front of the returner,
David Meggett. The Jets' James Farrior tried to snare the ball, but
fumbled it away to Keith Burns on the Jets' 32.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a 44-yard field goal by Elam to tie the score at
10-10 with 8 minutes 23 seconds left in the third quarter. The
sense that something had turned was palpable. Soon, helped again by
good field position after Darrien Gordon's 11-yard punt return,
Elam cut through the dangerous winds for a 48-yard field and a
13-10 lead. It was Denver's first.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the third quarter ended, Davis punctuated the
Broncos' comeback with a 31-yard scoring run.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth quarter brought another Jets fumble, this time by the
seldom-used receiver Alex Van Dyke, and then Testaverde's first
interception of the game. Gordon returned it 18 yards to the Jets'
18, and it led to Elam's 35-yard field goal and the crushing 23-10
lead. Later, Testaverde was intercepted again, on a deflection as
he started to throw the ball _ a reminder of times when he played
for teams who needed his strong arm to mount comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, the team that had surrounded him most of the season
had collapsed, and so did many of its big-play performers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
