<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7122 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT     01-17 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JETS NOTEBOOK: HENDERSON'S MISPLAY COSTS HIM A UNIFORM
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ In a matter of weeks, Jerome Henderson has gone from
being a starter to the bench to not even dressing for Sunday's
game. Henderson, the Jets' former starting free safety, was
supposed to help Otis Smith on Jan. 10 as the half came to a close.
Instead, Jacksonville's Jimmy Smith slipped between the defenders
and snared a 52-yard touchdown pass from Mark Brunell. The Jets
won, but Henderson fell irretrievably out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   A first-stringer for the first 14 games, Henderson was first
benched in favor of Corwin Brown, a better open-field tackler. The
little-used rookie tight end Blake Spence suited up in place of
Henderson on Sunday. Spence blocked a third-quarter punt that gave
the ball to the Jets on the Denver 1-yard line. Curtis Martin
scored on the next play.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY OF GAME
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Paul Tagliabue delayed the Jets-Broncos start for
10 minutes because the National Football Conference championship
game between Atlanta and Minnesota had gone into overtime. The
actual kickoff came at 4:17 p.m., Eastern _ the moment Atlanta won
on a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   A ROOTING INTEREST
</P>
<P>
   The used-car chain owned by H. Wayne Huizenga, the Dolphins'
owner, took out an ad in The Rocky Mountain News before the game,
telling the Broncos, ``We look forward to welcoming you to Miami
for Super Bowl XXXIII.'' Many of the Jets were furious that
Huizenga would take out an ad to, in effect, root for their
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   NOT FRANCHISE PLAYERS
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have to list Monday the five players they are going to
make available to the Cleveland Browns in the expansion draft. Each
club can pull back two players after losing one. The maximum number
of players any team can lose is two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-01-17-99 2326EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990117.0231 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7128 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-BRONCOS-OFFENSE-N     01-17 1144
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-OFFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRONCOS' OFFENSE QUICKLY DEALS WITH THE WINDS OF CHANGE
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-FALCONS-VIKINGS, FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN,
FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN, FBN-JETS-BRONCOS, FBN-ARATON-COLUMN) 
(ms) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Like picking a lock, like cracking a safe, the Denver
Broncos tried a variety of combinations on the Jets. The Broncos
brought a slick plan and sly hands and crafty tools. But nothing
was working. The Jets were leading, 10-0, with 11 minutes 56
seconds left in the third quarter of the American Football
Conference championship game.
</P>
<P>
   And then what happened for the rest of the quarter was the stuff
that makes the Broncos so frightening. The Jets allowed a 47-yard
pass play that led to Denver's first points. The Jets let a kickoff
blow in the wind to lead to more Denver points. The Jets allowed
more big pass plays and then gave up Terrell Davis' 31-yard
touchdown run when they pursued too much and tackled too softly.
Swoosh! A 20-point quarter. A foot to the pedal. Another to the
throat.
</P>
<P>
   And that did it. The Broncos were galloping now. They stretched
the field and stepped to another gear and left the Jets gasping,
wallowing in their mistakes, marveling at the Broncos' force. It
was a 23-10 Denver victory before a crowd of 75,482 at Mile High
Stadium that pushed Denver into its second consecutive Super Bowl.
It won last year. It will shoot for another championship against
the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII.
</P>
<P>
   In the end the Jets were talking about their mistakes (six
turnovers) and the wind. They said it was a gusting, swirling wind,
one that changed the kicking game and the passing game.
</P>
<P>
   But really, the force of the Broncos, their mad dash to keep
their season alive was what blew the Jets away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be standing on the sideline and the wind would blow
you two feet,'' said Jets special teams ace Chris Hayes. ``It was
hard to judge the ball. I have never felt wind like that. But you
know, they are the champions. They played in it. They know how to
compete, especially at this level. We were up 10-0. And then I
looked at the scoreboard and all of sudden it was 20-10. I couldn't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentum changed. In the first half the Jets held the hybrid
Denver offense to a long run of 18 yards and long pass completion
of 12 yards. And then in the third quarter, after Denver receiver
Ed McCaffrey, wide open and deep over the middle, grabbed a 47-yard
catch to the Jets 17, the lock had been picked. The safe was
cracked. The Denver offense would earn a scoring pass of 11 yards
(John Elway to fullback Howard Griffith) and Davis would crank a
run of 20 yards before scoring on the 31-yarder.
</P>
<P>
   It was different. A different Denver from the game's first 33
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we get off the ground, we can fly,'' said Denver
linebacker Seth Joyner. ``Our offense got them on their heels. When
the Jets went up 3-0, we said, OK, we can make that up anytime. But
when they got up 10-0, we said, enough. We kicked it into another
gear. That' the type of football team we have. You look at the
Cowboys that won Super Bowls and the 49ers that won them, and they
had the kind of teams that if they got focused and would bear down,
you were in trouble. That's the kind of team this is. A 10-0 game
sinks in. It was knuckle up time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets were up 10-0 and then Elway hit McCaffrey for 47 yards.
Elway threw the scoring pass to Griffith. The Jets let the ensuing
kickoff flutter in the air and land short and Denver recovered it;
that let to a Denver field goal. The Jets let another kick flutter
before recovering this one short of the 20. The Jets went three
plays and punted. Denver took over and drove for another Elam field
goal. The Jets went three plays and punted. Davis scored on a
31-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Swoosh!
</P>
<P>
   We always hear about the howling wind at Giants Stadium, how it
swirls and spins and turns visiting teams upside down and inside
out. One would think the Jets would be familiar with this, even
here. They were not. They dropped the ball, they turned it over,
the passing game blew against the wind and the Jets, for all of
their effort on offense, would not score for nearly the final 42
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came in wanting to deliver some blows and tackle hard, but
no way did we think they would turn it over like that,'' said
Denver safety Steve Atwater. ``We took their running game away and
that hurt them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jets gained 14 rushing yards. Denver gained 178.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that is not the way that they wanted to play this
game,'' Joyner said. ``I know they didn't want to put it all on the
passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   He's right. Forced to throw it in the wind, the Jets chances
blew away. So did their confidence and their ability to hold onto
the ball. Denver, meanwhile, rode the wind like a friend. Once they
cracked the Jets, it was a swift breeze.
</P>
<P>
   The initial gust was the pass to McCaffrey. That was where the
Broncos began to pick the lock. To solve the combination.
</P>
<P>
   Funny, but it was on a near busted play. The Broncos receivers,
McCaffrey and Rod Smith, lined up opposite. McCaffrey ran toward
Elway under center as the team lined up but Elway told him to get
back, to go back to the left side of the formation. Elway simply
switched their pass routes. Smith, on the right, would now run the
crossing route. McCaffrey, on the left, would now run the post.
</P>
<P>
   And the Jets safety Victor Green would bite at play action and
at receiver action in front of him. He looked toward Smith, who was
crossing in front of him. McCaffrey flew past Green, wide open,
with Corwin Brown making the saving tackle at the Jets 17. The
Broncos call this kind of action a Cadillac route. It turned out
regal and royal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had struggled all day making a big play and the coaches saw
Green biting on stuff in front of him and called a great play,''
McCaffrey said. ``John did a great job of getting us together when
we weren't together. Green jumped on Rod's route. That left me
free. I was glad to get it started.''
</P>
<P>
   Shannon Sharpe, the Broncos tight end, said of Elway's
improvisation: ``Just another example of John making chicken salad
out of you-know-what. That's what a veteran and great leader like
John can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Momentum swung. The wind blew. After McCaffrey's catch, Denver
started beating the Jets with the first hit on both sides of the
ball. The doors flew open. The defending champions rose.
</P>
<P>
   In high school, college, in the pros, in all levels of football,
momentum changes things. One could feel it turning, sense it
blossoming for Denver in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it,'' said John Hall, the Jets kicker, ``but I
guess you'd have to say they are better than us. That was some
third quarter for them.''
</P>
<P>
   One where the Jets were swept away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
