<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Sunday 1/17/98. Photo clients
will automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or
may download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) NEW YORK -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- CONCERT-COUGHING, 1-17 --
Wayne Booth, emeritus professor of English at the University of
Chicago, at a recent conference of Chamber Music America, the
national society of professionals, has written a book on
amateurism, ``For the Love of It.'' ``We amateurish amateurs do
often inflict pain on others,'' Booth cautions. ``We just don't do
it on purpose.'' (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- ONLINE-ANTISMUT-LAW, 1-17
-- Ann Beeson and Christopher Hansen, foreground, of the American
Civil Liberties Union, are challenging a federal law that regulates
adult material on the Internet. Government lawyers say that a new
version of the law would not outlaw sexually explicit material
altogether, but require that it be put behind a kind of electronic
gate, like an online credit card verification system, on the
presumption that only adults would have access to it. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) DENVER -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-2, 1-17 --
Although the New York Jets rookie tight end Blake Spence was able
to block this Denver Broncos punt in the third quarter Sunday, the
Jets were unable to stop the high-powered Broncos from reaching
Super Bowl XXXIII on Jan. 31. In a 10-minute splurge after
halftime, the Broncos, the defending Super Bowl champions, rallied
for 20 points and defeated the Jets by 23-10. (Barton Silverman/New
York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) DENVER -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- FBN-JETS-BRONCOS-1, 1-17 --
The Denver Broncos Terrell Davis running through the air for a
touchdown in the third quarter Sunday against the New York Jets to
put the Broncos ahead 20-10 in the American Football Conference
championship game. In a 10-minute splurge after halftime, the
Broncos, the defending Super Bowl champions, rallied for 20 points
and defeated the Jets by 23-10 to earn a trip to Super Bowl XXXIII
on Jan. 31. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- MISLEADING-MORTGAGES, 1-17
-- Gloria Knight, a 55-year-old retired teacher, at her house in
Brooklyn, which she says she was persuaded by a salesmen to put up
as collateral for an $88,000 loan, even though she had no income
and no way to make the $973 monthly payments. Ms. Knight, who has
since been found to be delusional by a psychiatrist for the city's
Protective Services for Adults, cannot even afford gas and
electricity, so she cooks outside. (James Estrin/New York Times
Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- NY-TRASH-VIRGINIA, 1-17 --
The prospect of more barges of New York garbage being transported
to Virginia has created an uproar amongst Virginians, who already
have their state listed as the nation's second-largest trash
importer. Up to 2.2 million tons of New York garbage a year,
Virginians have learned, could be heading up the James River, bound
for landfills. (Keith Meyers/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- FUTURE-JOURNALISTS, 1-17 --
Professor Steven K. Feiner, left, of Columbia University who helped
design a portable journalist work station, watching Tobias Hllerer,
a graduate student, test the system. The mobile system would enable
journalists on assignment to download information from the Internet
and provide information about their surroundings. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 17, 1999 --SANFRAN-SPCA-4, 1-17 --
Richard Avanzino, former president of the San Francisco SPCA, with
Ashton. Avanzino is rallying support for a no-kill shelter policy
across the United States. ``We believe that killing is not an
acceptable management tool for us to use as stewards of our
nation's animals,'' he says. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) PHILADELPHIA -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- PHILLY-POLITICS, 1-17 --
Embarking upon the last of his eight years as Philadelphia's Mayor
and foremost cheerleader, Edward G. Rendell, enjoying a recent City
Hall ceremony, at which his Munchkinland counterpart gave him the
key to Oz as Mickey Rooney looks on. Rendell, a Democrat, hardly
seems ready to relinquish his reputation for drawing a spotlight to
cities as the economic engine of a metropolitan region. (Keith
Meyers/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 17, 1999 --SANFRAN-SPCA-3, 1-17 --
Sonia Raesly, a volunteer cat handler at the San Francisco SPCA,
with Amber in one of the SPCA's specially designed living quarters,
complete with televisions, for animals housed at the shelter. San
Francisco has become the first city in the country where animals
held for adoption are not euthanized. (Monica Almeida/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- Jan. 17, 1999 -- MILITARY-SPENDING, 1-17 --
Franklin C. Spinney, of the Office of Program Analysis and
Evaluation, has warned President Clinton's administration against
buying more complicated weapons. ``Spending more money the same way
the Reagan administration did isn't going to fix anything,'' he
says. Clinton has proposed the first increase in the Pentagon's
budget since 1991 and the largest since Reagan's heady days: $12
billion in new spending in 2000, and $110 billion over the next six
years. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TAPACHULA, Mexico -- Jan. 17, 1999 --
HURRICANE-MIGRANTS-2, 1-17 -- With ravaged lives behind them, a
group of Hondurans wait to jump a freight train in Tapachula,
Mexico. Since Hurricane Mitch struck Central America last fall,
leaving an estimated 9,000 dead and tens of thousands of people
homeless, officials say there has been an alarming increase in the
number of immigrants making this harrowing journey, heading to the
United States. (Luis Jimenez/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) TAPACHULA, Mexico -- Jan. 17, 1999 --
HURRICANE-MIGRANTS-1, 1-17 -- A group of immigrants from Honduras
on a freight train after crossing into Mexico. Since Hurricane
Mitch struck Central America last fall, leaving an estimated 9,000
dead and tens of thousands of people homeless, officials say there
has been an alarming increase in the number of immigrants making
this harrowing journey, heading to the United States. (Luis
Jimenez/New York Times Photos)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 17, 1999 --SANFRAN-SPCA-2, 1-17 --
A cat enjoying the comforts of the specially designed living
quarters for animals housed at the San Francisco animal shelter.
Many of the rooms have furniture as well as televisions to make the
pets stay an enjoyable one. San Francisco has become the first city
in the country where animals held for adoption are not euthanized.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) SAN FRANCISCO -- Jan. 17, 1999 --SANFRAN-SPCA-1, 1-17 --
Laica, a ten-year old dog at the San Francisco animal shelter, lies
comfortably on a ``doggie sofa'' in one of the SPCA's specially
designed living quarters. San Francisco has become the first city
in the country where animals held for adoption are not euthanized.
(Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
