<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7132 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-FANS-NYT &LR;      01-17 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-FANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOWN COMES TO LIFE FOR ITS HOMETOWN HERO
</HEADLINE>
   (ms) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ELMONT, N.Y. _ As night fell on this working-class hamlet just
over the Nassau County border from the borough of Queens, the
Testaverde family home looked like any other house here. The front
window glowed blue.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Mercedes out front with ``HEISMN86'' license plates
suggested the people inside might be a little more worked up than
their neighbors about the Jets-Broncos game on television.
</P>
<P>
   Across Elmont, the once-again-proud hometown of Jets quarterback
Vinny Testaverde, it seemed as if everyone was feeling the strain
of the American Football Conference championship game: Dogs didn't
get walked until halftime. Pizza makers raced to fill
house-party-sized orders, spinning pies with one eye on the game.
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, and for the first time in memory, life in sleepy,
out-of-the-way Elmont has actually been exciting. Longtime Giants
fans draped themselves in Jets green. Students at Sewanhaka High
School, Testaverde's alma mater, became used to the television
cameras out front. Little kids practically tripped over their
bright new oversized No. 16 jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   The die-hard fans _ the ones whose beat-up shirts and hats have
the swept-wing design from the long, lean years _ have had to prove
themselves to upstarts who never winced through an entire season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I own this bar nine years,'' said Joe Funaro, pulling beers at
Bleachers, near the south end of town, as his tavern filled with
fans. ``The Jets always took a back seat to the Giants, until
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Civic pride surfaced on the signs of shops along Hempstead
Turnpike just east of Belmont Raceway. Cinelli's Restaurant
advertised its $5.95 lunch special beneath a more pressing message:
``Vinny Vidi Vinci _ Go Jets Go _ Beat the Broncos!'' The Giordano
family, owners of Tulip Caterers, got into the act, too, coming up
with the Vinny Testaverde hero: prosciutto, sopressata, fresh
mozzarella, roasted peppers and red onions on a footlong roll.
Sunday, they were selling faster than scratch tickets and beer.
``This makes my blood flow,'' said Vincent Giordano Sr., standing
behind the counter. He added that his son had played Pop Warner
football with Testaverde when they were both 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   Even Sunday night, as the Jets squandered an early lead in a
23-10 loss, people kept comparing their connections to the
Testaverdes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vinny's father did the patio on my backyard,'' said Mike
Tetro, a retired postal worker who was visiting American Legion
Post 1033.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mechanic's helper is his nephew,'' said Frank Klappert, a
retired electrician. ``He once got a tour of the locker room.''
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the bar, three generations of men named Bill
Ost were watching the game, losing their voices spelling
``J-E-T-S'' just in time to sit too quietly through a disappointing
fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Bill J. Ost, 68, the post commander, was hoping the Jets would
pull out a victory and make it to the Super Bowl so Testaverde
could follow up a storybook season with an appearance as grand
marshal of Elmont's Memorial Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he got the Heisman Trophy, we gave him a parade,'' Ost
said. ``That was the first time they closed down Hempstead Turnpike
on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill M. Ost, 41, a technician for Bell Atlantic and a Sewanhaka
booster, was thinking of what a Super Bowl appearance would do for
Elmont and the high school. ``Telly Savalas went to Sewanhaka,'' he
said. ``And Al Oerter. He won four gold medals in the discus. But
that's nothing next to the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill E. Ost, 16, a backup running back on this year's Sewanhaka
football team, was hoping all the hype would renew interest in his
team's games, which has been flagging as the school's enrollment
has dwindled in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to say a rosary,'' his grandmother, Mary Ost, said
near the end of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better make it a novena,'' her son said.
</P>
<P>
   All of Elmont's prayers weren't enough. By 7:45 p.m., minutes
after the game ended, the American Legion hall was as quiet as
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate this!'' said young Bill E. Ost, walking out, his voice
hoarse, with nothing to show for it. ``Just when you think they're
finally going to make it, it's `wait till next year' again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
