<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7137 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS_VIKINGS-A     01-17 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS_VIKINGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FALCONS EXPOSE VIKINGS AS MERE MORTALS  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Wait until the boys who were out ice-fishing
Sunday afternoon get wind of this one.
</P>
<P>
   The Minnesota Vikings, with the most prolific offense in the
history of the game, reinforced by a kicker who hadn't missed since
before the country ever heard of Monica Lewinski, supposedly could
walk across a lake whether it was frozen or not.
</P>
<P>
   But in the second half of the NFC championship game, when the
walleye had to be biting more than the Atlanta Falcons'
cornerbacks, who stayed in a soft zone and prevented Minnesota's
big-play receivers from doing their thing, the Vikings took a
chilling dip.
</P>
<P>
   After Gary Anderson of the Vikings had a streak of 101
successful place-kicks come to a stunning end when he misfired from
38 yards with 2:18 to go, Falcons quarterback Chris Chandler drove
his team to a tying touchdown and then to the game-winning field
goal in overtime that put the Falcons into their first Super Bowl
with a 30-27 upset win.
</P>
<P>
   Exciting, but not heart-stopping, as Falcons Coach Dan Reeves
vouched.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I can stand today, my heart must be in pretty good shape,''
said Reeves, who had bypass surgery five weeks ago. ``The only
thing better would be doing the Dirty Bird (the Falcons' victory
dance) in downtown Miami in two weeks. That might not be pretty.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta meets the AFC champion Denver Broncos, the team that
Reeves took to the Super Bowl three times in the 1980s, for the NFL
title in Miami on Jan. 31.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons led the NFL in time of possession and turnover
margin, two statistics that go a long way toward assuring victory.
Their defense was second only to San Diego's in stopping the run.
</P>
<P>
   But few gave them a chance against the explosive Vikings, who
scored an NFL-record 566 points in the regular season and 41
against the Cardinals in their playoff opener. But Minnesota, which
had the ball eight times after halftime, scored only seven points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a guy who never misses, missed,'' Reeves said. ``When
they drove it into field-goal range, I'm sure they felt pretty good
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson, 39, with 17 years' experience, has made more field
goals than any kicker in the history of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously that's a disappointing time for that to happen,''
Anderson said. ``We were working as hard as we can to get to the
Super Bowl, and then for that to happen. . . . That is a part of
field-goal kicking. My job is to line up and fire those field goals
through, and unfortunately, that one didn't go through. Most of
them have, which makes it bitterly disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who counts the Cardinals among the many teams that
cast him off, completed four passes for 58 yards, including a
16-yard touchdown pass to to Terance Mathis, that tied the score at
27 with 49 seconds left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Then, to the disgust of the 64,060 in the Metrodome, Vikings
Coach Dennis Green ordered quarterback Randall Cunningham to take a
knee with 30 seconds remaining on third down.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two good downs, and if you don't have a first down by
then, there are a lot of things that could have happened with
another play that would not have worked in our favor,'' Green said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Vikings' strategy just before halftime, when they
had the ball and a 20-7 edge with 1:17 remaining, was questioned by
the fans. Rather than running out the clock and taking the
two-score lead at the break, the Vikings might have gotten greedy.
</P>
<P>
   From their 18-yard line, Cunningham threw twice, completing
neither. On third down, Cunningham tried to throw again, but
Falcons defensive end Chuck Smith got to Cunningham and stripped
the ball. Falcons tackle Travis Hall recovered at the 14 with 59
seconds to go.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who completed 27 of 43 passes for 340 yards and three
touchdowns, needed only one play to connect with Mathis on a
scoring pass that reduced the Falcons' halftime deficit to 20-14.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was huge,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   But not as huge as the Falcons making the Vikings punt twice in
overtime, or as huge as Chandler firing two passes for 41 yards to
tight end O.J. Santiago, whose second-quarter fumble set up a
Vikings touchdown. That positioned another aging kicking legend,
Morten Andersen _ also in his 17th season _ to send the Falcons to
the Super Bowl with a 38-yard field goal, from nearly the exact
spot where Gary Anderson had missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You hear about our defense but never about our offense,''
Falcons linebacker Cornelius Bennett said. ``You hear about
Minnesota's offense. But I don't think our offense gets enough
credit. We have a great offense, and Chris Chandler and the guys
keep proving it over and over again.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are still going to say that we don't deserve to be in
the Super Bowl. If we win, they'll say we are lucky. It's going to
take some time, but maybe some day we'll get some credit. We have a
pretty good football team.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
