<SLUG> BC-NY-CONGRESS-DELEGATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S VOICE GROWS FAINTER IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif. Texas) (ko) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ No one ever said it was easy being a member of
Congress from New York state, with all those stereotypes to
overcome. Too liberal. Too greedy. Too pushy. Too New York City.
(Even if you are from Buffalo.)
</P>
<P>
   And it just might be getting harder.
</P>
<P>
   As the 106th Congress prepares to get down to business in the
coming weeks, New York's delegation finds itself in a potentially
depressing, but increasingly familiar, spot: losing seniority on
important committees, marginalized by the Republican leadership and
likely to lose two more seats in the post-2000 redistricting, which
is expected to drop New York from the second to the third largest
delegation, behind California and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Last year alone, the delegation lost its three most influential
Republicans, a crucial change in a GOP-controlled Congress. Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato was defeated by Charles Schumer, then a member of
the House, while two other congressmen retired: Gerald Solomon of
Glens Falls, who was chairman of the powerful House Rules
Committee, and Bill Paxon from the Buffalo region, who was a top
political adviser to House leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Those departures came on top of the 1977 resignations of Susan
Molinari, a Staten Island Republican who was part of the House
leadership, and Floyd H. Flake, a respected six-term Democrat from
Queens. And last year, one of the delegation's longest-serving
Democrats, Thomas J. Manton from Queens, retired.
</P>
<P>
   If all that were not enough, the state's senior Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, a four-term Democrat who sits on the Finance
Committee and has been a major force in directing federal aid to
the state, plans to retire at the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Malbin, a professor of political science at the State
University of New York at Albany, said that together those
departures would ``hurt the state's ability to get things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Al D'Amato, whatever else you thought about him, was a man who
fought hard for projects,'' Malbin said. ``Schumer will work just
as hard, but he'll have less bargaining power with the Republican
majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is upset by the changes: For junior members, the
turnover represents an opportunity to shine. ``We've experienced a
loss, and we need to work hard to help fill that vacuum,'' said
Rep. Rick Lazio, a four-term Republican from Suffolk County who as
a deputy whip is now the highest ranking New Yorker in the House
Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   To Democrats, the ouster of D'Amato, a powerhouse in both state
and national Republican politics, was a major victory, particularly
since he has been replaced by Schumer, who served nine terms in the
House and is expected to be a force in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   But state and local officials worry that the delegation's
diminished stature could hamstring their efforts to obtain federal
money for hospitals, education and transportation projects this
year. The delegation will also have its hands full fending off
attempts in Congress to block New York City from transporting its
garbage to other states.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, in a recent interview, said he was concerned that the
new Congress would not meet New York's needs. ``We in New York are
discriminated against by the rest of the country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats and even some Republicans questioned the significance
of the delegation's recent departures, contending that Paxon and
Solomon were not always effective advocates for the state among
their conservative colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   But many members said they expected the delegation to have to
scratch and claw a bit harder for most of the things it wants this
year.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that long ago that the rest of the House allied
itself against New York mainly because the state's delegation was
so big and influential. As recently as in the 1960s, New York's
41-member delegation was the largest. But the state's population
growth has not kept pace with growth in the South and the West, and
the delegation has shrunk steadily to its current 31 members, a
distant second to California's 52.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the delegation's diminished size, some analysts contend
that New York's current members of Congress, a few exceptions
notwithstanding, lack the flamboyance and aggressive ambition of
their predecessors. But, paradoxically, that may be to the state's
benefit if it means today's members stay put, gaining seniority and
power in the House the way Southern members historically have done.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point is Rep. Charles Rangel, who is arguably less
colorful than the man he unseated, Adam Clayton Powell Jr., but
whom his peers consider a more effective legislator. Rangel is in
line to become chairman of the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee
if the Democrats recapture the House in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Still, New York's delegation has several important things going
for it. For one, its many moderate Republicans are in a position to
exert considerable influence over their conference this year
because their party holds such a thin majority and the Republican
leadership will need their votes to pass anything.
</P>
<P>
   For another, several New Yorkers, particularly Schumer, have
strong ties to the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   Third, New York members hold leading positions on several major
committees, the most important being five seats on the House
Appropriations Committee, which sets federal spending levels.
</P>
<P>
   Other New Yorkers have emerged as leaders in areas of particular
importance for the state, including Rep. James Walsh, a Republican
from Syracuse, as chairman of a subcommittee that oversees veterans
affairs and housing, and Rep. John LaFalce of Buffalo, as the
ranking Democrat on the banking committee.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a Republican from Utica, said: ``We've
always had to scramble. And we'll be just fine. It's New York
against the world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
