<HEADER>
A7155 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-FALCONS-FANS-1STL     01-17 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-FANS-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: 1ST UPDATE _ also sent to (a) General News category.
 &HT;    Fans' dream comes true
 &HT;    By Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlantans, as inexperienced at celebrating a pro
football championship as teenagers embarking on a first date,
figured out what to do by the thousands as they partied in the
streets of Buckhead, jammed Hartsfield International Airport and
swarmed the city of Suwanee to welcome home their Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   When Morten Andersen's overtime field goal sailed through the
uprights Sunday, it propelled the Falcons to their first Super
Bowl. It also set off a wild celebration that had metro Atlanta
partying well into the night, and sent fans scrambling to make
travel arrangements for Miami.
</P>
<P>
   More than 6,000 people filled the E concourse at the airport
awaiting the 10:35 p.m. arrival of the team. Thousands more were
turned away after 8:30 p.m. when airport security closed access for
fear the crowd posed a safety threat.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,000 other fans were waiting in Suwanee at the team's
training facility. Suwanee police requested help from nearby police
forces for traffic and crowd control.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been waiting for this for 30 years,'' said Gala
Hambrick, 35, who was part of the airport throng.
</P>
<P>
   ``This feels great,'' said her brother-in-law Kelvin Hill Sr.,
36, who brought his wife, son, two sisters-in-law and niece to
celebrate. ``I'm so proud of them, I could just burst.''
</P>
<P>
   In Suwanee, Ga., a spirited crowd clogged streets, honking horns
and waving signs. Thousands spilled over the practice field waiting
for the late arrival of their beloved Falcons. Traffic was at a
crawl.
</P>
<P>
   Delta officials gave periodic updates of the chartered jet's
flight home from the North, and with each announcement, the crowd
cheered louder. At 10:05 p.m., Delta announced the jet was just
south of Gainesville, Ga., and the crowd erupted into a frenzy,
chanting ``Super Bowl, Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   No serious incidents were reported at the airport or in Suwanee,
according to officials. At the airport, one fan was evicted from
the concourse for shoving a man in a wheelchair to position herself
for a better view. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The airport crowd included a lot of young children who have a
school holiday today for Martin Luther King Jr.'s birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to beat Denver,'' said Andrew Filipp, 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our mother told us if the Falcons won, we could have a Super
Bowl party with pizza and everything,'' said Andrew's brother,
Brett Mitchell, 13.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in a dream,'' said Helen Lowe, 50, of Atlanta.
``In a minute, I'm afraid I'm going to wake up and it's not going
to be real.''
</P>
<P>
   Phones at travel agencies began ringing immediately after the
game ended as fans looked for deals to fly to Miami for the Jan. 31
Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``The phones have been ringing off the hook,'' said Don Furlong,
division manager at AAA Norcross World Travel.
</P>
<P>
   Most commercial airlines are sold out to Miami already, said
Furlong. Super Bowl packages are not for the budget-conscious: A
four-night air travel deal including end-zone tickets goes for
$3,999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last Sunday we offered a charter to Minneapolis for the
championship game, it was sold out by Tuesday morning,'' said
Furlong.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Bross of Peachtree City already has booked airline tickets
and a hotel room. She's a Falcons season ticket holder who has
entered the lottery for a chance to buy Super Bowl tickets. If the
lottery doesn't come through, she'll go to Miami anyway and
scrounge for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's phenomenal,'' she said. ``I've been following the Falcons
for 20 years and I can't believe we're going to the Super Bowl.''
When the Falcons overcame the Vikings in overtime, emotion overcame
Don Lancaster, 33.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried. I mean you can't beat that,'' said Lancaster. ``When
you take into consideration how many people it takes to make
something like that work and then a team like Atlanta that just
hasn't had any support, and then it took somebody like Dan (Reeves)
to bring it together. You've got to thank him for that.''
</P>
<P>
   One fan who could have attended the NFC Championship game but
chose not to was Rebecca Smith, the daughter of team president
Taylor Smith. She stayed home to celebrate her 14th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting to watch it on TV, but I was kind of mad I
wasn't with my dad,'' Rebecca said. ``I was cheering, I was so
excited, I was real tense, I couldn't watch. I had my doubts, but I
knew something good would come out of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Anderson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga. Larry Hartstein, Peter Kent, Diane Loupe, Ralph Ellis,
Wayne Snow, Doug Payne, Craig Schneider, Cheryl Crabb and Susan
Gast contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
