<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7156 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-EXAM-REACTION-NYT &LR;      01-17 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-EXAM-REACTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: EXPERTS SAY NEW READING TEST WAS WORTH THE ANXIETY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ko) 
 By ANEMONA HARTOCOLLIS     
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At school-bus stops and in playgrounds, parents
across New York  &QR; 
state greeted their fourth-graders for three days in a row last
week with the same question: ``How was the test?'' Now, as everyone
emerges from the rocky debut of the feared and heralded
fourth-grade English test, the state's first major new test in a
decade, education officials are being forced to confront a painful
version of the same question: Was it a good test, or was it
hopelessly compromised?
</P>
<P>
   In many ways it was plagued by problems like late distribution
and accusations that some children might have had an unfair
advantage because they had been exposed to some of the subjects,
even a reading passage, in advance.
</P>
<P>
   But in interviews over the last few days, experts on educational
testing said the reality was more complicated: The new exam
embodied not only the worst but also the best of what standardized
testing is all about.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good test has to be worth teaching towards, and hopefully
this is,'' Lucy Calkins, a professor of education and a reading and
writing expert at Teachers College in New York City, said last
week. ``It's a huge jump ahead from our high-stakes exam last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   The new test raises the bar for what children should know.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, fourth-graders were tested on skills like
listening and note-taking and were required to synthesize
information and write it down, rather than simply answer
multiple-choice questions about reading passages. In future years
the test will play a crucial role in whether fourth-graders move on
to fifth grade, but even this year it will be used to compare
schools with one another, unless the state decides that any such
comparison was compromised by the security lapses.
</P>
<P>
   Most troubling to many parents were the suggestions that the
test was vulnerable to widespread cheating and fraud, in part
because of what some critics called a series of missteps by state
officials and by the testing company, CTB/McGraw-Hill, which has a
three-year, $5.8 million contract with New York state to develop
and distribute the test. State Education Commissioner Richard P.
Mills has promised to appoint a panel to investigate such charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a bit of urban folklore typical of the charged atmosphere,
the test was rumored to have been posted on the Internet, said
Education Department spokesman Alan Ray. The rumor was false, he
said, although someone did post the official practice test.
</P>
<P>
   And in many ways, Deputy Education Commissioner James Kadamus
said, the new English Language Arts test is more secure than the
Degrees of Reading Power test it replaced. The old multiple-choice
test, he said, recycled the same questions roughly every three
years. Although teachers were not supposed to use old tests for
practice, they inevitably became increasingly familiar, if not
intimate, with the actual questions.
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials, along with outside testing experts, came
to believe that this familiarity with the test accounted for some
of the steady improvement in scores. In 1997, 94 percent of
students outside New York City passed the old test. Reading
passages and questions on the new test, Kadamus said, will be
changed every year, and never repeated.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the old answer sheets, scored by machine and locked up,
the test booklets' essays are graded by committees of teachers and
will be returned to schools so that children, teachers and parents
can see how they performed.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts said security was beside the point. Because the
new test focuses on reading long passages from literature, on
making inferences and writing essays with correct spelling, grammar
and punctuation, simply recognizing the literature or having
studied the subject may not confer much of an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Darling-Hammond, a professor of education at Stanford
University, compared the new test to the exam for a driver's
license. ``Most people already know what they're going to have to
do: parallel park, observe certain safety laws,'' she said. ``The
whole point of the test is not to be secret, but to demonstrate
that people actually have the skills it's designed to evaluate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the biggest blow to the test's credibility, children at many
public schools were delighted to discover that two out of six
reading passages on the multiple-choice section covered subjects _
the Wright brothers and the inventor Elijah McCoy _ that they had
studied in class. Those subjects had been included in a popular
commercial curriculum used in more than 260 schools across the
state, including 78 in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   But Susan Harmon, a teacher in San Pablo, Calif., who has
written about test bias, said a test that reflected the
fourth-grade curriculum, as this one does, could level the playing
field for disadvantaged children who are not exposed to the kind of
books, travel and other enrichment that middle-class children
typically enjoy.
</P>
<P>
   New York City Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew, who has sparred with
the state commissioner over whether it is fair to use a new test to
judge schools, said he, too, found some value in the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been one of the healthiest discussions we've had
in New York City since I've been here,'' he said Friday. ``I do
think there's a special kind of commendation that goes to these
children, in the sense that they have withstood all the anxiety,
that was adult-driven anxiety. At the same time, they are getting
clear messages about what it takes to do hard work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
