<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-01-17 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7161 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INSURANCE-LOOPHOLE-LA     01-17 1115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSURANCE-LOOPHOLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOOPHOLE ALLOWS MOTORISTS TO DODGE CALIFORNIA'S MANDATORY AUTO
INSURANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LEE CONDON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE, Calif. -- When judges in Glendale Municipal Court
fired traffic commissioner Dona Bracke, they exposed a loophole
that officials say allows hundreds of drivers to escape the state's
mandatory auto insurance law.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers ticketed for failing to carry proof of insurance were
turning up in her courtroom to fight $1,325 fines with what they
said were valid insurance cards.
</P>
<P>
   Without any formal method for verifying the cards, Bracke
ordered bailiffs to call insurance companies and check _ angering
lawyers because she was overstepping her judicial bounds but
exposing more than 50 cheats this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a perception out there that you can lie in traffic
court, that it's OK,'' said Bracke, who held her job for seven
years before she was fired. &UR;  &LR; ``People shouldn't be able to get off
for an inventive, imaginative story.''
</P>
<P>
   Glendale police officers said they will miss Bracke.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me she was expediting a system that definitely has some
loopholes that people found and were abusing,'' said Sgt. Rick
Young, a spokesman for the Glendale Police Department. ``She was
trying to fill that loophole. She was seeking truth in a system
that often doesn't get to the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Bracke's system clearly was not foolproof. Public defenders
fighting off the perjury charges against traffic defendants accused
her of collecting evidence and taking on the role of prosecutor. In
some cases traffic defendants who did have insurance were hauled
off to jail because insurance companies gave Bracke bad
information. Bracke was sued in federal court by three former
defendants alleging she violated their civil rights, but the case
was dismissed because the judge found she had judicial immunity.
</P>
<P>
   Bracke freely admits she made up the insurance verification
procedures in her courtroom as she went along, trying to come up
with the most efficient way possible to deal with an annual
caseload of 15,000-18,000 defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be easier for everyone if I just called the
insurance company. It was like one-stop shopping. They didn't have
to take another day off work,'' Bracke said. ``If there's no way to
check then the law is gutted.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislator who wrote the law will try to introduce new
legislation that would close the loophole by linking courts and the
Department of Motor Vehicles with insurance companies. And five
insurers are signed up for a pilot program that might lead to
quicker verification of a driver's insurance.
</P>
<P>
   The new insurance law has dramatically increased the caseload at
municipal courts throughout the state. In Los Angeles County,
nearly 50 percent of the cases heard in traffic court now involve a
defendant trying to fight off the fine for driving without proof of
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically what you have to do is rely on the person who is
saying, `This is my insurance,' that it's the truth,'' said Terrie
Wilfong, a government affairs analyst for the Judicial Council of
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge really doesn't have the authority to demand anything
other than what it says in the code. There's no sure way to find
out whether a person has insurance without getting the insurance
companies involved.''
</P>
<P>
   After judges objected to Bracke's techniques, she abandoned them
in March and began requiring people with questionable proof to
return with a letter from their insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her softening, her courtroom demeanor continued to
bother lawyers and she was fired in mid-December. Though Bracke is
gone _ she is considering a wrongful termination lawsuit _ the case
has legislators, police and court officials pondering how to close
the loophole.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Jackie Speier, D-San Francisco, wrote the mandatory
insurance bill in 1996 when she was in the Assembly. Insurance
companies at the time fought off her attempt to get them to
electronically link their records with the DMV and the courts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The insurance industry has got to get with the program. That
way judges and the DMV and the police making the stop would know if
a person has insurance or not,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Speier said she was happy that Bracke tried to enforce the law,
but acknowledged that the commissioner may have gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   ``My intention wasn't to get people thrown in jail. My intention
was to get people to buy auto insurance.''
</P>
<P>
   The DMV is slated next month to start a pilot program that would
electronically link five insurance companies to the state agency so
workers can immediately check whether a policy is valid.
</P>
<P>
   The DMV receives about 100,000 registration renewals every
working day and cannot now check the validity of all the proof of
insurance documents that are presented to them, said spokesman Evan
Nossoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``The volume makes it difficult and we don't have funding for
that level of effort. The law does not set up checks and
balances,'' Nossoff said. ``The law says they have to present
proof. It doesn't authorize us to conduct investigations.''
</P>
<P>
   Vito Scattaglia, a commander in the DMV division of
investigations, said the quality of fake documents is improving and
that the problem grows worse by the day.
</P>
<P>
   When investigators do stings at DMV offices, about 35 of every
50 documents labeled as suspicious by front-line clerks turn out to
be bogus. But there is little review of registration renewals sent
in by mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's minimal screening of the mailings. That's a big flaw
in our system now,'' Scattaglia said.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists working for insurance companies oppose linking
insurance records with the DMV and courts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Packer, a spokesman for the Association of California
Insurance Companies, said they have opposed electronic transfer and
will continue with that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard the error factor could be as high as 35 percent.
You'd have a situation where hundreds of insurance companies with
all different kinds of computer systems trying to link up with one
(DMV) computer system,'' Packer said.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance arm of the Auto Club of Southern California is
part of the pilot program.
</P>
<P>
   Glendale police are finding that counterfeit car insurance
documents have become a major problem with the insurance law. Young
noted that some of Bracke's referrals to the police led them to
investigate bogus insurance companies that were selling fake
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Defendants have pleaded guilty in three cases, one case is in
trial and a fifth is still under investigation. One case involved
79 victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
